<HTML><HEAD>
<TITLE>The development of a natural gas fuel infrastructure</TITLE> 
<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="AutoGen by Bayleaf Software Inc."> 
<META NAME="SUBJECT" CONTENT="Citation #2565"> 
</HEAD> <BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">
<BODY>
<H1>The development of a natural gas fuel infrastructure</H1><HR>

<B>Title: </B>
The development of a natural gas fuel infrastructure<BR>

<B>Authors: </B>
Bol M.A.<BR>

<B>Source: </B>
4th Biennial International Conference & Exhibition on Natural Gas Vehicles, Toronto, October 3-6th, 1994<BR>

<B>Date: </B>
October 3, 1994<P>

<B>Abstract: </B><BR>

This report describes the results produced from a computer model that was used for assessing the different ways that the infrastructure for alternative transportation fuels could develop. The model includes demand, production, transportation, local distri
bution, retailing, economic returns and environmental impacts. A business module within the model analyses the cost and revenue components of fuel supply and presents them in the form of cash flow formats.
<P>

<B>Keywords: </B>

COST,ECONOMIC,ENVIRONMENT,MODEL,PRODUCTION
<BR><B>File Reference: </B>
5029<P>

<P><HR>We apologize that for copyright reasons, BCRI is unable to provide copies of any article catalogued here.  For further information contact <A HREF="mailto:inglis@bcr.bc.ca">Alan Inglis</A>, CATF Database Coordinator.<BR>

