<HTML><HEAD>
<TITLE>The past and future of the petroleum problem: the increasing need to  develop alternative transportation fuels.</TITLE> 
<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="AutoGen by Bayleaf Software Inc."> 
<META NAME="SUBJECT" CONTENT="Citation #2585"> 
</HEAD> <BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">
<BODY>
<H1>The past and future of the petroleum problem: the increasing need to  develop alternative transportation fuels.</H1><HR>

<B>Title: </B>
The past and future of the petroleum problem: the increasing need to  develop alternative transportation fuels.<BR>

<B>Authors: </B>
Santini, D.J.<BR>

<B>Source: </B>
National Technical Information Service, Springfield, VA 22161. No. DE88-010048.<BR>

<B>Date: </B>
<P>

<B>Abstract: </B><BR>

A 20th century historical study of the interactions of petroleum supply and demand patterns and subsequent macroeconomic events suggests that the often-erratic behavior of the oil markets consistently contributes to economic instability.  The obvious depl
etion of U.S. oil reserves and the increasing importance of oil consumption in U.S. transportation are argued to be causes for greater attention to the development of alternative (non-oil based) transportation fuels.  Absent such development, the historic
al lessons in this paper suggest that another period of rising oil prices, erratic oil market behavior, and subsequent economic difficulty is probable within the next two decades.  Methanol is argued to be the most likely and most desirable sustitute tran
sportation fuel, because it can be produced more economically and used more efficiently than gasoline when derived from the rapidly expanding worldwide supplies of natural gas (author abstract 11 figs., 28 refs
<P>

<B>Keywords: </B>

DEMAND,ECONOMIC,FUEL,MARKET,SUPPLY
<BR><B>File Reference: </B>
1627<P>

<P><HR>We apologize that for copyright reasons, BCRI is unable to provide copies of any article catalogued here.  For further information contact <A HREF="mailto:inglis@bcr.bc.ca">Alan Inglis</A>, CATF Database Coordinator.<BR>

