<HTML><HEAD>
<TITLE>The Combustion of Methane with Reference to Its Utilization in Power  Systems.</TITLE> 
<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="AutoGen by Bayleaf Software Inc."> 
<META NAME="SUBJECT" CONTENT="Citation #2397"> 
</HEAD> <BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">
<BODY>
<H1>The Combustion of Methane with Reference to Its Utilization in Power  Systems.</H1><HR>

<B>Title: </B>
The Combustion of Methane with Reference to Its Utilization in Power  Systems.<BR>

<B>Authors: </B>
Karim, G.A.; D'Souza, M.V.<BR>

<B>Source: </B>
Jl. of the Institute of Fuel, 45(376):335-339.<BR>

<B>Date: </B>
<P>

<B>Abstract: </B><BR>

The problems associated with the high temperature oxidation of methane when natural gas is used as an engine fuel are discussed.  A reaction scheme consisting of 24 reaction steps and involving 15 species is used to predict methane combustion in a flow sy
stem.  Comparisons with experimental work reported in the literature indicate similar trends both in the calculated values of the induction period and in the calculated concentrations profiles
<P>

<B>Keywords: </B>

CHAMBER,COMBUSTION,METHANE,REACTIONS
<BR><B>File Reference: </B>
310<P>

<P><HR>We apologize that for copyright reasons, BCRI is unable to provide copies of any article catalogued here.  For further information contact <A HREF="mailto:inglis@bcr.bc.ca">Alan Inglis</A>, CATF Database Coordinator.<BR>

