<HTML><HEAD>
<TITLE>Performance and Emissions of a 0.273 Liter Direct Injection Diesel Engine Fuelled with Neat Dimethyl Ether</TITLE> 
<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="AutoGen by Bayleaf Software Inc."> 
<META NAME="SUBJECT" CONTENT="Citation #1947"> 
</HEAD> <BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">
<BODY>
<H1>Performance and Emissions of a 0.273 Liter Direct Injection Diesel Engine Fuelled with Neat Dimethyl Ether</H1><HR>

<B>Title: </B>
Performance and Emissions of a 0.273 Liter Direct Injection Diesel Engine Fuelled with Neat Dimethyl Ether<BR>

<B>Authors: </B>
S.C. Sorenson, Svend-Erik Mikkelsen<BR>

<B>Source: </B>
SAE International, Paper # 950064Int. Congress & Exposition, Detroit, Michigan,Feb. 27-March 2, 1995.<BR>

<B>Date: </B>
February 27, 1995<P>

<B>Abstract: </B><BR>

An experimental study is presented in which the use of neat dimethyl ether (DME) in a small non-turbo-charged diesel engine is demonstrated. It was found that with only minor fuel system modifications, DME gave very satisfactory combustion, performance an
d emissions. Engine operation with thermal efficiency equivalent to diesel fuel was achieved with much lower NOx emissions and with extremely low smoke and less engine noise. Additional NOx reductions were obtained by the use of EGR, without visible smoke
and without deterioration in thermal efficiency. A limited durability study showed that the diesel fuel injection pump operate on DME for more than 500 hours. A comparison of pure and technical grade DME was conducted.
<P>

<B>Keywords: </B>

DIESEL,DIMETHYL ETHER,EMISSIONS,ENGINE,LOW,NITROGEN-OXIDES,NOISE,PERFORMANCE,SMOKE
<BR><B>File Reference: </B>
5547<P>

<P><HR>We apologize that for copyright reasons, BCRI is unable to provide copies of any article catalogued here.  For further information contact <A HREF="mailto:inglis@bcr.bc.ca">Alan Inglis</A>, CATF Database Coordinator.<BR>

