<HTML><HEAD>
<TITLE>The San Antonio Story.</TITLE> 
<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="AutoGen by Bayleaf Software Inc."> 
<META NAME="SUBJECT" CONTENT="Citation #2530"> 
</HEAD> <BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">
<BODY>
<H1>The San Antonio Story.</H1><HR>

<B>Title: </B>
The San Antonio Story.<BR>

<B>Authors: </B>
Brooks, John W.<BR>

<B>Source: </B>
Nonpetroleum Vehicular Fuels II, Detroit, Mich., June 15-17, pp. 401-407.<BR>

<B>Date: </B>
June 15, 1981<P>

<B>Abstract: </B><BR>

In the search for a viable alternative fuel Liquid Petroleum Gas (propane) has been used successfully as a vehicular power source by the City of San Antonio since 1970.  One thousand city vehicles had been converted from gasoline to propane fuel as of 198
1.  The City has found vehicle performance quite satisfactory and have saved literally millions of petro-dollars by converting to propane
<P>

<B>Keywords: </B>

BENEFIT,CONVERSION,COST,LPG
<BR><B>File Reference: </B>
387<P>

<P><HR>We apologize that for copyright reasons, BCRI is unable to provide copies of any article catalogued here.  For further information contact <A HREF="mailto:inglis@bcr.bc.ca">Alan Inglis</A>, CATF Database Coordinator.<BR>

