<HTML><HEAD>
<TITLE>Thermodynamic Properties Of Methane And Air, And Propane and Air For Engine  Performance Calculations.</TITLE> 
<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="AutoGen by Bayleaf Software Inc."> 
<META NAME="SUBJECT" CONTENT="Citation #2602"> 
</HEAD> <BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">
<BODY>
<H1>Thermodynamic Properties Of Methane And Air, And Propane and Air For Engine  Performance Calculations.</H1><HR>

<B>Title: </B>
Thermodynamic Properties Of Methane And Air, And Propane and Air For Engine  Performance Calculations.<BR>

<B>Authors: </B>
Starkman, E.S.; Newhall, H.K.<BR>

<B>Source: </B>
Society of Automotive Engineers, SAE Paper 670466, 13 pp.<BR>

<B>Date: </B>
<P>

<B>Abstract: </B><BR>

This paper presents thermodynamic properties of selected fuel-air mixtures, in this case methane and propane, in a form suitable for utilization in engine performance calculations.  Comparisons are made between the performance to be expected with these ga
seous fuels compared to octane, as representative of gasoline.  As expected from the predictions engine power is reduced when converting from fuel of the gasoline range to LPG and further loss between LPG and natural gas
<P>

<B>Keywords: </B>

FUEL,PERFORMANCE,PROPERTIES,THERMODYNAMICS
<BR><B>File Reference: </B>
698<P>

<P><HR>We apologize that for copyright reasons, BCRI is unable to provide copies of any article catalogued here.  For further information contact <A HREF="mailto:inglis@bcr.bc.ca">Alan Inglis</A>, CATF Database Coordinator.<BR>

