<HTML><HEAD>
<TITLE>Use of Natural Gas as Fuel in Urban Transportation:  A Brazilian Experience</TITLE> 
<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="AutoGen by Bayleaf Software Inc."> 
<META NAME="SUBJECT" CONTENT="Citation #2668"> 
</HEAD> <BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">
<BODY>
<H1>Use of Natural Gas as Fuel in Urban Transportation:  A Brazilian Experience</H1><HR>

<B>Title: </B>
Use of Natural Gas as Fuel in Urban Transportation:  A Brazilian Experience<BR>

<B>Authors: </B>
Tombi, R.L.<BR>

<B>Source: </B>
Gaseous Fuels for Transportation I, Vancouver, B.C., August 7-10, 1986 pp 1117-1138  (B.C. Research -- Institute of Gas Technology)<BR>

<B>Date: </B>
<P>

<B>Abstract: </B><BR>

Recently significant supplies of gas have been discovered in Brazil, generating optimistic expectations of its future use especially in urban mass transportation.  These discoveries have prompted government agencies and oil companies to start test program
mes with compressed natural gas (CNG) in bus fleets in 7 Brazilian cities.  The purpose is to develop CNG technology, and provide a technico-economic evaluation of: performance of Otto Cycle and diesel engines; processes for gas storage and supply; operat
ion and maintenance of supply centers; costs and fares.  The test vehicles have been used in regular service, covering an average distance of 250 km/day.  They use an average of 0.4 SCM/km for Otto cycle bus engines and have a diesel substitution rate of
70% in dual-fuel applications.  The gas is being stored at 20 MPa in steel cylinders.  The results obtained during the testing period, and a technico-economic evaluation will be used for planning an Ipiranga Gas-Programme for the future.  (From author abs
tract
<P>

<B>Keywords: </B>

BRAZIL,BUS,DEMAND,MARKET,RESERVES
<BR><B>File Reference: </B>
1153<P>

<P><HR>We apologize that for copyright reasons, BCRI is unable to provide copies of any article catalogued here.  For further information contact <A HREF="mailto:inglis@bcr.bc.ca">Alan Inglis</A>, CATF Database Coordinator.<BR>

