<HTML><HEAD>
<TITLE>The Private Sector Response:  Establishing an Auto-Propane Distribution  Network.</TITLE> 
<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="AutoGen by Bayleaf Software Inc."> 
<META NAME="SUBJECT" CONTENT="Citation #2512"> 
</HEAD> <BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">
<BODY>
<H1>The Private Sector Response:  Establishing an Auto-Propane Distribution  Network.</H1><HR>

<B>Title: </B>
The Private Sector Response:  Establishing an Auto-Propane Distribution  Network.<BR>

<B>Authors: </B>
Strauch, M.B.<BR>

<B>Source: </B>
Gaseous Fuels for Transportation I, Vancouver, B.C., August 7-10, 1986, pp 447-458  (B.C. Research -- Institute of Gas Technology)<BR>

<B>Date: </B>
<P>

<B>Abstract: </B><BR>

Before 1979 the use of Auto-Propane was limited to propane marketers and selective high mileage fleets and individuals.  In that year the Federal and some Provincial governments recognized the potential for propane to reduce gasoline consumption and hence
resolve the concern about the potential oil shortage in the eighties.  Accordingly, both governments offered incentive programs to encourage propane conversions.  Thus government created the stimulus for an auto-propane market and provided a challenge to
the private sector to build the necessary distribution network.  The paper describes the process followed by the Propane industry in building up a fueling system in Ontario that began with virtually no outlets to today's total of over 1100 locations.  Th
e industry has taken five years to create what has taken the other automotive fuels over 75 years.  First the changes to the various channels of distribution are discussed starting with what was in place in 1979.  This is followed by a description of the
factors involved in choosing appropriate outlets.  A brief discussion of variables in station design are discussed as well as the important role equipment development has played.  Finally a look into the future of the auto-propane distribution network is
made to describe trends and potential changes.  (From author abstract
<P>

<B>Keywords: </B>

DISTRIBUTION,FUEL,MARKETING,PROPANE,REFUELLING,STATION
<BR><B>File Reference: </B>
1118<P>

<P><HR>We apologize that for copyright reasons, BCRI is unable to provide copies of any article catalogued here.  For further information contact <A HREF="mailto:inglis@bcr.bc.ca">Alan Inglis</A>, CATF Database Coordinator.<BR>

