<HTML><HEAD>
<TITLE>Molecules with Passports to the Interior of a Zeolite.</TITLE> 
<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="AutoGen by Bayleaf Software Inc."> 
<META NAME="SUBJECT" CONTENT="Citation #1640"> 
</HEAD> <BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">
<BODY>
<H1>Molecules with Passports to the Interior of a Zeolite.</H1><HR>

<B>Title: </B>
Molecules with Passports to the Interior of a Zeolite.<BR>

<B>Authors: </B>
Emsley, J.<BR>

<B>Source: </B>
New Scientist, #1667: 31, 3 June 1989.<BR>

<B>Date: </B>
June 3, 1989<P>

<B>Abstract: </B><BR>

Chemists at the University of Cambridge found a way to look inside the microscopic pores of a zeolite catalyst.  As zeolites have been used to turn chemicals into fuels, i.e. natural gas into liquid petroleum fuel, scientists are most interested in determ
ining why and how zeolites behave the way they do
<P>

<B>Keywords: </B>

ADSORPTION,CATALYST,CONVERSION,FUEL
<BR><B>File Reference: </B>
1671<P>

<P><HR>We apologize that for copyright reasons, BCRI is unable to provide copies of any article catalogued here.  For further information contact <A HREF="mailto:inglis@bcr.bc.ca">Alan Inglis</A>, CATF Database Coordinator.<BR>

