<HTML><HEAD>
<TITLE>The Effects Of Plasma Jet Ignition On A Methane Fueled Internal Combustion  Engine.</TITLE> 
<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="AutoGen by Bayleaf Software Inc."> 
<META NAME="SUBJECT" CONTENT="Citation #2439"> 
</HEAD> <BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">
<BODY>
<H1>The Effects Of Plasma Jet Ignition On A Methane Fueled Internal Combustion  Engine.</H1><HR>

<B>Title: </B>
The Effects Of Plasma Jet Ignition On A Methane Fueled Internal Combustion  Engine.<BR>

<B>Authors: </B>
Pitt, P.L.; Clements, R.M.<BR>

<B>Source: </B>
Combustion Science and Technology, 30:327-333.<BR>

<B>Date: </B>
<P>

<B>Abstract: </B><BR>

The burning characteristics of CNG in a single-cylinder spark ignition engine using two ignition sources (conventional capacitive ignition and plasma jet ignition) are examined.  The test engine was operated with a constant fuel flow rate so that measurem
ent of engine output power or the combustion chamber pressure recorded how each ignition source caused the fixed fuel-air charge to burn.  It was noted that for optimal engine efficiency considerably less timing advance is required with plasma jet ignitio
n, and that ignition delay time is considerably reduced
<P>

<B>Keywords: </B>

CHAMBER,COMBUSTION,IGNITION,METHANE,PLASMA,SYSTEMS
<BR><B>File Reference: </B>
942<P>

<P><HR>We apologize that for copyright reasons, BCRI is unable to provide copies of any article catalogued here.  For further information contact <A HREF="mailto:inglis@bcr.bc.ca">Alan Inglis</A>, CATF Database Coordinator.<BR>

