<HTML><HEAD>
<TITLE>Progress in the Development of Recycling Processes for Electric Vehicle Batteries</TITLE> 
<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="AutoGen by Bayleaf Software Inc."> 
<META NAME="SUBJECT" CONTENT="Citation #2031"> 
</HEAD> <BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">
<BODY>
<H1>Progress in the Development of Recycling Processes for Electric Vehicle Batteries</H1><HR>

<B>Title: </B>
Progress in the Development of Recycling Processes for Electric Vehicle Batteries<BR>

<B>Authors: </B>
R. G. Jungst, R. P. Clark<BR>

<B>Source: </B>
Symposium Proceedings, Vol. 2, Sessions 3A-6D, The 12th International Electric Vehicle Symposium (EVS-12) and Electric Vehicle Exposition.  pp 758-767<BR>

<B>Date: </B>
December 5, 1994<P>

<B>Abstract: </B><BR>

Disposition of electric vehicle (EV) batteries after they have reached the end of their useful life is an issue that could impede the widespread acceptance of EVs in the commercial market.  This is especially true for advanced battery systems where workin
g recycling processes have not as yet been established.  The U.S. Department of Energy sponsors an Ad Hoc Electric Vehicle Battery Readiness Working Group to identify barriers to the introduction of commercial EVs and to advise them of specific issues rel
ated to battery reclamation / recycling, in-vehicle battery safety, and battery shipping.A Sub-Working Group on the reclamation/recycle  topic has been reviewing the status of recycling process development for the principal battery technologies that a
re candidates for EV use from the near-term to the long-term.  Recycling of near-term battery technologies, such as Lead-Acid and Nickel/Cadmium, is occuring today and it is believed that sufficient processing capacity can be maintained to keep up with th
e large number of units that could result from extensive EV use.  Reclamation/recycle processes for mid-term batteries are partially developed.  Good progress has been made in identifying processes to recycle Sodium/Sulphur batteries at a reasonable cost
and pilot scale facilities are being tested or planned.  A pre-feasibility cost study on the Nickel/Metal Hydride battery also indicates favorable economics for some of the proposed reclamation processes.  More work on defining the process details is need
ed in this case.  Long-term battery technologies, including Lithium-Polymer and Lithium/Iron Disulfide, are still being designed and developed for EVs, so descriptions of prototype recycling processes are rather general at this point.  However, some issue
s related to the recycling of Lithium have already become apparent.  Due to the long time required to set up new, full-scale recycling facilities, it is important to develop a reclamation/recycling process in parallel with the battery technologies themsel
ves.
<P>

<B>Keywords: </B>

BATTERY,CADMIUM,ELECTRIC,IRON,LITHIUM,SAFETY,SODIUM,SULFIDE,SULPHUR
<BR><B>File Reference: </B>
5359<P>

<P><HR>We apologize that for copyright reasons, BCRI is unable to provide copies of any article catalogued here.  For further information contact <A HREF="mailto:inglis@bcr.bc.ca">Alan Inglis</A>, CATF Database Coordinator.<BR>

