<HTML><HEAD>
<TITLE>Performance Testing of a Dual-Fuel Conversion System for a Two-Stroke  Detroit Diesel 6V-71 Engine</TITLE> 
<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="AutoGen by Bayleaf Software Inc."> 
<META NAME="SUBJECT" CONTENT="Citation #1942"> 
</HEAD> <BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">
<BODY>
<H1>Performance Testing of a Dual-Fuel Conversion System for a Two-Stroke  Detroit Diesel 6V-71 Engine</H1><HR>

<B>Title: </B>
Performance Testing of a Dual-Fuel Conversion System for a Two-Stroke  Detroit Diesel 6V-71 Engine<BR>

<B>Authors: </B>
Applied Physics and Engineering Division, B.C. Research<BR>

<B>Source: </B>
Prepared for Energy, Mines and Resources, Transportation Energy Division,  July 1986<BR>

<B>Date: </B>
<P>

<B>Abstract: </B><BR>

A dual-fuel conversion of a two-stroke Detroit Diesel Allison bus engine developed by Pro-Staff Fuels was tested at B.C. Research.  A converted engine was mounted on the dynamometer and tested over its operating range.  Performance and fuel consumption we
re measured on both fuels.  Cylinder pressures were monitored in two cylinders and exhaust temperatures were measured for all cylinders.  It was found that on average the torque developed on dual-fuel was lower by 7% at high speeds and higher by 9% at 100
0 rpm.  The peak pressures on dual-fuel were typically between 70 and 80% of those on diesel.  The thermal efficiency of the converted engine was on average lower by 18%.  The diesel substitution varied from 0% at idle to 87% at 1000 rpm and full load.  T
here was no sign of detonation at any operating conditions on dual-fuel.  (Author abstract
<P>

<B>Keywords: </B>

BUS,CONSUMPTION,DUAL-FUEL,ENGINE,FUEL,PERFORMANCE,TWO-STROKE
<BR><B>File Reference: </B>
1200<P>

<P><HR>We apologize that for copyright reasons, BCRI is unable to provide copies of any article catalogued here.  For further information contact <A HREF="mailto:inglis@bcr.bc.ca">Alan Inglis</A>, CATF Database Coordinator.<BR>

