<HTML><HEAD>
<TITLE>Ozone Precursor Emissions from Alternatively Fueled Vehicles</TITLE> 
<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="AutoGen by Bayleaf Software Inc."> 
<META NAME="SUBJECT" CONTENT="Citation #1923"> 
</HEAD> <BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">
<BODY>
<H1>Ozone Precursor Emissions from Alternatively Fueled Vehicles</H1><HR>

<B>Title: </B>
Ozone Precursor Emissions from Alternatively Fueled Vehicles<BR>

<B>Authors: </B>
Gabele P.<BR>

<B>Source: </B>
SAE # 941905 presented at Fuels & Lubricants Meeting and Exposition, Baltimore, Maryland Oct 17-20, 1994<BR>

<B>Date: </B>
October 17, 1994<P>

<B>Abstract: </B><BR>

Smog chamber tests were conducted using automobile exhaust gas generated during emissions tests with a group of alternatively fueled vehicles.  The tests were designed to evaluate the photochemical characteristics of organic emissions from vehicles operat
ing on compressed natural gas, methanol, ethanol, liquefied petroleum gas, and reformulated gasolines.  A description of the emissions characterization portion of the study is presented in this paper to assist in better understanding the chamber experimen
ts described in the companion paper (SAE # 941906, Article # 5057).  The study is part of a larger program in which the U.S. Department of Energy (DOE), in cooperation with the U.S. Enviromental Protection Agency is examining the effects of alternative fu
el usage on emissions and fuel economy.  In this study methanol, ethanol, CNG, LPG and four blends of gasoline emissions were measured for NMOG, CO, NOx and MIR (maximum incremental reactivity) emission rates. (from Author's abstract)
<P>

<B>Keywords: </B>

EMISSIONS,ETHANOL,EXHAUST,GASOLINE,LPG,METHANOL,NATURAL GAS,PROPANE
<BR><B>File Reference: </B>
5056<P>

<P><HR>We apologize that for copyright reasons, BCRI is unable to provide copies of any article catalogued here.  For further information contact <A HREF="mailto:inglis@bcr.bc.ca">Alan Inglis</A>, CATF Database Coordinator.<BR>

