<HTML><HEAD>
<TITLE>The LNG/LIN Scheme As A Transport Alternative For Northern Norwegian Gas.</TITLE> 
<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="AutoGen by Bayleaf Software Inc."> 
<META NAME="SUBJECT" CONTENT="Citation #2480"> 
</HEAD> <BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">
<BODY>
<H1>The LNG/LIN Scheme As A Transport Alternative For Northern Norwegian Gas.</H1><HR>

<B>Title: </B>
The LNG/LIN Scheme As A Transport Alternative For Northern Norwegian Gas.<BR>

<B>Authors: </B>
Bakke, J.<BR>

<B>Source: </B>
GasTech 85, LNG/LPG Conference, Nice, France, Nov. 12-15, pp. 219-224.<BR>

<B>Date: </B>
November 12, 1986<P>

<B>Abstract: </B><BR>

The LNG/LIN transport system for offshore natural gas is discussed. Liquid nitrogen is produced in an onshore plant and loaded onboard the LNG/LIN shuttle tanker.  At the offshore field natural gas is transferred from a loading buoy and liquefied onboard
the vessel by heat exchange with vaporizing nitrogen.  The vessel then returns with LNG to the onshore terminal and unloads the LNG simultaneously loading liquefied nitrogen.  This system has a number of serous drawbacks which this paper identifies and th
en suggests ways of eliminating
<P>

<B>Keywords: </B>

BOAT,DISTRIBUTION,FUEL,LIQUEFIED,NATURAL GAS
<BR><B>File Reference: </B>
925<P>

<P><HR>We apologize that for copyright reasons, BCRI is unable to provide copies of any article catalogued here.  For further information contact <A HREF="mailto:inglis@bcr.bc.ca">Alan Inglis</A>, CATF Database Coordinator.<BR>

