<HTML><HEAD>
<TITLE>Thermal Management for Hybrid-Electric Vehicle Valve-Regulated Lead-Acid (VRLA) Batteries</TITLE> 
<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="AutoGen by Bayleaf Software Inc."> 
<META NAME="SUBJECT" CONTENT="Citation #2599"> 
</HEAD> <BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">
<BODY>
<H1>Thermal Management for Hybrid-Electric Vehicle Valve-Regulated Lead-Acid (VRLA) Batteries</H1><HR>

<B>Title: </B>
Thermal Management for Hybrid-Electric Vehicle Valve-Regulated Lead-Acid (VRLA) Batteries<BR>

<B>Authors: </B>
Simon G. Barnes, Frank A. Fleming, Alexander P. Rafalovich  &  William J. Longardner<BR>

<B>Source: </B>
Symposium Proceedings, Vol. 2, Sessions 3A-6D, The 12th International Electric Vehicle Symposium (EVS-12) and Electric Vehicle Exposition.  pp 27-37<BR>

<B>Date: </B>
December 5, 1994<P>

<B>Abstract: </B><BR>

In this paper, the Valve-Regulated Lead-Acid (VRLA) batteries are used for the study of thermal management for the improvement of long term reliability and the performance in a battery used in the electric (EV) or the hybrid-electric (HEV) vehicles.  The
cause of the critical problem of heat produced in a EV or HEV is the actual construction of the batteries used.  The individual cells or the multi-celled monoblocs are very closely packed due to the physical limitation of the EVs and HEVs.  The system com
ponents are also outlined and described.  HEV Duty Cycle and  Free Air tests were done to simulate the batteries in working condition.  Areas for development and long term improvements of the project were outlined for future activities.
<P>

<B>Keywords: </B>

BATTERY,ELECTRIC,HYBRID,LEAD,MANAGEMENT,PERFORMANCE,RELIABILITY,THERMAL,VALVE
<BR><B>File Reference: </B>
5209<P>

<P><HR>We apologize that for copyright reasons, BCRI is unable to provide copies of any article catalogued here.  For further information contact <A HREF="mailto:inglis@bcr.bc.ca">Alan Inglis</A>, CATF Database Coordinator.<BR>

