<HTML><HEAD>
<TITLE>Operation of Dual-Fuel Engines in Pipeline Service.</TITLE> 
<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="AutoGen by Bayleaf Software Inc."> 
<META NAME="SUBJECT" CONTENT="Citation #1887"> 
</HEAD> <BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">
<BODY>
<H1>Operation of Dual-Fuel Engines in Pipeline Service.</H1><HR>

<B>Title: </B>
Operation of Dual-Fuel Engines in Pipeline Service.<BR>

<B>Authors: </B>
Kelgard, Erik<BR>

<B>Source: </B>
American Society of Mechanical Engineers, New York, ASME Paper No.  61-OGP-1, 15 pp.<BR>

<B>Date: </B>
<P>

<B>Abstract: </B><BR>

Internal combustion engines used in natural gas pipelines are discussed. For best fuel economy, dual fuel engines should be so arranged that when the engine is operated as a gas diesel, combustion air quantity is reduced to about 75 percent of that requir
ed for the engine when operating as an oil diesel.  Fuel economy/efficiency is affected by changes in ambient temperature, as well as changes in pilot fuel timing and quantity as a result of speed changes.  If these variables are controlled it is possible
to have as high as 20 percent savings in fuel
<P>

<B>Keywords: </B>

CONSUMPTION,DUAL-FUEL,FUEL,PIPELINE
<BR><B>File Reference: </B>
557<P>

<P><HR>We apologize that for copyright reasons, BCRI is unable to provide copies of any article catalogued here.  For further information contact <A HREF="mailto:inglis@bcr.bc.ca">Alan Inglis</A>, CATF Database Coordinator.<BR>

