<HTML><HEAD>
<TITLE>Spark Ignition of Natural Gas: Theory and Practice</TITLE> 
<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="AutoGen by Bayleaf Software Inc."> 
<META NAME="SUBJECT" CONTENT="Citation #2251"> 
</HEAD> <BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">
<BODY>
<H1>Spark Ignition of Natural Gas: Theory and Practice</H1><HR>

<B>Title: </B>
Spark Ignition of Natural Gas: Theory and Practice<BR>

<B>Authors: </B>
Sayers, J.F.; Tewarei, G.P.; Wilson, J.R.; Jessen, P.F.<BR>

<B>Source: </B>
IGE Journal, May 1971, pp. 322-338.<BR>

<B>Date: </B>
<P>

<B>Abstract: </B><BR>

In this paper the basic aspects of spark ignition and the potential problems associated with its use in appliances run on natural gas are presented.  As natural gas has a lower diffusity in air, a lower burning velocity and narrower flammability limits co
mpared to gasoline, problems arise with flame stability and ignition in certain areas of domestic and commercial use.  Research was conducted to determine the minimum energy requirements needed to ensure reliable ignition.  Results indicate the relative i
mportance in spark ignition, of gas/air mixtures of factors such as gas composition, vitiation level, electrode geometry, and material, circuit characteristics, etc.  It is thought that spark ignition should prove attractive in domestic use, providing car
eful consideration is given to the design and integration of the appliance and spark ignition's source
<P>

<B>Keywords: </B>

FLAMMABILITY,IGNITION,SYSTEMS
<BR><B>File Reference: </B>
719<P>

<P><HR>We apologize that for copyright reasons, BCRI is unable to provide copies of any article catalogued here.  For further information contact <A HREF="mailto:inglis@bcr.bc.ca">Alan Inglis</A>, CATF Database Coordinator.<BR>

