<H1>Natural-Gas-Powered Vehicles</H1><HR>

<B>Title: </B>
Natural-Gas-Powered Vehicles<BR>

<B>Authors: </B>
Golovoy, Amos; Nichols, Roberta J.<BR>

<B>Source: </B>
Chemtech June 1983, pp. 359-363.<BR>

<B>Date: </B>
<P>

<B>Abstract: </B><BR>

Running cars on natural gas should offer a cost advantage--without one, it's difficult to justify coping with all of the disadvantages and complexities of the system.  If one builds vehicles to suit the system, however, it's possible to achieve satisfacto
ry performance with a reasonable range.  Because public refueling stations are nonexistant, these vehicles currently are limited to fleet operation with central refueling.  But preliminary studies show that the home refueling system offers an alternative
superior to the electric vehicle
<P>

