<HTML><HEAD>
<TITLE>Research & Development of Mazda MX-5EV</TITLE> 
<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="AutoGen by Bayleaf Software Inc."> 
<META NAME="SUBJECT" CONTENT="Citation #2138"> 
</HEAD> <BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">
<BODY>
<H1>Research & Development of Mazda MX-5EV</H1><HR>

<B>Title: </B>
Research & Development of Mazda MX-5EV<BR>

<B>Authors: </B>
Michio Yoshino<BR>

<B>Source: </B>
Symposium Proceedings, Vol. 2, Sessions 3A-6D, The 12th International Electric Vehicle Symposium (EVS-12) and Electric Vehicle Exposition.  pp 856-864<BR>

<B>Date: </B>
December 5, 1994<P>

<B>Abstract: </B><BR>

Based on the understanding that performance compatible with gasoline-powered vehicles is vital for the prevalence of electric vehicles, we have developed a two-seater MX-5 EV intended for commuting and short distance routine business activities that may n
ot be affected by its short driving range and other weaknesses.  Equipped with a high-power AC (Alternate Current) motor and high-power and high-energy Ni-Cd batteries, the MX-5 EV has proved having an accelerating performance equivalent to that of gasoli
ne-powered vehicles as a result of performance tests.Furthermore, it has been judged through practicability tests that the vehicle can be used without any problem with the driving performance for routine business activities, and no other problems have
been identified for future improvement .
<P>

<B>Keywords: </B>

ACCELERATION,CADMIUM,ELECTRIC,MAZDA,NICKEL,PERFORMANCE
<BR><B>File Reference: </B>
5368<P>

