<TITLE>Vapor Delivered Lubrication Concepts for Natural Gas Engines.</TITLE> 
<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="AutoGen by Bayleaf Software Inc."> 
<META NAME="SUBJECT" CONTENT="Citation #2681"> 
</HEAD> <BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">
<BODY>
<H1>Vapor Delivered Lubrication Concepts for Natural Gas Engines.</H1><HR>

<B>Title: </B>
Vapor Delivered Lubrication Concepts for Natural Gas Engines.<BR>

<B>Authors: </B>
Klaus, E.E.<BR>

<B>Source: </B>
Presented at Gas Research Institute and Center for Advanced Materials  workshop "Advanced Materials in Natural Gas Engines" Chicago, May 22-23.<BR>

<B>Date: </B>
<P>

<B>Abstract: </B><BR>

Vapor delivered lubrication was designed to meet two special needs. First, vapor delivery of a lubricant in a carrier gas provides a method of delivering small, but precise amounts of lubricant to a bearing system.  Second, the lubricant delivered in a ca
rrier gas can be designed to provide good lubrication without undesireable buildup over the temperature range of 200 degrees C to 1600 degrees C.  Various modes of vapor lubrication are discussed.  The methods of delivering vapor phase lubricants in an en
gine are not yet well developed.  Improved methods for the application of lubrication technology to engines need to be developed and evaluated.  Presentation is in outline format.  (from author abstract
<P>

<B>Keywords: </B>

CERAMIC,DESIGN,ENGINE,LUBRICANT,WEAR
<BR><B>File Reference: </B>
1966<P>

