<TITLE>Simple and effective solution to smoke emission from buses for developing countries: Dual fuel application in retrofited bus fleets in Ankara</TITLE> 
<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="AutoGen by Bayleaf Software Inc."> 
<META NAME="SUBJECT" CONTENT="Citation #2216"> 
</HEAD> <BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">
<BODY>
<H1>Simple and effective solution to smoke emission from buses for developing countries: Dual fuel application in retrofited bus fleets in Ankara</H1><HR>

<B>Title: </B>
Simple and effective solution to smoke emission from buses for developing countries: Dual fuel application in retrofited bus fleets in Ankara<BR>

<B>Authors: </B>
Yahsi O.S., Albayrak K., Eralp O.C., Bayka A.D., Ada O., Safak A.<BR>

<B>Source: </B>
4th Biennial International Conference & Exhibition on Natural Gas Vehicles, Toronto, October 3-6th, 1994<BR>

<B>Date: </B>
October 3, 1994<P>

<B>Abstract: </B><BR>

Municipality of Ankara due to the economical and environmental reasons decided to use natural gas as the fuel in its buses. In 1993 the system developed in the Middle East Technical University was decided to be adopted to 60 M.A.N. buses. Fifty of these b
uses are already in service for more than six months. In this study, the operation of the dual fuel buses in public transportation was investigated. The technical, environmental, social, and economic aspects of these applications are discussed. In two yea
rs trial period they did not observe any extraordinary increase in the maintenance cost for the converted buses, compared to the original diesel buses.
<P>

<B>Keywords: </B>

BUS,DUAL-FUEL,TRANSIT
<BR><B>File Reference: </B>
4995<P>

