<HTML><HEAD>
<TITLE>Review of Ignition and Combustion Processes in Methane-Air Mixtures</TITLE> 
<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="AutoGen by Bayleaf Software Inc."> 
<META NAME="SUBJECT" CONTENT="Citation #2165"> 
</HEAD> <BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">
<BODY>
<H1>Review of Ignition and Combustion Processes in Methane-Air Mixtures</H1><HR>

<B>Title: </B>
Review of Ignition and Combustion Processes in Methane-Air Mixtures<BR>

<B>Authors: </B>
Gettel, L.E.; Evans, R.L.; Hill, P.G.<BR>

<B>Source: </B>
Department of Mechanical Engineering, University of British Columbia, 80 pp.<BR>

<B>Date: </B>
July 31, 1982<P>

<B>Abstract: </B><BR>

The fundamental ignition and combustion processes in methane-air mixtures, appropriate for use in internal combustion engines, is reviewed.  Internal combustion engine converted to run on natural gas (methane) experience a considerable power loss.  Part o
f this is due to the difficulty of igniting methane, (its long ignition delay and induction period), and its slow burning velocity relative to gasoline.  Four different methods to reduce ignition delay and enhance the initial burning rate are presented.
These include:  fuel additives, alternative ignition sources, energy redistribution in the spark discharge, and increased flame kernel volume.  The effect of mixture motion and turbulence on engine combustion processes has also been reviewed.  Combustion
duration can be reduced and power improved by increasing the turbulent intensity in the engine.  This is due to an increase of the flame speed due to the turbulent eddies.  Turbulent intensity can be increased by either changes in the combustion chamber o
r inlet flow geometry
<P>

<B>Keywords: </B>

ADDITIVE,CHAMBER,COMBUSTION,FLAME,FUEL,IGNITION,METHANE,SYSTEMS
<BR><B>File Reference: </B>
245<P>

<P><HR>We apologize that for copyright reasons, BCRI is unable to provide copies of any article catalogued here.  For further information contact <A HREF="mailto:inglis@bcr.bc.ca">Alan Inglis</A>, CATF Database Coordinator.<BR>

