<HTML><HEAD>
<TITLE>Rationale for Proposed American Nations Standard AGA NGV2</TITLE> 
<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="AutoGen by Bayleaf Software Inc."> 
<META NAME="SUBJECT" CONTENT="Citation #2093"> 
</HEAD> <BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">
<BODY>
<H1>Rationale for Proposed American Nations Standard AGA NGV2</H1><HR>

<B>Title: </B>
Rationale for Proposed American Nations Standard AGA NGV2<BR>

<B>Authors: </B>
<BR>

<B>Source: </B>
American Gas Association<BR>

<B>Date: </B>
<P>

<B>Abstract: </B><BR>

A national standard is needed for compressed Natural Gas Cylinders used as On-board Vehicle Fuel Containers.  The need for this standard is accelerated by the recent passage of the Clean Air Act which mandates the use of alternative fueled vehicles in non
-containment areas and promotes their use throughout the country.The existing national standard for Compressed Natural Gas (CNG) Vehicular Fuel Systems, ANSI/NFPA 52, recognizes DOT Cylinders for fuel containers, but state and locla jurisdictions are ap
plying supplementary or contradictory standards.  The proposed AGA NGV2 voluntary standard fills this need that provides a basis for acceptance of Compressed Natural Gas Cylinders as vehicle containers. (from Author's opening statement)
<P>

<B>Keywords: </B>

COMPOSITE,CYLINDER,SAFETY,STANDARDS,STORAGE
<BR><B>File Reference: </B>
5091<P>

<P><HR>We apologize that for copyright reasons, BCRI is unable to provide copies of any article catalogued here.  For further information contact <A HREF="mailto:inglis@bcr.bc.ca">Alan Inglis</A>, CATF Database Coordinator.<BR>

