<HTML><HEAD>
<TITLE>Outdoor Smog Chamber Studies of Alternative Fuel Vehicle Emissions</TITLE> 
<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="AutoGen by Bayleaf Software Inc."> 
<META NAME="SUBJECT" CONTENT="Citation #1909"> 
</HEAD> <BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">
<BODY>
<H1>Outdoor Smog Chamber Studies of Alternative Fuel Vehicle Emissions</H1><HR>

<B>Title: </B>
Outdoor Smog Chamber Studies of Alternative Fuel Vehicle Emissions<BR>

<B>Authors: </B>
Harvey Jeffries, Kenneth G. Sexton, Judith Charles<BR>

<B>Source: </B>
Proceedings of the SAE Annual Automotive Technology Development Contractors' Coordination Meeting 1994, SAE reference P-289, pp 613-621<BR>

<B>Date: </B>
October 24, 1994<P>

<B>Abstract: </B><BR>

The University of North Carolina (UNC) has been conducting outdoor smog chamber experiments since 1971.  All chemical reaction mechanisms in use in EPA air quality models have been tested with data from the UNC Outdoor Smog Chamber.  In recent years, sign
ificant chamber time has been devoted to studies of the effects of alternative fuels on ozone (O3) production.  Under the sponsorship of the Coordinating Research Council, two years of experiments were devoted to studying industry average gasoline, variou
s reformulated gasolines, and blended methanol fuels in combination with complex urban volatile organic compounds (VOCs).  This project builds upon the large UNC smog chamber data base and extends the work to include the natural gas fuels (compressed natu
ral gas, CNG and liquefied propane gas, LPG), and ethanol blended fuels.  The results of these experiments are reported in this paper.  These experiments will utilize advanced analytical methods to identify and quantify previously undetected chemical inte
rmediates.  The remainder of this project is to use these experiments to test and improve our current chemical mechanisms and, with Urban Air Shed model simulations, help answer questions concerning the effect on urban ozone from the use of alternative fu
els.
<P>

<B>Keywords: </B>

COMPRESSED,EMISSION,GASOLINE,LPG,METHANOL,NATURAL GAS,OZONE,SIMULATION
<BR><B>File Reference: </B>
5415<P>

<P><HR>We apologize that for copyright reasons, BCRI is unable to provide copies of any article catalogued here.  For further information contact <A HREF="mailto:inglis@bcr.bc.ca">Alan Inglis</A>, CATF Database Coordinator.<BR>

