<TITLE>Planning For Transport Fuel Use In The 1980's.</TITLE> 
<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="AutoGen by Bayleaf Software Inc."> 
<META NAME="SUBJECT" CONTENT="Citation #1981"> 
</HEAD> <BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">
<BODY>
<H1>Planning For Transport Fuel Use In The 1980's.</H1><HR>

<B>Title: </B>
Planning For Transport Fuel Use In The 1980's.<BR>

<B>Authors: </B>
Mayes, Robert R.; Johnson, William F.<BR>

<B>Source: </B>
Ottawa, Transport Canada, (Paper for presentation at RTAC Annual  Conference, Sept. 20-23) 25 pp.<BR>

<B>Date: </B>
September 20, 1982<P>

<B>Abstract: </B><BR>

A number of elements are identified as aspects of the fuel use planning problem which need to be addressed if Canada wishes to deal effectively with the "energy crisis".  They include l) efficiency of energy use in transportation, 2) security of supply, 3
) the safety problems associated with the use of alternative fuels, as well as changes in the safety of the transportation system brought about by other energy use changes; and, 4) conservation of energy, in particular oil-based fuels.  The author suggest
s that as we can not predict future economic trends it is not possible to set out a detailed activity plan but rather a strategic plan.  Some of the potential options available to Canada are discussed, and the need to engage in consistent long-term planni
ng for energy research and development identified
<P>

<B>Keywords: </B>

CANADA,DEVICE,ENERGY,MANAGEMENT,SAFETY,SUPPLY
<BR><B>File Reference: </B>
810<P>

