<TITLE>Mother/daughter station concept combined with CNG/NGV activities worldwide.</TITLE> 
<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="AutoGen by Bayleaf Software Inc."> 
<META NAME="SUBJECT" CONTENT="Citation #1643"> 
</HEAD> <BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">
<BODY>
<H1>Mother/daughter station concept combined with CNG/NGV activities worldwide.</H1><HR>

<B>Title: </B>
Mother/daughter station concept combined with CNG/NGV activities worldwide.<BR>

<B>Authors: </B>
Kelly, Rex; Zwemmer, Anthony J.<BR>

<B>Source: </B>
Presented at the First International Conference and Exhibition, Sydney,  Australia, Oct. 27-30, 1988.<BR>

<B>Date: </B>
October 27, 1988<P>

<B>Abstract: </B><BR>

In non-reticulated areas, road transport can be used to supply bulk gas to CNG (NGV) vehicle refuelling facilities.  This concept is generally described as a mother/daughter distribution system and essentially consists of three major elements: the mother
station, a gas transportation method, and one or more daughter stations The fundamental principle of operation is that transporters are filled with compressed gas at the mother station and then distribute the gas to the various satellite stations.  Gas is
typically transported at pressures ranging from 20 to 25 MPa which maximises the quantity of gas transported and maintains an economic transporter volume to weight ratio The mother/daughter station system has been widely used in Italy, where it is also k
nown as the Travasi system, and to a lesser extent in New Zealand. Other countries (Australia, Indonesia, Malaysia) either have or propose using transporter systems for NGV refuelling (Author introduction 3 refs., 5 figs., 4 plate
<P>

<B>Keywords: </B>

DISTRIBUTION,FUEL,NEW ZEALAND,REFUELLING,STATION
<BR><B>File Reference: </B>
1504<P>

<P><HR>We apologize that for copyright reasons, BCRI is unable to provide copies of any article catalogued here.  For further information contact <A HREF="mailto:inglis@bcr.bc.ca">Alan Inglis</A>, CATF Database Coordinator.<BR>

