<TITLE>The Benefits and Risks Associated with Gaseous Fueled Vehicles.</TITLE> 
<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="AutoGen by Bayleaf Software Inc."> 
<META NAME="SUBJECT" CONTENT="Citation #2377"> 
</HEAD> <BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">
<BODY>
<H1>The Benefits and Risks Associated with Gaseous Fueled Vehicles.</H1><HR>

<B>Title: </B>
The Benefits and Risks Associated with Gaseous Fueled Vehicles.<BR>

<B>Authors: </B>
Shooter, Douglas; Kalelkar, Ashok<BR>

<B>Source: </B>
Arthur D. Little, Inc. (Report to Massachusetts Turnpike Authority), 85 pp.<BR>

<B>Date: </B>
May 5, 1972<P>

<B>Abstract: </B><BR>

This study was initiated in an attempt to convince the Massachusetts Turnpike Authority to change their ruling prohibiting vehicles carrying (including those powered by) flammable gases from using their tunnels and bridges.  The purpose of the study was t
o both discover if there are additional risks from allowing these vehicles to use these facilities and to discover the impact on overall air quality should motor vehicles be converted to gaseous fuel use.  Additional information is included on conversion
systems, fueling and economics of conversion.  In this report' conclusions there is a breakdown of benefits, risks and recommendations associated with vehicles converted to alternative fuels
<P>

<B>Keywords: </B>

DEVICE,ENGINE,GAS,POLLUTION,RISK,SAFETY
<BR><B>File Reference: </B>
416<P>

