<HTML><HEAD>
<TITLE>Propane Carburetion - Some Technical Considerations</TITLE> 
<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="AutoGen by Bayleaf Software Inc."> 
<META NAME="SUBJECT" CONTENT="Citation #2041"> 
</HEAD> <BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">
<BODY>
<H1>Propane Carburetion - Some Technical Considerations</H1><HR>

<B>Title: </B>
Propane Carburetion - Some Technical Considerations<BR>

<B>Authors: </B>
Energy, Mines and Resources Canada<BR>

<B>Source: </B>
Energy, Mines and Resources Canada, 16 pp.<BR>

<B>Date: </B>
<P>

<B>Abstract: </B><BR>

Propane is becoming increasingly popular as a vehicle fuel.  Comparable to gasoline and diesel in performance and efficiency, propane offers the additional advantages of low maintenance costs, reduced emissions and longer engine life.  It is also signific
antly cheaper than gasoline in most parts of Canada, and this price advantage is expected to continue and increase as the price of gasoline rises.  Propane supply is, of course, limited in comparison to gasoline, but Canada's production of propane now exc
eeds domestic requirements by over 50% and this surplus is more than adequate to meet foreseeable transportation needs Propane differs physically from its competitors in several important ways, however.  Understanding these differences and what they mean
for vehicle operation is an important part of the decision to switch Propane Carburetion:  Some Technical Considerations will provide basic information on propane, on fuel system conversions and on vehicle operation with propane.  For information on how t
o convert a vehicle and for specific information on equipment requirements, however, it is essential to deal with a reliable parts supplier or conversion centre
<P>

<B>Keywords: </B>

CONVERSION,GAS,MAINTENANCE,PROPANE,PROPERTIES
<BR><B>File Reference: </B>
219<P>

<P><HR>We apologize that for copyright reasons, BCRI is unable to provide copies of any article catalogued here.  For further information contact <A HREF="mailto:inglis@bcr.bc.ca">Alan Inglis</A>, CATF Database Coordinator.<BR>

