<HTML><HEAD>
<TITLE>Performance And Exhaust Emissions Of A Multicylinder S.I. Engine Fueled  With Methanol and Gasoline.</TITLE> 
<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="AutoGen by Bayleaf Software Inc."> 
<META NAME="SUBJECT" CONTENT="Citation #1933"> 
</HEAD> <BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">
<BODY>
<H1>Performance And Exhaust Emissions Of A Multicylinder S.I. Engine Fueled  With Methanol and Gasoline.</H1><HR>

<B>Title: </B>
Performance And Exhaust Emissions Of A Multicylinder S.I. Engine Fueled  With Methanol and Gasoline.<BR>

<B>Authors: </B>
Gulder, O.L.<BR>

<B>Source: </B>
Energy to the 2lst Century, Proc. 15th Intersociety Energy Conversion Engineering Conference, Seattle, Wa., Aug. 18-22, Vol. l, pp. 298-703.<BR>

<B>Date: </B>
August 18, 1980<P>

<B>Abstract: </B><BR>

Gasoline and methanol fuels were tested in a multicylinder passenger car engine to compare their effects on performance, exhaust emissions and mixture distribution.  As well, effects of water addition to methanol on exhaust emissions and engine performanc
e are presented.  Some of the conclusions reached during this study included:  1) an improvement over the air/fuel ratio distribution typical of current conventional gasoline engines is essential to realize fuel benefit of methanol fuel, 2) at steady-stat
e road load conditions on a multicylinder engine, NO emissions are considerably reduced with methanol as fuel compared to those with gasoline; and, 3) presence of 10% water in methanol fuel causes a decrease in engine efficiency up to 10% at 70 km/hr road
load conditions.  NO emission levels decrease by up to 40%, although unburned hydrocarbon emissions increase by about 20%
<P>

<B>Keywords: </B>

ALCOHOL,CONTROL,CONVERSION,EMISSION,GASOLINE,GASOLINE,MEASUREMENT,PERFORMANCE
<BR><B>File Reference: </B>
781<P>

<P><HR>We apologize that for copyright reasons, BCRI is unable to provide copies of any article catalogued here.  For further information contact <A HREF="mailto:inglis@bcr.bc.ca">Alan Inglis</A>, CATF Database Coordinator.<BR>

