<HTML><HEAD>
<TITLE>Plasma Jet Ignition of Natural Gas Burning Engines.</TITLE> 
<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="AutoGen by Bayleaf Software Inc."> 
<META NAME="SUBJECT" CONTENT="Citation #1983"> 
</HEAD> <BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">
<BODY>
<H1>Plasma Jet Ignition of Natural Gas Burning Engines.</H1><HR>

<B>Title: </B>
Plasma Jet Ignition of Natural Gas Burning Engines.<BR>

<B>Authors: </B>
Ridley, J.D.; Fisher, P.D.; Pitt, P.L.; Clements, R.M.<BR>

<B>Source: </B>
23rd Automotive Technology Development Contractors Coordination Meeting,  Dearborn, MI, Oct. 21-24, pp. 313-317.<BR>

<B>Date: </B>
October 21, 1985<P>

<B>Abstract: </B><BR>

Plasma jet igniters have demonstrated their ability to ignite lean methane-air mixtures both in combustion bomb tests and in a single cylinder internal combustion engine, and to be less sensitive to spark timing than conventional ignition systems.  In thi
s paper the ignition properties of plasma jet igniters are characterized and their application to natural gas burning engines discussed.  Results of tests conducted on a Chevrolet S10 dual-fuel vehicle are included
<P>

<B>Keywords: </B>

CHAMBER,COMBUSTION,ENGINE,GAS,IGNITION,PLASMA,SYSTEMS
<BR><B>File Reference: </B>
934<P>

