<TITLE>Simulation Study of Hybrid Electric Transit Buses on Selected Routes</TITLE> 
<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="AutoGen by Bayleaf Software Inc."> 
<META NAME="SUBJECT" CONTENT="Citation #2218"> 
</HEAD> <BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">
<BODY>
<H1>Simulation Study of Hybrid Electric Transit Buses on Selected Routes</H1><HR>

<B>Title: </B>
Simulation Study of Hybrid Electric Transit Buses on Selected Routes<BR>

<B>Authors: </B>
Mutch G., Drozdz P., Ramsay M.<BR>

<B>Source: </B>
Ortech Corporation  Transport Canada Publication No. TP 12266E<BR>

<B>Date: </B>
July 1, 1994<P>

<B>Abstract: </B><BR>

Reduction of air pollution in densely popluated areas is a driving factor in the development of alternative propulsion systems for urban transit vehciles.  the concept of a hybrid transit bus offers a potential for significant fuel consumption and exhaust
emission reductions as a result of the elimination of the transient operation of the engine and partial recuperation of braking energy.  This study assess the technical and economic viability of hybrid propulsion for a full-sized trnasit bus, with partic
ular emphasis on near-term diesel-electric systems.  The simulation results for fuel consumption and emissions are presented for selected Montreal adn Toronto bus routes, including morning and evening ruch hour and off-peak hours.  An analysis of costs, a
s compared to those of a conventionsl bus, is presented.  Finally, a hybrid electric drive development plan is proposed.(from Authors abstract)
<P>

<B>Keywords: </B>

DIESEL,ELECTRIC,HYBRID
<BR><B>File Reference: </B>
5189<P>

