<HTML><HEAD>
<TITLE>The Ignition of a Premixed Fuel and Air Charge by Pilot Fuel Spray  Injection with Reference to Dual-Fuel Combustion</TITLE> 
<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="AutoGen by Bayleaf Software Inc."> 
<META NAME="SUBJECT" CONTENT="Citation #2471"> 
</HEAD> <BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">
<BODY>
<H1>The Ignition of a Premixed Fuel and Air Charge by Pilot Fuel Spray  Injection with Reference to Dual-Fuel Combustion</H1><HR>

<B>Title: </B>
The Ignition of a Premixed Fuel and Air Charge by Pilot Fuel Spray  Injection with Reference to Dual-Fuel Combustion<BR>

<B>Authors: </B>
Karim, G.A.<BR>

<B>Source: </B>
Imperial College of Science and Technology, Mechanical Engineering  Department, pp 3017-3024<BR>

<B>Date: </B>
<P>

<B>Abstract: </B><BR>

Dual fuel engines compress the air/gas fuel mixture to just below autoignition conditions and then ignite it by the injection of a small amount of liquid fuel.  The use and performance of these engines, however, have been limited by knock.  Single cylinde
r engine experiments show that this limitation is a readily defined autoignition phenomenon, and can be analyzed by a mathematical model that indicates the effects on performance imposed by fuel changes and operating conditions.  Experimental findings con
firm that these performance data correlate broadly with those obtained conventionally in standard spark ignited or motored engines
<P>

<B>Keywords: </B>

CHAMBER,COMBUSTION,DUAL-FUEL,KNOCK
<BR><B>File Reference: </B>
66<P>

<P><HR>We apologize that for copyright reasons, BCRI is unable to provide copies of any article catalogued here.  For further information contact <A HREF="mailto:inglis@bcr.bc.ca">Alan Inglis</A>, CATF Database Coordinator.<BR>

<HR>This database is supported by the Transportation Group of the CANMET Energy Technology Centre, Natural Resources Canada.

<H5>The Centre for Alternative Transportation Fuels, located at British Columbia Research Inc. in sunny Vancouver B.C., Canada, uses ideas and software from <A HREF="http://www.bayleaf.com/">Bayleaf Software Inc.</A> (or <A HREF="mailto:info@bayleaf.com">email</A>) to maintain, publish, and distribute its databases.</H5>
