<HTML>

<HEAD>
<TITLE>CATF Review Newletter: Issue No. 21 (April, 1995)</TITLE>
<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Word 2.0z Beta>
<META NAME="AUTHOR" CONTENT="Andrea Gomory">
<!-- Last Update: 01/10/96 -->
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#FF0000" VLINK="#8080C0" ALINK="#E629A">
<BASEFONT SIZE=3>

<BODY>
<IMG border=0 SRC="../cr_gifs/catf_pg3.gif"><BR>

<!-- begin table--><!-- total=630 -->
<table border=0 width=630 cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0>

<tr>
<td width=150 valign=top rowspan=1>
<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=6 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG border=0 align=top SRC="../cr_gifs/toc_thin.gif"><BR>
<A HREF="hybrid.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="21toc_1.gif"></A><br>
<IMG border=0 align=top SRC="../cr_gifs/toc_thik.gif"><BR>
<A HREF="dimethyl.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="21toc_2.gif"></A><br>
<IMG border=0 align=top SRC="../cr_gifs/toc_thik.gif"><BR>
<A HREF="cng_fuel.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="21toc_3b.gif"></A><br>
<IMG border=0 align=top SRC="../cr_gifs/toc_thik.gif"><BR>
<A HREF="notes.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="21toc_4.gif"></A><br>
<IMG border=0 align=top SRC="../cr_gifs/toc_thik.gif"><BR>
<A HREF="alt_fuel.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="21toc_5.gif"></A><br>
<IMG border=0 align=top SRC="../cr_gifs/toc_thin.gif"><BR>
</td>

<td valign=top colspan=2 width=480>
<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
These types of limit gauges have now been supplanted by solid-state devices, by programmable logic controllers (PLCs), and by microprocessor controllers. Each jump in controller technology facilitates a new level of sophistication in control strategy, so that compressor strategy can now be designed to minimize frequent cycling, reduce variations in compressor temperature, reduce startup power loads, and program electricity usage for off-peak times to minimize costs.<BR>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
High pressure storage is typically regulated by solenoid-operated valves. The classic control device to determine delivery routes and pressures was the dome load valve, which routed high pressure gas depending on pressure differentials between storage tanks. In the past few years, this device has been supplanted by systems of pressure sensors, with the system logic contained within PLCs or micro-computers. Priority and sequential valves may now be actuated pneumatically, with electronic control. These are easier and more precise to set and adjust, and permit more sophisticated control strategies, to provide a faster, denser fill and to ensure more efficient compressor use. In some cases, improved control strategies can facilitate savings in storage tank costs, or increase their effective capacity.<BR>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
Over the past few years, CNG dispensers have assumed all the trappings of gasoline dispensers, including Cardlock systems, Pay at the pump, and LED or LCD displays. The basic measurement of the gas delivered, however, is by mass flow meter. Safety is served by automatic hose-venting systems, fail-safe valving, and control of maximum fill pressure and automatic overfill protection, along with various safety shutdown interlocks.<BR>


<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
Dispensers are built with full communications capabilities in order to transmit information to various point of sale recording systems, cash registers, etc. Once again, control electronics are required to be housed in an explosion-proof case.<BR>


<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
High pressure gas engineers have understandably opted for the tried and true for safety and reliability. However, the advantages of programmable electronic control have not been ignored by the industry, and the micro-computer, which can manage sophisticated and easily adjustable control strategies, monitor many sensors simultaneously, maintain long term logs, and facilitate both automatic and remote operation, is now a serious option for the fuelling station control system. It may offer the best chance of making a CNG refuelling facility as simple to operate as a gasoline pump.<BR>

</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td><A HREF="cng_2.htm"><IMG align=left BORDER=0 SRC="../cr_gifs/back.gif"></A></td>
<td><br></td>
<td width=480><br></td>
</tr>
</table>
<!-- end of table-->

<IMG align=top align=right vspace=1 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><br>
<IMG align=top align=left width=630 height=5 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_catf.gif"><BR>
<IMG align=top align=right vspace=1 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><br>

<A HREF="../default.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../cr_gifs/cr_home.gif" ALT="Review Homepage"></A>
<A HREF="/catf/default.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../cr_gifs/catfhome.gif" ALT="CATF Homepage"></A>
<A HREF="/default.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../cr_gifs/bcrihome.gif" ALT="BCRI Homepage"></A>
<A HREF="/enviro/cln_tr_s.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../cr_gifs/clean_t.gif" ALT="BCRI Clean Transportation"></A>
