<HTML>

<HEAD>
<TITLE>CATF Review Newletter: Issue No. 21 (April, 1995)</TITLE>
<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Word 2.0z Beta>
<META NAME="AUTHOR" CONTENT="Andrea Gomory">
<!-- Last Update: 01/10/96 -->
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#FF0000" VLINK="#8080C0" ALINK="#E629A">
<BASEFONT SIZE=3>

<BODY>
<IMG border=0 SRC="../cr_gifs/catf_pg2.gif"><BR>

<!-- begin table--><!-- total=630 -->
<table border=0 width=630 cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0>

<tr>
<td width=150 valign=top rowspan=1>
<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=6 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG border=0 align=top SRC="../cr_gifs/toc_thin.gif"><BR>
<A HREF="hybrid.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="21toc_1.gif"></A><br>
<IMG border=0 align=top SRC="../cr_gifs/toc_thik.gif"><BR>
<A HREF="dimethyl.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="21toc_2.gif"></A><br>
<IMG border=0 align=top SRC="../cr_gifs/toc_thik.gif"><BR>
<A HREF="cng_fuel.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="21toc_3b.gif"></A><br>
<IMG border=0 align=top SRC="../cr_gifs/toc_thik.gif"><BR>
<A HREF="notes.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="21toc_4.gif"></A><br>
<IMG border=0 align=top SRC="../cr_gifs/toc_thik.gif"><BR>
<A HREF="alt_fuel.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="21toc_5.gif"></A><br>
<IMG border=0 align=top SRC="../cr_gifs/toc_thin.gif"><BR>
</td>

<td valign=top colspan=2 width=480>
<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
The control systems requirements of a CNG fuelling installation are:<BR>
<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=12 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">for the compressor(s): electrical switching for starting up and shutting down high-horsepower electric motors (or, in some cases, diesel or natural gas engines) under load; shutdown in case of fault conditions, in the compressors, themotors, the gas intake, or elsewhere in the fuelling system.<br>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=12 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">for the high pressure storage: operation of valves to route gas from compressors to storage, and from storage to dispenser; maintenance of appropriate pressures (whether buffer bulk storage or a cascade system), shutoff in case of fault conditions.<br>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=12 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">for the dispensers: optimization of fuel delivery, which includes gas temperature and pressure feedback (in some cases, from the vehicle), orderly start and shutdown of filling; venting and recovery of leftover gas, shutdown in case of fault conditions, measurement and price calculation of gas delivered.<br>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=12 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">for the entire system: measurement of critical pressures and temperatures, measurement of throughput and performance, detection of fault and out-of-tolerance conditions, clocking of preventative maintenance.<br>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<font size=3><b>Design of the installation</b></font><BR>
<IMG align=top vspace=2 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
An effective control and monitoring system for a CNG fuelling installation starts with the design of the system. This is done with a computer simulation program, with gas supply (pressure, temperature, and flow capacity) and gas delivery demand (including provision for daily demand peaks) as essential parameters. The resultant flows, temperatures, and pressures can then be calculated, and potential problems such as insufficient flow capacity, inadequate storage, or not enough compressor power can be identified. In addition, the behavioural stability of the overall system can be monitored, so that control strategies vital to performance and safety can be identified. A system designed with inherent stability will be much easier to control.<BR>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<font size=3><b>Control strategy</b></font><BR>
<IMG align=top vspace=2 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
The basic control strategy is that the dispenser draws fuel from the high pressure storage, with pressures and flow rates selected so as to fuel the vehicle in as short a time as possible while not allowing on-board gas temperatures to rise so high that the vehicle does not receive a full charge. The high pressure storage is then replenished from the compressors.<BR>


<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
Compressors are powered by high horsepower electric motors, and early control systems emphasized the switching of these motors with electrical equipment in explosion-proof housings. Typically, motor switches were activated by pressure gauges with pre-set limits (the Frank W. Murphy SWICHGAGE was an early, and still used, example).<BR>


</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td><A HREF="cng_fuel.htm"><IMG align=left BORDER=0 SRC="../cr_gifs/back.gif"></A></td>
<td><br></td>
<td width=480>
<A HREF="cng_3.htm"><IMG align=right BORDER=0 SRC="../cr_gifs/forward.gif"></A>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<!-- end of table-->

<IMG align=top align=right vspace=1 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><br>
<IMG align=top align=left width=630 height=5 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_catf.gif"><BR>
<IMG align=top align=right vspace=1 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><br>

<A HREF="../default.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../cr_gifs/cr_home.gif" ALT="Review Homepage"></A>
<A HREF="/catf/default.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../cr_gifs/catfhome.gif" ALT="CATF Homepage"></A>
<A HREF="/default.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../cr_gifs/bcrihome.gif" ALT="BCRI Homepage"></A>
<A HREF="/enviro/cln_tr_s.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../cr_gifs/clean_t.gif" ALT="BCRI Clean Transportation"></A>
