<!DOCTYPE HTML"-//IETF//DTD HTML 3.0//EN">
<HTML>

<HEAD>
<TITLE>CATF Review Newletter: Issue No. 27 (October, 1996)</TITLE>
<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Word 2.0z Beta>
<META NAME="AUTHOR" CONTENT="Andrea Gomory">
<!-- Last Update: 10/11/96 -->
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#FF0000" VLINK="#8080C0" ALINK="#E629A">
<BASEFONT SIZE=3>

<BODY>
<IMG border=0 SRC="../cr_gifs/catf_pg2.gif"><BR>

<!-- begin table--><!-- total=630 -->
<table border=0 width=630 cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0>

<tr>
<td width=150 valign=top rowspan=1>
<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=6 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG border=0 align=top SRC="../cr_gifs/toc_thin.gif"><BR>
<A HREF="geo.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="27toc_1b.gif"></A><br>
<IMG border=0 align=top SRC="../cr_gifs/toc_thik.gif"><BR>
<A HREF="after.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="27toc_2.gif"></A><br>
<IMG border=0 align=top SRC="../cr_gifs/toc_thik.gif"><BR>
<A HREF="cummins.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="27toc_3.gif"></A><br>
<IMG border=0 align=top SRC="../cr_gifs/toc_thin.gif"><BR>
<td>

<td valign=top colspan=2 width=480>
<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
Because most OEMs are extremely reluctant to divulge the specifications and operational logic of their PCMs, much time-consuming reverse engineering must usually be carried out by the conversion equipment manufacturer. Suzukis co-operation in this project has resulted in no requirement for reverse engineering, resulting in significant savings both in the research costs and the manufacturing costs of this conversion.<BR>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
In fact, virtually no wiring cuts or modifications are necessary, and the original PCM is used to control both fuel and ignition, as well as operate the now mandatory emission control systems checking required by OBDII regulations.<BR>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
In 1996, virtually all gasoline vehicles utilize electronically controlled fuel injection to achieve reliability and low emissions. However, this technology is still not widely used in gaseous fuel conversions. The natural gas conversion system, developed by Saskatchewan Research Council (SRC), has gas injectors directly substituted for the gasoline injectors.<BR>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
The result is an economical, simple engine conversion with the expected reliability of the gasoline version. The original catalytic converter is used, and SRC expect that emissions will be in the ULEV range. Testing is scheduled at BC Research Inc. (BCRI) in October.<BR>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
As a light car, the Geo Metro cannot be weighed down by heavy NGV cylinders, yet good capacity is essential in order to achieve adequate range for city delivery service. At the same time, the cylinders used cannot be too expensive. Two Luxfer aluminum cylinders, with a total capacity of 70 litres, are used, and are mounted lengthwise in the passenger seat position, to be covered by the cargo floor.<BR>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
A special mounting system, designed by BCRI, was prototyped and tested with equipment simulating a 30g impact. The floor of the Geo Metros unit body showed little distortion.<BR>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
At press time, the first prototype Geo Metro NGV has been in service with Lordco for some time and has clocked 40,000 km so far. Records indicate that fuel savings will be in the range of $800$1200 per year, with payout of the conversion cost within the first year and a half.<BR>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
The funding sponsors of the development projectNatural Resources Canada, the Saskatchewan Research Council, Gas Technology Canada, and Dan Ellis of the Customer Technologies Division of BC Gas Utility Ltd., feel that their objectives for the project have been met. The participantsSuzuki Motor Corporation, Luxfer, BC Gas, Lordco AutoParts, BCRI, and SaskEnergy have developed a low-cost, economical, reliable, durable and practical light delivery vehicle.<BR>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
<I>For more information contact: Mike Sulatisky at SRC (306) 933-5468 or <A HREF="mailto:nfitz@bcr.bc.ca">Nigel Fitzpatrick</A>, at BCRI (604) 224-4331. Worldwide, you can contact Adrian Ghelesel  (604) 443-6788 or Bill Paine (604) 895-3580, both at BC Gas International Inc.</I><BR>


</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td><A HREF="geo.htm"><IMG align=left BORDER=0 SRC="../cr_gifs/back.gif"></A></td>
<td><br></td>
<td width=480>
<br></td>
</tr>
</table>
<!-- end of table-->

