<HTML>

<HEAD>
<TITLE>CATF Review Newletter: Issue No. 25 (May, 1996)</TITLE>
<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Word 2.0z Beta>
<META NAME="AUTHOR" CONTENT="Andrea Gomory">
<!-- Last Update: 10/11/96 -->
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#FF0000" VLINK="#8080C0" ALINK="#E629A">
<BASEFONT SIZE=3>

<BODY>
<IMG border=0 SRC="../cr_gifs/catf_pg3.gif"><BR>

<!-- begin table--><!-- total=630 -->
<table border=0 width=630 cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0>

<tr>
<td width=150 valign=top rowspan=1>
<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=6 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG border=0 align=top SRC="../cr_gifs/toc_thin.gif"><BR>
<A HREF="stay.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="25toc_1.gif"></A><br>
<IMG border=0 align=top SRC="../cr_gifs/toc_thik.gif"><BR>
<A HREF="step.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="25toc_2b.gif"></A><br>
<IMG border=0 align=top SRC="../cr_gifs/toc_thik.gif"><BR>
<A HREF="toe.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="25toc_3.gif"></A><br>
<IMG border=0 align=top SRC="../cr_gifs/toc_thin.gif"><BR>
<td>

<td valign=top colspan=2 width=480>
<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<font size=3><b>The need for a strategy</b></font><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
Pilot projects for the use of hydrogen-powered vehicles have clearly been hampered by the lack of a convenient supply of hydrogen. This applies particularly when the pilot project grows to the over-the-road trial stage. The capital cost threshold, and resultant per unit cost of the fuel, could well be sufficient to discourage development if electrolysis at market rates of electricity is used.<BR>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
Clearly, cheaper and more easily accessible hydrogen will be essential if the possibilities of this fuel are to be pursued. A possible strategy for market/supply growth might be:<BR>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=12 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"> <IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">first, to process a small quantity of hydrogen from a refinery, while returning any surplus hydrogen back to the refinery.<BR>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=12 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"> <IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">when the refinery hydrogen is completely utilized, initiate a plant to process and compress hydrogen from a chlor-alkali bleach plant.<BR>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=12 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"> <IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">to supplement the hydrogen supply, initiate storage of hydrogen electrolysed using intermittent electricity.<BR>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=12 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"> <IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">when these three sources are being employed with some degree of efficiency, study the relative economics of other electricity sources, given the guaranteed electrolysis load that has been identified.<BR>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
The presence of other hydrogen users with access to local supplies would change the economics of this, and probably affect the strategy.<BR>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<font size=3><b>Summary</b></font><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
This strategy focuses on moving from cheap, easily accessible sources to more expensive sources with larger threshold capital costs. It does, however, provide a way to grow a local supply of compressed hydrogen to support an expanding fleet of hydrogen powered vehicles. The chicken and egg problem characteristic of many alternative fuelsno fuel supply because there are no vehicles; no vehicles because there is no fuel supplycan be avoided through planning for incremental growth using multiple sources of supply.<BR>

</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td><A HREF="steppg2.htm"><IMG align=left BORDER=0 SRC="../cr_gifs/back.gif"></A></td>
<td><br></td>
<td width=480>
