<!DOCTYPE HTML"-//IETF//DTD HTML 3.0//EN">
<HTML>

<HEAD>
<TITLE>CATF Review Newletter: Issue No. 25 (May, 1996)</TITLE>
<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Word 2.0z Beta>
<META NAME="AUTHOR" CONTENT="Andrea Gomory">
<!-- Last Update: 10/11/96 -->
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#FF0000" VLINK="#8080C0" ALINK="#E629A">
<BASEFONT SIZE=3>

<BODY>
<IMG border=0 SRC="../cr_gifs/catf_pg2.gif"><BR>

<!-- begin table--><!-- total=630 -->
<table border=0 width=630 cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0>

<tr>
<td width=150 valign=top rowspan=1>
<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=6 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG border=0 align=top SRC="../cr_gifs/toc_thin.gif"><BR>
<A HREF="stay.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="25toc_1.gif"></A><br>
<IMG border=0 align=top SRC="../cr_gifs/toc_thik.gif"><BR>
<A HREF="step.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="25toc_2b.gif"></A><br>
<IMG border=0 align=top SRC="../cr_gifs/toc_thik.gif"><BR>
<A HREF="toe.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="25toc_3.gif"></A><br>
<IMG border=0 align=top SRC="../cr_gifs/toc_thin.gif"><BR>
<td>

<td valign=top colspan=2 width=480>
<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<font size=3><b>Cheaper hydrogen</b></font><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
There are several common industrial processes that produce large amounts of hydrogen as a byproduct. Sometimes it is recycled for use as fuel for the plant, sometimes it is flared off, and sometimes it escapes to the atmosphere. As a waste product, it has no cost; its value is set by its market as an industrial feedstock, less the cost of recapture and transportation. It may be very pure and require little processing.<BR>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
In centres with a large amount of petroleum processing, pipeline distribution systems have been built to serve a local market for industrial hydrogen, sometimes as fuel. In these locations, the price of hydrogen is well established, and may range from $2.50 to $10 per thousand scf. In these cases, the cost of compressing hydrogen and transferring it to a vehicle may, in the final analysis, make it more expensive than other fuels.<BR>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<font size=3><b>A petroleum refinery source</b></font><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
However, in centres where there is no other market for hydrogen it may prove to be an economical alternative transportation fuel. For example, three tonnes per day of high purity hydrogen is available from a local refinery at a 350psi feed pressure. If it is not used for anything else, it can be recycled into the refinery as fuel, so it has some value to the refinery.<BR>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
It could be purified and compressed to sell at $2.50 per thousand scf, or about $1.25 per gasoline gallon equivalent, including the amortization of the total capital cost of the processing plant of C$2.5 million.<BR>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<font size=3><b>Chemical industry byproducts</b></font><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
Hydrogen can be recovered from high pressure but impure purge streams from processes such as ammonia synthesis or ethylene production.<BR>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
Another example would be hydrogen from a chlor-alkali bleach plant. In this case, the hydrogen is usually flared at atmospheric pressure, and thus has no residual value to the plant operator. To capture, purify, and compress this gas would probably cost more than the petroleum refinery case because of the necessity to compress a large amount of gas fed at atmospheric pressure.<BR>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
The rapid growth of on-site industrial hydrogen uses is driving both the development of new and improved on-site generation technologies, and the recovery of hydrogen from refinery or chemical industry waste streams. This improved infrastructure will eventually increase the availability of hydrogen for transportation use.<BR>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
Highquest Engineering in Vancouver is developing a compact, high efficiency pressure swing adsorption process for purifying hydrogen. It will be able to handle hydrogen generated by Hydrogen Burners partial oxidation process, by steam reforming of natural gas, or by recovery of hydrogen from refinery off-gases.<BR>

</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td><A HREF="step.htm"><IMG align=left BORDER=0 SRC="../cr_gifs/back.gif"></A></td>
<td><br></td>
