<HEAD>
<TITLE>CATF Review Newletter: Issue No. 28 (January, 1997)</TITLE>
<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Word 2.0z Beta>
<META NAME="AUTHOR" CONTENT="Andrea Gomory">
<!-- Last Update: 10/11/96 -->
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#FF0000" VLINK="#8080C0" ALINK="#E629A">
<BASEFONT SIZE=3>

<BODY>
<IMG border=0 SRC="../cr_gifs/catf_pg2.gif"><BR>

<!-- begin table--><!-- total=630 -->
<table border=0 width=630 cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0>

<tr>
<td width=150 valign=top rowspan=1>
<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=6 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG border=0 align=top SRC="../cr_gifs/toc_thin.gif"><BR>
<A HREF="cylinders.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="28toc_1.gif"></A><br>
<IMG border=0 align=top SRC="../cr_gifs/toc_thik.gif"><BR>
<A HREF="bus.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="28toc_2b.gif"></A><br>
<IMG border=0 align=top SRC="../cr_gifs/toc_thik.gif"><BR>
<A HREF="last.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="28toc_3.gif"></A><br>
<IMG border=0 align=top SRC="../cr_gifs/toc_thin.gif"><BR>
<td>

<td valign=top colspan=2 width=480>
<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<font size=3><b>Warranty and deficiencies</b></font><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
Both groups of buses are covered by the same warranty package, 24 months for engines and transmissions, structural components for five years, and bus components for 12 months. The natural gas buses currently have warranty costs at $0.15 per kilometre, while the diesel buses are at $0.04 per kilometre. The major difference is accounted for by the high cost of natural gas components. Failures of fill valves have also been experienced. BC Transit is anticipating increased reliability of the natural gas components in the future.<BR>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
Diesel buses have experienced injector solenoid failures, and both types of buses have required rear brake relines.

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
This group of natural gas buses was the first run that New Flyer Industries had undertaken, and BC Transit says that considerable engineering was completed on the buses while they were on-line.<br>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<font size=3><b>Fuel</b></font><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
The current cost per litre of diesel to BC Transit is $0.4010 (Cdn) and of compressed natural gas $0.268. So fuel costs are significantly lower with the natural gas buses. Natural gas in BC carries no provincial or federal fuel tax, but the federal GST at 7% is payable.<BR>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<font size=3><b>The refuelling station</b></font><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
A companion report from BC Gas Utility Ltd., operators of the CNG refuelling station, indicates that the station has reliably refuelled the buses during the regular evening refuelling times. The average fill is 150kg of natural gas, and takes 5.5 minutes. A completely empty bus takes 242 kg of natural gas in 9.5 minutes.<br>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
If buses are refuelled immediately one after another the refuelling station storage may be depleted and refuelling is straight from the compressors. In the worst case, the 150 kg fill can take 10 minutes.<br>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
The most serious problem with the installation occurred one evening in January 1996, when a relief valve in the pressure regulating system before the compressor station opened and froze in the open position, allowing some gas to be released before BC Gas personnel arrived. The system has been modified to prevent a reoccurrence and the Port Coquitlam Fire Department has been trained in how to shut off the gas.<br>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
Other problems have been minor. They included: An additional emergency shut down button installed close to the rear of the bus where refuellers are conducting other checks while the bus is being refuelled. The original refuelling nozzles and receptacles were changed on all buses to eliminate a small persistent gas leak. High summer temperatures lengthened fuelling times, and additional storage vessels will be added to the refuelling station to overcome this.<br>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<font size=3><b>What did the riders think?</b></font><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
Of those passengers who voluntarily completed a ridership questionnaire, 70% said that the buses were superior to diesel buses for smoothness of ride, and 93% said they were better in terms of outside smoke and odour. About two-thirds of riders found them less noisy than the diesel bus. The majority (85%) had no safety concerns.<br>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td><A HREF="bus.htm"><IMG align=left BORDER=0 SRC="../cr_gifs/back.gif"></A></td>
<td><br></td>
<td width=480>
