<HEAD>
<TITLE>CATF Review Newletter: Issue No. 20 (January, 1995)</TITLE>
<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Word 2.0z Beta>
<META NAME="AUTHOR" CONTENT="Andrea Gomory">
<!-- Last Update: 01/10/96 -->
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#FF0000" VLINK="#8080C0" ALINK="#E629A">
<BASEFONT SIZE=3>

<BODY>
<IMG border=0 SRC="../cr_gifs/catf_hdr.gif"><BR>
<IMG border=0 SRC="../cr_gifs/catf_20.gif"><BR>

<!-- begin table--><!-- total=600 -->
<table border=0 width=630 cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0>

<tr>
<td width=150 valign=top rowspan=2>
<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=6 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG border=0 align=top SRC="../cr_gifs/toc_thin.gif"><BR>
<A HREF="cummins.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="20toc_1.gif"></A><br>
<IMG border=0 align=top SRC="../cr_gifs/toc_thik.gif"><BR>
<A HREF="ngvmark.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="20toc_2.gif"></A><br>
<IMG border=0 align=top SRC="../cr_gifs/toc_thik.gif"><BR>
<A HREF="promise.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="20toc_3.gif"></A><br>
<IMG border=0 align=top SRC="../cr_gifs/toc_thik.gif"><BR>
<A HREF="Arizona.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="20toc_4b.gif"></A><br>
<IMG border=0 align=top SRC="../cr_gifs/toc_thik.gif"><BR>
<A HREF="gas_car.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="20toc_5.gif"></A><br>
<IMG border=0 align=top SRC="../cr_gifs/toc_thin.gif"><BR>
</td>

<td valign=top colspan=2 width=480>
<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<font size=6><b>Arizona gives its government fleets a choice</b></font><BR>
<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=8 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
The State of Arizona, having legislated rapid adoption of alternate fuels for vehicles owned by both the state and local governments, has signed overall contracts that give agency fleet managers a choice of natural gas or propane.<br>

<IMG align=top vspace=8 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
This is the background to the almost simultaneous announcement of statewide contracts by North American Fleet Services, Inc. of Phoenix (a GFI distributor) for conversions to CNG, and Metropane Inc. of Columbus, Ohio for conversions to propane. And IMPCO Technologies say that at least 100 of their ADP natural gas and propane systems will be installed.<BR>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
Cummins describes the combination of control systems used on the B 5.9G as second generation technology. The six cylinder, two valve per cylinder engine operates on a closely controlled lean-burn strategy, which uses a higher air-to-fuel ratio than stoichiometric. This reduces NOx levels and gives lower fuel consumption. Cummins says that the electronic closed loop system is essential to maintain the lean burn strategy through a wide variety of operating conditions and variations in fuel quality.<BR>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
The Arizona legislation requires that 40% of the states own vehicles be operating on alternate fuels by December, 1995. Vehicles belonging to cities, towns, school districts, etc. must be 18% on alternate fuels by December, 1995, and 75% by the year 2000. Phoenix is currently a non-attainment area for CO, particulates, and ozone.<BR>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
The State of Arizona procurement office has contracted with suppliers to provide conversion work, service facilities, and training. The state has also initiated a system of grants to local governments for conversions, and for fuelling stations that will be available to the public. <BR>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
Arizona is particularly targeting non-diesel school buses. Of 21 school districts that have so far applied for grants, 19 have opted for natural gas and two for propane.<BR>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
To encourage conversions to alternate fuels by the public and business, Arizona offers a 60% reduction in the vehicle licence tax, and a $1,000 state income tax credit.

</td>
</tr>

