<HTML>

<HEAD>
<TITLE>CATF Review Newletter: Issue No. 28 (January, 1997)</TITLE>
<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Word 2.0z Beta>
<META NAME="AUTHOR" CONTENT="Andrea Gomory">
<!-- Last Update: 10/11/96 -->
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#FF0000" VLINK="#8080C0" ALINK="#E629A">
<BASEFONT SIZE=3>

<BODY>
<IMG border=0 SRC="../cr_gifs/catf_pg3.gif"><BR>

<!-- begin table--><!-- total=630 -->
<table border=0 width=630 cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0>

<tr>
<td width=150 valign=top rowspan=1>
<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=6 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG border=0 align=top SRC="../cr_gifs/toc_thin.gif"><BR>
<A HREF="cylinders.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="28toc_1b.gif"></A><br>
<IMG border=0 align=top SRC="../cr_gifs/toc_thik.gif"><BR>
<A HREF="bus.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="28toc_2.gif"></A><br>
<IMG border=0 align=top SRC="../cr_gifs/toc_thik.gif"><BR>
<A HREF="last.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="28toc_3.gif"></A><br>
<IMG border=0 align=top SRC="../cr_gifs/toc_thin.gif"><BR>
<td>

<td valign=top colspan=2 width=480>
<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<font size=3><b>Plastic cylinder liners</b></font><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
The liners in the Type 4 all-composite cylinders are typically thermoplastics. The report advises that long-term experience is needed with such plastics in a high-pressure gas environment, and that they be monitored for premature aging, deterioration from extreme temperatures, and gas permeation.<br>


<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<font size=3><b>Fatigue life</b></font><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
Powertech says that the fatigue life is well understood and is a key cylinder design factor; the cylinders are marked to be removed from service before a fatigue crack could grow to failure over too many filling cycles. The number of cycles tested well exceeds possible usage on a vehicle. All metal and hoop-wrapped designs are also required to show that when a fatigue crack grows through the cylinder wall, the result is a leak and not a rupture, a leak-before-burst.<br>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
Fully wrapped designs are considered to provide leak-before-burst performance because of their construction, in which the majority of the strength is in the wrap.<BR>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<font size=3><b>All composite design</b></font><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
The report expresses concern that all-composite designs require excellent manufacturing quality control, particularly in the joint between the plastic liner and the metal end boss. Carbon fibre wrapped cylinders are also noted to be more susceptible to impact damage, particularly when not pressurized.<br>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
Glass fibre wrapped designs need careful coating because of the increased susceptibility of the glass fibre to environmental damage.<BR>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<font size=3><b>Summing up safety</b></font><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
All cylinders meeting the new cylinder standards are considered to be safe for use within the defined service conditions. That said, the report then goes on to summarize expected performance under exceptional conditions of collision, fire, and impact. The risk assessments are based on failure history, the observed degradation of materials in service, and the perceived likelihood that NGV cylinder manufacturing standards might not be as strictly applied as they were intended.<BR>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<font size=3><b>Recommendations for NGV cylinder standards</b></font><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
Having carried out the risk analysis, Powertech then goes on to make a number of important recommendations for changes to the US NGV292 standard to deal with the possible risks to the various types of cylinders. These include a number of new test methods to detect design and material weaknesses in specific types.<BR>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<font size=3><b>Pressure Relief Devices</b></font><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
The report points out that Pressure Relief Devices (PRD) have worked reliably in the case of fire. On-board cylinders have traditionally been protected from non-fire induced overpressurization by the inability of filling station compressors to generate excessive pressures... says the report. Approvals in British Columbia already take into account the fact that Powertech testing work has identified that some devices leak and that those devices (CG5 type) which utilized a burst disk supported by a fusible metal backing could not protect a partially filled cylinder under fire conditions, since the pressure rise in a fire would not be sufficient to burst the burst disk before the cylinder ruptured due to a fire-induced loss in its strength.<BR>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
The report recommends that devices be limited to thermally-activated designs, developing more realistic tests, and improving manufacturing quality.<br>

</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td><A HREF="cyl_pg2.htm"><IMG align=left BORDER=0 SRC="../cr_gifs/back.gif"></A></td>
<td><br></td>
<td width=480>
<A HREF="cyl_pg4.htm"><IMG align=right BORDER=0 SRC="../cr_gifs/forward.gif"></A>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<!-- end of table-->

