<HTML>

<HEAD>
<TITLE>CATF Review Newletter: Issue No. 28 (January, 1997)</TITLE>
<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Word 2.0z Beta>
<META NAME="AUTHOR" CONTENT="Andrea Gomory">
<!-- Last Update: 10/11/96 -->
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#FF0000" VLINK="#8080C0" ALINK="#E629A">
<BASEFONT SIZE=3>

<BODY>
<IMG border=0 SRC="../cr_gifs/catf_pg2.gif"><BR>

<!-- begin table--><!-- total=630 -->
<table border=0 width=630 cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0>

<tr>
<td width=150 valign=top rowspan=1>
<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=6 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG border=0 align=top SRC="../cr_gifs/toc_thin.gif"><BR>
<A HREF="cylinders.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="28toc_1b.gif"></A><br>
<IMG border=0 align=top SRC="../cr_gifs/toc_thik.gif"><BR>
<A HREF="bus.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="28toc_2.gif"></A><br>
<IMG border=0 align=top SRC="../cr_gifs/toc_thik.gif"><BR>
<A HREF="last.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="28toc_3.gif"></A><br>
<IMG border=0 align=top SRC="../cr_gifs/toc_thin.gif"><BR>
<td>

<td valign=top colspan=2 width=480>
<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<font size=3><b>Cylinder technologies</b></font><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
The manufacturing technologies used for NGV cylinders were grouped in eleven major classifications for the purpose of assessing their safety. All cylinders were assumed to meet the current cylinder standards for their type:<br>

Type 1: ALL-METAL<br>
<IMG align=top hspace=19 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"> <IMG align=top hspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">All-steel<br>
<IMG align=top hspace=19 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"> <IMG align=top hspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">All-aluminum<br>
Type 2: HOOP-WRAP<br>
<IMG align=top hspace=19 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"> <IMG align=top hspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">Steel linerglass fibre<br>
<IMG align=top hspace=19 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"> <IMG align=top hspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">Steel linercarbon fibre<br>
<IMG align=top hspace=19 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"> <IMG align=top hspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">Aluminum linerglass fibre<br>
<IMG align=top hspace=19 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"> <IMG align=top hspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">Aluminum linercarbon fibre<br>
Type 3: FULL-WRAPPED<br>
<IMG align=top hspace=19 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"> <IMG align=top hspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">Aluminum linerglass fibre<br>
<IMG align=top hspace=19 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"> <IMG align=top hspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">Aluminum linercarbon fibre<br>
Type 4: ALL-COMPOSITE<br>
<IMG align=top hspace=19 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"> <IMG align=top hspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">Carbon fibre<br>
<IMG align=top hspace=19 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"> <IMG align=top hspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">Hybrid fibre<br>
<IMG align=top hspace=19 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"> <IMG align=top hspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">Glass fibre<br>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<font size=3><b>Few cylinder failures</b></font><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
Cylinder failures in natural gas vehicles are relatively rare, with only fifteen ruptures and some twenty cases of leaks recorded worldwide over the last twenty years. Each of these failures was investigated, so far as possible, by Powertech. Eleven of the ruptures occurred in steel cylinders, of which there have been about one and a half million in use worldwide. There were small numbers of ruptures reported in the wrapped cylinders, while all of the leaks were reported in all-composite Type 4 cylinders.<BR>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<font size=3><b>Specific risks</b></font><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
The study examined the specific risk of each type of failure for each type of cylinder under twelve different scenarios as follows:<BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=19 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"> <IMG align=top hspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">Fatigue (a test of leak before burst)<br>
<IMG align=top hspace=19 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"> <IMG align=top hspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">Fire<br>
<IMG align=top hspace=19 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"> <IMG align=top hspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">Extremes of temperature<br>
<IMG align=top hspace=19 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"> <IMG align=top hspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">Handling and dropping of cylinder<br>
<IMG align=top hspace=19 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"> <IMG align=top hspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">Collision impact<br>
<IMG align=top hspace=19 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"> <IMG align=top hspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">External corrosion (metallic)<br>
<IMG align=top hspace=19 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"> <IMG align=top hspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">Internal corrosion or aging<br>
<IMG align=top hspace=19 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"> <IMG align=top hspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">Stress rupture of composite (wrapped cylinders)<br>
<IMG align=top hspace=19 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"> <IMG align=top hspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">Permeation or leakage (plastic liners)<br>
<IMG align=top hspace=19 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"> <IMG align=top hspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">Stress corrosion cracking of composite (wrapped cylinders)<br>
<IMG align=top hspace=19 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"> <IMG align=top hspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">Sustained load cracking (aluminum)<br>
<IMG align=top hspace=19 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"> <IMG align=top hspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">Sulphide stress cracking (steel)<br>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
Specific comments from the report follow.<BR>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<font size=3><b>Steel cylinders</b></font><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
Used in NGV service since the 1940s, steel cylinders have an excellent safety record. An examination of cylinders that have been in use up to fifteen years has shown that internal corrosion is not a concern. The risk of premature failure in steel cylinders, says the report, has been virtually eliminated by the quality control system and non-destructive examination requirements in current NGV cylinder standards.<BR>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
The report also notes that steel cylinders have recorded no damage in numerous vehicle accidents, and also offer the best resistance to the effects of fire.<BR>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<font size=3><b>Aluminum cylinders</b></font><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
Materials tests are recommended to ensure adequate resistance to general surface corrosion, stress corrosion cracking and sustained load cracking. Again, examples of failures are rare. AA6351 alloy, which was prone to sustained load cracking, is pictured in the report although not produced in North America. To minimize external corrosion, Powertech considers the use of coating systems essential.<BR>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<font size=3><b>Composites</b></font><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
Aramid and carbon fibres used for wrapping cylinders have higher strength, better fire resistance, relative immunity to stress corrosion cracking, and superior fatigue resistance to glass fibres. Carbon fibres have superior resistance to stress rupture, and aramid fibres have superior resistance to impact.<BR>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
Most concerns with composites used for cylinder wrapping relate to the damage that can be done to the composites by abrasion and impact. The report recommends protective coatings, but suggests that it should be ensured that such coatings can retain their integrity over the life of the cylinder, given environmental conditions ranging from expansion and contraction of the cylinder to ultraviolet radiation, salt spray, vehicle exhaust gases, etc.<br>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td><A HREF="cylinders.htm"><IMG align=left BORDER=0 SRC="../cr_gifs/back.gif"></A></td>
<td><br></td>
<td width=480>
<A HREF="cyl_pg3.htm"><IMG align=right BORDER=0 SRC="../cr_gifs/forward.gif"></A>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<!-- end of table-->

<IMG align=top align=right vspace=1 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><br>
<IMG align=top align=left width=630 height=5 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_catf.gif"><BR>
<IMG align=top align=right vspace=1 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><br>

