</DOCHDR>
<!DOCTYPE HTML"-//IETF//DTD HTML 3.0//EN">
<HTML>

<HEAD>
<TITLE>CATF Review Newletter: Issue No. 28 (January, 1997)</TITLE>
<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Word 2.0z Beta>
<META NAME="AUTHOR" CONTENT="Andrea Gomory">
<!-- Last Update: 10/11/96 -->
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#FF0000" VLINK="#8080C0" ALINK="#E629A">
<BASEFONT SIZE=3>

<BODY>
<IMG border=0 SRC="../cr_gifs/catf_pg4.gif"><BR>

<!-- begin table--><!-- total=630 -->
<table border=0 width=630 cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0>

<tr>
<td width=150 valign=top rowspan=1>
<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=6 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG border=0 align=top SRC="../cr_gifs/toc_thin.gif"><BR>
<A HREF="cylinders.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="28toc_1b.gif"></A><br>
<IMG border=0 align=top SRC="../cr_gifs/toc_thik.gif"><BR>
<A HREF="bus.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="28toc_2.gif"></A><br>
<IMG border=0 align=top SRC="../cr_gifs/toc_thik.gif"><BR>
<A HREF="last.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="28toc_3.gif"></A><br>
<IMG border=0 align=top SRC="../cr_gifs/toc_thin.gif"><BR>
<td>

<td valign=top colspan=2 width=480>
<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<font size=3><b>Cylinder weights and sizes</b></font><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
The report goes on to examine the cylinder weights and package sizes required to provide a 200 to 400 mile range in a number of typical vehicle platforms.<br>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
Recognising that wall thicknesses and weights vary both between technologies and for different sizes of cylinders, Powertech created a computer model to calculate these for a range of cylinder outside diameters. This was done for all the technologies under consideration. (Not all cylinders, of course, are available in all sizes; for some, major investments would be required.)<BR>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
For example, a cylinder 15 in. long and 48 in. in diameter made of high strength steel has a capacity of 1008 standard cubic feet (scf) of natural gas and weighs about 230 lb., while an all composite E-glass cylinder has a capacity of 785 scf and a weight of about 165 lb. An NGV292 specification all steel cylinder would hold 957 scf and weigh 327 lb.; a high strength aluminum cylinder would hold 870 scf and weigh 171 lb.; and a thin aluminum liner, fully wrapped in carbon fibre, would hold 950 scf and weigh 72 lb. All these cylinders have the same outside dimensions, and all capacities are measured at 3000 psi.<BR>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
Using this same size of cylinders for the calculation, Powertech calculated weight/ storage volume ratios for the different cylinder types. The highest was the NGV292 steel cylinder, at .341 lb/scf; the lowest was the thin aluminum liner, fully carbon fibre wrapped, at .076 lb/scf. High strength steel was .229 lb/scf, high strength aluminum was .196 lb/scf, while all compositeE glass was .221 lb/scf. Given fixed outside dimensions, an increase in service pressure from 3000 psi to 3600 psi does not result in a great increase in storage capacity, because the cylinder walls must be thicker, and therefore the internal volume is less. For a high strength steel cylinder, the capacity increase is about 11.4% for this 20% increase in pressure. The weight increase is 19%.<br>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<font size=3><b>Manufacturing costs</b></font><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
Powertech created a cost model for the manufacture of similar sized cylinders using each of the listed technologies. This included raw material costs, the capital cost of manufacturing equipment, all manufacturing costs (including an allowance for wastage), and a 30% allowance for overhead. The result of these detailed calculations was a table of cylinder costs per scf (at 3000 psi).<br>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
The costs, in $US, are calculated to be .383 per scf stored for the billet-pierced NGV292 steel cylinder. This compares with .323 per scf for a high strength steel cylinder drawn from plate. The lowest cost per scf is .313 for a steel cylinder drawn and spun from tube stock. A billet pierced high strength aluminum cylinder is calculated at .624 per scf, reflecting high material costs for aluminum; this is more than a billet pierced steel liner hoop-wrapped with E-glass, at .525. The thin aluminum liner, fully wrapped in carbon fibre, comes out at 1.265 per scf, but the all-composite cylinder wrapped in E-glass is .857. Aluminum and carbon fibre are, of course, the two most expensive materials under consideration.<BR>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<font size=3><b>Future developments</b></font><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
The report went on to identify future materials and technology developments which might have a significant impact on the costs of cylinders. These included a significant drop in the cost of carbon fibre, the availability of higher strength aluminum alloys (less material required for same strength), and the use of higher strength steels (the report points out that these are not permitted by existing US cylinder standards).<BR>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
The report also discusses a number of design and production optimization strategies for various cylinder manufacturing technologies. Suggestions are made for simplified pressure relief devices, the optimization of filament winding patterns, and the autofrettage of all-metal cylinders.<br>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<font size=3><b>Recommendations</b></font><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
The report recommends the continued development of NGV21 high strength aluminum cylinders, both with and without carbon fibre hoop wrapping. It also recommends changes in the NGV292 and FMVSS 304 standards to allow the US use and production of high strength steel cylinders.<BR>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
A simple low-cost thermally-activated pressure relief device is also advocated.<br>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td><A HREF="cyl_pg3.htm"><IMG align=left BORDER=0 SRC="../cr_gifs/back.gif"></A></td>
<td><br></td>
<td width=480>
<br>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<!-- end of table-->

<IMG align=top align=right vspace=1 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><br>
<IMG align=top align=left width=630 height=5 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_catf.gif"><BR>
<IMG align=top align=right vspace=1 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><br>

<A HREF="../default.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../cr_gifs/cr_home.gif" ALT="Review Homepage"></A>
<A HREF="/catf/default.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../cr_gifs/catfhome.gif" ALT="CATF Homepage"></A>
<A HREF="/default.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../cr_gifs/bcrihome.gif" ALT="BCRI Homepage"></A>
<A HREF="/enviro/cln_tr_s.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../cr_gifs/clean_t.gif" ALT="BCRI Clean Transportation"></A>
