<DOC>
<DOCNO>WT04-B17-108</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA006-000056-B016-45</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://www.bcr.bc.ca:80/catf/review/issue_25/staypg2.htm 204.191.240.6 19970221185514 text/html 7735
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Date: Fri, 21 Feb 1997 18:55:34 GMT
Server: WebSitePro/1.1g (S/N WPO-22E6)
Accept-ranges: bytes
Content-type: text/html
Last-modified: Mon, 17 Feb 1997 23:44:52 GMT
Content-length: 7524
</DOCHDR>
<!DOCTYPE HTML"-//IETF//DTD HTML 3.0//EN">
<HTML>

<HEAD>
<TITLE>CATF Review Newletter: Issue No. 25 (May, 1996)</TITLE>
<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Word 2.0z Beta>
<META NAME="AUTHOR" CONTENT="Andrea Gomory">
<!-- Last Update: 10/11/96 -->
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#FF0000" VLINK="#8080C0" ALINK="#E629A">
<BASEFONT SIZE=3>

<BODY>
<IMG border=0 SRC="../cr_gifs/catf_pg2.gif"><BR>

<!-- begin table--><!-- total=630 -->
<table border=0 width=630 cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0>

<tr>
<td width=150 valign=top rowspan=1>
<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=6 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG border=0 align=top SRC="../cr_gifs/toc_thin.gif"><BR>
<A HREF="stay.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="25toc_1b.gif"></A><br>
<IMG border=0 align=top SRC="../cr_gifs/toc_thik.gif"><BR>
<A HREF="step.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="25toc_2.gif"></A><br>
<IMG border=0 align=top SRC="../cr_gifs/toc_thik.gif"><BR>
<A HREF="toe.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="25toc_3.gif"></A><br>
<IMG border=0 align=top SRC="../cr_gifs/toc_thin.gif"><BR>
<td>

<td valign=top colspan=2 width=480>
<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
The CGA has led the way in setting market objectives that benefit every member of the industry. In the United States, the American Gas Association has performed a similar leadership role. This type of industry-wide support is essential to introduce a concept like natural gas vehicle fuelling, which must have the clear commitment of large and responsible organizations in order to achieve the public acceptance necessary for the creation of a long term market. The 1996-1999 NGV Technology Program Plan published by Gas Technology Canada shows a path to meet 
the technical challenges through to the end 
of the century.<BR>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
One of the ways the natural gas industry on both sides of the border has demonstrated this commitment is through its support of research and development. While fuelling stations might be said 
to be the responsibility of their proprietors, vehicle conversion 
kits and storage cylinder design the responsibility of conversion kit and 
cylinder manufacturers, and regulation the responsibility of government, cross-industry support for each of these areas clearly has benefits for all. Unless the technology of fuelling and vehicle operation works, and works to the satisfaction of the customer, 
the gas distribution companies would not benefit from the improved load factor which the vehicle market offers.<BR>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
As an additional benefit, the organizations and people who have carried out this research in Canada are now in a position to help in the development of NGV markets around the world. This is good international business.<BR>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
The research carried out in Canada through the NGV Research and Development fund up to the present has focussed on safe dispensing to vehicles and then ensuring that it works in these vehicles. Responsible standards, education, and codes ensure that it is as safe as or safer than conventional fuels. The task ahead is to ensure that it is practical and, in fact, an ideal fuel in a number of targeted markets.<BR>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
This, combined with new public awareness of air quality, greenhouse gas effects, energy efficiency, and vehicle operational performance, means that new and more difficult technological challenges lie ahead for the transportation market. More than ever, NGV market development depends on continuing research to maintain its advantages over conventional fuels.<BR>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
The automobile industry itself has demonstrated this awareness over the past few years. Driven sometimes by legislation but ultimately by markets, the technological sophistication of todays vehicles is far ahead of what it was a few years ago. NGV technology must keep up. While no one player in the NGV industry can do this by itself, the combined efforts of the industry have proven to be extremely effective.<BR>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
The 19961999 NGV TPP research objectives include the continued development of heavy duty natural gas engines for trucks and buses; efficient, low maintenance, low emission engines for high mileage urban applications, such as light delivery trucks, taxis, and limousines; further improvements in CNG and LNG storage containers for all types of vehicles; development of a smart, more sophisticated control system for automated CNG fuelling stations; and the demonstration of natural gas vehicles in heavy-duty applications, like urban buses, garbage trucks, and highway tractors. These research projects directly support the market development plan.<BR>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
Todays vehicle buyers expect that the cars and trucks they purchase will be fuel-efficient, non-polluting, minimize the production of greenhouse gases, and be economical in both the energy and financial senses. These expectations not only apply to day-to-day operation, but to the entire life cycle of the vehicle, including its original manufacture and recycling at the end of its useful life.<BR>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
The NGV industrys responsibility to its existing and future customers is to meet those expectations. This objective cannot be accomplished without continuing co-operative research.<BR>

</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td><A HREF="stay.htm"><IMG align=left BORDER=0 SRC="../cr_gifs/back.gif"></A></td>
<td><br></td>
<td width=480>
<br></td>
</tr>
</table>
