<!DOCTYPE HTML"-//IETF//DTD HTML 3.0//EN">
<HTML>

<HEAD>
<TITLE>CATF Review Newletter: Issue No. 21 (April, 1995)</TITLE>
<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Word 2.0z Beta>
<META NAME="AUTHOR" CONTENT="Andrea Gomory">
<!-- Last Update: 01/10/96 -->
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#FF0000" VLINK="#8080C0" ALINK="#E629A">
<BASEFONT SIZE=3>

<BODY>
<IMG border=0 SRC="../cr_gifs/catf_pg2.gif"><BR>

<!-- begin table--><!-- total=630 -->
<table border=0 width=630 cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0>

<tr>
<td width=150 valign=top rowspan=1>
<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=6 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG border=0 align=top SRC="../cr_gifs/toc_thin.gif"><BR>
<A HREF="hybrid.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="21toc_1b.gif"></A><br>
<IMG border=0 align=top SRC="../cr_gifs/toc_thik.gif"><BR>
<A HREF="dimethyl.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="21toc_2.gif"></A><br>
<IMG border=0 align=top SRC="../cr_gifs/toc_thik.gif"><BR>
<A HREF="cng_fuel.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="21toc_3.gif"></A><br>
<IMG border=0 align=top SRC="../cr_gifs/toc_thik.gif"><BR>
<A HREF="notes.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="21toc_4.gif"></A><br>
<IMG border=0 align=top SRC="../cr_gifs/toc_thik.gif"><BR>
<A HREF="alt_fuel.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="21toc_5.gif"></A><br>
<IMG border=0 align=top SRC="../cr_gifs/toc_thin.gif"><BR>
</td>

<td valign=top colspan=2 width=480>
<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<font size=3><b>Three groups</b></font><BR>
<IMG align=top vspace=2 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
The HEV Challenge attempted to classify hybrids into three groups:<BR>
<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=12 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"> <IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">Charge depleting: the concept is essentially that of an electrically powered vehicle, its batteries recharged from utility-supplied electricity, but which also has a small ICE which will provide either supplemental power, or additional range, or both. Mainly, vehicles of this type are conceived as commuter vehicles of limited range. Typically, they will have large battery capacity and the ICE will be small relative to the electric drive motor.<br>
<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=12 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"> <IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">Charge sustaining: these differ in that the on-board ICE and generator are sufficient to keep the batteries charged while the vehicle is in use. The range of the vehicle is thus limited by the amount of fuel it can carry. The vehicle is not dependent on being plugged in overnight, but the ICE does not run all the time either, but only when the batteries need charging. The battery capacity would typically be less than the charge depleting group, but would be sufficient to operate the vehicle for some distance on electrical power alone. Again, most vehicles built so far have been conceived as commuter vehicles.<br>
<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=12 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"> <IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">Reserve sustaining: This type of vehicle operates in hybrid mode at all times and has minimal battery reserves. Typically, the vehicle operates under a strategy that attempts to maximize the performance of electric components while minimizing the pollution from the ICE. Its range is limited by the amount of fuel it can carry, and examples constructed so far have not necessarily been limited to commuter use.<br>
<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
Its clear that the choice of a strategy involves a complex series of tradeoffs, including the classic: power vs. weight. And one cant ignore the inevitable increase in complication over both conventional and electric vehicles.<br>


<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<font size=3><b>Two approaches</b></font><BR>
<IMG align=top vspace=2 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
To illustrate these trade-offs, hybrids of all three types may be serial or parallel:<BR>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=12 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"> <IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">Serial vehicles have the ICE operating a generator which charges batteries which power a large electric motor(s) which drive the wheels. The ICE is not directly connected to the wheels at any time.<br>
<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=12 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"> <IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">Parallel hybrids use both the electric motor and the ICE to drive the wheels: on some vehicles the same wheels, on others, separate drive trains for the front and rear of the vehicle. The electric motor may be smaller than on a serial vehicle.<br>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
All hybrids have some sort of load leveling or energy storage device. This is usually batteries, but other devices used are supercapacitors, flywheels, and hydraulic or pneumatic storage devices. How suitable these may be depend, once again, on the intended use of the vehicle and on its energy strategy.<BR>


</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td><A HREF="hybrid.htm"><IMG align=left BORDER=0 SRC="../cr_gifs/back.gif"></A></td>
<td><br></td>
<td width=480>
<A HREF="hybrid_3.htm"><IMG align=right BORDER=0 SRC="../cr_gifs/forward.gif"></A>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<!-- end of table-->

<IMG align=top align=right vspace=1 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><br>
<IMG align=top align=left width=630 height=5 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_catf.gif"><BR>
<IMG align=top align=right vspace=1 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><br>

<A HREF="../default.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../cr_gifs/cr_home.gif" ALT="Review Homepage"></A>
<A HREF="/catf/default.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../cr_gifs/catfhome.gif" ALT="CATF Homepage"></A>
<A HREF="/default.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../cr_gifs/bcrihome.gif" ALT="BCRI Homepage"></A>
<A HREF="/enviro/cln_tr_s.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../cr_gifs/clean_t.gif" ALT="BCRI Clean Transportation"></A><br>
