<HEAD>
<TITLE>CATF Review Newletter: Issue No. 21 (April, 1995)</TITLE>
<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Word 2.0z Beta>
<META NAME="AUTHOR" CONTENT="Andrea Gomory">
<!-- Last Update: 01/10/96 -->
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#FF0000" VLINK="#8080C0" ALINK="#E629A">
<BASEFONT SIZE=3>

<BODY>
<IMG border=0 SRC="../cr_gifs/catf_pg3.gif"><BR>

<!-- begin table--><!-- total=630 -->
<table border=0 width=630 cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0>

<tr>
<td width=150 valign=top rowspan=1>
<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=6 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG border=0 align=top SRC="../cr_gifs/toc_thin.gif"><BR>
<A HREF="hybrid.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="21toc_1b.gif"></A><br>
<IMG border=0 align=top SRC="../cr_gifs/toc_thik.gif"><BR>
<A HREF="dimethyl.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="21toc_2.gif"></A><br>
<IMG border=0 align=top SRC="../cr_gifs/toc_thik.gif"><BR>
<A HREF="cng_fuel.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="21toc_3.gif"></A><br>
<IMG border=0 align=top SRC="../cr_gifs/toc_thik.gif"><BR>
<A HREF="notes.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="21toc_4.gif"></A><br>
<IMG border=0 align=top SRC="../cr_gifs/toc_thik.gif"><BR>
<A HREF="alt_fuel.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="21toc_5.gif"></A><br>
<IMG border=0 align=top SRC="../cr_gifs/toc_thin.gif"><BR>
</td>


<td valign=top colspan=2 width=480>
<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<font size=3><b>What are the advantages?</b></font><BR>
<IMG align=top vspace=2 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
So what are the advantages of hybrids? First, better range and sometimes higher performance than pure electric vehicles, together with very low emissions. The low emissions result from running a small internal combustion engine within a speed range where efficiency is high and emissions are very low. Many hybrids, true to their electric vehicle heritage, can operate for some distance without using the ICE at all; they are ZEVs for some of the time. This time can be chosen, for example in stop & start city traffic, when the internal combustion engine is hard put to maintain low emissions and at the same time produce adequate acceleration.<BR>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
The hybrid may also require less batteries than a pure electric vehicle. This cuts down weight, which in turn increases performance and/or range, or may reduce the power required. And battery replacement will be cheaper. Hybrids that do not need overnight recharging also will not require the additional electrical utility infrastructure that might be necessitated by widespread use of battery-powered vehicles.<BR>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
The combination of a small gaseous fuelled engine with an efficient electric motor in a hybrid can result in very low net emissions per mile. Yet drivers require not only low emissions, but also adequate range between fuelling stops, adequate power for acceleration, hills, and heavy loads, adequate carrying capacity for passengers and freight, ease and reliability of operation, and low purchase cost (necessitating a simple, easily built and repaired vehicle). The variety of approaches currently evident in the design of hybrids stems largely from different concepts of the relative importance of these sometimes competing factors.<BR>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<font size=3><b>Emissions</b></font><BR>
<IMG align=top vspace=2 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
HEV emissions depend on how much of the vehicles energy is provided by charging batteries from utility power (which has no associated emissions, at least from the vehicle), and how much use is made of the ICE, particularly at non-optimum speeds and loads. Either way, emissions should be well under ULEV levels. Some HEV builders have suggested that a new standard should be created at, say, 1/2 ULEV emission levels.<BR>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<font size=3><b>Range</b></font><BR>
<IMG align=top vspace=2 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
HEV range depends, for the most part, on how much fuel can be carried for the ICE, which we may expect will run at its maximum efficiency much of the time. Add to this range the energy gained by pre-charging the batteries. In any event, range should be better than a ULEV carrying the same amount of fuel, no matter what fuel is used.<BR>




</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td><A HREF="hybrid_2.htm"><IMG align=left BORDER=0 SRC="../cr_gifs/back.gif"></A></td>
<td><br></td>
<td width=480>
<A HREF="hybrid_4.htm"><IMG align=right BORDER=0 SRC="../cr_gifs/forward.gif"></A>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<!-- end of table-->

