<HTML>

<HEAD>
<TITLE>CATF Review Newletter: Issue No. 22 (July, 1995)</TITLE>
<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Word 2.0z Beta>
<META NAME="AUTHOR" CONTENT="Andrea Gomory">
<!-- Last Update: 01/10/96 -->
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#FF0000" VLINK="#8080C0" ALINK="#E629A">
<BASEFONT SIZE=3>

<BODY>
<IMG border=0 SRC="../cr_gifs/catf_pg2.gif"><BR>

<!-- begin table--><!-- total=630 -->
<table border=0 width=630 cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0>

<tr>
<td width=150 valign=top rowspan=1>
<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=6 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG border=0 SRC="../cr_gifs/toc_thin.gif"><BR>
<A HREF="niche.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="22toc_1b.gif"></A><br>
<IMG border=0 SRC="../cr_gifs/toc_thik.gif"><BR>
<A HREF="ballard.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="22toc_2.gif"></A><br>
<IMG border=0 SRC="../cr_gifs/toc_thik.gif"><BR>
<A HREF="online.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="22toc_3.gif"></A><br>
<IMG border=0 SRC="../cr_gifs/toc_thik.gif"><BR>
<A HREF="gotran.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="22toc_4.gif"></A><br>
<IMG border=0 SRC="../cr_gifs/toc_thik.gif"><BR>
<A HREF="students.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="22toc_5.gif"></A><br>
<IMG border=0 SRC="../cr_gifs/toc_thik.gif"><BR>
<A HREF="afv.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="22toc_6.gif"></A><br>
<IMG border=0 SRC="../cr_gifs/toc_thik.gif"><BR>
<A HREF="ngv.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="22toc_7.gif"></A><br>
<IMG border=0 SRC="../cr_gifs/toc_thin.gif"><BR>
<td>

<td valign=top colspan=2 width=480>
<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
The use of some fuels offers advantages to the community or the nation. The effect of larger scale use of some alternative fuels may be significant improvements in air quality, or reduction in
national dependence on imported oil.<BR>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
For these very good reasons, governments mandate the use of alternate fuels, or reward through tax concessions. Some have complained that it's 'not a level playing field' because of 'government interference'. But these legitimate community or national interests are not represented
by any other player, only government.<BR>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
The alternatives range from new and improved types of gasoline to new developments such as DME and hythane.<BR>

<IMG align=top vspace=8 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<font size=3><b>So let's look at the alternative fuelsall of them</b></font><BR>
<IMG align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
Gasoline: Overwhelmingly dominant in supply, distribution, and current use. Not the cheapest of the fuels, but for most users the simplest. Considerable environmental impact, through its refining, distribution, and use. Toxic and easily flammable. Emissions acceptable
under current regulations; further technical developments (close coupled preheated catalysts) may be necessary in future. Distribution structure trending to fewer and larger stations; transport mainly by diesel truck. Pressure for improved emissions performance may result in increased use of oxygenated blends.<BR>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
Reformulated Gasoline: Improved gasoline at increased cost. Will require additional infrastructure unless it replaces one or more of the existing gasoline grades. Other gasoline characteristics
continue to apply; possibly increased use of more expensive crude oil feedstocks, including imported crude.<BR>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
Methanol: Appears in a variety of concentrations, such as M85, which is methanol with 15% gasoline added. Requires separate distribution infrastructure. Costs more than gasoline. Spark ignition engines designed for gasoline may require a number of engineering and materials changes to use it. Methanol mainly comes from processing natural gas with some concomitant energy loss.<BR>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
Ethanol: Essentially the same as methanol except that it is refined from plants (often corn, but other plants may be used). Since ethanol must be transported to refinery sites for blending, high     
costs outside midwest states. Again, requires separate distribution infrastructure, truck transport.<BR>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td><A HREF="niche.htm"><IMG align=left BORDER=0 SRC="../cr_gifs/back.gif"></A></td>
<td><br></td>
<td width=480>
<A HREF="nichepg3.htm"><IMG align=right BORDER=0 SRC="../cr_gifs/forward.gif"></A>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<!-- end of table-->

