<!DOCTYPE HTML"-//IETF//DTD HTML 3.0//EN">
<HTML>

<HEAD>
<TITLE>CATF Review Newletter: Issue No. 22 (July, 1995)</TITLE>
<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Word 2.0z Beta>
<META NAME="AUTHOR" CONTENT="Andrea Gomory">
<!-- Last Update: 01/10/96 -->
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#FF0000" VLINK="#8080C0" ALINK="#E629A">
<BASEFONT SIZE=3>

<BODY>
<IMG border=0 SRC="../cr_gifs/catf_pg3.gif"><BR>

<!-- begin table--><!-- total=600 -->
<table border=0 width=630 cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0>

<tr>
<td width=150 valign=top rowspan=1>
<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=6 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG border=0 align=top SRC="../cr_gifs/toc_thin.gif"><BR>
<A HREF="niche.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="22toc_1b.gif"></A><br>
<IMG border=0 align=top SRC="../cr_gifs/toc_thik.gif"><BR>
<A HREF="ballard.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="22toc_2.gif"></A><br>
<IMG border=0 align=top SRC="../cr_gifs/toc_thik.gif"><BR>
<A HREF="online.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="22toc_3.gif"></A><br>
<IMG border=0 align=top SRC="../cr_gifs/toc_thik.gif"><BR>
<A HREF="gotran.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="22toc_4.gif"></A><br>
<IMG border=0 align=top SRC="../cr_gifs/toc_thik.gif"><BR>
<A HREF="students.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="22toc_5.gif"></A><br>
<IMG border=0 align=top SRC="../cr_gifs/toc_thik.gif"><BR>
<A HREF="afv.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="22toc_6.gif"></A><br>
<IMG border=0 align=top SRC="../cr_gifs/toc_thik.gif"><BR>
<A HREF="ngv.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="22toc_7.gif"></A>
<br><IMG border=0 align=top SRC="../cr_gifs/toc_thin.gif"><BR>
</td>

<td valign=top colspan=2 width=480>
<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
Diesel: Fuel of choice for heavy duty engines; particularly energy efficient. Supply and distribution system well established; transport mainly by diesel truck. Currently 'clean' and low-sulphur diesel are replacing variable grades of diesel available in the past.
Particulate emissions continue to be a problem. Better diesel requires better (and more expensive) feedstocks.<BR>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
Biodiesel: Diesel fuel blended with biologically derived ethyl esters. Still experimental so far as its benefits as a fuel are concerned. Would require separate distribution infrastructure
unless it completely replaced regular diesel. Possibly represents a step beyond 'clean' diesel, probably at increased cost. Questions about adequate supply of additive, also its transportation to refining and blending site.<BR>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
DME: Dimethyl ether. Fuel which produces clean combustion in diesels but for which there is currently no manufacturing or distribution capacity.<BR>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
Hydrogen: Very clean fuel of very low energy density. No infrastructure exists for production, distribution, and bulk storage; because of the low energy density, storing sufficient hydrogen in the vehicle to give it sufficient range is a problem. May well be 'the fuel of the future' because of inherent advantages as far as emissions are concerned, but need for vehicle and storage development and a total lack of any distribution infrastructure make this a non-starter for the time being.<BR>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
Hythane: A mixture of hydrogen and methane. Engine development for this fuel is currently in very early stages. If it does succeed, it will be difficult to develop a fuelling infrastructure.<BR>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
Propane, or Liquefied Petroleum Gas: Propane is used as a gaseous fuel but stored as a liquid at relatively low pressures. It is easy to handle, and makes a good clean automotive fuel. Vehicle
conversions or OEM vehicles are easily available, and relatively inexpensive.<BR>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
Sold all over the continent, propane can be produced as a byproduct either of natural gas scrubbing (in the field) or of refining. It is also used as a petrochemical feedstock. It is distributed primarily by truck or railcar, although sometimes, over long distances,
by pipeline. <BR>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td><A HREF="nichepg2.htm"><IMG align=left BORDER=0 SRC="../cr_gifs/back.gif"></A></td>
<td><br></td>
<td width=480>
<A HREF="nichepg4.htm"><IMG align=right BORDER=0 SRC="../cr_gifs/forward.gif"></A><br>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<!-- end of table-->

<IMG align=top align=right vspace=1 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><br>
<IMG align=top align=left width=630 height=5 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_catf.gif"><BR>
<IMG align=top align=right vspace=1 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><br>

<A HREF="../default.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../cr_gifs/cr_home.gif" ALT="Review Homepage"></A>
<A HREF="/catf/default.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../cr_gifs/catfhome.gif" ALT="CATF Homepage"></A>
<A HREF="/default.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../cr_gifs/bcrihome.gif" ALT="BCRI Homepage"></A>
<A HREF="/enviro/cln_tr_s.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../cr_gifs/clean_t.gif" ALT="BCRI Clean Transportation"></A>
