<HTML>

<HEAD>
<TITLE>CATF Review Newletter: Issue No. 23 (October, 1995)</TITLE>
<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Word 2.0z Beta>
<META NAME="AUTHOR" CONTENT="Andrea Gomory">
<!-- Last Update: 01/10/96 -->
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#FF0000" VLINK="#8080C0" ALINK="#E629A">
<BASEFONT SIZE=3>

<BODY>
<IMG border=0 SRC="../cr_gifs/catf_pg2.gif"><BR>

<!-- begin table--><!-- total=630 -->
<table border=0 width=630 cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0>

<tr>
<td width=150 valign=top rowspan=1>
<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=6 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG border=0 align=top SRC="../cr_gifs/toc_thin.gif"><BR>
<A HREF="hd_lean.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="23toc_1.gif"></A><br>
<IMG border=0 align=top SRC="../cr_gifs/toc_thik.gif"><BR>
<A HREF="LEVs.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="23toc_2b.gif"></A><br>
<IMG border=0 align=top SRC="../cr_gifs/toc_thik.gif"><BR>
<A HREF="Chilling.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="23toc_3.gif"></A><br>
<IMG border=0 align=top SRC="../cr_gifs/toc_thik.gif"><BR>
<A HREF="NGV_pres.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="23toc_4.gif"></A><br>
<IMG border=0 align=top SRC="../cr_gifs/toc_thik.gif"><BR>
<A HREF="CGA_send.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="23toc_5.gif"></A><br>
<IMG border=0 align=top SRC="../cr_gifs/toc_thin.gif"><BR>
</td>

<td valign=top colspan=2 width=480>
<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<font size=3><b>Emissions benefits</b></font><BR>
<IMG align=top vspace=2 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
The study points to reductions in emissions that go with increased fuel efficiency. Drawing on studies that consider the total emissions that result from both production and consumption of the fuel, they conclude that significant reductions can be made in both regulated and greenhouse gas emissions. Canada, they say, gives electric vehicles, which require little marginal power, a particular advantage because so much of its electricity 
is produced from either hydroelectric or nuclear sources. But even for vehicle designs that use internal combustion engines, they conclude that significant reductions in emissions can be gained in the future at little or no 
cost to the consumer.<BR>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
A number of cost studies cited in the report indicate 
that the actual vehicle purchase cost disadvantage, even today, can be offset over the vehicle lifetime by reduced operating costs. Future cost premiums for LEVs and ZEVs will, they conclude, represent a small percentage of the vehicle price. Many of the cost premiums that have been quoted, they feel, have been due to inefficient, very low volume manufacture.<BR>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
The authors feel that Canada could, through policies encouraging the use of 
LEVs and ZEVs, both add significantly to production volumes, and take advantage of 
the technology development costs which manufacturers have already incurred in order to satisfy mandates in California and other states.<BR>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=8 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<font size=3><b>Special Canadian conditions</b></font><BR>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
The authors refuse to accept either that Canadian regulations make it uneconomic to produce special vehicles for Canada, or that the dreaded Canadian winter would render these vehicles unusable.<BR>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
First, the regulations. The study points out that, in fact, the differences between Canadian and U.S. safety requirements are not particularly significant. Some are rather obvious, such as metric labeling and speedometers in kph, but they clearly feel that these would be no barrier to the sort of flexible, small volume manufacturers which are found in the emerging specialty ZEV market. The report notes that a large number of specialty (and not so specialty) automobiles currently sell less than 1,000 units a year in Canada, yet these manufacturers remain in the Canadian market.<BR>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
Second, the climate. Canadians, they say, mostly live within a hundred miles of the US border, so the climate cant be all that different. It may not be California, but New York and Massachusetts, two states currently debating ZEV mandates, arent all that tropical in the winter either.<BR>

</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td><A HREF="LEVs.htm"><IMG align=left BORDER=0 SRC="../cr_gifs/back.gif"></A></td>
<td><br></td>
<td width=480>
<A HREF="LEVs_pg3.htm"><IMG align=right BORDER=0 SRC="../cr_gifs/forward.gif"></A>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<!-- end of table-->

<IMG align=top align=right vspace=1 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><br>
<IMG align=top align=left width=630 height=5 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_catf.gif"><BR>
<IMG align=top align=right vspace=1 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><br>

<A HREF="../default.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../cr_gifs/cr_home.gif" ALT="Review Homepage"></A>
<A HREF="/catf/default.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../cr_gifs/catfhome.gif" ALT="CATF Homepage"></A>
<A HREF="/default.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../cr_gifs/bcrihome.gif" ALT="BCRI Homepage"></A>
<A HREF="/enviro/cln_tr_s.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../cr_gifs/clean_t.gif" ALT="BCRI Clean Transportation"></A>
