</DOCHDR>
<!DOCTYPE HTML"-//IETF//DTD HTML 3.0//EN">
<HTML>

<HEAD>
<TITLE>CATF Review Newletter: Issue No. 27 (October, 1996)</TITLE>
<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Word 2.0z Beta>
<META NAME="AUTHOR" CONTENT="Andrea Gomory">
<!-- Last Update: 10/11/96 -->
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#FF0000" VLINK="#8080C0" ALINK="#E629A">
<BASEFONT SIZE=3>

<BODY>
<IMG border=0 SRC="../cr_gifs/catf_pg2.gif"><BR>

<!-- begin table--><!-- total=630 -->
<table border=0 width=630 cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0>

<tr>
<td width=150 valign=top rowspan=1>
<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=6 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG border=0 align=top SRC="../cr_gifs/toc_thin.gif"><BR>
<A HREF="geo.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="27toc_1.gif"></A><br>
<IMG border=0 align=top SRC="../cr_gifs/toc_thik.gif"><BR>
<A HREF="after.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="27toc_2b.gif"></A><br>
<IMG border=0 align=top SRC="../cr_gifs/toc_thik.gif"><BR>
<A HREF="cummins.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="27toc_3.gif"></A><br>
<IMG border=0 align=top SRC="../cr_gifs/toc_thin.gif"><BR>
<td>

<td valign=top colspan=2 width=480>
<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<font size=3><b>A shortage of resources</b></font><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
Some of the reasons for this technological lag are not difficult to identify. First, it's clear that the aftermarket companies don't have the resources needed to carry out this development. The OEMs do, and in fact, engine management systems have been the main focus of their R&D over the last ten years. They are driven by the absolute necessity, for their survival, to meet US federal, California, and Canadian MOT emission regulations. Until recently, aftermarket conversions have not been required to meet these standards. But now they must.<br>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<font size=3><b>Losing the inherent advantage</b></font><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
If the gaseous fuels are going to meet equivalent standards, they must use technology of equivalent sophistication. In the seventies and the early eighties, gaseous fuels had an inherent advantage in emission testing: during the cold start part of the test, they didnt require enrichment like gasoline. But that advantage has gone; gasoline vehicles with fuel injection operate with an absolute minimum of enrichment; computer controlled cold start routines ensure optimum burning and early light-off of the catalytic converter. The gasoline vehicles get better all the time.<BR>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<font size=3><b>Reverse engineering</b></font><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
A second reason for the technological lag is the problem of reverse engineering. OEMs have, with few exceptions, made available little information about their engine control electronics. This means that aftermarket product development teams, in developing accessory electronics that will translate the outputs from the OEM ECMs to signals that can be used to control gaseous fuel systems, have to divine the logic used by the OEM by testing ECM behaviour under a wide variety of engine conditions. As the OEM ECM becomes more sophisticated, this type of reverse engineering becomes more difficult, more time consuming, and more expensive.<BR>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
Even when the aftermarket team have it all figured out, they have to design their own plug in accessory electronics that will ensure that all the functions of the OEM ECM are retained. This can be difficult when dealing with the OBDII requirements, where a single slip can result in false signals.<BR>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
And all this work has to be carried out in time to market the conversion while vehicles of the current model year are still being sold.<BR>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
Elsewhere in this issue, there is a report on the development of a natural gas Geo Metro in which the OEM manufacturer, Suzuki, developed a gaseous fuels version of their original ECM. No reverse engineering was necessary. No rewiring or additional electronic components are needed for the conversion. The advantages in terms of simplification and cost reduction for the conversion are obvious.<BR>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<font size=3><b>Fuel injectiona must</b></font><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
A third problem is fuel injection. Gaseous fuel injectors must be substituted for the gasoline injectors; this would make it very difficult to do bi-fuel conversions, with the option of switching back to gasoline (particularly a problem on natural gas, where CNG tank range may be an operationally limiting factor). These gaseous injectors have only recently become available; they require precise specifications differing from engine family to engine family; and they may also require more precise control of fuel pressure than was necessary for gaseous fuel carburetion. On propane, there is the option of liquid injection. Recent truck engine research at BC Research Inc. (BCRI) indicated that this could be superior.<BR>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
The development of these gaseous injection systems is no longer brand new technology, but it takes time and effort. Once again, for a relatively small aftermarket equipment company to carry out this development for a number of engine platforms, the sales revenue may not cover the development cost.<BR>

</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td><A HREF="after.htm"><IMG align=left BORDER=0 SRC="../cr_gifs/back.gif"></A></td>
<td><br></td>
<td width=480>
<A HREF="afterpg3.htm"><IMG align=right BORDER=0 SRC="../cr_gifs/forward.gif"></A>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<!-- end of table-->

<IMG align=top align=right vspace=1 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><br>
<IMG align=top align=left width=630 height=5 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_catf.gif"><BR>
<IMG align=top align=right vspace=1 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><br>

<A HREF="../default.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../cr_gifs/cr_home.gif" ALT="Review Homepage"></A>
<A HREF="/catf/default.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../cr_gifs/catfhome.gif" ALT="CATF Homepage"></A>
<A HREF="/default.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../cr_gifs/bcrihome.gif" ALT="BCRI Homepage"></A>
<A HREF="/enviro/cln_tr_s.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../cr_gifs/clean_t.gif" ALT="BCRI Clean Transportation"></A>
<p>
<FONT SIZE=1>
The CATF Review is published by:<p>
BCRI<br>
3650 Wesbrook Mall, Vancouver, B.C. Canada V6S 2L2<BR>
CDN (604) 224-4331  fax (604) 224-0540<BR>
USA (360) 738-0958  fax (360) 733-3590<p>

Editor: Patrick Brown<p>

Email your comments to <A HREF="mailto:ainglis@bcr.bc.ca">ainglis@bcr.bc.ca</A><p>

<A href=/Copyrite.htm>&copy; Copyright 1996 BC Research Inc.</A><BR>
</FONT>
</BODY>
</HTML>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>WT04-B17-122</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA006-000056-B016-324</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://www.bcr.bc.ca:80/catf/review/issue_27/afterpg3.htm 204.191.240.6 19970221190006 text/html 8902
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Date: Fri, 21 Feb 1997 19:00:26 GMT
Server: WebSitePro/1.1g (S/N WPO-22E6)
Accept-ranges: bytes
Content-type: text/html
Last-modified: Mon, 17 Feb 1997 23:43:24 GMT
Content-length: 8691
</DOCHDR>
<!DOCTYPE HTML"-//IETF//DTD HTML 3.0//EN">
<HTML>

<HEAD>
<TITLE>CATF Review Newletter: Issue No. 27 (October, 1996)</TITLE>
<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Word 2.0z Beta>
<META NAME="AUTHOR" CONTENT="Andrea Gomory">
<!-- Last Update: 10/11/96 -->
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#FF0000" VLINK="#8080C0" ALINK="#E629A">
<BASEFONT SIZE=3>

<BODY>
<IMG border=0 SRC="../cr_gifs/catf_pg3.gif"><BR>

<!-- begin table--><!-- total=630 -->
<table border=0 width=630 cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0>

<tr>
<td width=150 valign=top rowspan=1>
<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=6 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG border=0 align=top SRC="../cr_gifs/toc_thin.gif"><BR>
<A HREF="geo.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="27toc_1.gif"></A><br>
<IMG border=0 align=top SRC="../cr_gifs/toc_thik.gif"><BR>
<A HREF="after.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="27toc_2b.gif"></A><br>
<IMG border=0 align=top SRC="../cr_gifs/toc_thik.gif"><BR>
<A HREF="cummins.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="27toc_3.gif"></A><br>
<IMG border=0 align=top SRC="../cr_gifs/toc_thin.gif"><BR>
<td>

<td valign=top colspan=2 width=480>
<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<font size=3><b>Cost</b></font><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
This brings us to the escalating cost of gaseous fuel conversions. The cost of R&D must be covered; the manufacturing costs of sophisticated electronics and fuel injection systems are greater than the mixers that the industry previously used. There are two possible results: first, that manufacturers will only develop conversions for those engine platforms where significant sales can be expected; second, that the conversions will cost moreit will take longer to recover conversion costs from fuel savings, and so customers will only convert vehicles which use a lot of fuel.<br>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<font size=3><b>Sharpening the marketing focus</b></font><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
So whats the probable result? Inevitably,  a sharpening of marketing focus. Conversions will only be available for a limited number of engine platforms. Customers will only convert vehicles that use enough fuel to ensure an early payout of conversion costs. Conversion manufacturers and gaseous fuel marketers will concentrate on specific customers for whom high quality conversions are available and the economics are clearly favourable. These customers will likely convert current year vehicles.<BR>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
We may also see certain manufacturers concentrate on conversions for certain platforms, and ignore others. This would be the result of a conscious decision to optimize the return for a limited amount of R&D investment and manufacturing capital. So, specialization is another possible result.<BR>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
Some manufacturers may decide that the North American market requires too much new investment to remain competitive. With demand for alternative fuel vehicles increasing in the third world where emission regulations are not so strict and often nonexistent, a better corporate strategy may be to stay with the existing technology and market it aggressively overseas.<BR>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
Such a strategy would make it difficult to return to the North American market as long as the present pace of technological development in the automotive industry continues.<BR>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
A manufacturer may also choose to abandon the aftermarket in favour of gaseous fuel conversion development for an OEM. Chrysler, General Motors, and Ford (through their QVM program) have all marketed gaseous fuel vehicles over the last few years. Its notable that the OEM vehicles have shown generally good performance and excellent emissions results, but they have not been enthusiastically marketed. At press time, Chrysler had suspended their natural gas program, GM had made no new commitments, and Ford was only marketing Crown Victorias, primarily for the police car market.<BR>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
Recent OEM gaseous fuel vehicles have shown a superior technological standard, although they cost a lot more and have not been without teething troubles. OEMs have spent the money, however, to carry out R&D to produce vehicles which match the standard they have reached with gasoline vehicles in recent years. They also face additional development costs, such as for crash testing, that the aftermarket is not presently required to incur.<BR>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
That said, the question for an OEM is whether to invest in alternative fuel development in the expectation of gaining additional market share in markets mandated by government, or whether to put its R&D investment into the improvement of/or cost reduction in all the vehicles the OEM sells. Its a difficult financial and strategic decision, and it may account for the somewhat ambivalent attitude that all the OEMs seem to be taking towards alternative fuel vehicles today.<BR>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<font size=3><b>A continuing need for the aftermarket</b></font><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
Of course, the OEMs, with their emphasis on mass production and offering of standard vehicles, cannot meet the total demand for gaseous fuel vehicles anyway. A significant number of such vehicles are specialized. From the customers point of view, his best strategy is to order the specialized vehicles he needs and then have them converted.<BR>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
So there is a continuing need for the aftermarket, but the aftermarket faces declining ability to deliver economical conversions, particularly on the latest technology vehicles.<BR>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<font size=3><b>One solution</b></font><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
A greater level of cooperation between the OEMs and the alternative fuel equipment manufacturers might lead to a win-win situation. Possibly the Geo Metro/Suzuki Swift project points the way. The participation of the Suzuki R&D people in the reprogramming of the standard ECM has eliminated the usual reverse engineering and enabled both Suzuki and the natural gas industry to offer a current technology vehicle at a low cost suitable for a new niche market.<BR>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
This is the kind of idea that could change the structure of the aftermarket and give new growth to the gaseous fuels fleet.<BR>

</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td><A HREF="afterpg2.htm"><IMG align=left BORDER=0 SRC="../cr_gifs/back.gif"></A></td>
<td><br></td>
<td width=480>
<br>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<!-- end of table-->

