<!DOCTYPE HTML"-//IETF//DTD HTML 3.0//EN">
<HTML>

<HEAD>
<TITLE>CATF Review Newletter: Issue No. 23 (October, 1995)</TITLE>
<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Word 2.0z Beta>
<META NAME="AUTHOR" CONTENT="Andrea Gomory">
<!-- Last Update: 01/10/96 -->
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#FF0000" VLINK="#8080C0" ALINK="#E629A">
<BASEFONT SIZE=3>

<BODY>
<IMG border=0 SRC="../cr_gifs/catf_pg2.gif"><BR>

<!-- begin table--><!-- total=630 -->
<table border=0 width=630 cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0>

<tr>
<td width=150 valign=top rowspan=1>
<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=6 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG border=0 align=top SRC="../cr_gifs/toc_thin.gif"><BR>
<A HREF="hd_lean.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="23toc_1.gif"></A><br>
<IMG border=0 align=top SRC="../cr_gifs/toc_thik.gif"><BR>
<A HREF="LEVs.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="23toc_2.gif"></A><br>
<IMG border=0 align=top SRC="../cr_gifs/toc_thik.gif"><BR>
<A HREF="Chilling.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="23toc_3b.gif"></A><br>
<IMG border=0 align=top SRC="../cr_gifs/toc_thik.gif"><BR>
<A HREF="NGV_pres.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="23toc_4.gif"></A><br>
<IMG border=0 align=top SRC="../cr_gifs/toc_thik.gif"><BR>
<A HREF="CGA_send.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="23toc_5.gif"></A><br>
<IMG border=0 align=top SRC="../cr_gifs/toc_thin.gif"><BR>
</td>

<td valign=top colspan=2 width=480>
<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<font size=3><b>New looks at an old problem</b></font><BR>
<IMG align=top vspace=2 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
The University of Victoria team have identified several novel refrigeration technologies which appear to have the potential for use on-site in a relatively small LNG/CNG fuelling station. One of these is an Orifice Pulse Tube liquefier, which utilizes a reciprocating piston in a cylinder to push the working gas past a regenerator and a cold heat exchanger to a pulse tube. At the upper end of the pulse tube is a hot heat exchanger, utilizing water as the cooling medium, and a small orifice leading to a ballast tank.<BR>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
The reverse cycle of the piston pulls the working gas back through the system. The orifice restricts flow resulting in expansion and thus further cooling of the working gas. The cold heat exchanger is used to cool and liquefy incoming gaseous methane to make LNG, which then accumulates to further cool the cold end of the pulse tube.<BR>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
According to Dr. Barclay, this simple technology has the advantages of having no cold moving parts (only the working gas is moving), high reliability, and being inexpensive to manufacture.<BR>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
A second technology being explored by the University of Victoria group involves active magnetic regeneration (AMR) and utilizes the magnetocaloric effect: when magnetic materials are magnetized and demagnetized adiabatically, they experience a temperature change. In the case of a magnetic liquefier, a heat-transfer fluid (helium) is circulated through a wheel of magnetic material. On one side of the wheel, a superconducting magnet is used to create a temperature differential which transfers heat from the cold side transfer fluid to the hot side transfer fluid, where it is continuously pumped to a heat exchanger. This heat exchanger is used to cool the fluid, thus exhausting heat to the environment.<BR>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
On the cold side, the helium is cooled to a temperature lower than the liquefaction point of natural gas, thus enabling liquefaction by simple heat exchange.<BR>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
This technology is more efficient than pulse tube, but is more complex and has more moving parts.<BR>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=8 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<font size=3><b>More technologies</b></font><BR>
<IMG align=top vspace=2 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
Dr. Barclay and his team have more ideas up their collective sleeve, but they are keeping them quiet for now. One of these, they feel, may well be the breakthrough which would make CNG/LNG fuelling stations, and thus natural gas vehicles, more economic for many fleets.<BR>


</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td><A HREF="Chilling.htm"><IMG align=left BORDER=0 SRC="../cr_gifs/back.gif"></A></td>
<td><br></td>
<td width=480><br></td>
</tr>
</table>
<!-- end of table-->

