<HEAD>
<TITLE>CATF Review Newletter: Issue No. 20 (January, 1995)</TITLE>
<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Word 2.0z Beta>
<META NAME="AUTHOR" CONTENT="Andrea Gomory">
<!-- Last Update: 01/10/96 -->
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#FF0000" VLINK="#8080C0" ALINK="#E629A">
<BASEFONT SIZE=3>

<BODY>
<IMG border=0 SRC="../cr_gifs/catf_pg2.gif"><BR>

<!-- begin table--><!-- total=630 -->
<table border=0 width=630 cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0>

<tr>
<td width=150 valign=top rowspan=1>
<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=6 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG border=0 align=top SRC="../cr_gifs/toc_thin.gif"><BR>
<A HREF="cummins.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="20toc_1.gif"></A><br>
<IMG border=0 align=top SRC="../cr_gifs/toc_thik.gif"><BR>
<A HREF="ngvmark.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="20toc_2.gif"></A><br>
<IMG border=0 align=top SRC="../cr_gifs/toc_thik.gif"><BR>
<A HREF="promise.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="20toc_3b.gif"></A><br>
<IMG border=0 align=top SRC="../cr_gifs/toc_thik.gif"><BR>
<A HREF="Arizona.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="20toc_4.gif"></A><br>
<IMG border=0 align=top SRC="../cr_gifs/toc_thik.gif"><BR>
<A HREF="gas_car.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="20toc_5.gif"></A><br>
<IMG border=0 align=top SRC="../cr_gifs/toc_thin.gif"><BR>
</td>

<td valign=top colspan=2 width=480>
<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<font size=3><b>Energy storage density</b></font><BR>
<IMG align=top vspace=2 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
Energy storage density is the Achilles heel of the natural gas vehicle. Compressing the gas to 3000 or 3600 psi means bulky storage cylinders, high pressure plumbing, and four stage fuelling compressors; the cost of energy used for compression can equal the cost of the natural gas.<BR>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
So the potential of adsorbents for vehicle natural gas storage comes from their ability to store large quantities of natural gas at relatively low pressures. Research has been concentrated on improving the energy storage density of the adsorbents.<BR>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
Adsorbents have the greatest volume advantage over compressed gas at pressures around 4 MPa (500 psi), when the adsorbent will store about four times the quantity of gas that could be stored at the same pressure in an empty container. At these pressures, the vehicle could be fuelled using a two stage compressor, using much less energy, and the adsorbent container need not be cylindrical. In other words, it could be shaped to suit the vehicle design, so there is potential for greater fuel storage without intrusion into the mechanical and cargo-carrying parts of the vehicle. Of course, a low-pressure adsorbent equipped vehicle could be fuelled at a conventional high pressure CNG station provided it was equipped with a pressure reduction device.<BR>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=8 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<font size=3><b>Groups reach their target</b></font><BR>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
Two groups working on activated carbons report that they have achieved their target of developing a material which will store 150 volumes of natural gas at 25 deg. C. and 3.5 MPa. This is a volume ratio that is achieved with compressed gas at a pressure of around 13 MPa, or a little over 2000 psi.<BR>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
One group is the Atlanta Gas Light Adsorbent Research Group (AGLARG), which includes the Atlanta Gas Light Co., British Gas, Sutcliffe Speakman Carbons, Amoco, Pacific Gas & Electric, Consumers Gas, the Gas Research Institute, and the Northern Illinois Public Service Co. The group is funding work at Cataraqui Research Associates, in Kingston, Ontario. The second group is a consortium of  CANMET, the Hydrogen Research Institute of the University of Quebec at Trois Rivires, the Natural Gas Technologies Centre of Gaz Metropolitain, and FRE Composites.<BR>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
The Atlanta group have developed a cellular extruded aluminum storage container into which sticks of adsorbent can be fitted. They are currently working on production engineering to make larger quantities of their adsorbent and move the cost down from the currently estimated $5 per lb. to around $2. The CANMET group have not yet released the results of their current testing.<BR>


</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td><A HREF="promise.htm"><IMG align=left BORDER=0 SRC="../cr_gifs/back.gif"></A></td>
<td><br></td>
<td width=480>
<A HREF="promise3.htm"><IMG align=right BORDER=0 SRC="../cr_gifs/forward.gif"></A>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<!-- end of table-->

<IMG align=top align=right vspace=1 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><br>
<IMG align=top align=left width=630 height=5 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_catf.gif"><BR>
<IMG align=top align=right vspace=1 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><br>

<A HREF="../default.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../cr_gifs/cr_home.gif" ALT="Review Homepage"></A>
