<HTML>

<HEAD>
<TITLE>CATF Review Newletter: Issue No. 20 (January, 1995)</TITLE>
<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Word 2.0z Beta>
<META NAME="AUTHOR" CONTENT="Andrea Gomory">
<!-- Last Update: 01/10/96 -->
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#FF0000" VLINK="#8080C0" ALINK="#E629A">
<BASEFONT SIZE=3>

<BODY>
<IMG border=0 SRC="../cr_gifs/catf_pg3.gif"><BR>

<!-- begin table--><!-- total=630 -->
<table border=0 width=630 cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0>

<tr>
<td width=150 valign=top rowspan=1>
<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=6 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG border=0 align=top SRC="../cr_gifs/toc_thin.gif"><BR>
<A HREF="cummins.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="20toc_1.gif"></A><br>
<IMG border=0 align=top SRC="../cr_gifs/toc_thik.gif"><BR>
<A HREF="ngvmark.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="20toc_2.gif"></A><br>
<IMG border=0 align=top SRC="../cr_gifs/toc_thik.gif"><BR>
<A HREF="promise.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="20toc_3b.gif"></A><br>
<IMG border=0 align=top SRC="../cr_gifs/toc_thik.gif"><BR>
<A HREF="Arizona.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="20toc_4.gif"></A><br>
<IMG border=0 align=top SRC="../cr_gifs/toc_thik.gif"><BR>
<A HREF="gas_car.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="20toc_5.gif"></A><br>
<IMG border=0 align=top SRC="../cr_gifs/toc_thin.gif"><BR>
</td>

<td valign=top colspan=2 width=480>
<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=8 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<font size=3><b>Still some problems to overcome</b></font><BR>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
Cost is not the only factor which will determine whether adsorbents will, in the end, prove practical. While the adsorbent can be fuelled at lower pressures, the fuelling produces heat, which slows fuelling. And, with some adsorbents, not all the fuel that goes into the pores can be retrieved at low pressures. Contaminants in the natural gas can plug up the adsorbent. The Atlanta group suggests a front end adsorbent filter cartridge.<BR>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
Another consideration is weight. Adsorbent containers, designed for lower pressures than CNG cylinders, weigh less. But the adsorbent itself, a solid carbon, presently weighs about .8lb per litre.  If we compare the weight of modern carbon-fibre CNG cylinders  with their energy equivalent in a full steel gasoline tank, we see that the CNG cylinders are becoming weight-competitive. It remains to be seen whether containers of adsorbent will land in the same weight ballpark.<BR>

</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td><A HREF="promise2.htm"><IMG align=left BORDER=0 SRC="../cr_gifs/back.gif"></A></td>
<td><br></td>
<td width=480><br>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<!-- end of table-->

