<HTML>

<HEAD>
<TITLE>CATF Review Newletter: Issue No. 20 (January, 1995)</TITLE>
<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Word 2.0z Beta>
<META NAME="AUTHOR" CONTENT="Andrea Gomory">
<!-- Last Update: 01/10/96 -->
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#FF0000" VLINK="#8080C0" ALINK="#E629A">
<BASEFONT SIZE=3>

<BODY>
<IMG border=0 SRC="../cr_gifs/catf_pg2.gif"><BR>

<!-- begin table--><!-- total=630 -->
<table border=0 width=630 cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0>

<tr>
<td width=150 valign=top rowspan=1>
<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=6 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG border=0 align=top SRC="../cr_gifs/toc_thin.gif"><BR>
<A HREF="cummins.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="20toc_1.gif"></A><br>
<IMG border=0 align=top SRC="../cr_gifs/toc_thik.gif"><BR>
<A HREF="ngvmark.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="20toc_2b.gif"></A><br>
<IMG border=0 align=top SRC="../cr_gifs/toc_thik.gif"><BR>
<A HREF="promise.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="20toc_3.gif"></A><br>
<IMG border=0 align=top SRC="../cr_gifs/toc_thik.gif"><BR>
<A HREF="Arizona.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="20toc_4.gif"></A><br>
<IMG border=0 align=top SRC="../cr_gifs/toc_thik.gif"><BR>
<A HREF="gas_car.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="20toc_5.gif"></A><br>
<IMG border=0 align=top SRC="../cr_gifs/toc_thin.gif"><BR>
</td>

<td valign=top colspan=2 width=480>
<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<font size=3><b>Who pays the front end costs?</b></font><BR>
<IMG align=top vspace=2 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
While compressed natural gas itself may be cheaper than gasoline, its adoption involves front end capital costs, both for the vehicle owner and the station operator. The user looks to either government or his local NGDC to assist.<BR>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
The rule of thumb in northern parts of the continent is that a vehicle uses as much natural gas as a house. NGDCs often expend substantial amounts of their own capital installing pipeline distribution systems to secure homeowners as committed customers. Should they be prepared to invest similar amounts in order to secure the commitment of vehicle operators? And who should finance the investment: the NGV users, the existing customer base, or the shareholders?<BR>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
Some Public Utility regulating bodies have opposed investment by NGDCs to develop the NGV market. Existing natural gas customers should not be required to subsidize such market growth, they say.<BR>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
Shareholders may support such investment, or they may view it as carrying substantially greater risk than other gas utility investments, and thus less desirable. And if there is a greater risk, should there not also be a greater return? <BR>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
Some oil companies, while admitting their interest in selling compressed natural gas through their own retailing stations, say that regulated NGDCs should not be able to include their NGV market investments in their rate base, and thus in their regulated prices. This, they say, is unfair competition with unregulated gasoline marketers. Gas company executives point out that oil companies include their market development costs in their prices.<BR>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
Some NGDCs have been able to rate base their investments in the market, and some have not. Some have spent non-rate-base money. Some have chosen to encourage third parties to provide infrastructure financing. And as more NGDCs get into the market, there will be more different combinations.<BR>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=8 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<font size=3><b>How are they paid?</b></font><BR>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
So the chicken and egg problem, combined with the need for front end capital investment for infrastructure and vehicles, has led to some interesting schemes. We can measure these schemes against the approaches described above. Some examples:<BR>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=12 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"> <IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">Grants to vehicle purchasers or converters, and to builders of fuelling stations. A NGDC could look upon grants as an investment, with the return from future natural gas sales profits. Subsidies can be used to accelerate conversions or purchases and station construction, thus driving the market beyond chicken/egg uncertainty to the point where it is self sustaining.<br>
<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>

<IMG align=top hspace=12 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"> <IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">a gas utility may lend funds for vehicle acquisition or fuelling station construction. It will otherwise be difficult for smaller businesses or individuals to obtain loans for these purposes, and so this in itself may be an incentive, but the individual who must pay the loan back must perceive that the costs will be covered by fuel cost savings. Otherwise, why participate in such a program?<br>

</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td><A HREF="ngvmark.htm"><IMG align=left BORDER=0 SRC="../cr_gifs/back.gif"></A></td>
<td><br></td>
<td width=480>
<A HREF="ngvmark3.htm"><IMG align=right BORDER=0 SRC="../cr_gifs/forward.gif"></A>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<!-- end of table-->

<IMG align=top align=right vspace=1 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><br>
<IMG align=top align=left width=630 height=5 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_catf.gif"><BR>
<IMG align=top align=right vspace=1 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><br>

<A HREF="../default.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../cr_gifs/cr_home.gif" ALT="Review Homepage"></A>
<A HREF="/catf/default.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../cr_gifs/catfhome.gif" ALT="CATF Homepage"></A>
<A HREF="/default.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../cr_gifs/bcrihome.gif" ALT="BCRI Homepage"></A>
<A HREF="/enviro/cln_tr_s.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../cr_gifs/clean_t.gif" ALT="BCRI Clean Transportation"></A>
<p>
<FONT SIZE=1>
The CATF Review is published by:<p>
BCRI<br>
3650 Wesbrook Mall, Vancouver, B.C. Canada V6S 2L2<BR>
CDN (604) 224-4331  fax (604) 224-0540<BR>
USA (360) 738-0958  fax (360) 733-3590<p>

Editor: Patrick Brown<p>

Email your comments to <A HREF="mailto:ainglis@bcr.bc.ca">ainglis@bcr.bc.ca</A><p>

