</DOCHDR>
<!DOCTYPE HTML"-//IETF//DTD HTML 3.0//EN">
<HTML>

<HEAD>
<TITLE>CATF Review Newletter: Issue No. 20 (January, 1995)</TITLE>
<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Word 2.0z Beta>
<META NAME="AUTHOR" CONTENT="Andrea Gomory">
<!-- Last Update: 01/10/96 -->
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#FF0000" VLINK="#8080C0" ALINK="#E629A">
<BASEFONT SIZE=3>

<BODY>
<IMG border=0 SRC="../cr_gifs/catf_pg3.gif"><BR>

<!-- begin table--><!-- total=630 -->
<table border=0 width=630 cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0>

<tr>
<td width=150 valign=top rowspan=1>
<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=6 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG border=0 align=top SRC="../cr_gifs/toc_thin.gif"><BR>
<A HREF="cummins.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="20toc_1.gif"></A><br>
<IMG border=0 align=top SRC="../cr_gifs/toc_thik.gif"><BR>
<A HREF="ngvmark.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="20toc_2b.gif"></A><br>
<IMG border=0 align=top SRC="../cr_gifs/toc_thik.gif"><BR>
<A HREF="promise.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="20toc_3.gif"></A><br>
<IMG border=0 align=top SRC="../cr_gifs/toc_thik.gif"><BR>
<A HREF="Arizona.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="20toc_4.gif"></A><br>
<IMG border=0 align=top SRC="../cr_gifs/toc_thik.gif"><BR>
<A HREF="gas_car.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="20toc_5.gif"></A><br>
<IMG border=0 align=top SRC="../cr_gifs/toc_thin.gif"><BR>
</td>

<td valign=top colspan=2 width=480>
<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=12 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"> <IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">Preferential gas rates: generally, the cost of natural gas will be less than diesel or gasoline, if only because of preferential treatment of fuel taxes. These savings may be made even more attractive by providing a special price to either vehicle users or to fuelling stations. Such special price arrangements are often made with commercial or industrial gas users, or special volume or demand based rates are established, and approved by regulators. However, someregulators may not see this as fair to other users.<br>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=12 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"> <IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">Some NGDCs have made direct capital investments in infrastructure. Often this takes the form of constructing stations, or joint venturing with others in their establishment. They are thus competing directly with other fuels in the vehicle market.<br>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=8 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<font size=3><b>A six year plan</b></font><BR>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
One most interesting approach has been put forward by the Southern California Gas Company, which services Los Angeles. Recognising that the purpose of the company is primarily to supply gas to customers at competitive prices, but also faced with a legislative mandate to put forward a six year program to develop the NGV market, SoCal has designed a business plan which gets the company into the fuel retailing market, and then out of it, within six years.<BR>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
The plan provides for SoCal to build a total of 150 fuelling stations (59 have already been built) and sell them to private enterprise at the end of the six years, or earlier. (At the same time, SoCal expects others to build a further 450 stations.) In the end, SoCal should have minimal rate base investment in NGVs, but should have started a market for the private sector.<BR>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
The plan has been under consideration by the regulatory authorities for the past year; SoCal has proposed that the cost of the capital required be incorporated in the overall rate structure, with a payback (and consequent reduction in rates) at the end of the program. A regulatory decision on this is expected in the spring of 1995.<BR>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=8 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<font size=3><b>The importance of public trust</b></font><BR>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
Experience in New Zealand and Canada has shown that, in order to create an NGV market which will be sustainable in the long term, initial investments must be accompanied by a clear long term commitment to fuel availability and stable fuel prices and taxes. Gas distribution companies have, by and large, provided stable fuel prices.<BR>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
This commitment is important because investments made by individuals and businesses in the NGV market have payout times which may well exceed the term of office of the present government, or of the Public Utility Board office holders.<BR>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
The legislation intended to improve air quality is very widely supported. The natural gas distribution companies have an obvious and logical interest in making the necessary investments in initial infrastructure and market development.<br>
<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
Regulators should allow them to match their initiative to their commitment. Their success is in everyones interest.

</td>
</tr>

