<!DOCTYPE HTML"-//IETF//DTD HTML 3.0//EN">
<HTML>

<HEAD>
<TITLE>CATF Review Newletter: Issue No. 22 (July, 1995)</TITLE>
<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Word 2.0z Beta>
<META NAME="AUTHOR" CONTENT="Andrea Gomory">
<!-- Last Update: 01/10/96 -->
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#FF0000" VLINK="#8080C0" ALINK="#E629A">
<BASEFONT SIZE=3>

<BODY>
<IMG border=0 SRC="../cr_gifs/catf_pg2.gif"><BR>

<!-- begin table--><!-- total=600 -->
<table border=0 width=630 cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0>
<tr>
<td width=150 valign=top rowspan=1>
<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=6 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG border=0 SRC="../cr_gifs/toc_thin.gif"><BR>
<A HREF="niche.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="22toc_1.gif"></A><br>
<IMG border=0 SRC="../cr_gifs/toc_thik.gif"><BR>
<A HREF="ballard.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="22toc_2b.gif"></A><br>
<IMG border=0 SRC="../cr_gifs/toc_thik.gif"><BR>
<A HREF="online.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="22toc_3.gif"></A><br>
<IMG border=0 SRC="../cr_gifs/toc_thik.gif"><BR>
<A HREF="gotran.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="22toc_4.gif"></A><br>
<IMG border=0 SRC="../cr_gifs/toc_thik.gif"><BR>
<A HREF="students.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="22toc_5.gif"></A><br>
<IMG border=0 SRC="../cr_gifs/toc_thik.gif"><BR>
<A HREF="afv.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="22toc_6.gif"></A><br>
<IMG border=0 SRC="../cr_gifs/toc_thik.gif"><BR>
<A HREF="ngv.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="22toc_7.gif"></A><br>
<IMG border=0 SRC="../cr_gifs/toc_thin.gif"><BR>
<td>

<td valign=top colspan=2 width=480>
<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
How does the PEM fuel cell work? Basically, gaseous hydrogen and oxygen are introduced to either side of a platinum catalysed membrane, and the protons from the hydrogen pass through the membrane to the oxygen side, producing water, heat, and an electrical potential between each side. Each individual cell consists of a sandwich about nine inches square and half an inch thick consisting of an anode, a cathode, distribution plates to provide air and hydrogen under low positive pressure to either side of the membrane, and the catalysed membrane itself. Each fuel cell produces about one volt, and so they are stacked together in banks and connected to manifolding which supplies hydrogen and oxygen, and removes water and unused air.<BR>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
So electricity is produced without any moving parts, but various electrically powered pumps and compressors, and a turbocharger, are used to ensure supplies of both hydrogen and air at about
30 psi, and to circulate cooling water through a conventional radiator.<BR>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
The resultant exhaust consists of water and unused air. For a vehicle, that means Zero Emissions.<BR>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
Ballard sold its first fuel cell for stationary power generation in 1994. Its first mobile application was in a 32 foot bus, which went on the road in mid 1993. In this bus, the fuel cell and its accessories took up close to a quarter of the vehicle's volume. In Ballard's latest bus prototype, the fuel cell engine occupies the same space that would normally be occupied by the bus's diesel engine. It produces 275 horsepower, the same as the diesel; and the weight is about the same as the diesel. The bus has the same number of seats as the diesel bus. It has a range of 250 miles between refuelling stops.<BR>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
Ballard has come a long way up the technology development curve. Research now concentrates on improvements in the energy efficiency of the engine, and reducing the cost of its manufacture. This pre-production prototype bus, they say, will be run for about three years to gain operating experience. In that time, between ten and fifteen more will be made. Then they'll be ready for commercial production.<BR>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
Ballard emphasizes that they are in the engine business, not the bus business. They anticipate having fuel cell engines for sale commercially in 1998.<BR>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td><A HREF="ballard.htm"><IMG align=left BORDER=0 SRC="../cr_gifs/back.gif"></A></td>
<td><br></td>
<td width=480><br></td>
</tr>
</table>
<!-- end of table-->

