<HTML>

<HEAD>
<TITLE>CATF Review Newletter: Issue No. 21 (April, 1995)</TITLE>
<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Word 2.0z Beta>
<META NAME="AUTHOR" CONTENT="Andrea Gomory">
<!-- Last Update: 01/10/96 -->
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#FF0000" VLINK="#8080C0" ALINK="#E629A">
<BASEFONT SIZE=3>

<BODY>
<IMG border=0 SRC="../cr_gifs/catf_pg2.gif"><BR>

<!-- begin table--><!-- total=630 -->
<table border=0 width=630 cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0>

<tr>
<td width=150 valign=top rowspan=1>
<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=6 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG border=0 align=top SRC="../cr_gifs/toc_thin.gif"><BR>
<A HREF="hybrid.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="21toc_1.gif"></A><br>
<IMG border=0 align=top SRC="../cr_gifs/toc_thik.gif"><BR>
<A HREF="dimethyl.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="21toc_2.gif"></A><br>
<IMG border=0 align=top SRC="../cr_gifs/toc_thik.gif"><BR>
<A HREF="cng_fuel.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="21toc_3.gif"></A><br>
<IMG border=0 align=top SRC="../cr_gifs/toc_thik.gif"><BR>
<A HREF="notes.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="21toc_4.gif"></A><br>
<IMG border=0 align=top SRC="../cr_gifs/toc_thik.gif"><BR>
<A HREF="alt_fuel.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="21toc_5b.gif"></A><br>
<IMG border=0 align=top SRC="../cr_gifs/toc_thin.gif"><BR>
</td>

<td valign=top colspan=2 width=480>
<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
There are many greenhouse gases, but their effect can be measured in terms of CO2 equivalents, and that is what these studies have done. The studies also measured the generation of greenhouse gases both in the production of fuel and in its use in the vehicle. This total emissions approach reflects the fact that it doesn't matter where greenhouse gases are generated, they affect everyone on earth.<br>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
Clearly, while alternative transportation fuels are chosen because they have an edge when it comes to reducing undesirable tailpipe emissions, their use also confers some benefits in the reduction of greenhouse gas generation.<br>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG BORDER=0 SRC="table.gif"></BR>


<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
With present fuel production methods, these benefits are significant (up to 25% reduction) but not spectacular. While virtually all alternative fuels produce less greenhouse gases than gasoline (regular or reformulated), the total figures are very sensitive to the method of production of the fuel. For example, the greenhouse gases resulting from the 
production of electricity are based on the mix of electricity generation plants in the 
U.S. for the year 2000. If there were a higher proportion of renewable generation, the figure could be substantially lower. Similarly, emissions for the production of other fuels assume 
current technology.<br>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
But we can conclude that alternative transportation fuels do have a role to play in meeting international commitments to reduce greenhouse gas generation. And this approach gives us new reasons to focus on the emissions involved in the production of transportation fuel, as well as its consumption.<br>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<font size=1>
1 Light Duty Vehicle Full Fuel Cycle Emissions Analysis, GRI-93/0472, Gas Research Institute, April 1994.<br>
2 "Choosing an Alternative Transportation Fuel" OECD 1993.<br>
</font>

</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td><A HREF="alt_fuel.htm"><IMG align=left BORDER=0 SRC="../cr_gifs/back.gif"></A></td>
<td><br></td>
<td width=480><br></td>
</tr>
