<HTML>

<HEAD>
<TITLE>CATF Review Newletter: Issue No. 24 (January, 1996)</TITLE>
<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Word 2.0z Beta>
<META NAME="AUTHOR" CONTENT="Andrea Gomory">
<!-- Last Update: 10/11/96 -->
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#FF0000" VLINK="#8080C0" ALINK="#E629A">
<BASEFONT SIZE=3>

<BODY>
<IMG border=0 SRC="../cr_gifs/catf_pg2.gif"><BR>

<!-- begin table--><!-- total=600 -->
<table border=0 width=630 cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0>
<tr>
<td width=150 valign=top rowspan=1>
<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=6 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG border=0 align=top SRC="../cr_gifs/toc_thin.gif"><BR>
<A HREF="elect.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="24toc_1.gif"></A><br>
<IMG border=0 align=top SRC="../cr_gifs/toc_thik.gif"><BR>
<A HREF="propane.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="24toc_2b.gif"></A><br>
<IMG border=0 align=top SRC="../cr_gifs/toc_thik.gif"><BR>
<A HREF="new_bus.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="24toc_3.gif"></A><br>
<IMG border=0 align=top SRC="../cr_gifs/toc_thik.gif"><BR>
<A HREF="hybrids.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="24toc_4.gif"></A><br>
<IMG border=0 align=top SRC="../cr_gifs/toc_thin.gif"><BR>
<td>

<td valign=top colspan=2 width=480>
<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<font size=3><b>The G3306 engine</b></font><BR>
<IMG align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
Caterpillars production G3306 engine is designed to be a drop-in substitute for the equivalent diesel. It has similar power, driveability, and durability. In addition to significantly reduced emissions, it yields substantial economies due to the favourable price of propane.<BR>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
The G3306 is a six cylinder, four stroke engine with a displacement of 638 cubic inches. Spark ignited with a 10.5:1 compression ratio, it is rated at 235 hp at 2,100 rpm, with a peak torque of 820 lbs-ft at 1,200 rpm.<BR>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
The fuel strategy is stoichiometric, with turbocharger and air-to-air charge intercooling. The exhaust manifold is water cooled. Caterpillar has developed a new digital ignition system along with advanced engine sensor technology to calculate timing and fuel delivery. A three way catalyst is used.<BR>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
Caterpillar is confident that this approach enables the G3306 to operate under a wide variety of operating conditions. The engine is also available for operation on natural gas.<BR>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<font size=3><b>Engine application</b></font><BR>
<IMG align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
While the engine currently sells at a price premium over its diesel equivalent, marketing efforts are targeted at intensive user applications. Applications include urban delivery, waste haulage, and urban transit, where returns from fuel use savings and maintenance economies, together with substantial emissions improvements, increase the attractiveness of the G3306 to prospective purchasers.<BR>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<font size=3><b>The G3406: Caterpillar's next gaseous fuel engine</b></font><BR>
<IMG align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
Caterpillar is expected to announce the production of the 14 litre G3406 engine soon. Advance information indicates that this new six cylinder engine will employ a lean burn engine management strategy, with a two-way catalyst, to meet stringent emissions standards.<BR>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
The G3406 will be available with a 350 hp rating at 2000 rpm, with torque rise capability similar to Caterpillar diesel truck engines. Using a two-way catalytic converter, the engine complies with 1994 EPA emissions regulations. The total engine system produces less than 2 g of NOx and less than .05 g of particulates per brake horsepower hour.<BR>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
Both the G3306 and G3406 share blocks, crankshafts, cylinder liners and connecting rods with their Cat diesel counterparts. Both engines have camshafts and turbochargers designed especially for gaseous fuel application, and both have Air-to-Air Aftercooling (ATAAC).<BR>


</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td><A HREF="propane.htm"><IMG align=left BORDER=0 SRC="../cr_gifs/back.gif"></A></td>
<td><br></td>
<td width=480><br></td>
</tr>
</table>
<!-- end of table-->

