<HEAD>
<TITLE>CATF Review Newletter: Issue No. 24 (January, 1996)</TITLE>
<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Word 2.0z Beta>
<META NAME="AUTHOR" CONTENT="Andrea Gomory">
<!-- Last Update: 10/11/96 -->
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#FF0000" VLINK="#8080C0" ALINK="#E629A">
<BASEFONT SIZE=3>

<BODY>
<IMG border=0 SRC="../cr_gifs/catf_pg3.gif"><BR>

<!-- begin table--><!-- total=600 -->
<table border=0 width=630 cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0>

<tr>
<td width=150 valign=top rowspan=1>
<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=6 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG border=0 align=top SRC="../cr_gifs/toc_thin.gif"><BR>
<A HREF="elect.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="24toc_1b.gif"></A><br>
<IMG border=0 align=top SRC="../cr_gifs/toc_thik.gif"><BR>
<A HREF="propane.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="24toc_2.gif"></A><br>
<IMG border=0 align=top SRC="../cr_gifs/toc_thik.gif"><BR>
<A HREF="new_bus.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="24toc_3.gif"></A><br>
<IMG border=0 align=top SRC="../cr_gifs/toc_thik.gif"><BR>
<A HREF="hybrids.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="24toc_4.gif"></A><br>
<IMG border=0 align=top SRC="../cr_gifs/toc_thin.gif"><BR>
</td>

<td valign=top colspan=2 width=480>
<font size=3><b>Monitoring catalysts</b></font><BR>
<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
One of the functions of the closed-loop feedback system is to ensure that there is sufficient oxygen in the engine exhaust to ensure that the catalytic converter is able to do its job. Many catalytic converters have been damaged through too rich or too lean alternative fuel operation. With OBD II, oxygen sensors are installed both upstream and downstream of the catalytic converter to check on its operation; both are linked to the OEM computer.<BR>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<font size=3><b>Real electronic engine control</b></font><BR>
<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
Digicon uses a current project at BCRI to illustrate what can be done with electronic engine controls and alternative fuels. A Cummins 8.3 litre, six cylinder diesel engine has been converted to spark ignition and electronically controlled gaseous propane injection. The engine has special high-turbulence combustion chambers and a turbocharger with electronically controlled wastegate.<BR>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
Using the Motorola 68332 computer, a powerful commercially available 16 Mhz 32 bit machine, Digicon has programmed a control algorithm using the same Proportional Integral Derivative (PID) approach used in many industrial control applications. The oxygen sensor used on this project is one which outputs a proportional signal rather than the on/off signal emitted by normal oxygen sensors.<br>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
The control system also reads signals from the Mass Airflow sensor, throttle position, manifold pressure, turbocharger boost pressure, propane pressure and temperature, engine coolant temperature, crankshaft and camshaft degrees, and vehicle speed. It controls the DIS ignition system, six individual fuel injectors, and idle air bleed.<br>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
This array of inputs feeds a complex three dimensional mapping algorithm, in which all parameters are individually adjustable. Adjustment is carried out through an operator interface which enables adjustment while the engine (or vehicle) is running, using a notebook PC connected to the Motorola.<br>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
This sophisticated control system is designed to enable BCRI engineers to explore the limits of high turbulence lean-burn combustion in a wide range of operating conditions, including full load and part load acceleration, engine braking, and idle and low speed operation. It is an example of the type of control system that can be designed for alternative fuel engines if the designer is not hampered by having to adapt to the unknown and undocumented characteristics of an OEM computer designed to facilitate operation on gasoline.<br>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td><A HREF="electpg2.htm"><IMG align=left BORDER=0 SRC="../cr_gifs/back.gif"></A></td>
<td><br></td>
<td width=480><br></td>
</tr>
</table>
