<DOCNO>WT04-B17-134</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA006-000056-B016-67</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://www.bcr.bc.ca:80/catf/review/issue_24/electpg2.htm 204.191.240.6 19970221185548 text/html 6666
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Date: Fri, 21 Feb 1997 18:56:09 GMT
Server: WebSitePro/1.1g (S/N WPO-22E6)
Accept-ranges: bytes
Content-type: text/html
Last-modified: Mon, 17 Feb 1997 23:46:24 GMT
Content-length: 6455
</DOCHDR>
<!DOCTYPE HTML"-//IETF//DTD HTML 3.0//EN">
<HTML>

<HEAD>
<TITLE>CATF Review Newletter: Issue No. 24 (January, 1996)</TITLE>
<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Word 2.0z Beta>
<META NAME="AUTHOR" CONTENT="Andrea Gomory">
<!-- Last Update: 10/11/96 -->
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#FF0000" VLINK="#8080C0" ALINK="#E629A">
<BASEFONT SIZE=3>

<BODY>
<IMG border=0 SRC="../cr_gifs/catf_pg2.gif"><BR>

<!-- begin table--><!-- total=630 -->
<table border=0 width=630 cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0>

<tr>
<td width=150 valign=top rowspan=1>
<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=6 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG border=0 align=top SRC="../cr_gifs/toc_thin.gif"><BR>
<A HREF="elect.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="24toc_1b.gif"></A><br>
<IMG border=0 align=top SRC="../cr_gifs/toc_thik.gif"><BR>
<A HREF="propane.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="24toc_2.gif"></A><br>
<IMG border=0 align=top SRC="../cr_gifs/toc_thik.gif"><BR>
<A HREF="new_bus.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="24toc_3.gif"></A><br>
<IMG border=0 align=top SRC="../cr_gifs/toc_thik.gif"><BR>
<A HREF="hybrids.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="24toc_4.gif"></A><br>
<IMG border=0 align=top SRC="../cr_gifs/toc_thin.gif"><BR>
<td>

<td valign=top colspan=2 width=480>
<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<font size=3><b>Fault detection</b></font><BR>
<IMG align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
All the OEM systems were designed to detect faults in the operation of the systems or the engine, to turn on a check engine light on the instrument panel, and to store fault codes in the on-board computer for future diagnosis by a technician. This capability is known as On-Board Diagnostics (OBD). During the past year and a half, most new vehicles have been manufactured in compliance with new and more extensive diagnostic requirements (OBD II); the new requirements are mandatory on 1996 model year vehicles. OBD II computers detect a much wider range of faults, including poor performance of major emissions control components such as the catalytic converter. Some of these faults can result in the vehicle going into a limp home mode.<BR>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
OEM computers are able to detect spurious signals or results from operation of the vehicle on an alternative fuel. Aftermarket fixes have usually concentrated on blocking or diverting signals so that spurious error codes did not occur. But with OBD II, strategies have had to shift to working with the OEM computer, rather than just trying to fool it.<BR>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<font size=3><b>Reverse engineering</b></font><BR>
<IMG align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
The OEMs have not made this easy. Anxious to protect their immense investment in computer hardware and software, they have been most reluctant to release any information about how their on-board computers actually work. This means that designers of aftermarket electronics have had to resort to forms of reverse engineering in order to develop systems which will manage engines on alternative fuels to produce emissions performance equivalent to the OEM gasoline vehicles.<BR>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
At first, this reverse engineering was somewhat crude, amounting to little more than blocking key inputs and outputs of the OEM computer. Early aftermarket conversions to closed-loop feedback-equipped vehicles used open-loop technology. Often the signal from the oxygen sensor was ignored, and the equipment supplied was little more than fix boxes.<BR>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<font size=3><b>Working with the OEM computer</b></font><BR>
<IMG align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
Douglas Yip, of Digicon Engineering Incorporated in North Vancouver, BC, is one of the few electromechanical engineers who has experience in this kind of reverse engineering. He uses a variety of data acquisition systems to analyse the inputs and outputs of the OEM computer in real time and translate them into the signals necessary to accomplish the same results on alternative fuels. This means that the alternative fuel system uses the same algorithm as the OEMs system in order to control the engine. This could be termed working with the OEM computer rather than trying to circumvent it. But it requires a considerable amount of analysis of the behaviour of the OEM computer before its outputs can be effectively translated into the signals necessary to control the alternative fuel system.<BR>

<IMG border=0 align=top vspace=3 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif"><BR>
<IMG align=top hspace=10 SRC="../cr_gifs/dot_clr.gif">
And with OBD II, the number of functions carried out by the OEM computer is much increased. This means even more reverse engineering to adapt the vehicle to alternative fuels.<BR>

</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td><A HREF="elect.htm"><IMG align=left BORDER=0 SRC="../cr_gifs/back.gif"></A></td>
<td><br></td>
<td width=480>
<A HREF="electpg3.htm"><IMG align=right BORDER=0 SRC="../cr_gifs/forward.gif"></A>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<!-- end of table-->

