<html><head><title>CSPP Press Release 10/24/96</title></head>

<body background="../images/bkground.gif" link=003399 vlink=cc3366>

<P></P>
FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE:<br>
October 24, 1996
<P></P>

CONTACT:<br>
<a href="mailto:kay@podesta.com">Ken Kay</a> or
<a href="mailto:barnes@podesta.com">Beverly Barnes </a><br>
(202) 393-1010
<P></P>

<h1><CENTER>Computer Industry Leaders Detail<BR>
Regulatory Obstacles to Digital Marketplace<BR>
Report Calls for New Public Policy Fundamentals for the 21st Century</H1></CENTER>
<P></P>

WASHINGTON, D.C. -- The CEOs of the nation's twelve leading computer systems manufacturers today called on government policy makers to rewrite outdated regulations so that consumers, businesses and society can realize the full potential of dynamic, new digital products and services.
<P></P>
In a report entitled <A HREF="../reports/digicomp.html">Public Policy in the Information Age: Digitization and Competition,</A> the coalition of CEOs emphasizes the endless potential benefits of digitization.  Among the benefits the report cites are more efficient products and services, easy access to resources across the country or around the world, and new trading relationships for consumers and businesses.  Digitization also will increase competition, innovation and customer choice, as well as reduce prices, the report says.
<P></P>
However, impediments to digital competition found in existing regulations could jeopardize the advantages of digitization, according to the CEOs, who together form the Computer Systems Policy Project (CSPP).
<P></P>
"The digitization of information will revolutionize the way we live and work, on a scale similar to the industrial revolution," said Lewis E. Platt, Hewlett-Packard chairman, president and CEO and co-chair of CSPP's GII committee.  "For people to enjoy the full benefits of the digital age, we must take a new approach to policy."
<P></P>
Digitization is the process by which all forms of information can be reduced to a single common denominator (a bit) that can be transmitted, received and manipulated by many different types of equipment.  Thus, products that traditionally perform one function can now perform unexpected tasks, e.g. computers can now receive fax transmissions.  As a result, distinctions among equipment such as telephones, televisions and computers begin to fade, and whole new devices combining their functions begin to emerge.
<P></P>
Without clear boundaries to distinguish products, the report cautions that regulators may subject emerging products and services to existing rules, for the sake of convenience and precedent.
<P></P>
<I>Public Policy in the Information Age: Digitization and Competition</I> is the first comprehensive evaluation of how applying old regulations to cutting-edge technologies can hinder the development of the Global Information Infrastructure (GII).  The report lists five types of regulatory barriers that could thwart new digital products and services by maintaining the segregation between industries and markets and by sheltering incumbents from new market entrants.  These barriers are described as: geographic and cultural; classification-related; technological; false scarcity; and market solutions.
<P></P>
An example of a geographic barrier cited in the report is the current state-by-state medical licensing scheme.  The advent of telemedicine, offered across several state borders through digitization, will be jeopardized if more states prevent patient care by doctors licensed in another state.  State officials in Kansas, South Dakota, Oklahoma and Nevada have barred physicians without a state license from practicing telemedicine there.  The CSPP reports says another 20 states are considering similar restrictions.
<P></P>
The report suggests that, under digitization, yesterday's technological constraints should give way to virtually limitless networks.  In addition, monopoly markets should expand to include multiple players.  Global communications links should replace national and local connections.
<P></P>
While public policy makers must initially protect emerging competition from dominant market players, the ultimate challenge will be to shift from specific market regulation to open, deregulated markets.  CSPP challenges legislators to develop regulatory principles that do not constrict the dynamic potential of industries, services and products in the digital era.
<P></P>
"New public policy fundamentals for the next century must be embraced now," said Edward R. McCracken, chairman and CEO of Silicon Graphics and co-chair of CSPP's GII committee.  "Rather than regulation, a new framework is needed to encourage economic and social growth on a global scale."
<P></P>
The report articulates those ten policy fundamentals as: allowing previously segregated industries to compete for the consumer's attention; freeing the market from regulations; creating temporary, new regulations to serve transitional needs while moving toward open markets; considering a global digital common market; developing new legal understandings, particularly with regard to intellectual property law; increasing public access to the digital environment; and developing industry rather than government standards.
<P></P>
"It would be unfortunate if in 10 years we were to look back and say 'everything in the world changed except the way we regulate technology,'" said Robert B. Palmer, Digital chairman and chairman of CSPP.  "Digitization doesn't erase the need to protect the public.  It does demand that we create new rules.  Our report lays out this challenge."
<P></P>
CSPP member companies include
<a href="http://www.apple.com">Apple</a>,
<a href="http://www.att.com">AT&T</a>,
<a href="http://www.compaq.com">Compaq</a>,
<a href="http://www.dg.com">Data General</a>,
<a href="http://www.digital.com">Digital Equipment</a>,
<a href="http://www.hp.com">Hewlett-Packard</a>,
<a href="http://www.ibm.com">IBM</a>,
<a href="http://www.sig.com">Silicon Graphics</a>,
<a href="http://www.stratus.com">Stratus</a>,
<a href="http://www.sun.com">Sun Microsystems</a>,
<a href="http://www.tandem.com">Tandem</a> and
<a href="http://www.unisys.com">Unisys</a>.  Together the companies employed more than 815,000 people and generated more than $216 billion of revenue in 1994.  Ken Kay, of <a href="http://www.podesta.com">Podesta Associates</a>, is CSPP's executive director.<P></P>
<P></P>

