<html><head><title>CSPP Press Release 10/01/96</title></head>

<body background="../images/bkground.gif" link=003399 vlink=cc3366>

<P></P>
FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE:<br>
October 1, 1996
<P></P>

CONTACT:<br>
<a href="mailto:kay@podesta.com">Ken Kay</a> or
<a href="mailto:barnes@podesta.com">Beverly Barnes </a><br>
(202) 393-1010
<P></P>

<h1><CENTER>CSPP Position Statement<BR>
Updating Export Controls for Encryption and<BR>
Developing Key Recovery Technologies</h1></CENTER>
<p></P>

WASHINGTON, D.C. -- The Computer Systems Policy Project (CSPP), a coalition of the chief executive officers of the 12 leading U.S. computer systems companies, supports the Administration's decision to permit the export of 56-bit encryption products and comparable strength key exchange technology for legitimate uses in all but terrorist nations.  CSPP also supports the Administration's decision to allow U.S. firms to take the lead in developing key recovery technologies that can be exported at unlimited strengths.  CSPP believes that these steps are essential to improving the competitiveness of U.S. computer companies in the world market, stemming the loss of U.S. jobs to overseas firms and laying the foundation for commercially successful key recovery products and systems.
<P></P>
While the U.S. government does not regulate the domestic use of encryption, it has controlled the export of encryption, which significantly restricts technological developments and impairs U.S. competitiveness in the global marketplace.  Encryption is a mathematical "lock" which renders digital information worthless to all but those who have the "keys" to unlock it.  CSPP has been working with the Clinton Administration and with Congress to update restrictive export controls and provide immediate relief to global customers who demand stronger encryption to protect their data.
<P></P>
CSPP supports the Administration's decision to encourage voluntary, industry-led key recovery technologies as a means of satisfying important law enforcement and national security concerns.  CSPP member companies recognize that key recovery may have value to customers for commercial reasons and are prepared to invest in key recovery technologies to satisfy customer needs.  CSPP member companies are equally dedicated to ensuring that customers who adopt non-key recovery products are adequately supported in the future.<P></P>
CSPP believes that only market-driven and customer-responsive key recovery products will gain commercial acceptance.  Therefore, CSPP advocates the adoption of voluntary, industry-led standards that are interoperable with existing and future non-escrow encryption systems.  CSPP also favors an approach to encourage development of key recovery technologies that focuses on overall industry progress, rather than on each individual company's implementation plan.
<P></P>
CSPP agrees with the Administration that the ability to export strong encryption is in the interest of national security and the U.S. economy and that exporting strong, high-quality encryption products will help safeguard private and confidential information of law-abiding U.S. citizens and companies.  CSPP commends the Administration for recognizing cryptography as a valuable commercial product by transferring jurisdiction over export of encryption products from the Department of State to the Department of Commerce.
<P></P>
While there are issues yet to be resolved, CSPP acknowledges the progress made by the Administration in removing export restrictions on cryptography.  CSPP stands ready to work with the Administration to expedite the implementation of these decisions that balance the Information Age interests of America's citizens, companies, and government.
<P></P>
CSPP member companies include
<a href="http://www.apple.com">Apple</a>,
<a href="http://www.att.com">AT&T</a>,
<a href="http://www.compaq.com">Compaq</a>,
<a href="http://www.dg.com">Data General</a>,
<a href="http://www.digital.com">Digital Equipment</a>,
<a href="http://www.hp.com">Hewlett-Packard</a>,
<a href="http://www.ibm.com">IBM</a>,
<a href="http://www.sig.com">Silicon Graphics</a>,
<a href="http://www.stratus.com">Stratus</a>,
<a href="http://www.sun.com">Sun Microsystems</a>,
<a href="http://www.tandem.com">Tandem</a> and
<a href="http://www.unisys.com">Unisys</a>.  Together the companies employed more than 815,000 people and generated more than $216 billion of revenue in 1994.  Ken Kay, of <a href="http://www.podesta.com">Podesta Associates</a>, is CSPP's executive director.<P></P>
<P></P>

