<center><h1>Computer Company Executives<BR>
Praise Administration for Concluding<BR>
International Negotiations on Export Controls</h1></center>
<P></P>

WASHINGTON, D.C. -- The chief executive officers of 13 of the country's leading computer systems manufacturers today commended the Clinton Administration on successfully concluding the international negotiations necessary to ease export controls on the sale of high-performance computers.
<p></P>
"This was a major victory for the United States" said Robert B. Palmer, chairman and CEO of Digital Equipment and chairman of the coalition of the 13 CEOs.  "Streamlining controls will enable American computer companies to compete more effectively with their overseas counterparts, generating jobs and promoting continued U.S. technological leadership."
<p></P>
The Computer Systems Policy Project (CSPP), as the coalition is known, has worked to underscore the importance of reforming export controls to reflect the rapid technological advances made in computing power.
<p></P>
The Administration policy will streamline control on all computers to be exported.  It will enable U.S. firms to compete fairly in the international marketplace, while continuing an embargo on the sale of computers to select countries.
<p></P>
CSPP intends to work closely with the Administration to ensure that the final rules do not impose administrative burdens that would undercut the progress of these reforms.
<p></P>
CSPP member companies include
<a href="http://www.apple.com">Apple</a>,
<a href="http://www.att.com">AT&T</a>,
<a href="http://www.compaq.com">Compaq</a>,
<a href="http://www.dg.com">Data General</a>,
<a href="http://www.digital.com">Digital Equipment</a>,
<a href="http://www.hp.com">Hewlett-Packard</a>,
<a href="http://www.ibm.com">IBM</a>,
<a href="http://www.sig.com">Silicon Graphics</a>,
<a href="http://www.stratus.com">Stratus</a>,
<a href="http://www.sun.com">Sun Microsystems</a>,
<a href="http://www.tandem.com">Tandem</a> and
<a href="http://www.unisys.com">Unisys</a>.  Together the companies employed more than 815,000 people and generated more than $216 billion of revenue in 1994.  Ken Kay, of <a href="http://www.podesta.com">Podesta Associates</a>, is CSPP's executive director.<P></P>
