<html><head><title>CSPP Press Release 01/22/96</title></head>

<body background="../images/bkground.gif" link=003399 vlink=cc3366>

FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE<br>
January 22, 1996
<p></p>

CONTACT:<br>
<a href="mailto:barnes@podesta.com">Beverly Barnes</a><br>
(202) 393-1010
<P></P>

<center><h1>Japan Computer Agreement Generates Mixed Results</h1></center>
<P></P>

WASHINGTON, D.C. -- The government of Japan purchased more computers from U.S. and other international computer manufacturers in 1994 than in 1993.  However, in one critical area of the Japanese public sector market, foreign computer manufacturers lost share and in another area, procurement was stagnant.  This information is part of a study released today by a coalition of chief executive officers from 13 leading American computer companies.
<P></P>
The study, sponsored by the Computer Systems Policy Project (CSPP), revealed that U.S. and foreign computer manufacturers' share of  the Japanese public sector increased by 5 percent, from 9 percent in 1993 to 14 percent in 1994, the latest year for which data are available.  By contrast, though, U.S. and other international computer manufacturers attained a 37 percent share of Japan's non-public sector market in 1994.
<p></P>
"When market forces can operate without restraints, purchases of our products are almost three times greater," said Robert B. Palmer, chairman and CEO of Digital Equipment and chairman of CSPP.  "The 1992 U.S.-Japan Computer Agreement, which was designed to open Japanese public sector procurement to foreign computer manufacturers, has improved our position, but ever so slowly."
<p></P>
Foreign computer manufacturers achieve the largest percent of purchases in the quasi-government part of the public sector, which includes government-related corporations and agencies such as the NTT.  Sales to the quasi-government sector jumped significantly in 1992,  the year the agreement was implemented, and increased again in 1993.  Last year, however, the U.S. and other international computer system companies' share dropped significantly in the quasi-government sector.  These foreign computer manufacturers received only 21 percent of quasi-government procurement in 1994, as compared to 33 percent in 1993.
<p></P>
Procurement by quasi-government agencies has most closely approximated the non-public sector purchases of foreign-manufactured computers.  In 1993, only 4 percentage points separated foreign manufacturers' share of non-public sector purchases and their share of quasi-government purchases.  A year later, the difference is 16 points.  However, in the same 12 months, total computer purchases by quasi-government agencies surged dramatically, going from 3 percent of Japan's total computer hardware market in 1993 to 8 percent in 1994.  This surge boosted the procurement of computers from foreign manufacturers, despite the drop in market share.
<p></P>
Meanwhile, local government computer procurement dropped, but by less than a percent. Foreign manufacturers' share of those sales edged up to 3.5 percent last year, from 3 percent 12 months earlier.
<p></P>
"Our survey results show that local government and quasi-government agencies can still do a lot more to increase their purchases of competitive offerings by foreign computer makers," said Eckhard Pfeiffer, president and CEO of Compaq and co-chairman of CSPP's working group on Japan public procurement. "It is clear that more needs to be done before we can be satisfied that the Japanese government procurement market is open and competitive."
<p></P>
The brightest spot in the CSPP study is the Japanese national government purchasing twice as many computers from foreign manufacturers in 1994 as in 1993.   National government purchases rose from 6 percent in 1993 to 12 percent in 1994.  This increase took place during a period in which the national government reduced its computer purchases by about 15 percent, or 1 percent as compared to the total market.
<p></P>
"We are pleased to see the U.S. share of  national government purchases double," said William E. Foster, CEO of Stratus Computer and co-chairman of CSPP's working group on Japan public procurement.  "We are eager for local governments to follow suit and for the quasi-government agencies to continue the progress they made earlier in this process."
<p></P>
Computer purchases by the whole Japanese public sector continued to grow last year, as compared to total computer hardware purchases, increasing from 20 percent in 1993 to 24 percent in 1994.
<p></P>
CSPP worked closely with the U.S. government to negotiate the 1992 agreement.  The organization will continue to press for full implementation of the agreement.  CSPP members believe the Japanese government should more strongly encourage local governments to adopt the procedures outlined in the agreement, which can lead to more open practices and result in greater market share for foreign computer manufacturers.
<p></P>
CSPP member companies include
<a href="http://www.apple.com">Apple</a>,
<a href="http://www.att.com">AT&T</a>,
<a href="http://www.compaq.com">Compaq</a>,
<a href="http://www.dg.com">Data General</a>,
<a href="http://www.digital.com">Digital Equipment</a>,
<a href="http://www.hp.com">Hewlett-Packard</a>,
<a href="http://www.ibm.com">IBM</a>,
<a href="http://www.sig.com">Silicon Graphics</a>,
<a href="http://www.stratus.com">Stratus</a>,
<a href="http://www.sun.com">Sun Microsystems</a>,
<a href="http://www.tandem.com">Tandem</a> and
<a href="http://www.unisys.com">Unisys</a>.  Together the companies employed more than 815,000 people and generated more than $216 billion of revenue in 1994.  Ken Kay, of <a href="http://www.podesta.com">Podesta Associates</a>, is CSPP's executive director.<P></P>
<P></P>

