<HTML><head><title>CSPP Press Release 01/17/96</title>

<body background="../images/bkground.gif" link=003399 vlink=cc3366>

FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE<br>
January 17, 1996<p>

CONTACT:<br>
<a href="mailto:barnes@podesta.com">Beverly Barnes</a><br>
(202) 393-1010
<P></P>

<center><h1>Computer CEOs Say Export Policy Reform Required to
Protect "Cyberproperty" and Competitiveness</h1></center>
<P></P>

WASHINGTON, D.C. -- A report released today by the chief executive officers of the 13 leading computer systems companies calls on the federal government to lift its strict controls on U.S. commercial cryptographic products when competitive products are available on the international market from foreign sources.
<p></P>
The report, <A HREF=../reports/report1-96.html">Perspectives on Security in the Information Age,</A> also recommends the U.S. government end technology-based restrictions on exporting strong, commercial cryptographic products to legitimate, commercial users.
<p></P>
Individual and business owners of electronic property, or "cyberproperty," should determine the type and strength of security needed to protect what is fast becoming the most valuable form of currency in the Information Age, according to the report.
<p></P>
The Computer Systems Policy Project (CSPP), as the CEO coalition is known, contends that users of the global information infrastructure (GII) have the need, right and responsibility to protect their confidential information as it travels over open electronic pathways or is stored in unsecured facilities attached to those pathways.
<p></P>
"Cryptographic technology is a must for every individual and business with sensitive data on the Internet or some other component of the global information infrastructure," said Robert B. Palmer, chairman and CEO of Digital Equipment and chairman of CSPP.
<p></P>
The report likens the intangible personal data that, for instance, users of the Internet's World Wide Web transmit instantaneously across geographic borders to the tangible documents the same individuals might store in locked file cabinets or send through the mail. Both types of information are property, similar to manufactured goods or land.
<p></P>
The report states that the most efficient and cost-effective way to protect cyberproperty is with cryptographic products, many of which are subject to 50-year-old export control policies.
<p></P>
Cryptographic products encode and decode individual pieces of cyberproperty at the  point of transmission and receipt.  Since no one nation, corporation or person controls the network of electronic pathways that constitute the GII, the whole of it cannot be secured.  It spans more than 100 countries and serves millions of users.
<p></P>
Encryption is a cryptographic tool that enables owners to protect their individual pieces of cyberproperty from intrusion and theft, much the same way a padlock protects property in a locker or an envelope protects property traveling through the mail.  Encryption hardware or software uses computers to employ many more numbers than are possible even on a sophisticated padlock.  The longer the "combination," the stronger the encryption, and the more secure the cyberproperty.
<p></P>
"As the number of linked networks increases and the cost of computing continues to fall, individual and business owners will require effective security solutions -- effective encryption -- to safeguard their cyberproperty from vandals, thieves, industrial spies and terrorists," said Scott G. McNealy, CEO of Sun Microsystems and co-chairman of CSPP's working group on security, encryption and export controls.
<p></P>
"Indeed, government and industry should be working together to protect government, industry and individuals from these vulnerabilities, rather than struggling over the futile endeavor to control' encryption," McNealy added.  "The growing number of global interactions by individuals and businesses will also require security solutions that are global in nature," he said.
<p></P>
The U.S. State Department regulates hardware and software encryption products--even when specifically designed for commercial purposes--as munitions that are deemed "inherently military in character."  This policy severely limit the ability of American companies to provide customers with security solutions, based on encryption, that are seamlessly integrated into their computer systems.  Meanwhile, many foreign competitors already export competitive security solutions that U.S. companies cannot.
<p></P>
The competitive advantage that foreign companies derive from their ability to meet the growing demand for secure, integrated, global solutions may well result in lost U.S. market share in encryption and in general computer systems, the report concludes.  Foreign competitors will attract sales not only from foreign companies, but also from U.S. companies.  The report argues that, over time, the government's current restrictive practice threatens to drive sales, technologies and jobs to foreign competitors who are able to produce and export cryptographic products.
<p></P>
The CSPP report reviews the possible consequences facing the American economy and the computer systems industry, specifically, if policy dating back to World War II is not modernized. It proposes a list of principles to shape current and future federal policy controlling the availability and use of cryptography.  Finally, it recommends four critical first steps to bring U.S. export policy, created to protect America's national security interests, in line with the realities of the 21st century.
<p></P>
"Policy changes that reflect these recommendations will promote the legitimate use of security by individuals and companies on the GII, while addressing the U.S. government's concerns about its intelligence gathering and law enforcement capabilities," said James A. Unruh, CEO of Unisys and co-chairman of CSPP's working group on security, encryption and export controls.
<p></P>
The recommendations for changes to U.S. export control policy are:
<ol>
<li>Link the decontrol of U.S. commercial cryptographic products to the availability of competitive products in the international marketplace;<p>
<li>Permit export of effective U.S. commercial cryptographic products, without technology restrictions on key escrow requirements, for legitimate commercial end users, unless the government clearly demonstrates a risk;<p>
<li>Permit the export of effective U.S. commercial cryptographic products that meet reasonable government access needs; and,<p>
<li>Embargo U.S. commercial cryptographic products to terrorist countries.
</ol>
"CSPP believes that the U.S. government, other national governments, the private sector and individual users should work together to develop encryption policies that enable individuals and businesses to protect their cyberproperty and that allow users worldwide to fully benefit from the global information infrastructure," said Palmer.
<p></P>

CSPP member companies include
<a href="http://www.apple.com">Apple</a>,
<a href="http://www.att.com">AT&T</a>,
<a href="http://www.compaq.com">Compaq</a>,
<a href="http://www.dg.com">Data General</a>,
<a href="http://www.digital.com">Digital Equipment</a>,
<a href="http://www.hp.com">Hewlett-Packard</a>,
<a href="http://www.ibm.com">IBM</a>,
<a href="http://www.sig.com">Silicon Graphics</a>,
<a href="http://www.stratus.com">Stratus</a>,
<a href="http://www.sun.com">Sun Microsystems</a>,
<a href="http://www.tandem.com">Tandem</a> and
<a href="http://www.unisys.com">Unisys</a>.  Together the companies employed more than 815,000 people and generated more than $216 billion of revenue in 1994.  Ken Kay, of <a href="http://www.podesta.com">Podesta Associates</a>, is CSPP's executive director.<P></P>
<P></P>

