<html><head><title>CSPP Press Release</title></head>

<body background="../images/bkground.gif" link=003399 vlink=cc3366>

<p>FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE:<br>
October 6, 1995
<P></P>

CONTACT:<br>
<a href="mailto:barnes@podesta.com">Beverly Barnes</a><br>
(202) 393-1010
<P></P>

<h1><CENTER>American Computer Companies<BR>
Welcome Export Announcement</h1></CENTER>
<h2><center><em>CEOs Cite Job Opportunities, Forward Vision</em></h2></CENTER>
<p></P>

WASHINGTON, D.C. -- The chief executive officers of 13 leading American computer
companies today commended the Clinton Administration for raising the performance threshold on commercial computers exported to most countries.  The new guidelines clear the way for increased sales of American computer technology abroad.
<p></P>
"Continued deregulation of the computer industry creates new job opportunities for American workers and brings new revenue into the U.S. economy," said Robert B. Palmer, chairman of Digital Equipment and chairman of the coalition of these companies, called the Computer Systems Policy Project.  "The Administration is to be commended for making these goals consistent with national security by continuing the ban on exports of  computers to rogue nations and limiting exports for military uses."
<p></P>
CSPP members worked closely with the Clinton Administration in securing significant export control reform in 1993.  The group played a similar role leading up to today's announcement.
<p></P>
"The Administration recognized the need for decontrol in 1993, and they've done it again with this prudent and very necessary action," Palmer said.  "The market and the technology have outpaced the controls.  This decision enhances the competitiveness of U.S. computer companies without jeopardizing national security."
<p></P>
The decision by the Administration brings computer export controls more in line with the rapid technological advances and ready foreign availability of equivalent computing power.
<p></P>
"These exports help us continue a high level of R&D.  This R&D keeps us number one in the global information society, creates good jobs and promotes our national security," said Scott G. McNealy, CEO of Sun Microsystems.
<p></P>
"I commend the Administration for a policy that keeps pace with both rapid technological change and the realities of the post-Cold War world,"  said James A. Unruh, CEO of Unisys.  "Today's action addresses one of many export control issues that impact the competitiveness of American business.  We look forward to speedy implementation of today's announcement and will continue to work towards a more comprehensive reform of export controls."
<p></P>
CSPP member companies include
<a href="http://www.apple.com">Apple</a>,
<a href="http://www.att.com">AT&T</a>,
<a href="http://www.compaq.com">Compaq</a>,
<a href="http://www.dg.com">Data General</a>,
<a href="http://www.digital.com">Digital Equipment</a>,
<a href="http://www.hp.com">Hewlett-Packard</a>,
<a href="http://www.ibm.com">IBM</a>,
<a href="http://www.sig.com">Silicon Graphics</a>,
<a href="http://www.stratus.com">Stratus</a>,
<a href="http://www.sun.com">Sun Microsystems</a>,
<a href="http://www.tandem.com">Tandem</a> and
<a href="http://www.unisys.com">Unisys</a>.  Together the companies employed more than 815,000 people and generated more than $216 billion of revenue in 1994.  Ken Kay, of <a href="http://www.podesta.com">Podesta Associates</a>, is CSPP's executive director.<P></P>
