<HTML><head><title>CSPP Press Release 02/15/95</title>

<body background="../images/bkground.gif" link=003399 vlink=cc3366>

FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE:<BR>
February 15, 1995
<p></p>

CONTACT:<br>
<a href="mailto:barnes@podesta.com">Beverly Barnes</a><br>
(202) 393-1010
<P></P>


<center><h1>Computer Company CEO's Issue<br>
Recommendations for Government,<br>
Industry Roles In GII</h1></CENTER>
<P></P>

WASHINGTON, D.C. -- The chief executive officers of 13 leading American computer companies today released a report calling on the U.S. and foreign governments to let the private sector lead the development of a truly global information infrastructure (GII). The report, entitled
<A HREF="../reports/perspectives.html">Perspectives on the Global Information Infrastructure,</A> highlights actions governments should take to support private sector efforts to expand the GII.
<P></P>
The report was prepared by the Computer Systems Policy Project(CSPP), an affiliation of the CEOs of the 13 companies.  Among the report's recommendations is a call for governments to remove regulatory and trade barriers that can impede competition and limit the growth of the GII. The report also urges industry and government to jointly sponsor test projects that can identify technological and policy obstacles facing the GII and point the way to solutions.
<P></P>
"Industry has moved with accelerating speed to create applications that bring the benefits of the latest information technologies to people worldwide," said James Unruh, chairman and CEO of Unisys and chairman of CSPP.  "There are several important steps governments must take to support industry efforts to build a GII that can improve the access of people all over the world to public services, cultural opportunities, commercial transactions and much more."
<P></P>
Michael Spindler, CEO and president of Apple Computer and chairman of CSPP's working group on the GII said, "The Administration has done an outstanding job of launching the debate and creating significant international forums to discuss the GII.  Now it is up to the private sector to be a full participant in those discussions.  This report outlines the computer industry's view of its role and the role of government in advancing the GII."
<P></P>
<I>Perspectives on the Global Information Infrastructure</I> describes the GII as a "worldwide assembly of systems that integrates five components -- networks, information equipment (such as telephones, televisions and computers), information resources, applications and people."  The report delineates seven  key CSPP messages on the GII:
<OL>
<LI>The global information infrastructure is already beingestablished.
<LI>The private sector must take the lead in developing the GII.
<LI>The policy agenda for the GII must go beyond issues of concern to the telecommunications sector.
<LI>Competitive markets and deregulation are critical.
<LI>Governments and the private sector must work to achieve global accessibility.
<LI>Substantive issues to be addressed include:  interoperability, market access, security, privacy and intellectual property protection.
<LI>Commercial testbeds, sponsored jointly by industry and governments, will help identify potential barriers to fully developing the GII and point the way to solutions.
</OL>
<P></P>
The report begins with the premise that the needs of the GII are much broader than telecommunications alone.  Deregulating telecommunications is critical, but countries must also look beyond issues such as competition, privatization and market access in the telecommunications sector when formulating policy governing the GII.
<P></P>
Companies and governments must seek to bring the competition that has marked the computer industry to bear on other components of the GII.
<P></P>
"The U.S. government should work aggressively with other governments and within the appropriate international organizations to achieve competitive, deregulated markets," the report says.  Government restrictions and government-sanctioned monopolies of critical network services prevent the informationindustry from participating fully in foreign markets.  Competitive, deregulated markets will stimulate innovation, expand customer choice and reduce costs.  This will go along way to fostering the GII's development, CSPP believes.
<P></P>
While underscoring the importance of the GII being affordable and accessible to people throughout the world, the report states that it would be counterproductive to develop requirements for universal service before the market for the GII has been clearly delineated.  "As the GII evolves, the private sector has a responsibility to work with governments to identify strategies, other than government mandates, for making essential services and information sources broadly accessible to people and communities," the report states.
<P></P>
The report calls for governments worldwide to support industry work to adopt common practices in several critical technological areas.  The first of these is the need for internationally accepted standards to enable interoperability between computers, telephones, televisions, applications and databases, which can interact with counterparts anywhere in the world.  These standards should develop through voluntary industry processes rather than government mandates.
<P></P>
Security and privacy are two other concerns for users of the GII.  Policies addressing these areas must balance the need for information to flow freely across borders with viable protections for sensitive data.  Governments must help the private sector adopt standards that insure confidential material is protected as it travels through the GII.
<P></P>
"The U.S. government must work with industry to implement policies that will allow for the use of international encryption mechanisms necessary for commercial transactions," said Scott McNealy, CEO of Sun Microsystems and chairman of the CSPP trade committee.  "Those security mechanisms must ensure privacy and authentication for personal and business data."
<P></P>
Finally, the report recommends that the U.S. government continue its activities to strengthen intellectual property protection.  The owners of work that consumers will access through the GII need assurances that their copyrighted material and proprietary designs are safeguarded all along the GII.  "The U.S. government must be willing to take an aggressive stand in negotiating needed copyright protections abroad," the report states.
<P></P>
CSPP member companies include
<a href="http://www.apple.com">Apple</a>,
<a href="http://www.att.com">AT&T</a>,
<a href="http://www.compaq.com">Compaq</a>,
<a href="http://www.dg.com">Data General</a>,
<a href="http://www.digital.com">Digital Equipment</a>,
<a href="http://www.hp.com">Hewlett-Packard</a>,
<a href="http://www.ibm.com">IBM</a>,
<a href="http://www.sig.com">Silicon Graphics</a>,
<a href="http://www.stratus.com">Stratus</a>,
<a href="http://www.sun.com">Sun Microsystems</a>,
<a href="http://www.tandem.com">Tandem</a> and
<a href="http://www.unisys.com">Unisys</a>.  Together the companies employed more than 815,000 people and generated more than $216 billion of revenue in 1994.  Ken Kay, of <a href="http://www.podesta.com">Podesta Associates</a>, is CSPP's executive director.<P></P>
<P></P>

