<html><head><title>CSPP Report 10/24/96</title></head>

<body background="../images/bkground.gif" link=003399 vlink=cc3366>

<P></P>

<H1><CENTER>Public Policy in the Information Age:<BR>
Digitization and Competition</H1></CENTER>
October 1996
<P></P>
<H2>EXECUTIVE SUMMARY</H2>
<P></P>
The digital revolution has the potential to alter our lives as comprehensively as the industrial revolution.  New digital technologies have already changed the communications and information industries dramatically and have given rise to many new products and services.  The vision of a globally interconnected world is becoming a reality.  The Global Information Infrastructure (GII) will enable people to exchange information and to participate in the marketplace with greater ease and flexibility. Individuals can choose the form (audio, video or text) in which they prefer to interact, rather than have it dictated by technology.  For instance, the World Wide Web can offer the most current information days, even weeks, before hard-copy materials are available.
<P></P>
The digital revolution traces its history to the computer industry's process of digitization. Digitization reduces all forms of information to a single common denominator (the bit) that can be transmitted, received and manipulated by many different types of equipment.  This single common denominator allows traditional equipment to perform numerous non-traditional functions, such as computers receiving faxes.  As a result, distinctions between equipment such as telephones, televisions and computers begin to fade and the possibility of whole new devices -- e.g., "Internet browsers" -- becomes a reality.
<P></P>
Digitization will foster increased consumer participation in the marketplace and intense competition among different networks, appliances and content formats.  The GII also will enable competition to occur across geographical and political borders as never before and will allow new entrants to compete with market incumbents.  From competition, major economic and social changes will flow.
<P></P>
Digitization's benefits to consumers and businesses are endless.  Digitization will create more efficient products and services.  It will put national and international resources at consumers' fingertips.  It will make innumerable activities possible from the comfort of consumers' homes or offices.  It will speed transactions, reduce costs and open up new sources for business. It will foster new trading relationships for consumers and businesses a world apart.
<P></P>
However, these benefits are far from being fully realized.  In fact, impediments to competition found in existing laws and regulations may jeopardize many of the benefits of digitization and prevent the digital era from ever reaching its full potential.  For instance, applying existing regulations to new digital technologies may limit their availability and usefulness. Classifying goods and services into narrowly defined trade categories -- for example, the classification and regulation of computers as "telecommunications devices" if they contain a modem -- may limit consumer choice.  Further, imposing limits on digital products and services curbs the natural tendency of digitization to minimize the importance of geographic borders and product differentiation.
<P></P>
Policy makers are being challenged to develop regulatory principles that do not constrict the dynamic potential of industries, services and products in the digital era.  With minimal regulation, widespread competition and increased consumer choice should prevail.  The resulting changes in market dynamics should alter the assumptions that policy makers traditionally bring to the table and should virtually eliminate the need for economically based regulation.
<P></P>
It is possible that, in certain situations, creating a truly competitive marketplace may require a transition period. Policy makers can facilitate this transition by protecting emerging competition from dominant players until it is possible to shift from specific market regulation to open, deregulated markets.  Policy makers must also continue to use regulation, as necessary, to protect consumers from dangerous products, fraudulent claims and other social concerns.
<P></P>
Accordingly, CSPP recommends the following policy fundamentals as a starting point for developing affirmative doctrines to replace the out-moded regulatory models of the past:
<P></P>
<OL>
<LI>Previously segregated industries, products and services must be allowed to compete for the consumer's attention.
<P></P>
<LI>Policy makers should strive to impose the fewest possible burdens on the market and should err on the side of regulations that are the least intrusive and offer consumers the greatest choice.  Policy makers should reserve prescriptive government policies for circumstances -- such as health and safety or incumbent domination of a market -- in which the need for intervention is clear and overwhelming.
<P></P>
<LI>Governments, in certain situations, may need to create new regulatory frameworks that address short-term transitional needs while still moving toward competition and open markets.
<P></P>
<LI>The GII can be the foundation of a global digital common market in which world-wide open trade is facilitated by digital technology.
<P></P>
<LI>Public policy should encourage a marketplace in which consumers, rather than regulators, direct the availability of applications.
<P></P>
<LI>Public access to the GII should be promoted through common points of access to public facilities and through individual choice, not through rigid prescriptions for universal service.
<P></P>
<LI>The private sector, not government, should take the lead in developing international GII standards.
<P></P>
<LI>Traditional legal thinking about property law, personal rights and responsibility should recognize that transactions and communications on the GII will take place without reference to physical form or location.
<P></P>
<LI>Governments should rely on general legal concepts, such as antitrust, rather than sector-specific statutes to guide legal issues related to the GII.  Broad, industry-neutral concepts are more readily adaptable to the changing technological circumstances created by the digital era.
<P></P>
<LI>New economic regulations created to foster initial competition should contain sunset provisions to ensure that they do not become permanent barriers to an open and competitive market.
<P></P>
</OL>
<hr align=center width=50%>
<H2>INTRODUCTION</H2>
<P></P>
In recent years, policy makers and the media have heralded the arrival of the digital era and have embraced the image of computer technology linking people across a vast sea of world-wide information networks.  The digital era is expected to bring with it increased consumer benefits and choice as networked, digital appliances with improved functionality and flexibility are developed.  The question of where the digital era will take us, on an economic and societal level, has been the starting point of a number of discussions.
<P></P>
The digital era holds the promise of dramatic change in the way people use technology to accomplish commercial, educational, social, governmental and personal goals.  Digital appliances and networks that will compose the Global Information Infrastructure (GII) are accelerating the world-wide integration of our economic and social communities.   As a result, a radically different marketplace, characterized by competition and choice, will emerge.
<P></P>
However, the full benefits of the digital era may never be realized unless affirmative efforts are taken to enhance its prospects for success. This paper focuses on the challenges for policy makers in the rapidly changing information technology environment.  As set forth below, the move to digitization changes fundamental assumptions about the marketplace and about the need for government intervention in shaping the marketplace. Policy makers need to work towards a new policy framework that limits reliance on government intervention and encourages the private sector to respond to consumer needs.  This paper offers recommendations for such a framework.
<P></P>
<hr align=center width=50%>
<H2>DIGITIZATION AND THE DIGITAL REVOLUTION</H2>
<P></P>
<I>What is Digitization?</I>
<P></P>
Digitization is the process by which information in any form (text, graphics, audio or video) is reduced to a single common denominator that can be transmitted and received by a variety of appliances. In the computer world, this common form is known as a bit and is represented by a 0 or 1.  This evolution to a digital format will create three major changes in the way consumers use communications and information technology.
<P></P>
First, as a result of digitization, many of the long-standing distinctions between telephones, televisions, computers and other consumer electronic devices will no longer be relevant.  Prior to digitization, devices based on analog technologies were often limited to performing only one function.  Digitization and computer technology have changed this picture.  Today, computer technology allows these familiar devices to perform more than their traditional functions. For instance, a business executive may now choose to conduct conference calls over a computer instead of a telephone, by utilizing the computers video conferencing capabilities.
<P></P>
Second, digitization is also lessening the importance of geographic boundaries as a necessary means of defining markets.  Now that information can be made available easily, quickly and in multiple forms, products and services traditionally offered to a limited region can be offered to new markets.  For consumers, the benefits of electronic commerce create far-reaching opportunities in all countries that foster the growth of the GII.  For producers, niche markets expanded globally have the potential to become quite significant.
<P></P>
Third, digitization increasingly allows information (content) to be delivered in many forms (video, audio, text) by multiple pipelines.  More often, consumer preference, provider ingenuity and cost, rather than technology alone, will dictate the format and delivery method.  The World Wide Web already allows students to locate up-to-date information on screen that might elude them if they were to rely solely on library encyclopedias and other hard-copy materials.
<P></P>
Thus, the digital era will be defined by the potential for expansion and growth.  This contrasts sharply with the implications "convergence," which suggests that as technology becomes more interchangeable, the market will reduce to a few vertically integrated corporations.  "Competition" rather than "convergence" best describes the market abundance that will characterize the digital era.
<P></P>
<I>Digitization Increases Competition.</I>
<P></P>
As digitization allows appliances (and networks) to be used interchangeably for a wide array of purposes, telephone and computer companies, for instance, will compete directly for consumers' information services business.  The disappearance of traditional boundaries between products and businesses will generate numerous business opportunities throughout the GII and among industries that rely on critical computing and communications links.
<P></P>
There is little doubt that digitization will produce wide-spread competition throughout the GII:
<P></P>
<UL>
<LI>Among network providers.  The infrastructure will not be limited to a single network.  In fact, multiple pathways to users -- whether at home, in the office or on the road -- will be created, and consumers will be free to choose which conduits they prefer.  Already, for example, competition exists between the wireless, wireline and satellite providers of telecommunications services.  In the near future, cable companies, public utilities and broadcasters will offer consumers additional conduits.
<P></P>
<LI>Among appliances.  Competition among the different information appliances, (such as the telephone, television and computer) is likely to be fierce.  Vendors will be fighting to provide the "appliance of choice" and will increasingly be forced to cater to consumer demands by providing versatile and flexible information equipment. As this competition grows, consumers will be able to substitute widely among different information appliances, and familiar functions will be performed by non-traditional devices. One example that is already commonplace is the use of digital phones to transmit paging messages.  Rather than leading to one dominant appliance or the creation of a standard function set, digitization both increases the functions traditional appliances can perform and expands the functional configurations that can be offered with these devices.
<P></P>
<LI>Among content formats.  Due to the new means of transmitting and manipulating information, content will be created and used in picture, text or audio form. Competition between content providers to meet the needs of consumers will force increased choice, customization and flexibility.  In addition, consumers will be able to create their own content through the use of digital technologies.
<P></P>
The current trials of interactive television are an example of this new flexibility, which gives television viewers the freedom to explore various programming options and areas of interest.  Many of these trials are testing video-on-demand, allowing in-home audiences to make individual selections of programs and viewing times.  Other trials are exploring viewer-controlled camera angles for televised sporting events and interactive menu systems that allow viewers access to supporting news and background data.
<P></P>
<LI>Across distances.  Since digital information will not be restrained by geographic borders, competition will likely emerge between businesses that were historically segmented due to their location in different cities, states or countries.  Emerging Internet-based companies, for instance, will be able to reach a broader marketplace and therefore, could thrive in this new environment, even if they may not have in their entrenched local market.
<P></P>
<LI>Among incumbents and new entrants using enabling technologies. As more individuals and businesses deploy advanced technologies and information services, competition will arise between incumbents and new market entrants. Small- and medium-sized businesses may soon be able to provide services previously offered only by large companies.  Customized small entrants will be able to interact directly with consumers, sidestepping middlemen and challenging vertically integrated enterprises.  This growth of competition between previously distinct industries has the potential to create revolutionary changes in the way business is done and in the structure of the global economy. Over the long term, various industries may be completely redefined, as nontraditional institutions or non-institutional settings offer new products and services.  Electronic payments and banking systems are examples from the financial industry.
<P></P>
This phenomenon can be seen in the growing on-line service market. Just a short time ago, the market was controlled by a few providers such as America OnLine, Prodigy and CompuServe.  Now, hundreds of new entrants, including companies that come from dissimilar consumer markets such as video rental and local telephone, are trying to carve out a portion of this market.
<P></P>
</UL>
<I>Digitization Benefits Consumers and Business.</I>
<P></P>
As described above, digitization injects the potential for competition within many industries and among many different goods, services and networks. Digitization and competition can foster innovation, increase consumer choice and availability, and reduce the overall cost of goods and services.
<P></P>
Digitization will offer the consumer new products and services that are more efficient or convenient to use.  It will create instant access to national and international information resources, expanding an individual's ability to make educated decisions about economic, health and other personal matters.  It also will enable individuals to perform from home many tasks that otherwise required physical mobility.
<P></P>
Businesses will be able to employ digital solutions throughout their operations.  For example, electronic commerce will speed transactions, reduce costs and open up new avenues for the supply of components and sale of goods.  In addition, companies will have increased flexibility in selecting geographic sites, since electronic communications will make it possible to effectively link divisions scattered across the country.  These and other changes created by digitization and by competition will encourage new market entry.
<P></P>
Further, digitization will have a global effect.  Consumers and businesses from across the globe will be able to build upon and leverage information created by the GII.  New trading relationships will be created.  Digitization and the GII will expand and change the shape of the world economy, benefiting users in every country that fosters its growth.
<P></P>
<hr align=center width=50%>
<H2>DIGITIZATION CREATES CHALLENGES FOR POLICY MAKERS</H2>
<P></P>
As digitization spreads, policy makers and regulators will be challenged to identify new economic principles that are appropriate to the dynamic industries, services and products that will characterize the digital era.  In creating and implementing new policies, it will be important to recognize that the cardinal feature of the digital era should be widespread competition accompanied by increased consumer participation in marketplace choices.  This feature alters the assumptions underlying traditional regulation of these industries and, in many cases, should remove the need for economic regulation.  Failure to address the characteristics of the new environment may actually prevent digitization from delivering its potential benefits to consumers.  The following section outlines the changing foundation for public policy and the challenges that will be faced by decision makers as they address digitization.
<P></P>
<I>Digitization Blurs Distinctions Between Markets.</I>
<P></P>
Digitization has caused many distinctions between existing information appliances, network services and geographic boundaries to erode.  The sharp lines that have traditionally segregated markets have also blurred.  In the past, regulations were designed with these industrial, technological and geographic segmentations in mind.  However, the new technological and economic realities of digitization largely eliminate these segmentations.
<P></P>
Faced with a world without clear boundaries, there is a danger that legislators and regulators may be inclined to fit emerging products, infrastructures and services into old regulatory schemes (e.g., regulating information services under telecommunications rules), subjecting them to out-dated rules for the sake of convenience and precedent.
<P></P>
In many cases, creating a truly competitive marketplace will require a transition period during which important changes must occur.  Yesterday's technological constraints should give way to virtually limitless networks and systems. Monopoly markets should expand to include multiple players.  National and local communications links should be replaced by global ones, and isolated consumers should become empowered.  Public policy makers initially must facilitate this transition by protecting emerging competition from dominant players already in the marketplace.  The ultimate challenge, of course, will be to shift  from specific market regulation to open and deregulated markets.
<P></P>
<I>Old Regulatory Assumptions May Not Apply.</I>
<P></P>
Historically, regulation and active government oversight have been premised on the inability of economic, competitive or social forces to protect citizens from harm.  For example, the inability of a city to support competing cable television networks has justified monopoly franchises of this service.  Meanwhile the existence of a monopoly has in turn justified the imposition of price regulation.
<P></P>
By expanding the competitive options and the availability of goods and services, digitization challenges the regulatory assumption that the marketplace cannot be relied on to respond to consumer needs.  In the example of cable monopolies, it is clear that introducing full competition will encourage market-based pricing, obviating the need for government controls. Similarly, digitization should lead to a re-evaluation of the justification for regulation.
<P></P>
<I>Consumer Protection May Require Different Tools.</I>
<P></P>
At the same time, there is a risk that important public and social goals (such as health and safety) will be undermined by relying on outdated regulations to achieve them.  The public interest continues to demand that government step in to protect consumers from, among other things, dangerous products and fraudulent practices.  Policy makers must understand the effects of digitization on consumers in order to tailor public policy to today's consumer needs.  New technologies and expanded product choices will change the solutions available to individuals faced with specific consumer problems and will alter the extent to which governments must intervene directly.  This change in the way the market addresses individual needs requires a change in our assessment of when and why regulation is necessary.
<P></P>
<I>Incumbents May Resist Market Forces.</I>
<P></P>
Equally alarming is the possibility that incumbents will use regulation to affirmatively block new market entrants.  These incumbents already are actively involved in, and familiar with, the regulatory process in their existing markets.  They are in a position to manipulate the uncertainties surrounding new technologies and players.  This tendency may complicate regulators' attempts to re-structure and liberalize regulations to reflect the competitive environment.
<P></P>
<I>Barriers May Be Created Through Traditional Regulation.</I>
<P></P>
Rapidly changing technology and markets may be hampered by slowly changing laws and regulations.  The time lag opens up the possibility that new products and services will be thwarted by the current regulatory framework.  There already are a number of examples in which regulatory actions, reflecting out-dated assumptions, have reinforced or created barriers to entry for digital technology, product and service suppliers.  These barriers maintain the segregation between industries and markets and will shelter incumbents and traditional markets from new entrants.
<P></P>
Certain barriers, erected through the use of public policy tools, seem aimed at the most fundamental aspects of digitization.  These barriers can constrain immeasurably the growth of a fully open, competitive global market:
<P></P>
<UL>
<LI>Geographic and cultural barriers. Digitization can eliminate geography as a divider of markets and can expand capacity so that no one language or culture will be exclusive. However, state and national licensing schemes, domestic content requirements and cross-border sales limits are being used to shore up existing geographic and jurisdictional divisions between markets.
<P></P>
For example, the treatment of patients and the delivery of medical care today need not be confined to local doctors providing care within a geographically defined community.  Using digital, broadband communications networks,  patients can consult expert physicians in other regions and isolated or rural doctors can access innovations in research hubs.  However, these benefits are being sharply limited in the United States, due to the state-by-state licensing of medical professionals.
<P></P>
Strong licensing requirements are necessary to protect patients from unprofessional medical care, and states have a clear interest in ensuring that such requirements are enforced.  Unfortunately, the existing licensing system may prevent life-saving use of long-distance telemedicine and other innovative digital treatment methods.  Kansas, South Dakota, Oklahoma and Nevada bar physicians without a state license from practicing telemedicine there.  At least 20 other states are considering similar restrictions.
<P></P>
In the long-run, the public interest demands that a regulatory system be created that recognizes the role that digital technology can play in delivery of health care information.  The revised system should maximize both patient protection and wide access to medical care.
<P></P>
<LI>Classification barriers.  Classification of products and services into narrow categories for tariff purposes (or for any other regulatory purpose, such as licensing or interconnection) limits consumer choice.  In some cases, these classifications lead directly to higher customs duties and other consumer costs.  In other cases, mandatory technical standards and local testing and certification requirements limit suppliers' options and restrict consumer choice.
<P></P>
Many countries are moving to reclassify certain information technology products.  For instance, the European Union (EU) may reclassify computer imports both to limit the competition by foreign companies and to raise additional revenue for the European Commission.  Reclassification efforts have been justified by claiming that computers can now serve as telecommunications devices (if they contain modems or a local area network (LAN) card) or video reproduction devices and televisions (if they support multimedia functions such as full motion video, audio reproduction or television signal displays).  In 1995, the EU classified CD-ROM drives as video reproduction equipment because the CD-ROM can store enough data to develop full motion video.  Although the World Customs Organization, at Japan's request, found the European CD-ROM classification to be inappropriate, the EU has not accepted this finding.  In addition, there continues to exist a major controversy over the reclassification of LAN equipment as telecommunications devices.
<P></P>
At the time of this report's release, these attempts at reclassification are ongoing and may result in a significant increase in import tariffs paid by manufacturers.  More importantly, due to the higher costs of the appliances, these actions may limit consumer choice, thereby stifling the growth of the GII and preventing Europe from being the strong player it wants to be in the information society.
<P></P>
<LI>Barriers to new technologies.  Applying existing regulations to digital products and services could limit the usefulness or availability to consumers of new technologies.
<P></P>
For example, the Food and Drug Administration (FDA) oversees all medical devices.  Any new applications that are developed must undergo FDA approval before they can be used broadly.  While this process is extremely important for consumers, it must be applied thoughtfully to electronic and networked technologies.  Unless amended, existing regulations will increase the costs of launching new devices and may ultimately prevent their use.
<P></P>
This was illustrated by events at the University of North Carolina.  There, special software has been developed which, when run on high performance computers, can render a 3-D image of a cancerous tumor and model the reaction of the tumor when treated with a specific dose of radiation.  This process has been effective in treating cancerous tumors and minimizing tissue damage.  However, in order to make this system available beyond the North Carolina community, it must be approved as a medical device by the FDA.  The FDA regulations did not contemplate medical software and even a slight change in code requires time-consuming and expensive FDA re-approval.  Further, the FDA requires approval of complete systems and could therefore designate an entire telemedicine network as a medical device.
<P></P>
<LI>The barrier of false scarcity.  Historically, scarcity of resources, such as radio spectrum, has been a linchpin of certain regulations in the U.S. and abroad.  Scarcity has led to a complex framework of government licenses for operators and providers of services.  If it continues to direct regulation, it will limit dramatically the extent to which digital technologies can be offered to consumers.  Because new technological developments, such as digital compression, allow scarce resources to be used more efficiently and effectively, scarcity is of much less importance as a base for regulation today.
<P></P>
<LI>The barrier to market solutions.  In the past, regulators and policy makers have often imposed rigid standards, product criteria or universal service requirements to correct perceived failures of the market.  As the digital era unfolds, these regulatory responses, if applied to newly emerging industries, could unnecessarily distort the development of the GII.  Further, from the standpoint of technology alone, the digital marketplace can be expected to evolve rapidly and in unexpected ways.  If allowed to develop freely, the competitive marketplace may produce solutions that address many consumer needs and, therefore, allow consumers to decide whether they use a particular technology or service.  Premature regulatory requirements will deprive both consumers and the private sector of the ability to make these important decisions themselves.
<P></P>
</UL>
<I>Today's Challenges</I>
<P></P>In the United States and around the world, policy makers are confronting a whole new set of factors that affect the telecommunications, information and mass media industries.  [SEE ATTACHED <A HREF="sidebar.html">SIDE BAR</A> OF IMPEDIMENTS TO THE GII.]  The choices and debates policy makers face will be shaped by the emergence of digitization and its consequences.
<P></P>
<UL>
<LI>United States.  The Telecommunications Act of 1996 seeks to sweep away the historic divisions between the United States telecommunications, cable and broadcast industries.  The Act recognizes that a transition will be needed to foster emerging competition among existing providers and entrusts the Federal Communications Commission (FCC) with implementing the Act's provisions.
<P></P>
The FCC's ability to foresee the new digital environment and to provide for progressive deregulation in many areas will help shape the marketplace.  Among the issues to be addressed in the next twelve months are:  interoperability and
interconnection; universal service definition and supports; radio spectrum; and regulatory incentives to encourage deployment of advanced telecommunications capacity.
<P></P>
<LI>State approaches.  The states and public utility regulators have started to address questions raised by electronic communications and commerce, particularly as they relate to using the Internet for conducting business.  Legislatures in various states are deliberating Internet-related issues such as the validity of electronic signatures, the punishment for on-line crimes, the taxation of electronic mail and other transactions, and the applicability of universal service obligations.  These decisions and possibility of inconsistent state-by-state regulation will determine whether the GII continues to grow or becomes stagnant.
<P></P>
<LI>International approaches.  Because of its global nature, every country and region has a vested interest in promulgating its own rules on the GII.  In fact, in mid-1994, the European Union announced its own Action Plan to achieve a global information society.  The action plan identifies issues on which EU policy decisions are needed to create the appropriate legal and regulatory framework.  Some of these decisions include liberalizing Europe's telecommunications and cable infrastructure, financing universal service, improving intellectual property rights and privacy protection, and deploying advanced networks and applications.  In addition, many other countries, such as Japan and Singapore, are actively engaged in debates over how their countries will implement the GII.
<P></P>
</UL>
<hr align=center width=50%>
<H2>PUBLIC POLICY FUNDAMENTALS FOR THE FUTURE</H2>
<P></P>
The private sector must be ready to assist decision makers in the development of a public policy framework for the digital era that ensures the full benefits of the GII are realized.  Working with policy makers, industry must articulate new, affirmative doctrines to replace the inefficient regulatory models of the past and follow that action with a proactive public-private sector agenda that promotes those new doctrines.
<P></P>
The following ten policy fundamentals are suggested as a starting point in developing this new framework and a longer-term agenda. These concepts must be refined and evaluated in the context of both domestic and international debate.
<P></P>
<OL>
<LI>Consumer choice is the main benefit of digitization.  Digitization  promises to increase consumers' choice of products and services.  This benefit will be realized only if previously segregated industries and their products and services are allowed to cross over old barriers and compete for consumers' attention.
<P></P>
<LI>Let the market do the work.  Governments must adopt public policies that  foster competition and market growth.  Regulations should strive to impose the fewest possible burdens on the market.  Regulators should err on the side of policies that are the least invasive and offer consumers the greatest choice.  Prescriptive government policies should be reserved for circumstances in which there is an overwhelming need for intervention.
<P></P>
<UL>
<LI>In order to realize the full benefits of digitization, policies must encourage competition between previously segmented sectors of the information economy.
<P></P>
<LI>These policies should let consumers drive the market.  Market-driven solutions are more likely to reflect the needs of consumers and be available at a range of affordable prices than those solutions dictated by government.
<P></P>
<LI>Regulations generally should not be imposed on markets that are in rapid flux, since market forces frequently obviate the need for any government intrusion.
<P></P>
<LI>Before government intervenes to craft regulations or license requirements, industry should be challenged to develop solutions to perceived market limitations or failures.  An industry-led technological approach, coupled with an industry-government dialogue, will likely yield an effective framework that limits regulation or avoids it.
<P></P>
<LI>Mandatory technical standards and public service obligations should not be imposed unless it is clear that the market cannot respond.  To avoid premature regulatory impositions, criteria should be developed to determine when the market has reached its potential.
<P></P>
<LI>Regulation should empower consumers to make choices based on their own specific circumstances, rather than direct their behavior through subsidies to operators or producers.  This may require targeted subsidies to consumers or well-thought-out access points to public facilities as a short-run solution for certain consumer groups.
<P></P>
</UL>
<LI>Short-term transitional requirements must be addressed.  Unfortunately, the digital era will not suddenly create an open and competitive market in all sectors or in all regions of the world.  Historically, the communications marketplace has been dominated by monopoly providers of telecommunications and cable services and by limited numbers of broadcast licenses.  Meanwhile the computer industry has been largely unregulated.  Digitization changes the potential for competition and interaction among these players.
<P></P>
<LI>The chart below describes the necessary regulatory transition.  The optimal outcome is a world in which the consumer drives the market and competition is prevalent.  However, without the proper transitional framework, existing players and old institutional patterns could shift the process toward greater concentration (e.g. full-service digital monopolies), a less-than-optimal outcome.
<P></P>
<UL>
<LI>In certain cases, if there is a history of monopoly, or if the industry has been heavily regulated, there may be a need for a formal regulatory transition to an open, competitive market place.  This may include the need to protect new market entrants from an existing dominant operator that could leverage its market power to stifle competition.
<P></P>
<LI>Governments must provide the necessary leadership by creating new regulatory frameworks that address short-term transitional needs, while still moving toward competition, open markets and industry-led solutions.
<P></P>
</UL>
<LI>A global digital common market should emerge from the GII.  The GII can be the foundation of a global, digital common market in which world-wide open trade in goods and services is facilitated by electronic technology.  To achieve this goal, government and industry must tear down the barriers of location, origin and national identity that have historically blocked goods and services at the borders.  Generally, attempts to offer new products and services across borders should be encouraged, and regulatory efforts to impede the development of the GII should be discouraged.  To move from today's world of trade barriers to a global, digital common market, a number of regulatory matters must be resolved in favor of open, competitive markets.  Among the more critical matters for the digital common market are the following:
<P></P>
<UL>
<LI>The globalization of digital networks and the growth of the GII depend on favorable resolution of industry and user concerns regarding interoperability, security and intellectual property rights protection.  Less immediate, but nonetheless important, are questions of privacy, contract law, fraud and taxes.
<P></P>
<LI>Mutual recognition and non-discrimination policies are an important first step to increase cross-border access to goods and services.
<P></P>
<LI>Customs tariffs, rigid local certification and mandatory testing requirements can stifle competition and act as a tax on innovation, impeding the natural development of the emerging technologies.  These product-specific barriers hinder user access to the GII by making all goods and services less affordable and accessible.
<P></P>
Countries that choose not to encourage the growth of the GII and that do not become part of the digital common market may find that they have adversely affected the ability of their residents to use the electronic marketplace and, ultimately, compete in the global economy.
<P></P>
</UL>
<LI>Consumer empowerment is an important goal.  Various circumstances exist in which legislators and regulators must examine whether the marketplace is able to meet specialized consumer needs, such as access needs of consumers with sight, hearing or mobility restrictions.  The new technologies of the digital era offer the promise of expanded product choices for these consumers.  Public policy should encourage the development of this marketplace.
<P></P>
<LI>Public access to the GII should be encouraged.  Rigid prescriptions for universal service should not be used to achieve widespread consumer access to the products and services of the GII.  Instead, governments should emphasize individual choice, open markets and common points of access to public facilities.
<P></P>
<LI>International GII standards should be developed by industry.  Isolated, incompatible infrastructures must be avoided by encouraging interoperability at key interfaces.  Rather than developing or mandating standards, government's role should be to ensure that incompatible national certification and testing requirements do not discourage cross-border trade.
<P></P>
<LI>Our basic legal thinking must recognize the emergence of cyberspace and its characteristics.  Traditional thinking about property law, personal rights and other legal issues will continue to be relevant to the new information infrastructure.  However, the legal framework of the future should also specifically recognize that transactions and communications will take place without reference to physical form and location.  Many assumptions underlying  the traditional laws governing personal and property rights may be changed as a result of these differences.  This, in turn, may change the nature of the laws needed to encourage users to act responsibly in this new environment.
<P></P>
<LI>Laws of general application are preferable to sector-specific regulations.  Reliance on general legal concepts, rather than on idiosyncratic or sector-specific statutes, is generally more prudent.  Laws not crafted to the language of a particular industry or technology, such as antitrust laws, are often more readily adaptable to changing circumstances and are technology and industry neutral.
<P></P>
<LI>Our goal should be phasing-out economic regulation.  Competitive,  deregulated markets are the goal.  However, in the near term, governments may need to impose regulations on market conduct to foster competition.  New economic regulations, if needed, should contain sunset provisions to ensure that they do not become permanent barriers.  Further, governments should take notice that new market dynamics may change players incentives to engage in various types of conduct.  These changes should be factored into evaluating how other public needs, such as health and safety, should be met by new laws and regulations.
<P></P>
</OL>
<hr align=center width=50%>
<H2>CONCLUSION</H2>
<P></P>
The digital age offers the possibility of economic and social growth on a global scale.  However, to realize this potential, policy makers will need to address new digital technologies, widespread competitive opportunities and emerging issues of consumer protection and empowerment in a worldwide context.  In many instances, industry itself will offer solutions that are preferable to government mandates.  Rather than regulation, a new framework is needed to encourage the marketplace to meet economic challenges.  The principles outlined in this paper are a starting point for cooperative decision-making between government and the private sector.
<P></P>
