<hr align=left width=33%>

<a name="execsum"><h3>Executive Summary</h3>

The Information Age promises an explosion in economic growth, technological innovation
and educational opportunities that could improve the standard of living and the quality of
life around the world.  To achieve this promise, the private sector, with the encouragement
of government, is building the Global Information Infrastructure (GII), the electronic
pathways that will carry vast quantities of valuable commercial, scientific, and educational
information between individuals, companies and customers, doctors and patients, students
and teachers.<p>

While the GII offers unprecedented access to and exchange of information, it also exposes
users to breaches of confidentiality, disruption of their operations, destruction of
intellectual property and outright theft.  These are serious concerns because electronic
data in digital form -- or cyberproperty -- is emerging as the most valuable currency of the
Information Age.  Users of the GII have the need, right, and responsibility to protect the
access to, and the confidentiality of, their information.  They also have the right and
responsibility to determine the appropriate type and strength of protection for their
cyberproperty.<p>

Consider the case of U.S. companies, which currently lead the global information
technology market.  U.S. export control policies severely limit their ability to provide
customers global security solutions, based on encryption, that are seamlessly integrated
into their computer systems.  If U.S. companies are prohibited from meeting this growing
demand for secure electronic commerce, non-U.S. competitors are ready, willing and able
to do so.  In fact, many already are exporting security solutions stronger than those U.S.
firms can export.<p>

The advantage that competitors will derive from their ability to meet the growing demand
for secure, integrated global solutions will result in loss of market share for U.S. computer
systems manufacturers, not only in the encryption market, but also in the general computer
systems market.  Emerging Security Needs and U.S. Competitiveness: Impact of Export
Controls on Cryptographic Technology, a CSPP study released in December 1995,
estimates that the potential exposure to the U.S. information industry's annual revenues
could range from $30 to $60 billion by the year 2000.<p>

While individuals and industry have a compelling interest in protecting their cyberproperty,
the government has an interest in gathering intelligence and enforcing the law.  In addition
to lawful wiretaps and searches, the government meets its security objectives by
clandestinely intercepting information traveling on the GII among criminals and terrorists. 
The government is concerned that the spread of global security solutions may adversely
affect its law enforcement and international intelligence gathering responsibilities.  But 
strong security solutions are already available in the international marketplace to legitimate
users and terrorist and criminal elements alike.  Given this reality, the government  efforts
to prevent the global spread of security technology are doomed to fail.<p>

Governments and the private sector must reach a consensus on broad principles that can
serve as the foundation for a rational export control policy.  CSPP has developed a set of
security principles that offer a framework for agreement on a reasonable and achievable
national policy.  CSPP has also drafted specific recommendations for action that can
satisfy the U.S. computer industry's immediate export  needs while a  comprehensive
policy solution is designed.  How effectively individual users, the private sector, and  
governments work together to define a security policy that fairly balances competing
economic and security interests, will determine the scope and growth rate of the GII.<p>

CSPP believes existing and proposed U.S. policies controlling cryptography should be
based on the following security principles: 
<ol>
<li>Users have the need, right, and responsibility to determine the type and strength of security
required; 
<li>Governments should not impose unilateral controls on trade in commercial security
technology;
<li>Multilateral controls must cover all major sources of commercial security solutions
world-wide; 
<li>Commercial security solutions should be treated as commercial products under the
Department of Commerce export controls; 
<li>The availability of cryptography should not be regulated according to technology levels; 
<li>No regulatory distinctions should be made between hardware and software security solutions;
<li>Industry should be responsible for developing standards for commercial security solutions; 
<li>Actions permitted under the existing U.S. law should be exhausted before creating new laws
to address issues of government access; 
<li>There should continue to be no controls on domestic use of cryptography; and
<li>Export controls should not be used to impose controls indirectly on domestic availability of
cryptographic products.</ol>

Given the present market realities and government needs, CSPP recommends the
following  first steps to promote the legitimate use of security by individuals and companies
and to address the U.S. government's intelligence gathering and law enforcement
interests:
<ol>
<li>Link the decontrol of U.S. commercial cryptographic products to the availability of
competitive products in the international marketplace;
<li>Permit the export of stronger U.S. commercial cryptographic products, withouttechnology
restrictions, to legitimate, commercial end users;
<li>Discuss the export of stronger U.S. commercial cryptographic products that meet reasonable
government access needs; and
<li>Embargo U.S. commercial cryptographic products in  terrorist countries.</ul>

<hr align=center width=25%>

<a name="intro"><h3>Introduction</h3>

The GII offers new economic and educational opportunities to the corporate giants of Wall
Street,  small businesses and cottage industries of Main Street and individual residents
of Maple Street. It  allows companies to communicate more easily with regionally dispersed
departments and with increasing numbers of suppliers, partners, and customers around
the globe.  It is a cost-effective option for electronic commerce, opening new markets and
reducing the cost of doing business.  Companies that do not take advantage of the GII will
lose their competitive edge in the 21st century.<p>

The very aspects of the GII that make it so attractive as a tool for communications and
commerce -- its openness and breadth -- also create risks to the confidentiality, integrity,
and authenticity of data transmitted over the GII or stored in facilities attached to the GII. 
Unless users are assured that they can adequately secure their valuable information, the
GII will not realize its full economic, educational, and scientific benefits.  Companies that
are not permitted to supply secure solutions to users will forfeit enormous commercial,
economic, technological, and indeed global security leadership opportunities.<p>

CSPP's February 1995 report Perspectives on the Global Information Infrastructure
specified security as one of five substantive priorities that governments and the private
sector must address to ensure that the GII reaches its potential as a viable, cost-effective
tool. <p>

Perspectives on Security in the Information Age reviews the security issues that could
hobble development of the GII and  recommends changes to current and proposed U.S.
export policies to allow individuals and companies to protect their electronic information,
transactions, and communications worldwide.  This report establishes security principles
by which U.S. policies should be measured.  It concludes with recommended policy
changes that are in keeping with these principles.<p>

<hr align=center width=25%>

<a name="concept"><h3>The Concept of Cyberproperty</h3>

Electronic data in digital form -- or cyberproperty -- is emerging as the most valuable
currency of the Information Age.  We are on the verge of an explosion in the volume of
information being exchanged among individuals and companies via the GII.  Increasingly
this information is confidential and highly valuable.  Thus the files and messages that are
created in computers, stored on disks, and sent over communications links are becoming
more valuable than the computers, disks and network lines over which they travel.<p>

<a name="concept2"><h4>Cyberproperty at Risk</h4>

A decade ago breaking into a computer system was viewed more as a prank than as an
act with possibly dire consequences.  Laws against unauthorized access or hacking were
scarce.  Today most observers consider hacking a serious crime because once inside a
computer system, hackers can open "file cabinets" and read electronic files; pilfer, change
or delete information; and even steal documents.  Cyberproperty that is completely
unprotected, or "naked," in the GII is exposed to such unauthorized and unwanted access.<p>

Unprotected cyberproperty faces various types and degrees of exposure, just as tangible
property faces a range of threats from vandalism and theft to organized crime and
terrorism.   An individual hacker or credit fraud artist wreaks a different kind of havoc than
do well-financed criminal organizations, industrial spies or international terrorists seeking
to paralyze systems and infrastructure.  Unless effective security measures are
implemented, the potential exposure to global users is projected to reach between $320
billion and $640 billion by 2000.<br>
<br>
<a name="concept1"><TABLE border>
<TR>
     <TD align=center>
<font size=+2>Examples of Risks to GII Users</font>
     </TD>                                
<TR> 
     <TD>
<strong>Telemedicine and Privacy:</strong> The GII equalizes the disparity between developed
and underdeveloped countries by allowing individuals in underdeveloped areas access to
specialized medical expertise found only in developed nations.  However, if these medical
records are transmitted unprotected from a doctor's office to a hospital, individuals can be
exposed to violations of privacy rights and of the confidentiality between a doctor and patient.
Records tampered with by a vandal could result in a potentially disastrous mis-diagnosis and
dangerous treatment.<p>
                                
<strong>Engineering Designs and Industrial Espionage:</strong>  With the GII, companies can
more easily collaborate in strategic joint ventures for a particular product.  New designs
transmitted unprotected from a firm in one country to a firm in another country are subject to
industrial espionage, alterations in design, or outright theft.<p>
                                
<strong>Individuals and Electronic Commerce:</strong> Electronic commerce offers individuals
and companies alike new ways of doing business and reaching new markets.  However, simple
connections to open networks expose credit card information, as well as home computer files like
household spreadsheets, to outside access.<p>
                                
<strong>Small Companies in the GII:</strong>The GII offers new opportunities for small
companies to explore international markets.  Like their large counterparts, small companies
making a proposal to a prospective customer cannot afford to expose bid specifications and
amounts to global competitors. <p>
     </TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>                 
              
<a name="concept3"><h4>The Right to Protect Cyberproperty </h4>
                                
The ownership of tangible property, such as manufactured goods, confers on individuals
and companies the right and responsibility to control its use.   Custodians, such as doctors
responsibile for patients' files,  have the responsibility to safeguard the property entrusted
to their care.  Owners and custodians can choose the level of protection that best meets
their security needs, based on the threat to and value of their property.  They may choose
from a variety of security tools, including locks, alarms, and armed guards.<p>
                                
Similarly, business, individual, and custodial owners of intangible cyberproperty have the
right and responsibility to protect it as it travels through or is stored in the GII.  They also
have the right to determine the level of security required to safeguard  their cyberproperty,
and they can make that choice from among a number of security tools available today. <p>
                                
One way to think about the strength of available security solutions is to consider the
options for sending a letter.  Individuals, businesses, and governments secure information
being transmitted through the worldwide postal system with envelopes.  If greater security
is desired, envelopes can be sent certified, return receipt required or by courier.  Just as
increased levels of security are needed for the documents transmitted by mail, so
increased levels of security are needed for the documents and other data transmitted
through the GII. <p>
                                
<a name="concept4"><h4>The Tools to Protect Cyberproperty</h4>
                                
No one government, corporation or person controls the GII, which spans more than 100
countries and has millions of users connected to it. As a result, the GII cannot be secured,
so individual pieces of cyberproperty must be protected.  Means of protection to specific
networks such as firewalls, secure tokens and tamper-resistant modules cannot protect
messages and data being transmitted through the GII.  While large companies have been
able to protect cyberproperty through private, leased lines, the escalating cost and lack
of flexibility to connect to anyone, anywhere makes continuing this practice ineffective and
expensive. That leaves encryption as the best method for safeguarding cyberproperty
traveling on the GII.<br>
<br>                                
<TABLE Border>
<TR>
     <TD align=center><font size=+2>What Is Encryption?</font></TD>
<TR>
     <TD>
Encryption is a tool that individuals and companies can use to secure cyberproperty on the GII
from intrusion and theft much the same way a padlock protects property in a locker. 
Cryptography is the science of encrypting and decrypting data. <p>
                                
While a padlock employs only three or four tumblers, computers have the potential to employ
many more numbers as part of their combinations.   If a padlock has three tumblers, each with
10 digits, there are 1,000 possible combinations that a thief might have to try to open the lock --
at least several hours of manual labor.  A computerized cyberlock with as many as five
"tumblers," would take a thief with access to an off-the-shelf PC on several seconds to try all
100,000 possible combinations.  Clearly, a cyberlock with more tumblers is needed to protect
cyberproperty on the GII.  Encryption is available in both hardware and software forms and at
differing levels of strength.<p>

Whether they use a cyberlock or a padlock, the right and responsibility to secure the individual
property rests with the property owner.<p>  
     </TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<br>
<hr align=center width=25%>
<a name="security"><h3>Competitiveness and the Demand for Security in the GII</h3>

As businesses rely on the opportunities afforded them by the GII, confidential and
sensitive data must be protected from vandals, thieves, industrial spies and terrorists. 
Because of the increased number of linked networks and reduced costs of computing,
escalating demand for stronger security solutions is inevitable.  Already, growing reliance
on transmitting purchase orders and credit card numbers over phone lines and open
computer networks has created a demand for appropriate security measures.  Security for
businesses joined in strategic alliances, such as joint ventures, is especially critical when
companies share confidential information over networked computer systems. <p>

The demand for cryptographic-based security solutions is diverse and dependent upon a
variety of factors, such as sensitivity of the data, value of the data, security costs,
performance requirements, and implementation methods.  There is no "one-size-fits-all"
encryption solution.<p>

<a name="security1"><h4>Demand for More and Stronger Security </h4>

CSPP's Emerging Security Needs and U.S. Competitiveness:  Impact of Export Controls
on Cryptographic Technology found that businesses in industries such as financial
services, telecommunications/wireless, petrochemicals and pharmaceuticals need strong
security solutions to protect financial transactions and valuable research.<p>

The study also found that companies currently using security solutions are highly sensitive
to the increasing vulnerability of their systems to outside penetration, which can result in
direct financial losses and privacy invasions.  For example, a large multi-national
corporation was forced to shut down its computers for 72 hours to assess the damage from
someone infiltrating its Internet link.  In another instance, a large communications company
suffered a substantial financial loss when 100,000 stolen calling card numbers were used
to place $50 million worth of fraudulent calls.  When a competitor stole its unprotected
files, a U.S.-based manufacturer lost a $350 million contract that would have employed
more than 3,000 workers.<p>

Recently, a French student broke the strongest encryption that can be readily exported
from the U.S. for general GII applications.  By simply using computers to test every
possible combination to decode the message, the student cracked the code in eight days. 
The effort cost an estimated $10,000 in processing costs.   As the cost of computing goes
down, vulnerability in the GII will go up. <p>

Even strong encryption used today by the federal government and the financial services
industry may not be adequate to secure data in a few years.  This year the American
Banking Association recommends using triple Data Encryption Standard (DES) -- virtually
unbreakable encryption -- to safeguard financial data.  And forecasters believe the federal
government is unlikely to recertify DES as its federal standard because it won't be strong
enough by 1998.<p>

<a name="security2"><h4>Demand for Global Security Solutions </h4>

Security solutions that emerge over the coming years will have to be global in nature. 
Competition is driving more businesses to rely on international suppliers, partners and
customers.  Likewise, the GII recognizes no political or geographic boundaries.  Therefore,
international electronic commerce will require universally trusted security solutions. 
Computer systems manufacturers must be able to produce global solutions that also meet
universal export requirements.      
<br>
<br>

<TABLE border>
<TR>
     <TD align=center><font size=+2>What Is Required to Meet Security Goals For The
GII?</font>
     </TD>
<TR>
     <TD>
<ul>
<li>All participating countries must adopt standards to support security mechanisms that are
acceptable to the private sector and suitable to commercial transactions.  These standards must
also ensure privacy and authentication.  This may require nations to adopt commercial security
solutions that are different and separate from solutions for national security and diplomatic
purposes.

<li>The U.S. government must cooperate with industry to resolve U.S. policy concerns that have
blocked acceptance of international encryption mechanisms necessary for commercial
transactions.  

<li>The private sector and government should convene a joint international conference to address
the need for security mechanisms to support commercial applications and to develop a strategy
for implementing acceptable security solutions.  
</ul>
<h6>Excerpted from Perspectives on the Global Information Infrastructure, CSPP, February,
1995</h6>
     </TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>

<br>
<br>
<a name="security3"><h4>Global Competition and the Inevitability of Supply</h4>

There are more than 300 companies that develop and export cryptographic products from
the U.S. and more than 355 companies that provide similar products outside the U.S. 
However, U.S-based providers of cryptography can only sell their most effective security
solutions within the U.S.<p>

While U.S. information systems companies derive more than 50 percent of their revenue
from overseas, they also are restricted from exporting strong security solutions, except in
the case of related companies.  Moreover, they are barred from producing the integrated
information systems, complete with a range of security options, that customers worldwide
are demanding.   Further, they are prohibited from exporting pluggable systems, where no
cryptology is exported, but explicit interfaces are provided to allow users to "plug in" a
locally available solution.<p>

Given these constraints, non-U.S. competitors offering integrated, interoperable, market-driven
information systems will attract sales not only from foreign firms, but also from U.S.
companies.  Japanese and German firms are working on integrated information systems
products that will have encryption embedded in the system.   Other producers are racing
to fill the void left by U.S. firms to supply the worldwide demand for global security
solutions.  They will leverage this opportunity to gain market share in other segments of
the information technology industry, including computer systems sales where U.S.
companies currently have the lead.  This will erode U.S. market share in total systems
sales and undermine U.S. jobs and technological leadership.  This could expose $30
billion to $60 billion of the U.S. information industry's annual revenues by the year 2000.<p>

<hr align=center width=25%>

<a name="issues"><h3>Issues of Government Control and Access </h3>

While individuals and industry have a compelling interest in protecting their cyberproperty,
the government has an interest in gathering intelligence and enforcing the law.  In addition
to lawful wiretaps and searches, the government meets its security objectives by
clandestinely intercepting information traveling on the GII among criminals and terrorists.<p>

The government is concerned that the spread of global security solutions may adversely
affect its law enforcement and international intelligence gathering responsibilities.  This
concern ignores the fact that strong security solutions are already available in the
international marketplace to legitimate users and terrorist and criminal elements alike. 
Given this reality,  government  efforts to prevent the global spread of security technology
are doomed to fail.<p>

<a name="issues1"><h4>Enforcing the Law and Gathering International Intelligence </h4>

Domestic development and use of encryption by individuals and companies have never
been controlled within the U.S.  However, the U.S. government has begun to argue for
broader authority to carry out law enforcement activities, such as wire-tapping.  Law
enforcement officials say they are concerned that the spread of very strong encryption
would obstruct their ability to monitor communications and access electronic files.   CSPP
believes existing methods to obtain information, such as search warrants, surveillance and
other types of intelligence gathering resources available under current law, should be
sufficient to address this concern.<p>

<a name="issues2"><h4>Recovery of Stored Data</h4>

Today, companies that encrypt data usually hold copies of their keys within the company
to safeguard against losses, mishaps, disgruntled employees, or other contingencies.  This
practice is known as key retention or self escrow.  While companies usually do not ask
third parties to hold copies of their keys, key escrow systems might provide a useful data
recovery feature for some commercial customers who desire strong encryption but are
concerned about losing their keys.<p>
<br>

<TABLE border>
<TR>
     <TD align=center><font size=+2>What Are Crypto Keys?</font>
     </TD>
<TR>
     <TD>
Anyone who has used a padlock knows that it is necessary to keep a copy of the combination
stored safely away from the lock in case the original series of numbers is lost or forgotten. 
Crypto keys are like the combination to that padlock.  Copies are routinely made as backup
for accessing data secured with encryption in the eventuality that the encryption key cannot
be found. <p>
                                
A backup key for cyberproperty is even more important than one for physical property, because in
the GII there is no option to force entry.   Household tools can break open a padlock.  There are
no equivalent tools in cyberspace.<p>
                                
The concept of key escrow requires that backup keys be held by a third party or parties. 
Third parties could be private, commercial key holders or public, government key holders.<p>
     </TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>

<br>
<br>
<a name="issues3"><h4>The Administration Proposes Mandatory Key Escrow for Exports</h4>
                                
To access encrypted data, the Administration is pursuing a mandatory key escrow solution for
export of commercially available encryption.  Under a generic key escrow scenario, a copy of the
key used to encrypt or decrypt a message would be held in escrow by a third party approved by
the U.S. government.  The government would be able to access the escrowed key and encrypted
data only after meeting certain requirements, such as obtaining a search warrant.  In theory, the
strength of encryption would be irrelevant because the government would have access to an
authorized key to decrypt data.<p>
                                
While it is the responsibility of the  government to enforce the law and gather international
intelligence, a key escrow system is but one method to achieve those objectives. Not everybody
agrees that individuals and companies must provide the federal government with authorized keys
to their encrypted cyberproperty.<p>
                                
The discussion between users of cryptographic products, industry, and the  government is
whether 1) making backup keys to encrypted data is mandatory or voluntary,  2) backup keys
must be held by third parties, in escrow, and 3) such third-party systems will be commercially
viable.<p>
                                
Some individuals and companies may not be concerned about purchasing a product that
has keys in escrow available for authorized government use.  However, others will demand
availability of products without key escrow features and will look to non-U.S. vendors for
these solutions.  Independent of government policy concerns, the complexity, expense,
and potential abuses of a key escrow approach may make it unworkable or commercially
unacceptable to many users worldwide.<p>
                                
Government access to encrypted data may be required to enforce the law or gather
international intelligence, if potential uses of encryption are deemed to be a substantial
risk.  In developing the cryptographic products for these uses, voluntary, industry-led
standards should prevail over government-mandated, design-based solutions. 
Government, working closely with industry, should develop reasonable and achievable
objectives for government access.  This will allow industry groups to craft standards and
designs that meet government requirements for access to encrypted communications and
files using the strongest cryptographic techniques. <p>

<hr align=center width=25%>
                                
<a name="export"><h3>Consequences of U.S. Export Policies</h3>
                                
While demand for security products is growing, U.S. export policies on cryptography
remain frozen in the assumptions of the 1950s.  The State Department, for example,
controls not only the export of hardware products that encrypt data for transmission or
storage, but also the export of encryption software, as munitions -- items that are deemed
"inherently military in character."<p>
                                
Such government controls of strong encryption for export are antithetical to the needs of
individuals and companies to protect their cyberproperty in the age of the GII.<p>
                                
Informal inter-governmental agreements and national laws that allow for exceptions to U.S.
policy regulating export of encryption products exist, but their interpretation and
enforcement varies country by country.  Over time, the U.S.'s restrictive interpretation and
practice threaten to drive sales, technologies, and jobs to non-U.S. competitors.<p>
                                
Current export policies controlling the availability of U.S. security products threaten to
harm not just critical industries such as banking, telecommunications, pharmaceutical, and
petrochemical, but also the computer industry by restricting sales.  These industries and
others are driving the demand for strong security, and non-U.S. vendors are providing
solutions.  If current U.S. export policies remain unchanged, information systems sales and
technologies will erode, and jobs may be jeopardized.  In addition, the architecture of the
predominant security products will be controlled by those countries that do not impose
strict controls.  Ironically, U.S. export policies, created to protect  national security, are
likely to have an adverse impact on the U.S. economy and ability of the U.S. to gather
intelligence and enforce the law.<p>
                                
Current U.S. policies may:
<ul type=square>
<li>Restrict the development and availability of security solutions provided by U.S. firms. 
The need and demand for global security solutions are growing, but current export policies
restrict the availability of U.S. products abroad.  With substantial revenues generated overseas,
U.S. firms cannot afford to develop security solutions that cannot be exported or will be
unacceptable to customers.  This will retard the development in the U.S. of future security and
other information technologies;<p>
                                
<li>Allow non-U.S. competitors to develop and provide global security solutions.  The need for
cryptography to protect data in the GII, together with the declining cost of cryptographic
technologies, will outstrip the efforts of the federal government to control development and
availability.  As a result, non-U.S. competitors will supply cryptographic products.  Individuals
and companies unwilling to be exposed in the GII will purchase non-U.S. security solutions;<p>
                                
<li>Drive future computer sales to firms that can provide strong security solutions.  U.S. firms
must sell computer systems outside the U.S. without strong cryptography.  To protect
cyberproperty, individuals and companies abroad must purchase strong encryption devices
separately and bolt them on to their computer systems. Bolt-on security solutions are expensive
and clumsy.  Customers prefer integrated computer systems -- complete with security solutions. 
As non-U.S. firms provide integrated systems, the U.S. will lose market share not only for the
cryptographic products but also for total computer systems sales;<p>
                                
<li>Drive high technology jobs to firms that can provide strong and integrated security solutions. 
As total U.S. computer systems sales go to foreign firms, so will the high technology jobs;<p>
                                
<li>Drive information systems expertise to other fields.  With development of security solutions
restricted in the U.S., mathematicians, encryption programmers, and security systems experts will
migrate to other fields and diminish American capability to develop security solutions; and <p>
                                
<li>Hinder U.S. government access to future global security solutions. If non-U.S. companies
assume the lead in developing security solutions because U.S. companies are restricted from
exporting strong encryption, the U.S. government may end up with less access to and influence
over new the security solutions.
</ul>

<hr align=center width=25%>

<a name="proposal"><h3>CSPP Proposed Security Principles</h3>
                                
CSPP has developed security principles on which existing and proposed U.S. policies
controlling the availability and use of cryptography should be based.
<ol> 
<li><em>Users have the right, responsibility, and need to determine the type and strength of
protection required.</em>  The absence of a centralized security system in the GII requires
individuals and companies to bear the primary responsibility for their own security.  Global
commercial security solutions are essential if individuals and companies are to protect their
cyberproperty from vandals or thieves.  Users have the right and responsibility to determine the
level of protection required, based on an assessment of a number of factors, including cost, value
of cyberproperty, performance, and risk of penetration into files or communications. <p>
                                
<li><em>Governments should not impose unilateral controls on trade in commercial security
technology.</em>  Unilateral controls are viable only if one source of cryptography exists. Since
cryptography is available worldwide, unilateral controls will not prevent the availability and use of
those products.  <p>
                                
<li><em>Multilateral controls must cover all major sources of commercial security solutions
world-wide.</em>  Multilateral controls are effective only to the extent that all major sources of
commercial security solutions are subject to uniform controls and uniform enforcement.  <p>
                                
<li><em>Commercial security solutions should be treated as commercial products under the
Department of Commerce export controls.</em>  The military is no longer the predominant user
of cryptographic technologies.  As demand and need for stronger commercial security solutions
grow, cryptography should be treated as a commercial product.  <p>
                                
<li><em>Availability of cryptography should not be controlled by technology levels.</em> 
Technology advances will continue to drive the demand for stronger encryption. Export controls
that are tied to technology levels require regular updating, and often lag far behind technology and
commercial need.  Factors such as legitimate commercial use or risk of diversion should help
determine whether controls are necessary.<p>
                                
<li><em>No regulatory distinctions should be made between hardware and software security
solutions.</em> The ultimate result of cryptography is the same, whether the encryption occurs in
hardware or software.<p>
                                
<li><em>Industry has the responsibility to develop standards for commercial security
solutions.</em> Standards for encryption products should be voluntary and industry-led. 
Government-set product design standards stifle innovation and foster customer mistrust in
products built to these design standards.  However, government has a role in working with
industry standards groups to develop mutually agreeable objectives that are both reasonable and
achievable.  Industry standards groups can then develop product standards that factor in these
objectives and meet the need for commercially viable products.  <p>
                                
<li><em>Actions permitted under the existing U.S. legal framework should be exhausted before
creating new laws to address issues of government access.</em>  Before creating new laws to
guarantee access to private communications, the U.S. government should demonstrate clearly that
available courses of action are inadequate.<p>
                                
<li><em>Domestic use of cryptography should continue to be unrestricted.</em> The desire to
withhold cryptographic technologies from a small percentage of users should not proscribe
domestic availability of cryptographic products. <p>
                                 
<li><em>Export controls should not be used to impose controls indirectly on domestic availability
of cryptographic products.</em> oExport controls should be targeted explicitly at international
transactions and should contain no restrictions that would result in controlling the domestic use of
cryptography products.  
</ol>

<hr align=center width=25%>
                                
<a name="recommend"><h3>CSPP Policy Recommendations -- Constructive First Steps </h3>
                                
CSPP recommends that any long-term encryption policy incorporate all 10 security principles
listed above.  CSPP proposed security principles will serve as the basis for our own assessment of
current and future U.S. policies which control the use and availability of cryptographic
technologies.<p>
                                
Given the present market  realities and government needs, CSPP recommends several
first steps to promote the legitimate use of security by individuals and companies in the GII
and to address the federal government's intelligence gathering and law enforcement
interests.  Consistent with our security principles, CSPP recommends the following, initial
four-pronged approach to controlling the export of U.S. cryptography products:                            

<ol>   
<li><em>Link the decontrol of U.S. commercial cryptographic products to the availability of
competitive products in the international marketplace.</em>  The U.S. government already
acknowledges that lower encryption strengths do not present special threats to national security. 
For example, 40-bit encryption is not controlled for export as a munitions item today.  However,
stronger encryption cannot be exported from the U.S. without special licenses or exemptions,
even though it is available for sale in markets globally.  DES-based,  RC4-based, and RSA-based
products fall within this category. <p>
                                
Today, companies that encrypt data usually hold copies of their keys within the company to
safeguard against losses, mishaps, disgruntled employees, or other contingencies.  This practice is
known as key retention or self escrow.  While companies usually do not ask third parties to hold
copies of their keys, key escrow systems might provide a useful data recovery feature for some
commercial customers who desire strong encryption but are concerned about losing their
keys.<p>
                                
To the extent that comparable cryptographic products are available world-wide from uncontrolled
sources, attempts to control the spread of encryption are futile and harmful economically. <p>
                                
<li><em>Permit export of stronger U.S. commercial cryptographic products, without technology
restrictions, for legitimate commercial end users, unless the government clearly demonstrates a
risk.</em>  Today, banks, financial institutions, foreign subsidiaries of U.S. firms, and
governments that have encryption control agreements with the U.S. can receive strong U.S.
cryptographic products -- without government access requirements -- to satisfy special needs. 
CSPP recommends that other customers be considered in this category, for example, medical
institutions transmitting patients' records or large, trusted enterprises that need to protect vital
trade secrets.<p>
                                
Governments should assume it will approve export licenses for stronger cryptography, unless it
finds an unacceptable degree of risk.  The government interest in controlling the export of U.S.
cryptographic products is outweighed by the need for users to secure their cyberproperty from
large scale theft, fraud, tampering, or espionage in the GII.<p>
                                
<li><em>Discuss the export of stronger U.S. commercial cryptographic products that meet
reasonable government access needs.</em>  For customers who desire stronger  cryptography
products, but do not fall within the scope of Recommendation 2, above, CSPP recommends that
industry lead the effort to develop product standards.  Governments would discuss with industry
reasonable and achievable objectives to access encrypted data.  An industry-led group would then
develop product standards, including interoperability, which would factor-in the government's
objectives.<p>
                                
CSPP believes that only industry has the capability to design and produce a  commercial
cryptographic product that satisfies both customer and government needs.  This step could
include key escrow requirements but would not exclude other technology solutions.  Products
meeting these standards would be eligible for export.  <p>
                                
<li><em>Embargo U.S. commercial cryptographic products in terrorist countries.</em>  CSPP
supports the government's overriding national security interest in restricting the availability of
U.S. cryptographic products to terrorist countries.   
</ol>
                                
<hr align=center width=25%>

<a name="conclude"><h3>Conclusion</h3>
                                
The GII offers individuals, businesses, and governments, alike, unprecedented opportunities to
communicate, interact, and conduct business world-wide.  The promise of the Information Age
can be realized only if individuals and companies can adequately protect their cyberproperty
against risks inherent in the GII.  With or without U.S. government intervention in the security
aspects of the GII, encryption needs of GII users will inevitably be met by better cryptographic
products.<p>
                                
The growing demand for global security solutions contrasts sharply with current U.S. policies that
restrict the availability of U.S. solutions in international markets.  CSPP recommends the 
government and industry develop a national encryption policy together and take necessary steps
to help safeguard the future competitiveness of critical industries. <p>
                                
The GII will develop in one form or another.  Its benefit  in large part will be determined by
that form.  Individual users, the private sector, and the government must work together to
resolve critical security issues to realize fully the advantages of the Information Age. <p>

<hr align=center width=25%>
                                
<a name="append"><h3>Appendices</h3>
                                
<h4>Security issues raised in the GII.</h4>
<ul type=square>                                
<li><strong>Integrity:</strong>  the ability to protect information against the threat of
modification by unauthorized users.  This includes the ability to certify that information or data
was not modified or was legitimately modified during communication or in storage.<p>
                                
<li><strong>Access Control:</strong>  the ability for users and operators to precisely control
who accesses which resources. This also includes control of what level of access is allowed. <p>
                                  
<li><strong>Authentication:</strong>  the process of verifying an identity or credential, to ensure you are
who you say you are and the message has not been altered in transit.<p>
                                
<li><strong>Nonrepudiation or Accountability:</strong>  the ability to prevent communicating
parties in the network from denying that they sent or received given messages or engaged in
particular network activities.  <p>
                                
<li><strong>Confidentiality:</strong>  the ability to restrict access to authorized users only and
protect information against the threat of disclosure to or theft by unauthorized users.<p>
                                
<li><strong>Privacy:</strong>  the ability to ensure that personal and unrelated information are
not unnecessarily disclosed.
</ul>                                

<h4>Security tools</h4>

Several security tools are available and are used to safeguard electronic data.  Because
the GII is controlled by no one nation, corporation, or person, and millions of users are
connected presently in over 100 countries, encryption is the only cost effective means for
securing data.
<ul type=square>
<li><strong>Data Encryption Standard (DES)</strong>.  DES is a federal encryption standard
used in protecting unclassified computer data and communications.  DES uses a secret key
algorithm whereby the sending and receiving parties must know the secret key they will use to
communicate.<p>

<li><strong>Triple DES.</strong>  The use of three separate passes of information through the
DES algorithm increasing the strength from 56 bits to 168 bits.<p>

<li><strong>Rivest-Shamir-Adleman (RSA)</strong> public/private key cryptography.  Two
keys, one public and one private, which are mathematically related so that anything locked with
one key can be unlocked only by the other key.  <p>

<li><strong>Digital Signature Standard (DSS).</strong> DSS is a way to generate and verify
digital signatures. <p>

<li><strong>Pretty Good Privacy (PGP).</strong> PGP is a key management system available on
the Internet.<p>

<li><strong>Escrowed Encryption Standard (EES).</strong>  EES or "Clipper" is a key escrow
encryption product for federal departments and agencies and their contractors to protect
unclassified information and to encrypt voice, facsimile, and computer data communicated in a
telephone system.  It may be used to replace DES encryption devices now in use by federal
agencies and contractors.<p>

<li><strong>Fire walls.</strong>  A means of protecting a computer from an outside network,
often implemented as a dedicated computer that examines and restricts incoming and outgoing
communications, protecting an organization's network from outside intrusions and inside
disclosures.<p>
    
<li><strong>Secure tokens.</strong>  Tokens are physical devices used to identify users. Secure
tokens, such as Smart Cards that have a computer chip embedded in a credit card, PCMCIA
cards, or solid state floppies and can hold cash, credentials, cryptographic keys, and are built with
some degree of tamper-resistance.   <p>

<li><strong>Tamper-resistant modules.</strong>  These are sealed boxes which are hard to open,
requiring extensive probing and usually leaving evidence that tampering has occurred.  Hardened
modules, a variant, are sealed units that cannot be opened without destroying their contents.   <p>

<li><strong>Private leased lines and networks.</strong>  Dedicated point to point connections
that secure communications and information and are used usually within large organizations.
</ul>
<body>
<foot>
<p>
