<html><head><title>Perspectives on NII Interoperability</title></head>
<body>
<strong><font size=-2>May, 1995</font></strong><p>

<font size=+3>Perspectives on NII Interoperability:<br>
An Industry Strategy for Improving the<br>
Interoperability of Information-Rich Documents</font>
<hr align=left width=50%>
<font size=+1><strong>The Computer Systems Policy Project</strong></font><p>

<strong>Table of Contents</strong><p>
<a href="#intro">Introduction</a><br>
<a href="#import">The Importance of Interoperability</a><br>
<a href="#efforts">Efforts to Improve Document Interoperability</a><br>
<a href="#strat">Strategy for Improving the Interoperability of Complex Documents</a><br>
<a href="#conc">Conclusion</a><br>
<a href="#appen_a">Appendix A:  Key NII Interfaces for Interoperability</a><br>
<br>
<br>

<h3>Executive Summary</h3>

To be truly useful, the National Information Infrastructure (NII) will require a high level of
interoperability at a number of critical NII interfaces.  Industry has made significant progress
over the last several years in improving the interoperability of many of the important interfaces
in the evolving NII.  In this paper, the Computer Systems Policy Project (CSPP) describes some
of the computer industry's efforts to improve the interoperability of one subset of those
interfaces -- the exchange of information-rich documents -- and proposes an industry-led
strategy to further improve the interoperability of such documents. <p>

Some degree of interoperability already exists across computing platforms and NII applications. 
Most systems on the market today, and the majority in current use, are capable of performing
a number of basic functions, including exchanging and transporting data between different
devices on different networks, using widely available media, such as discs, modems, and local
area networks.  With these tools, almost every system in use today can save a text-based
document in a standard word processing format, move it to another system by floppy disc,
modem, local or wide-area network, and display it or print it without loss of meaningful
information.  Via the Internet, commercial on-line services, and networks, users can exchange
documents and conduct transactions over a variety of heterogeneous networked systems. 
Additional improvements in interoperability -- beyond today's capabilities -- would allow users
to easily, ubiquitously, and smoothly exchange and interact with data-rich documents that
include graphics (including 3D and color), video, and audio. <p>

The computer and software industries, driven by market forces and user demands, are
developing the tools needed for greater document interoperability through a variety of
voluntary, formal, informal, and ad hoc efforts.  A range of new and improved products, such as
Mosaic, CORBA, OpenDoc, Acrobat, OLE, MIME, and others, are now available to meet users'
differing needs for exchanging and interacting with various types of complex documents.<p>

<strong>Recommendations for Industry Action:</strong>  Further improvement in the interoperability of complex documents can be achieved, without reducing consumer choice or removing the incentive to innovate and compete, if the computer industry, in conjunction with the broader information technology and software industries, undertakes the following action agenda:
<ol>
<li>Participating in standards bodies to define standards for self-describing formats for data interchange and mechanisms to translate information from one format to another. <p>

<li>Urging appropriate standards bodies to adopt standards for software interoperability at higher levels than current networking protocols.  This will allow user applications to interact with distant systems while enabling a confederation, not a commoditization, of diverse, innovative and competitive systems.  Any such standards should possess the following characteristics:
<ol type="a">
<li>encapsulate the richest possible structure for capturing the contents of complex documents;<p>

<li>allow users to build and exchange the richest possible documents, but it must also be scalable, so that lower performance clients are not excluded; and<p>

<li>define a self-describing format for data interchange and provide mechanisms to translate information into and out of required formats.</ol>
<br>
<li>Considering implementing a multi-industry interoperability testbed facility to test potential solutions.<p>

<li>Continuing to advance technologies needed for enabling NII architectures, including:
<ul>
<li>infrastructure that works everywhere
<li>scalability
<li>full interconnection and interoperability technologies
<li>technologies to achieve commercial levels of security
<li>robustness/ability to recover after failure</ul></ol>

<strong>Recommendations for Government Support:</strong>  It is essential that NII interoperability continue to be achieved through the voluntary, industry-driven standards process.  That process affords industry the flexibility it needs to update and change products and guarantees
consumers a wide choice of innovative, useful products.  Government-mandated standards or
levels of interoperability, on the other hand, would inhibit innovation by removing the market
incentive to improve.  The federal government can support private sector interoperability
efforts by:
<ol>
<li>Participating in the industry-led, voluntary standards process. <p>

<li>Representing U.S. industry's positions in international standards fora where the U.S. government is the nation's representative and supporting industry's agenda in other international standards bodies.<p>

<li>Using government procurements to accelerate the adoption of industry-developed NII interoperability standards.<p>

<li>Continuing to fund precommercial R&D, including precommercial testbeds, needed to support standards development and interoperability.<p>

<li>Providing policy leadership where needed to ensure fair competition, protection of privacy, adoption of workable security and authentication solutions.<p>

<li>Championing a vision of industry-led interoperability at critical NII interfaces.
</ol>
<br>

<hr align=left width=25%>
<a name="intro"><h4>Introduction</h4>

The National Information Infrastructure (NII) is creating unprecedented opportunities for
people in a variety of situations and settings -- from offices to homes, schools, hospitals, and
even while traveling -- to access and exchange all types of information and interact with others
across interconnected, interoperable networks.  These new opportunities and applications will
require a high level of interoperability at a number of critical NII interfaces.  In "Perspectives on
the NII:  Ensuring Interoperability," (February, 1994) the Computer Systems Policy Project (CSPP) identified four categories of NII interfaces -- of the many that will exist -- for which
interoperability is essential to facilitate the use of different information appliances, applications,
communications networks, and information resources.  A list of the interface categories is
provided in <a href="#appen_a">Appendix A.</a><p>

This paper:  1) describes current computer industry activities to improve the interoperability of
one subset of the many important interfaces in the evolving NII --those that allow users to
exchange and interact with information-rich documents; and 2) proposes an industry strategy
to further improve the interoperability of standards for exchanging information-rich
documents.  While solving the information-rich document exchange challenge is critical to the
NII's success, many other interoperability challenges exist.  CSPP encourages other industries
with a stake in the NII to examine whether similar steps can be taken to improve the
interoperability of critical interfaces that fall within their purview.<p>

<hr align=left width=25%>
<a name="import"><h4>The Importance of Interoperability</h4>

In the NII, users will need to be able to share, transmit, and interact with complex documents
and conduct many types of transactions, regardless of differences in the software or hardware
they use, or on which platforms an application resides.  For example, doctors collaborating
over telemedicine links will need to see and manipulate medical charts and images just as they
could if the charts were on paper.  School teachers and their students will want to be able to
view and interact with multimedia educational materials and books from distant libraries that
look like the texts or movies they use in the classrooms.  Office workers will need to be able
to exchange and work with spreadsheets, charts, and reports among distant offices.  Users at
home will access and use on-line government forms, newspaper and magazine articles, play
video games, and select and pay for goods and services on-line. <p>

These NII applications all depend on users being able to easily and conveniently exchange and
use complex documents that are rich in information.  The adoption of standards for
interoperable document formats will greatly facilitate these types of activities.  Document and
data interoperability is typically thought of in terms of accessing remote information, but the
same interoperability requirements apply to modifying remote information via transaction
processing.  As the NII evolves, many types of activities -- from banking to ordering and paying
for goods and services -- will be conducted on line.  These types of transactions will require
accurate interactions with large numbers of dispersed databases and information repositories. 
With each interaction, information will be retrieved, modified, updated, and/or reviewed.  The
ease and accuracy of these types of transactions can be improved by the adoption of
widely-used standards for on-line transaction processing.  The interoperability requirements
for transaction processing are as important to the evolution of the NII as for complex
documents. <p>

As the NII evolves, people will use information appliances -- including computers (from
supercomputers to laptops), televisions, telephones, and personal communicators -- to access,
retrieve, store, create, transmit, and manipulate information of all types, in many different
formats.  Information appliances and applications for the NII are being developed, built, and
sold by many different vendors, using a variety of technologies.  A huge repository of installed
appliances, programs, and applications already exists in homes, schools, and businesses. 
Interoperability allows these diverse applications, devices, and systems to communicate with
each other.  In particular, interoperable document input and output formats will allow
recipients of information-rich documents to display the information, manipulate it, and print it
in the same form as it was created. <p>

<hr align=left width=25%>
<a name="efforts"><h4>Efforts to Improve Document Interoperability</h4>

As the NII evolves, people and businesses are increasingly using electronic formats, rather than
print, to capture and exchange documents of all types.  In the print world, exchanging a paper
document is a simple matter of printing or copying the document, and sending it by mail or
facsimile.  With these methods, the recipient receives a document that looks exactly like the
one that was sent.  Exchanging plain-text electronic documents is also relatively easy -- the
documents can be converted to ASCII and sent across a variety of communications networks. 
However, the electronic document received does not always look exactly the same as what
was sent because ASCII is not capable of handling formatting information, such as fonts, page
numbers, underlining, bolding, and other information about the document's appearance.  And,
since ASCII can only handle plain text documents, graphic, video, and audio information cannot
be sent.<p>

As technologies advance, users are increasingly able to create and store more complex forms
of documents, sometimes called "information rich" or "compound" documents, which include
images, video, audio, and graphics along with text.  These documents may also incorporate new
kinds of information in one part of the document that is "linked" with information in other
parts of the document or to other documents altogether.  Emerging NII applications will
require that users be able to exchange and interact with these types of complex documents.  <p>

At present, however, a lack of interoperability makes the exchange of these types of complex
electronic documents difficult.  In general, software applications create documents with unique
and non-interoperable characteristics.  Word processors, for example, typically create and
process documents that have specified formats which cannot be processed by other word
processors without special converter technologies.  Computer platform differences, which
often use incompatible applications and file formats, add a complicating factor to the exchange
of electronic documents.  Thus, people who want to exchange information-rich documents
electronically generally must communicate with each other to ascertain that they have the
appropriate software to accept and read the message being transferred. <p>

The computer and software industries, driven by market forces and user demands, are
continuing to develop the tools needed for greater document interoperability through a variety
of voluntary, formal, informal, and ad hoc efforts.  A few examples include methods for
exchanging formatted text (i.e., PostScript), images (i.e., GIF and JPEG), video (i.e., MPEG), and
hypertext links (i.e., HTML).  A range of new and improved products are now available to meet
users' differing needs for exchanging documents, including, for example:  Mosaic, a graphic
interface to the World Wide Web which allows users to access and view text, pictures, audio
and video files on their screens; the Object Management Group's Common Object Request
Broker Architecture (CORBA), which allows communication between different vendors'
software over any hardware; OpenDoc, a new open software technology that is being
developed by one multi-vendor team to allow complex information to be shared freely among
different applications and different platforms; Acrobat, a technology that handles multiple
document printing formats in a final-form environment; OLE, a Windows protocol for
referencing and including external objects in compound documents; and Multipurpose Internet
Mail Extension (MIME), which allows the exchange of multimedia electronic mail through the
Internet.<p>

The computer and software industries are making progress in developing structural markup
languages, such as the Standard Generalized Markup Language (SGML) or HyperText Markup
Language (HTML), to support the display of structured multimedia documents.  However,
while these markup languages solve some of the problems with the exchange of certain types
of complex documents across different computing platforms, the languages do not include
presentation specifics.  This means that in an Internet environment, for example, where the
World Wide Web has become a significant means of information exchange, most web
documents' presentation parameters are established in the "browser" for editing and viewing
programs, not within the documents themselves.  To solve these structural problems, new
browsers, such as Netscape, create new HTML tags that include presentation information. 
Unfortunately, these tags are non-standard, so the user is still unable to exchange documents
with others without losing important formatting information.<p>

In addition to individual company efforts, a number of cross-industry groups are working to
advance the interoperability of critical NII interfaces.  The American National Standards
Institute (ANSI) is a sponsoring a cross-industry body, the Information Infrastructure Standards
Panel (IISP), to bring companies from different industries, Standards Development
Organizations, consortia and ad hoc groups, and government personnel together to identify NII
standards needs and better coordinate NII standards-setting activities.  Multi-industry testbed
groups, such as NIIT and Smart Valley, are testing different solutions to interoperability
challenges.  The Cross Industry Working Team (XIWT) is examining and describing potential
architectures and technology solutions.  The Asynchronous Transfer Mode (ATM) Forum is an
association of vendors united to accelerate the development and adoption of standard,
interoperable technology.  The Internet Engineering Task Force continues to substantially
improve Internet standards that make the Internet available to over 20 million people
worldwide.<p>

<hr align=left width=25%>
<a name="strat"><h3>Strategy for Improving the Interoperability of Complex Documents </h3>

Exchanging information-rich documents in the NII requires meeting two fundamental goals:  1)
users must be able to see and interact with documents that look the same as they did when
they were created -- in other words, the document received must be what was sent; and 2)
users' investments in data, hardware, and software must be preserved to the extent possible. 
A scalable standard may provide a means to achieve the latter goal, as users would be able to
access as many of the components of the document as their system is capable of displaying and
manipulating.<p>

The voluntary private sector standards groups should designate as a priority the development
and adoption of data exchange standards that support these two goals.  Initially, the standards
should focus on allowing users to display formatted information-rich documents on their
computer screens.  Extensible standards would support eventual upgrades to allow users to
fully manipulate those documents. <p>

Any standards that are adopted should possess the following general characteristics:
<ol type="a">
<li>free of legal barriers, i.e., either public domain or licensed on reasonable and nondiscriminatory terms;
<li>well documented, with a public process for revision;

<li>based on available technology, as opposed to a set of abstract specifications;

<li>have reference implementation information readily available to developers, preferably with sample code widely distributed for testing to allow very broad, very rapid deployment; and

<li>responsive to market requirements, including legacy systems and international support.</ol>

These characteristics should apply to all of the interface standards that will be developed and
adopted by the private sector as the NII evolves.<p>

<hr align=left width=25%>
<a name="conc"><h3>Conclusion</h3>

CSPP recommends that the computer industry, working with the software and other key
information industries, adopt a strategy for improving the interoperability of complex
documents.  This strategy should include urging standards bodies to define standards for
self-describing formats for data interchange and mechanisms to translate information into and
out of required formats; urging standards bodies to adopt standards for software
interoperability at higher levels than current networking protocols; considering implementing a
multi-industry interoperability testbed facility to test potential solutions; and continuing to
advance technologies needed for enabling NII architectures.<p>

Competitive markets and the voluntary, industry-driven standards process are the best way to
drive interoperability for document exchange, while still providing industry with the flexibility
to compete and meet consumers demands.  Government-mandated standards or levels of
interoperability, on the other hand, would inhibit innovation by removing the market incentive
to improve.  Governments should take special care to support private sector efforts to
improve interoperability rather than setting their own interoperability goals and agendas.<p>


<hr align=left width=25%>
<a name="appen_a"><h3>Appendix A:  Key NII Interfaces for Interoperability</h3>

In "Perspectives on the NII:  Ensuring Interoperability," CSPP identified four categories of NII
interfaces -- of the many that will exist -- for which interoperability is essential to facilitate the
use of different information appliances, applications, communications networks, and
information resources.  Open interfaces at these key points will help ensure that the NII that
evolves is ubiquitous, interactive, and accessible to users and service providers.  Open
interfaces at critical NII locations will allow users and providers to transmit information
smoothly throughout the NII; stimulate competitive markets for NII products and services; and enable wide access to NII applications and services.  <p>

An interface is physically and logically "open" if its specifications are made readily available to all
vendors, service providers and users, and if such specifications are not revised without timely
notice or public process.  While open interfaces at critical points in the NII are important for
enabling interoperability, it is also important to maintain the intellectual property rights of
expressions of implementations as a key incentive to industry to develop advanced
technologies and applications that will speed the deployment of an enhanced NII.  The four
categories of critical interfaces identified by CSPP include: 
<ol>
<li>Information appliance to network service provider.  Open interfaces would allow users of the NII to attach any type of information appliance to the local access provider's network.<p>

<li>Applications Programming Interfaces (APIs) to information appliance and emerging NII applications, such as multimedia applications, telephony, database access, and X.400. Open APIs will enable developers of NII applications, such as interactive video games, remote database access, and electronic publishing, to make them available to any user regardless of the type of information appliance the user has. <p>

<li>The protocols that one NII application, service, or system uses to communicate with another service or system (for example, communications between different mail messaging systems or between database query programs and databases).  Open interfaces between different implementations of NII information systems, services, and applications that allow the systems, services, and applications to "communicate" with each other will enable users to generate and receive information in various formats and media, without having to make special adjustments to translate between different implementations. <p>

<li>The interfaces among and between network service providers, including between different local communications service providers, such as telephone companies and cable companies; interfaces to local companies' networks at key points and to intelligent switching software; and interfaces between local service providers and long distance carriers and enhanced service providers.  Open interfaces at certain key network points will ensure that users have maximum choice in their selection of and access to network and information services and that information providers can reach all users. </ol>
</body>
<foot>
<p>
