<html><head><title>Freedom To Grow</title></head>

<body>

<center><h4><i>PUBLIC POLICY AND THE U.S. COMPUTER INDUSTRY</i></h4>

<h1><font size=+3>FREEDOM TO GROW</font></h1>

<h4><i>LEADERSHIP INTO THE 21ST CENTURY</i></h4></center>

<p> <br> </p>

<hr s-ze=4>

<h1>BORN IN THE USA</h1>

<h2><i>Leading the World</i></h2>

<h3><i>An American Success Story</i></h3>

<p>Ever since the first commercial electronic computer was installed in 1951,
American computer technology has led the world. This home-grown industry is the
global leader in market share and technological innovation. It is a genuine
example of an American success.</p>


<blockquote><strong>Public policy decisions made in Washington, D.C., can either
help or hinder America's global technology leadership. The decisions made by the
U.S. government need to be carefully weighed for their impact on the computer
industry, a catalyst for our nation's economic growth.</strong></blockquote>

<hr size=4> <p> <br> </p>

<h1>GETTING THE FACTS STRAIGHT</h1>

<h3><i>The truth about the U.S. computer industry</i></h3>

<pre>

</pre>

<p><font size=+3><strong>FACT:  </strong></font><br> <blockquote><font
size=+2><strong>U.S. computer companies are creating high-quality, high-paying
jobs for Americans.</strong></font></blockquote></p>

<h3><i>The U.S. computer industry is <strong>not</strong> exporting American
jobs.</i></h3>

<p>Contrary to popular belief, the majority of computer jobs are located in the
U.S., not other countries. Computer companies employ nearly 1.2 million in the
U.S. An additional 1.5 million people are employed in the U.S. in
computer-related fields, like software design and telecommunications, which are
directly affected by the strength of computer-system makers.</p>

<ul type=disc><li>68% of computer industry employment is in the U.S., even though
62% of our sales are overseas.</li>

<li>88% of all research and development jobs are located in the U.S., and 70% of
all manufacturing jobs are located in this country.</li>

<li>Most computer jobs are knowledge-based, not manufacturing-based.</li>

<li>Over the next decade, it's projected there will be a 79% increase in the
number of systems analysts/computer scientists and a 56% increase in computer
programmers.</li></ul>

<p><i><strong><center><img src="freedom/graph1.gif"><br> The computer systems
industry creates high-paying jobs.</i></strong></p></center>

<p> <br> </p>

<p><strong>To continue to create jobs for the future and contribute to the
overall economic health of the country, U.S. computer companies need freedom to
grow.</strong></p>

<p><i><strong><center><img src="freedom/graph2.gif"><br> The U.S. computer
industry creates high-quality jobs for Americans.</i></strong></p></center>

<pre>

</pre>

<p><font size=+3><strong>FACT: </strong></font></br> <blockquote><font
size=+2><strong>The U.S. computer industry is fueling America's global
competitiveness.</strong></font></blockquote></p>

<h3><i>The U.S. computer industry is leading the competition in every major
product category.</i></h3>

<p>U.S. computer companies are the global leaders in computer systems -- ahead of
Japan and Europe. The economic impact of the industry extends deeply into the
American economy. Our products are essential to the improved efficiency,
competitiveness, and profitability of many other industries that rely on computer
technology to compete, including health care, manufacturing, transportation,
defense, entertainment, finance, retail, and real estate. The industry is an
<i>enabler</i>, helping the U.S. lead in productivity, creativity, and
ultimately, knowledge, which makes us all more competitive.<br>

<ul type=disc><li>U.S. computer companies spend more than 8% of their revenue in
research and development, second only to health care as an industry.</li>

<li>U.S. computer companies rank one, two, and three in worldwide sales of:
<blockquote>- supercomputers<br> - mid-range computers<br> - workstations<br> -
personal computers.</blockquote></li>

<li>U.S. computer companies rank one and two in worldwide sales of mainframe
computers.</li>

<li>U.S. computer companies compete successfully in more than 140 countries,
against 50,000 worldwide competitors.</li>

<li>By the year 2000, nearly 70% of the demand for information technology will
come from outside the U.S.</li></ul>

<p><strong>The ability to sell products and access technology worldwide is
essential to the continued competitiveness of the U.S. computer industry and its
success around the world. The industry must grow globally or die!</strong></p>

<p><i><strong><center><img src="freedom/graph3.gif"><br> The U.S. computer
industry is the worldwide market share leader.</i></strong></p></center>

<pre>

</pre>

<p><font size=+3><strong>FACT: </strong></font><br> <blockquote><font
size=+2><strong>Technology is perishable.</strong></blockquote></font></p>

<h3><i>Technology changes every 18 months and computer companies must
&quot;reinvent&quot; themselves and their product lines every 24 months.</i></h3>

<p>The incredibly rapid pace of change in the computer industry distinguishes it
from traditional manufacturing businesses. Every 18 months, improvements in
technology double the amount of computing power a dollar will buy. As a result, a
single bad public policy decision can wipe out an entire product generation. Miss
one development cycle and a company is seriously hurt; miss two and a company is
mortally wounded.</p>

<p>Given this business reality, computer companies are at the forefront of change
in the U.S., having adapted to a new way of doing business that requires us to
&quot;reinvent&quot; ourselves every two years.</p>

<ul><li>In 1993, 74% of computer companies' product revenues came from products
that did not exist two years ago.</li>

<li>Today, computer companies don't have time to make every thing in-house; they
need to form partnerships with other companies to source parts, technology, and
component anywhere in the world -- wherever the best can be found.</li>

<li>The continued success of the industry depends on its ability to bring the
best products to worldwide markets quickly.</li></ul>

<p><strong>The time-critical nature of our industry means that U.S. computer
companies must have access to the most innovative technologies, products, and
people in the other countries to produce the best products and continue to lead
in the world market.</strong></p>

<p><i><strong><center><img src="freedom/graph4.gif"><br> The U.S. computer
industry generates most of its revenue from new
products.</i></strong></p></center>

<p> <br> </p>

<hr size=4>

<p> <br> </p>

<p><h1>CREATING POLICIES THAT CREATE GROWTH</h1>  </p>

<h3><i>How government can help</i></h3>

<p><blockquote><strong>U.S. public policy must change to meet the realities of
the global marketplace and prepare for the 21st century. CSPP urges Congress and
the administration to consider the following recommendations to give computer
companies  freedom to grow.</strong></blockquote></p>

<pre>

</pre>

<p><h3><font size =+2>Work with industry to coordinate trade and technology
policies.</font></h3></p>

<p>Continued success of the U.S. computer industry around the world depends on
its ability to bring competitive products to market quickly. To do that, it's
essential that companies be able to source technology globally -- wherever it can
be found -- to maintain the industry's competitiveness and productivity. No
country can have a monopoly on technology -- its flow across international
boundaries is a business reality.</p>

<p><strong>CSPP recommends that the government: </strong><br>

<ul type=disc><li>Reform the export control system to keep pace with the
international marketplace and rapid advances in technology.</li>

<li>Reflect in U.S. policymaking the importance of exports to the economic
strength of the U.S., by assuring that U.S. competitiveness is not needlessly
undermined by inappropriate barriers to exports.</li>

<li>Avoid provisions restricting foreign participation in domestic markets, which
may lead to retaliation against U.S. companies in world markets.</li></ul></p>


<p><h3><font size =+2>Establish open markets.</font></h3></p>

<p>Open markets are the key to global competitiveness. To remain competitive
around the world, U.S. high-technology companies must be strong exporters and
wise importers.</p>

<p><strong>CSPP recommends that the government:</strong> <br>

<ul type=disc><li>Maintain open markets for trade and investment while
aggressively pushing other countries to open their borders to trade and
investment.</li>

<li>Devote adequate resources to ensure an effective implementation of the
Uruguay Round, the North American Free Trade Agreement, and other multilateral
trade and investment agreements.</li>

<li>Emphasize full implementation of the 1992 agreement to open Japan's public
sector computer market to foreign products and services while ensuring continued
progress on the 1990 Revised Supercomputer Procurement Agreement and the 1991
Semiconductor Trade Agreement with Japan.</li></ul></p>

<p><h3><font size =+2>Support industry efforts to develop national and global
information infrastructures.</font></h3></p>

<p>The private sector is, and will continue, investing in the development and
deployment of the National Information Infrastructure (NII) and Global
Information Infrastructure (GII). However, the government does have an important
role to play as a stimulator of private sector efforts.</p>

<p><strong>On the NII, CSPP recommends that the government:</strong><br>

<ul type=disc><li>Continue to promote a vision for the NII</li>

<li>Support an industry-led strategy to ensure interoperability</li>

<li>Implement a political and regulatory climate that encourages competitive
markets</li>

<li>Work with the private sector to address policy issues such as wide access to
the NII, privacy, authentication, security, and intellectual property
protection</li>

<li>Fund pre-commercial R&amp;D technologies and pre-commercial testbeds for the
NII</li>

<li>Make government information easily accessible electronically.</li></ul></p>

<p><strong>On the GII, CSPP recommends that the government:</strong><br>

<ul type=disc><li>Strongly encourage other nations to rely on industry-led,
market-driven processes to achieve global interoperability</li>

<li>Work to achieve open, competitive, and non-discriminatory markets
worldwide</li>

<li>Recognize the necessity for commercially acceptable security, authentication,
and privacy mechanisms to protect commercial transactions and individual privacy
rights</li>

<li>Continue efforts to strengthen international intellectual property rights
worldwide</li>

<li>Work with the private sector to establish one or more multinational testbeds
focusing on commercial applications.</li></ul></p>

<p><h3><font size=+2>Improve federal R&amp;D spending priorities and
incentives.</font></h3></p>

<p>The U.S. computer industry accounts for 21% of all private R&amp;D investment
in the country. Yet computer-related R&amp;D accounts for less than 4% of the
federal R&amp;D budget. Our goal is not to increase the federal budget, but to
reprioritize how it is spent.</p>

<p><strong>CSPP recommends that the government:</strong><br>

<ul type=disc><li>Improve federal R&amp;D budget review mechanisms and increase
industry involvement</li>

<li>Improve incentives for private investment in R&amp;D</li>

<li>Maintain federal R&amp;D funding for pre-commercial relevant technologies, in
particular:

<blockquote>- Research on high-performance computing and communications
technologies<br> - Research to address challenges in deploying the NII/GII,
emphasizing security, ease of use, and reliability<br> - Pre-commercial testbeds
to demonstrate the feasibility and benefits of selected NII
applications.</blockquote></li></ul></p>

<pre>

</pre>

<center><p><i><img src="freedom/kids.gif"><br> Public policy decisions today will
lay the groundwork for leadership into the 21st century.</i></p></center>

<pre>

</pre>

<hr>

