<html>
<head><title>
PERSPECTIVES ON COMPETITION AND DEPLOYMENT OF THE NII</title>
<center><h2>PERSPECTIVES ON COMPETITION AND DEPLOYMENT OF THE NII<br>
The Computer Systems Policy Project and<br>
The Information Technology Industry Council<br>
December, 1994</h2></center>
<hr>
<p></p>
<b><p>Executive Summary</p></b>
<p></p>
<p>The information technology industry believes that the competitive marketplace and open interfaces at critical locations will drive the availability of the affordable networks, information appliances, and information services that people will need to use the National Information Infrastructure (NII).</p>
<p></p>
<p>Over the past sixty years, the concept of universal service promoted the provision of affordable local telephone service by regulated franchised carriers.  It has been argued that federal and/or state governments should move quickly to establish a similar policy to promote a minimum level of NII service.  While service for all should remain a policy goal for the United States as the NII evolves, the information technology industry believes that market forces and competition, along with an infrastructure that provides open access at critical interfaces, are the best way to achieve this goal.</p>
<p></p>
<p>The NII is evolving rapidly, technologies are changing and advancing continually, and new, untried services are emerging.  In this environment, it is impossible to predict with accuracy the potential uses that people will make of the NII, the services they will want, or the prices they will be willing to pay for such services.  The highly competitive computer, electronics, and information industries are already successfully producing a wide array of products and services that meet users' needs at affordable prices.  In the increasingly competitive and diverse information and network service markets, the use of a broad, system wide regulatory structure, first established in the 1930's, will no longer serve the nation well.</p>
<p></p>
<p>The best way to ensure that markets drive widespread opportunities to use the NII is to remove unnecessary regulatory barriers and to encourage competition in NII markets and open access to communications networks.  Rather than attempting to fit a universal service regulatory structure onto new and varied NII services, policy makers should establish a goal of marketplace competition for all elements of the NII.  As the networks are deployed and the NII evolves, markets and private investment will work to ensure universal access to the networks, tools, and information resources people will need to use the NII, in their homes and through other facilities, such as public libraries and Schools.  Only as new NII services are widely adopted should policy makers consider whether the marketplace has not achieved the goal of enabling all users to obtain essential NII services. if there are limited cases where the goal is not achieved, appropriate mechanisms can then be considered for meeting these needs.</p>
<p></p>
<b><p>Government/Private Sector Roles</p></b>
<p></p>
<p>The information technology industry has identified the following roles for the government and the private sector in addressing the needs for access to the NII as it evolves.</p>
<p></p>
<b><p>Roles for State, and Local Governments:</p></b>

<ul>
1 .   Foster competition in NII markets and encourage open access to communication networks so any user or service provider can connect to the NII.<br><br>

2.	Refrain from imposing regulations in competitive markets.<br><br>

3.	Ensure that government information and services are available on line,	relying upon, and not competing with, commercial services to the extent	possible.<br><br>

4.	Provide incentives to states to incorporate NII use and training in public school curricula, such as including funding for training NII teachers, navigators, and "coaches" for community access centers.<br><br>

5.	Fund a pilot program, including a limited number of grants to communities, to test various concepts to establish community access, including access for people with disabilities, building to the extent possible on existing facilities.  If the test centers are successful, follow up with a program to help underwrite the establishment of centers in poorer communities around the country.<br><br>
6.	AS competition is fully realized, develop effective mechanisms to ensure that communications networks are available to users not served by the competitive marketplace.
</ul>
<b><p>Roles for Private Industry</p></b>

<ul>
1 .   Develop a vibrant market of competing goods and services to meet evolving customer needs.<br><br>
2.    Continue to invest in research on advanced networking technologies and easier to use, affordable appliances and information services.<br><br>
3.	Continue deploying new communication technologies and applications packages as widely as possible.<br><br>
4.	Continue efforts to train users of the NII.<br><br>
5.	Participate in government pilot programs to establish community NII access centers.</p>
</ul>

<p></p>
<b><p>What is the NII?</p></b>
<p></p>
<p>Conceptually, the NII is a nationwide assembly of systems that integrates five essential components -- communications networks, computers and information appliances, information, applications, and people -- using a wide variety of technologies to create a whole new way of learning, working, and interacting with others.</p>
<p></p>
<p>Information will be transmitted through the NII via a set of many interconnected, interoperable communications networks, both wired and wireless, that provide a range of different services and capabilities, from high to low speeds.  However, the NII will be much more than just communications networks. it also will include the information appliances and devices that people will use to access NII services, such as powerful personal computers and workstations, televisions) telephones, and devices that combine the functions of all of these.  It will encompass a wide range of information services, including public and private databases, digital libraries, and bulletin boards, government information, commercial applications, directory and other services, and entertainment programs.  Finally, the NII is being -- and will increasingly be -- used by people of all ages and backgrounds, who possess a very wide variety of experience, education, and training, in the skills necessary to locate, retrieve, use, and create electronic information, and whose interests, needs, desires, and physical abilities are likely to be quite varied.  Through these interconnected and interoperable components, the NII will link together people and public and private institutions and resources, from schools and businesses to libraries and laboratories.</p>
<p></p>
<p>While we do not know exactly what NII services people will use, we do know that they will not only be able to search an enormous variety of databases and information resources from around the world, containing information in text, audio, video, image, and multimedia formats, and they will also be able to create their own information and exchange it with virtually anyone else.  With the as-yet unimagined services and applications the NII will make available, distance, location, and time barriers will tend to disappear.  This is especially important for those in rural areas, those with disabilities, and those who work and learn at home.</p>
<p></p>
<b><p>Markets Will Drive Availability and Affordability</p></b>
<p></p>
<p>As the private sector works to develop and deploy the NII, the federal government can best help ensure that all Americans can obtain the NII information and services they need by removing unnecessary regulatory barriers and by encouraging competition in NII markets and open access to communications networks.  The information technology industry agrees with the Clinton Administration's recognition in the <i>Agenda for Action for the NII</i>  that markets are driving the evolution of new NII services and their widespread availability, and that policies to promote competition, in combination with targeted support for disadvantaged users, will advance both rapid infrastructure modernization and expanded access to the NII.</p>
<p></p>
<p>Rapid advances in technology are enabling increased competition in communication and information services, changing the communications environment from one of scarce resources to one of abundant choices.  The global computer, consumer electronics, and information industries are already applying these new technologies, through competitive markets, to make new products and services widely available and affordable.  For example, one-third of U.S. households already have personal computers -- many with CD-ROM drives and modems.  Many more households have radios, televisions, VCRs, stereos, and video games.  The prices of all of these products have declined significantly over the last decade, even though the Consumer Price Index has risen and the products' performance levels have improved exponentially.  Recently, the number of subscribers to on-line services, such as America OnLine, CompuServe, and Prodigy, have increased dramatically as those services compete for customers.  And the introduction of competition into the long-distance telephone market has resulted in improved service at lower prices.  We are confident that as the NII evolves, these competitive trends will continue to result in the deployment of new, advanced, and affordable products and services.</p>
<p></p>
<b><p>The NII is Evolving</p></b>
<p></p>
<p>Since the NII is evolving rapidly, technologies are Changing and advancing continually, and new services are only just coming on line, it is impossible to predict with accuracy the potential uses that people may make of the NII, the services they will want, or the prices they will be willing to pay for such services.  Initially, many people may not need to use many of the services available through the NII.  Some people will use the NII only occasionally.  Many of their uses will require different information appliances, different transmission capacities, and different applications.  Until people are familiar with the various services available, they may not be willing to make the investments necessary to purchase even the most basic options or service levels.</p>
<p></p>
<p></p>
<p>Until we are better able to assess the uses and needs people will have for NII services, we should not adopt policies requiring new services to be provided universally. in fact, it is entirely possible that many people will use some NII services so seldom that they will prefer to go to a public access point on those occasions when they need them, just as they go to public libraries to use materials they do not need to have at home.</p>
<p></p>
<b><p>Definitions</p></b>
<p></p>
<p>The terms "universal service" and "universal access" are often used when discussing how to ensure that people will be able to obtain information and reach other people in the NII.  To help provide a common ground for discussions about these important concepts, we propose the set of definitions below.  But first it is helpful to understand that there are three basic prerequisites for people to benefit from the NII:</p>
<p></p>
<ul>
1 .   There must exist an available network, either wired or wireless, to provide a connection to the NII;<br><br>
2.    A person must have the tools and skills necessary to connect to the NII and use its available services; and<br><br>
3.There must be some information or services available through the NII that a person wants to use.
</ul>
<p></p>
<p>With these prerequisites in mind, we developed the following definitions:</p>
<p></p>
<ul><i>NetWork Deployment</i> addresses the physical availability of a communications network to those in a region who wish to connect to the NII, creating a "network of networks." Thus, network deployment provides the medium to which a person may connect an information appliance -- personal computer, interactive television, wireless telephone -- to send, receive, and retrieve information.  <i>Universal Network Deployment</i> refers to the availability of reasonably convenient connections to the NII's communications networks at the necessary bandwidth.</ul>
<p></p>
<p>Access deals with the ability to use the services that are available, and thus relates primarily to the people and appliance aspects of the NII.  It focuses on the tools and the skills necessary to be able to use the services that are available and the existence of special features to meet the needs of disabled users.  <i>Universal Access</i> refers to the opportunity that everyone should have to use the NII, either in their homes, at work, or at public access points.  This must evolve over time and community by community as technologies and services become widely used and people's skills and interests develop.</p>
<p></p>
<p><i>Service</i> is an economic concept.  Historically, <i>universal service</i> referred to a policy goal to provide all Americans With the ability to obtain affordable telephone service.  Where regulated franchises on their own do not achieve this goal, federal, state, and local government mechanisms help to accomplish it.  In the context of the NII, universal service would refer to some minimum level of service that Should be affordable for all, either at home or work, or through public facilities.  It would only apply to essential economic, public safety, and educational uses, which would, for the most part, be provided through the competitive marketplace.  Other uses, such as entertainment or avocational uses, would be addressed solely through market mechanisms.</p>
<p></p>
<b><p>Ensuring Universal Access to the NII</p></b>
<p></p>
<p>The information technology industry recommends that rather than attempting to fit a regulatory concept born in a monopoly environment onto the NII, policy makers should adopt the following strategies to ensure universal access to the NII:</p>
<p></p>
<ul>1.	Communications Networks -- Federal, state, and local policy makers should encourage universal deployment of communications networks, with the necessary bandwidths and interoperable at critical interfaces, by encouraging competition and removing unnecessary regulations as effective competition emerges.  As network deployment occurs, policy makers should consider whether mechanisms are needed to ensure universal deployment or to assist users to connect to networks in special circumstances where competitive markets do not achieve this goal.<br><br>

2.	Tools and Skills -- The competitive marketplace will ensure that the necessary tools, including a variety of information appliances, will be affordable and available to most people.  Community-based public access centers would supplement that availability.  NII access centers can provide assistance with skills development, and provide special tools for people with disabilities, with additional government assistance where necessary.<br><br>

3.	Information -- Competitive markets, combined with open interfaces at critical network access points, will ensure that information resources are accessible to all.  Competition will create the information services that users demand, while open interfaces, which CSPP described in its February, 1994 paper, <i>Perspectives on the National Information Infrastructure: Ensuring Interpretability</i>, will enable any provider to make its information services available over the NII and enable users in any region of the country to access information.  In some cases, subsidies to users may be needed to make essential information resources affordable to certain users.<br><br>
</ul>
<p>Thus, as networks are deployed, markets and private investment, in conjunction with open interfaces at critical locations, will drive universal access to the resources made available by the NII.  Whether and where the concept of universal service may be appropriate in the NII remains to be seen.</p>
<p></p>
<p>Unlike today's telephone service, NII services will largely be provided by companies operating in competitive markets.  If it is determined based on experience that mechanisms are needed to achieve universal service, those mechanisms will have to be considered in the context of competitive markets and a diverse availability of technologies and services.  With today's "plain old telephone service," it is relatively easy to decide what services should be made available and affordable to all. in the diverse and competitive environment of the NII, it will be impossible to choose a particular technology or type or service for universal service without limiting consumer choices and inhibiting innovation.</p>
<p></p>
<b><p>Community NII Access Centers</p></b>
<p></p>
<p>Until we have a better idea about what technologies, services, and information people will want to use and how they will use them, community-based NII access centers, building on existing mechanisms and models for making information available, can help meet evolving needs for using the NII, as well as identify the applications people will most want to use.  Today, many people use centralIy-located facilities, such as libraries, schools, community centers, and social clubs, to obtain information.  The information technology industry believes that these institutions, and the mechanisms already in place to support them, provide a natural foundation for providing access to new information technologies and services made available by the NII.</p>
<p></p>
<p>Community NII access centers could offer a wide variety of technologies and services, tailored to meet community needs and commensurate with available resources.  The centers would help introduce people to new technologies and services without requiring them to commit to purchasing or subscribing to products before they are certain they want them.  For many people today, libraries and schools serve as the only connection to information not available in their homes; for many others, they are a key supplemental source of information.  Community NII access centers would ensure that this resource is not lost as we move into the digital age.</p>
<p></p>
<p>To the extent possible, community NII access centers should build on existing centers of information.  We believe that public libraries provide the most logical and appropriate locations for such activities.  However, where libraries are not convenient, many other types of existing facilities could serve as public access centers, including, for example, elementary and secondary schools, universities, and community colleges; government offices, including agricultural extension offices and recreational facilities; and privately-run facilities, such as veterans organizations, community health centers, and senior citizens clubs.</p>
<p></p>
<b><p>Initiatives for Community Access</p></b>
<p></p>
<p>Many communities are already beginning to invest in initiatives to provide public access to the NII in response to local needs, including providing on-line capabilities at public libraries, installing information kiosks at local government offices and other public locations, and funding access to low-cost community networks.  We encourage localities to provide these types of community access mechanisms.</p>
<p></p>
<p>For communities that do not have the resources to establish NII access centers, we recommend the federal government fund a series of demonstration projects to define the levels of needs for NII services in communities and to test potential approaches for addressing those needs.  The criteria and potential approaches could then be applied to address the needs of particular communities as necessary.</p>
<p></p>
<p>Funding for a set of pilot community access programs could be made available through federal, state or local grants, similar to the funds being provided through NTIA's program for connecting non-profit facilities to the NII, and by allowing companies that donate products or services to community centers to claim enhanced tax deductions.  Low income users who purchase information technology products, network time, or essential information services could be assisted with tax credits to offset the costs of use.  The source of funding for services with broad, general benefits such as the NII should be general government funds, rather than specific, targeted taxes, which tend to distort markets.</p>
<p></p>
<p>Whatever type of mechanism is used to fund community NII centers or the use of the NII by people who need financial assistance, any subsidies should be provided directly to the users or to the community access centers, rather than to service providers.  Such subsidies could take the form of vouchers to purchase network or information services.  Subsidizing providers would distort markets and limit the flexibility of choice for users and access centers.</p>
<p></p>
<b><p>Summary</p></b>
<p></p>
<p>Competition will ensure that the needs of most people to access information and communicate with others can be met through a combination of access to the NII in their homes and in community centers.  If, in the future competitive environment, a determination is made that the market has failed to address the needs of certain users, targeted and measured responses can be tailored to address these needs.</p>
<hr>
</html>
