<html>
<head><title>Information Technology's Contribution
to Lifelong Learning</title>
<h2 align=center>
Information Technology's Contribution<br>
to Lifelong Learning<br>


March, 1994</h2>
<hr>
<p><b>Executive Summary</b></p>
 
<p>Success in the knowledge-based society of the future will require a variety of critical skills, including active, self-directed learning, the ability to access, analyze and manipulate remote data, and the ability to communicate across regional and nati
onal boundaries.  In the job markets of the future, employers will demand workers who can learn new skills to adapt to changing job requirements and new technologies, use knowledge and information to make decisions, and work collaboratively in groups.  Mo
st Americans are not acquiring these types of skills as part of their education today.  Improving the effectiveness of our education system is essential if the United States is to compete effectively in the global work place of the future.  From pre-schoo
l through graduate school, we must provide a meaningful way for individuals to continue learning and retraining throughout their lives to obtain and maintain the skills they will need for the high wage, information-based economy of the future.</p>
 
 
 
<p>The Computer Systems Policy Project (CSPP) believes that the enhanced national information infrastructure (NII) will provide a tool to meet these needs by linking together a range of institutions and resources -- from schools, hospitals, and businesses
 to libraries, laboratories, and government agencies -- that will allow students of all ages to interact with each other and with teachers, mentors, advisers, and experts.  Through existing and new information technologies the NII will transform the way p
eople learn by enabling them to learn and work together and to access, share, and generate information without regard to geography.  Teachers will be able to custom tailor lessons to accommodate their students' special needs and interests.  Adult learners
 will be able to access, at their convenience, the information they need to learn new skills or improve current skills.  Learners of all ages will be able to find and use information from distant and distributed resources.  People in remote or less well o
ff areas will have access to the best learning resources available.  As the Clinton Administration noted in its 1993 Agenda for Action for the National Information Infrastructure, "Although technology alone cannot fix what is wrong with America's educatio
n and training system, the NII can help.  "</p>



<p>Innovative approaches to education and training using information technologies are already being applied in classrooms and corporate learning centers around the country.  The NII will provide opportunities to build on and expand these efforts.  CSPP be
lieves that demonstration projects highlighting the benefits of information technologies and addressing the problems that are hindering their adoption will accelerate the adoption of information technologies in classrooms, homes, and other learning enviro
nments.  CSPP recommends that the federal government and the private sector together invest in projects to demonstrate On-line Libraries, Electronic Librarians, Virtual Laboratories and Field Trips, Preschool/Head Start/Schools of Education Networks, Comm
unity-based Education and Vocational Resource Centers, the Internet as Library, and Electronic Assistants.</p>
 
<p>The Challenge -- Preparing the Workforce for the Future</p>
 
 
 
<p>Ensuring that all citizens are adequately trained and educated to meet the changing workforce needs of the future will require taking steps to provide the means to teach students the skills they will need to succeed in the high wage, information-based 
economy of the future, as well as providing the means for individuals to continue learning and upgrading their skills throughout their lives.  As many Americans are realizing, the best, highest-wage jobs are increasingly going to those who have the skills
 employers need, or who can upgrade their skills as job needs change.  The ability to locate, access, and use information is becoming essential to virtually every high-wage job.  The U.S. education and training system must help students of all ages acquir
e those skills.</p>
 
<p>The National Information Infrastructure (NII) will provide a powerful tool for meeting these challenges.  Through the NH, America's edge in computing and communications technologies can be extended to education services in schools, communities, work pl
aces, and homes, making knowledge and information resources of all types readily available, accessible, and usable by all Americans.  By using the resources of the NII to locate information, solve problems, and communicate interactively with others, peopl
e will learn and hone the skills they will need for the 21st century.</p>
 
 
 
<p>Teachers and students of all ages are already using information technologies to enhance and expand their learning experiences and opportunities.  As described in CSPP's report Perspectives on the National Information Infrastructure: CSPPs Vision and Re
commendations for Action, the NII will enhance and integrate four essential components -- communications networks, computers and information appliances, information, and people -- to revolutionize the way people learn.  The NII will enable students and te
achers to work together, to collaborate with experts, and to access, share and generate information -- all without regard to geographic, race, class and gender boundaries.  Information technologies will enable fundamental changes in the way students inter
act with their peers, their teachers, and information resources of all kinds, bringing information to learners when and where they want it.  The NII will provide a tool for addressing many of the learning needs the country is facing, including, for exampl
e:</p>


<ul>
<li>tailoring curriculum and instruction methods to meet the needs of individual students;



<li>providing teachers with the resources they need to improve their skills and update their knowledge;



<li>providing a means for Americans to continually acquire the knowledge to adapt to new or changed career objectives;

<li>providing seniors and disabled or homebound Americans direct access to information resources critical to their health and welfare; and

<LI>providing better access to information that affects our quality of life and cultural awareness.

</ul>

<p>President Clinton and Vice President Gore have explicitly recognized the benefits that information technologies can bring to achieving the education goals the nation has established for the beginning of the 21st century.  The Administration's technolog
y initiatives include a plan to improve technology for education and training by supporting the development and introduction of computer and communications equipment and software designed to increase the productivity of learning in formal school settings,
 a variety of business training facilities, and in homes.</p>

<hr>

<H2 ALIgn=center>How Can Information Technology<br>
Contribute to Achieving the Challenge?</h2>



<p>While information technologies are already being used in a variety of settings to improve the effectiveness of education and training, the enhanced NII will provide many opportunities to better prepare our population for the work place of the future:</
p>


<ul>
<li>Computers will make learning complex ideas easier by providing learning environments that closely approximate real work environments or experimental apparatus.

<li>Students interconnected via networks will be able to collaborate as teams, even though members of the team are geographically separated.  Teachers and school and college administrators from around the country will be able to communicate electronically
 to exchange ideas and build a sense of community.

<li>Instruction will be tailored to the specific learning needs of individuals, particularly adults re-entering a training environment, minorities, women, people with disabilities, and others that may benefit from customized approaches to instruction.

<li>People who do not have direct access to a wide variety of opportunities, either because they live in remote areas or because of the demands of work or family responsibilities, will be able to access information from other locations in a variety of for
mats and media, obtain degrees from distant colleges, and access facilities with unique learning resources.

<li>Information technologies, such as visualization, will provide new ways to learn difficult concepts and data.

<li>Information technologies will reduce the burden of record keeping and other paperwork that consumes so much of teachers' and administrators' time.
</ul>
<hr>
<h2 align=center>Meeting America 2000 Goals</h2>



<p>The following are just a few of the ways information technology, through the NII, can help us meet the America 2000 goals that were established by former President Bush and the National Governors Association in 1990. </p>
 
 
 
<p><b>Goal 1, By the year 2000, all children will start school ready to learn.</b> </p>
 
<p>An enhanced NII has the potential to move learning, at any age, from beyond the four walls of a classroom to a broad community of reamers.  Many of the problems that make it difficult for children to arrive at school ready to learn, including a variety
 of difficult societal problems, can be addressed or minimized through information technology.  For instance, through links to the home, the NII can provide parents with the necessary tools to expand their roles in their children's education and better pr
epare their children to enter schools ready to learn.  Through computers linked to social agencies, assistance with specific problems can be provided directly and confidentially to parents, or to schools, to help teachers and administrators deal more effe
ctively with learning difficulties caused by social problems.</p>


<ul>
<li>Linking from home with a personal computer or an interactive TV, a parent will be able to access high-quality and developmentally appropriate preschool education materials to use with their children.  Working in this fashion not only promotes inter-ge
nerational literacy but strengthens communications between parents and educators very early on.


<li>Through the NII, day care and other providers of services for young children will easily access the latest nutritional and healthcare information and services.  Model programs for early childhood care could be disseminated easily electronically, along
 with customized information for children with special problems or circumstances.

<li>Parents and preschool teachers will be able to access an interactive "Ask the Experts" electronic bulletin board to get insights on all types of developmental-related issues; or, with a simple electronic message, they would automatically receive a mon
thly newsletter with guidance on developmental milestones and exercises.

</ul>

<p><b>Goal 2,	By the year 2000, the high school graduation rate will increase to at least 90%.</b></p>



<p>One of the most common reasons cited by students for dropping out of school is a lack of relevancy in education -- they see little real-world pay back from traditional education.  By fostering better communications between the schools, the private sect
or, and higher education, and making learning more exciting and hands-on, the NII can play a crucial role in enhancing the linkages between education and career options, strengthening the school-to-work transition, and providing incentives for staying in 
school.</p>

<ul>

<li>NII applications will allow students to directly interact with scientists, researchers, journalists, entertainers, or even Members of Congress.  Through these interactions, students will see firsthand skills and education being applied in relevant rea
l-world situations, helping them gain an understanding of the benefits of staying in school.

<li>Career counseling and career information available electronically will provide students with immediate, interactive information about career options and education requirements.  Mentors and people practicing specific careers around the country could b
e available to answer students' questions via networks.

<li>Instruction can be made more exciting, and better tailored to students' interests and needs, through the use of networked multimedia, speech recognition, intelligent tutors and tools, and curricula that integrate voice, video, data and text.  This wil
l help enhance retention and provide the flexibility to meet the varying learning styles of disabled, at-risk, and other non-traditional students.
</ul>


<p><b>Goal 3.       By the year 2000, Americans will have competency in challenging subject matter, including English, mathematics, science, history and geography, and... be prepared for responsible citizenship, further learning, and productive employment
 in our modern economy.</b></p>



<p>In a global, knowledge-based economy, skills in generating, accessing, manipulating, and managing information will be paramount.  Information and the base of knowledge about any particular subject are growing so quickly that a person can no longer expe
ct to "know" all there is to know about a subject.  Instead, workers and students will need to know how to find the information they need quickly and in the right format.  While tools and software will help make the NII easier to use and navigate, informa
tion technology-based education techniques will still require reamers to conceptualize a problem, use critical thinking skills, access distant resources, and collaborate with fellow students, all while using basic reading and writing skills.</p>

<ul>

<li>Integrated curriculum supported by information technology will move learning beyond memorizing "facts" like the periodic table, to inquiry-driven, on-line, interactive sessions, such as discussions with NASA researchers working on the Hubble Telescope
, collaborations with oceanographers charting undersea volcanoes, or writing reports with images downloaded from the Voyager satellite.

<li>Global networking capabilities will enable students to interact with students and teachers around the world, bringing current events right into the classroom.  Projects like the National Geographic's Kids Net are already moving lessons from static tex
tbooks and outdated maps to powerful, interactive exchanges with students from cultures and countries around the globe. 
 
<li>Understanding and appreciating diversity, whether different countries, races, cultures or languages, will be essential for American students and workers operating in an increasingly interconnected, global environment.  Through the NII, information tec
hnologies will enable students and teachers to access resources and perspectives from around the world.</p>

</ul>

<p><b>Goal 4:	By the year 2000, U.S. students will be first in the world in science and mathematics achievement.</b></p>



<p>Through the NII, information technologies have a huge potential to reinvigorate how science and mathematics are taught, used, and learned by students.  With network-supported simulated experiments, project-based learning, and authentic problem solving 
exercises, students can generate their own scientific data, which they can share with researchers in the field.  This makes students active participants in their education, rather than passive observers.</p>

<ul>

<li>With electronic access to resources like the National Academy of Science's Science Resource Center, or materials from the Science 2000 and the AAAS's Project 2061, teachers will be able to develop exciting, up-to-date curricula.



<li>NII technologies will enable students to participate in creative, collaborative mathematics projects, such as student-conducted electronic polling, or designing an urban bike path, that provide hands-on experience in statistics, architecture, sample g
athering, testing, design, assessment and forecasting.

<li>Innovative curricula and technologies can significantly improve outreach to traditionally under-represented and under-served populations in math and science.

<li>Innovative tools and resources, such as supercomputers, visualization, and statistics software will bring difficult mathematic functions, including modeling, simulation, probability, and finite analysis alive and within the reach of many students.

</ul>

<p><b>Goal 5:	By the year 2000, every adult American will be literate and will possess the knowledge and skills necessary to compete in a global economy and exercise the rights and responsibilities of citizenship.</b></p>


<p>The global economy is moving rapidly to one driven by information and knowledge.  High-wage jobs, quality of life, and competitive advantage will be based on the ability to create, manipulate and deliver information quickly to the right person and plac
e.  Literacy, or technological fluency, will require the skills to acquire knowledge and to adapt to emerging technologies and work methods.</p>


<ul>
<li>A continuum of networked services and resources drawn from academia, business, and the community will provide lifelong learning opportunities for workers, students and teachers.  Distance learning technologies will enable innovative retraining initiat
ives, designed and adapted to meet the needs of mid-career and other non-traditional students.

<li>The NII will make possible expanded citizen access to Federal, State and Local information, (electronic town halls), or even the White House, providing an important tool for citizens to exercise their rights and responsibilities.

<li>The NII will improve the way adult literacy is addressed by providing opportunities to learn in convenient settings -- at home, at work, in libraries -- at times convenient to the users.  New multimedia learning tools and graphical interfaces will mak
e learning literacy skills easier.

</ul>

<p><b>Goal 6:	By the year 2000, every school in America will be free of drugs and violence and will offer a disciplined environment to learning.</b></p>



<p>Technology will not cure the societal problems that are making learning more difficult in many schools.  However, it can help create an environment in which the preconditions for drugs and violence are minimized.  Students that are excited, engaged, an
d challenged by the education system are less likely to turn to destructive behavior.  The NII will be a tool to engage students in meaningful, innovative, and interesting learning experiences as well as to directly address specific behavior problems via 
interactive programs.</p>

<ul>

<li>Innovative student assistance programs implemented with electronic support can provide anonymous and accurate information about specific problem areas to curious students or students-at-risk.

<li>Information technologies will support interdisciplinary research and development to produce educational products that address drug and alcohol abuse and an array of drug prevention and counseling techniques that can be made available to parents and te
achers electronically.

<li>Linking schools with community organizations, the police and other public safety agencies will facilitate communication among these agencies and assist in identifying trouble spots or issues before they erupt into classroom violence.

</ul>

<hr>
<h2 align=center>Research Challenges</h2>



<p>Delivery of advanced educational and learning services will be enabled by and built on richly varied and interoperable communications and computing technologies interconnecting millions of people with huge amounts of information and media services from
 public institutions and private enterprises.  While many of the technologies necessary to make this happen already exist, several research challenges must be addressed to achieve the vision:</p>

<ul>

<li>Improved end-user experience, including development of easy to use interfaces, such as speech and character recognition, common presentation and search languages, and information retrieval and analysis techniques.

<li>Improved authoring and service creation techniques, including multimedia authoring techniques, simulation software, and techniques for digitizing libraries.

<li>Improved platform technologies, such as reliable and fair mechanisms for protecting and publishing intellectual property, multi-user multimedia servers, distributed computer architectures, and multi-user multimedia conference bridges.

<li>Improved network connectivity, performance, and reliability, including interoperability between local telephone exchanges, wireless networks, cable networks, regional carriers, and national and international long distance service providers; low cost a
nd reliable two-way wireless communications; low cost high performance networks providing variable bandwidth on-demand, guaranteed latency, virtual circuits, and multi-point synchronization; and scaleable, consistent and pervasive network addressing and d
irectory schemes.

<li>Visualization technologies, to make it easier for students to see and understand difficult concepts, especially involving complex scientific data.

</ul>

<p>In addition to meeting the research challenges, effective deployment of an advanced computing and communications infrastructure for education and lifelong learning requires well trained and technologically experienced teachers and administrators.  Educ
ators must be able to facilitate the use, installation, and management of new instructional technologies, such as digital interactive video, local area networks, and gateways to national networks.  Users and students will need new skills to help them retr
ieve, review, categorize, and analyze the information and knowledge they will be able to access.  This will require investment in training for educators and students in the use of new technologies, development of model curricula, new instructional techniq
ues, development of new information resources, improvement in the quality of existing resources, and extension of public access to electronic schools and libraries. </p>
 
 
<p>The NII will make all kinds of information instantly accessible at the fingertips, regardless of where the information is physically located.  It will enable individuals of all abilities to create their own information resources for distribution across
 the nation.  This will help remove some of the traditional barriers to learning, such as distance, access to resources, gender, race, and differences in ability.  However, the NII must reduce, rather than exacerbate existing differences between technolog
y-rich and information-rich schools and communities and schools and communities that are less well-equipped.  Initiatives to increase the use of information technologies in classrooms must include specific measures to ensure access to the necessary basic 
technologies, including computers, network connections, and databases.  This will have to address how to account for the costs associated with incorporating new technologies -- including training people to use them, given the restrictive budgets most educ
ation institutions have available for new investments. </p>
 
 
 
<p>For the benefits and capabilities of the NII to become ubiquitous and universal, ease of use, simplicity of training, and interoperability across different vendors' systems is important.  Schools and communities will want to leverage their existing inv
estments and ensure that future investments are protected.  TVs will be critical at the implementation level if the sharing of information and resources among localities, states, regions, and nations is to be encouraged.</p>

<hr>
<h2 align=center>Recommended Demonstration Projects</h2>



<p>Many of the technologies necessary to bring exciting, effective information technology applications to classrooms, homes, business training centers, and community learning centers are available.  However, experience is still needed to integrate the tec
hnologies in ways that are easy to use and scaleable to the size and complexity needed to accommodate a very large number of school districts, colleges and universities, homes, and users.  Demonstration projects that focus on large-scale use of informatio
n technologies in classrooms, work places, and homes will test new ways of using information technologies in real-world settings, help identify technological and other barriers to widespread implementation of the techniques and technologies that work, and
 stimulate the adoption of innovative solutions by users. </p>
 
 
 
<b><p>Assessment of Ongoing Efforts </p></b>
 
<p>Many public and private schools and education institutions at all levels are planning to make major investments over the next ten years in experimental educational services.  These projects will be funded by a wide variety of private and public sector 
entities.  In this time of scarce public and private funds, both federal and private investments in educational technology must be based on the most effective instructional models.  In order to rapidly deploy proven effective instructional models, and to 
avoid very expensive redundant investment and costly repeated failures, CSPP recommends expanding the Department of Education's clearinghouse for gathering and disseminating information on ongoing public and private programs to integrate information techn
ologies into education and lifelong learning activities. </p>
 
 
 
<b><p>Recommended Demonstration Projects </p></b>
 
<p>It is equally important to move education reform forward both by applying existing technologies in increasingly more effective and innovative ways and by adopting breakthrough technologies as they emerge.  CSPP recommends allocating funds for new proje
cts that demonstrate innovative curricula and teaching methods within the context of the existing computing and networking technology base.  Funding should also be allocated for the use of existing technology in applications that foster collaboration and 
efficiency by integrating the instructional and administrative areas of educational institutions. </p>
 
 
 
<p>Technology advances in wireless LANS, speech synthesis and recognition, pen computing, extensions to multimedia technology, video conferencing, virtual reality, high speed, cost-effective communications networks, and other advances hold promise for enh
ancing, even transforming, the learning process and for providing effective and efficient management of our educational system.  As breakthroughs in technology take place, on going funding of leading edge demonstration projects will ensure that </p>
 
 
<p>Technological progress in education will continue to keep pace with other segments of the United States infrastructure. </p>
 
 
 
<p>The following are examples of the types of demonstration projects that would illustrate the potential range of education and lifelong learning applications:</p>

<ul>

<li><b>On-line Libraries </b>-- Develop and make available on-line at job sites information and knowledge on a wide variety of subject matter, including career and job training materials and federally-developed information.  This should include performanc
e support networks that would provide task-oriented information on job sites to make learning and job performance improvement incremental and casual rather than formal and intermittent.



<li><b>Electronic Librarian </b>-- Develop an electronic librarian capability for use by students in the classroom or at home, which would include tools to permit efficient literature reviews, identification and acquisition of relevant statistical data, a
nalysis and presentation of data, and searches of textual and multimedia information.

<li><b>Virtual Laboratories & Field Trips </b>-- Set up classroom virtual laboratories that would allow students to perform science experiments using equipment and facilities located anywhere in the United States and take "field trips" to museums, observa
tories, science exhibits, and research centers without leaving the classroom.  Students would experiment using computer simulations that would otherwise be too dangerous or too expensive to conduct on site.

<li><b>Preschool/Head Start/Schools of Education Network </b>-- Establish a network that would link preschools, head start programs and schools of education in a region or across the country that would make available innovative curricula and programming s
pecifically for day care, preschool, and head start facilities.

<li><b>Community-based Education and Vocational Resource Centers </b>-- To ensure greater access for traditionally underprivileged or economically depressed areas to the burgeoning resources of the NII, establish an initiative that gives priority access t
o community agencies offering job training and placement.  The initiative should target community based organizations such as the Boys and Girls Clubs, YMCAs and YWCAS, local schools that offer after-school hours, and other community learning centers.  Th
ese centers could be linked to job and training resources in a Jobs Clearinghouse that posts job information from state Divisions of Employment Security and private sector personnel offices.  The Clearinghouse should include a browsing/indexing interface 
so users can locate the job listings they are best suited for and a means for users to submit their resumes electronically to potential employers listed in the database.

<li><b>The Internet as Library </b>-- Give secondary-school students research projects on current topics and provide full Internet access (on-demand) as a data and information resource.  Students would learn to use the Internet resources to find experts a
nd data sources world-wide.  This should include evaluation of the quality of projects compared to students using traditional "library" methods, and evaluation of the students' abilities in and understanding of information gathering.

<li><b>Literacy Assistant </b>-- Develop an interface to on-line information resources for the "textually-challenged" to enable workers with poor literacy skills to access the information that is available, including basic literacy improvement tools, buil
t-in basic pictorial dictionaries, audio translators (text-to-audio readers), and reformatters for minimally-literate users.  A demonstration project could explore how much minimally-literate users will use on-line information if they have text-to-audio t
ranslators, how quickly they will become literate as they see what information is available, and to what extent information technologies can help make information available to minimally-literate adults.
</ul>
<hr>
<h2 align=center>Conclusion</h2>



<p>Information technologies are rapidly becoming available that will 
make learning more effective, more accessible, more interesting, and 
more convenient for reamers of all ages.  Through the NII, these 
technologies will be available to meet the education
 and training needs of Americans in classrooms, homes, at work, and in 
community public facilities.  Through new applications of information 
technologies, the NII will enable unemployed workers to train for new 
careers and employed workers to upgrade their skills to meet changing 
workplace demands; it will make learning exciting for students, from 
preschoolers to graduate students; it will allow teachers to create and 
customize multimedia curricula on demand; and it will turn community 
centers into information gateways for a host of network-based 
resources.  A coordinated effort among federal agencies, through 
programs that complement and supplement efforts by private, state, and 
public service organizations, will help bring the benefits of 
information technologies to the U.S. education and lifelong learning 
system.</p>

<hr>
</html>
