<html>
<head><title>ACCELERATING THE DEVELOPMENT AND DEPLOYMENT OF NII TECHNOLOGIES</title>
<h2 align=center>
PERSPECTIVES ON THE NATIONAL INFORMATION INFRASTRUCTURE:<br></h2>

<h3 align=center>ACCELERATING THE DEVELOPMENT AND DEPLOYMENT OF NII TECHNOLOGIES
<br>

February, 1994</h2>
<hr>

<p><b>TABLE OF CONTENTS </b></p>
 
 
 
<ul>
<li><a href="#introduction">INTRODUCTION</a> <br>
 <li><a href="#government">GOVERNMENT'S ROLE IN RESEARCH AND DEVELOPMENT</a><br>
 <li><a href="#goals">GOALS FOR THE  NII </a><br>
 <li><a href="#recommendations">RECOMMENDATIONS FOR TECHNOLOGY DEVELOPMENT AND R&D INVESTMENT </a><br>
 <li><a href="#scalability">SCALABILITY </a><br>
<li><a href="#interoperability">INTEROPERABILITY </a><br>
<li><a href="#robustness">ROBUSTNESS OF NETWORKS </a><br>
<li><a href="#security">SECURITY AND AUTHENTICATION </a><br>
<li><a href="#integrity">INTEGRITY AND ROBUSTNESS OF DATA STORAGE </a><br>
<li><a href="#database">DATABASE TECHNOLOGY </a><br>
<li><a href="#multimedia">MULTIMEDIA </a><br>
<li><a href="#ease">EASE OF USE </a><br>
<li><a href="#affordability">AFFORDABILITY AND HIGH PERFORMANCE </a><br>
<li><a href="#conclusion">CONCLUSION </a><br>
</ul>
 <hr>
<p><b><a name="introduction">INTRODUCTION</a> </b></p>
 
<p>The Computer Systems Policy Project (CSPP) outlined its vision for an enhanced National Information Infrastructure ( NII) in its January 1993 report, <i>Perspectives on the National Information Infrastructure</i>, which also recommended a joint effort between the Administration, Congress and the private sector to accelerate the development and deployment of the  NII.  In CSPP's vision, the  NII is an advanced information infrastructure that will be accessible to all Americans anytime, anywhere that will allow all Americans to take advantage of our rich resources in information, communication, and computing technologies.  The  NII will integrate four essential elements -- communications networks, computers, information, and people - to create a whole new way of learning, working and interacting with others.  It will put information technologies to work to benefit people through improved access to health care, better education opportunities, more efficient manufacturing processes and business practices, and easier access to all kinds of information and government services. </p>
 
 
 
<p>In order for this vision to become a reality, investments are needed in research on the underlying technologies that are critical to the NII's further enhancement and evolution.  The private sector is already investing heavily in a wide range of research on information technologies and applications.  The Administration's High Performance Computing and Communications (HPCC) Program, and in particular the Program's Information Infrastructure Applications Technologies component, is an excellent step in support of the private sector's efforts to lay the research foundation for the  NII.  To help guide federal R&D funding prioritization decisions in order to better meet the nation's needs for an enhanced  NII, this paper describes the research needed to advance nine technology areas that CSPP considers critical to enable the  NII, and identifies specific research needs in each of those areas that would benefit from federal funding support. </p>
 
 
 <hr>
<h2><a name="government">GOVERNMENT'S ROLE IN RESEARCH AND DEVELOPMENT </a></h2>
 
<p>The private sector has the primary responsibility for developing and deploying the  NII and is investing significant amounts in R&D to advance the necessary technologies.  However, there are certain pre-commercial research challenges -generally long-term and high risk -- that are beyond the scope of any single company.  In these cases, the federal government, with private sector input, has a role in funding research and in promoting collaborative work among industries, academia, and government labs.  Universities, government labs, and private industry should all participate in carrying out such research.  Pilot projects that will apply and integrate advanced technologies must involve users and private sector participants as well as technology providers and academic researchers. </p>
 
 
<p><b>Testbeds and Demonstration Projects </b></p>
 
<p>It is important to address, apply, and integrate the nine technology areas identified in this paper in  NII pilot projects to obtain near-term feedback on the most pressing problems, on what technology works, and where more work is needed.  Pilot projects will help to rapidly develop and integrate needed technologies, to make them responsive to real requirements, and ultimately, to achieve the NII goals as expeditiously as possible.  Testbeds and demonstration projects should focus on precommercial areas and should include benchmarking of present status, agreed-upon evaluation processes, and a mechanism for technology information dissemination to take advantage of the outcome.  To the extent possible, demonstrations of the use of information technologies should include testing and deployment in appropriate government institutions. </p>
 
 
 
<p>Funding of NII pilot projects should be based on the following considerations:</p>
<ul>
<li>Relative importance of the pilot application to national goals.
Healthcare, manufacturing, and education should be given highest priority.  High priority should also be placed on pilot projects focused on government and library applications.<br>

<li>Quality and aggressiveness of the proposal, with respect to the scope of work and to how hard it pushes the technology envelope.<br>

<li>Likelihood of the participants to successfully complete the proposed work and to transfer resulting new technologies into robust commercial products.

</ul>

<p>In order to make best use of its R&D resources, the U.S. government should develop a set of guidelines for determining when a given technology, demonstration project, or testbed is precommercial (thus qualifying for government R&D support) and when it has matured to be competitive (therefore best addressed by competing commercial providers).  When funding R&D on precommercial technologies, the government should develop a plan for how it will phase out its role as the technologies, demonstration projects, and testbeds evolve and become competitive. </p>
 
 <hr>
<h2><a name="goals">GOALS FOR THE  NII</a></h2>
 
<p>To bring the benefits of information technology to all Americans, the  NII must be powerful enough to carry voice, video, and text simultaneously, provide two-way interactive capabilities when users need them, be easily accessible by users with widely varying skills and abilities, operate across different technologies and media, provide the right amounts of reliability and security, and be flexible enough to grow to meet the changing demands of an increasing number of users, all at a cost that makes it affordable to large numbers of users. </p>
 
 
<p>The information technologies of the  NII must provide the underpinning needed to advance and support large-scale applications in healthcare, education, manufacturing, and access to government information and services.  To focus on one application area for example, NII technologies, as they mature and are integrated and deployed, will help improve the quality and the efficiency of the U.S. healthcare industry.  Through the use of advanced information technology, the healthcare industry will shift from using information technology to perform basic data processing tasks like client and insurance billing and hospital management to using it for a wide variety of advanced applications aimed at providing better and more efficient client care and training of healthcare professionals.  The following are a few examples of how the delivery of healthcare can be improved through advancements in the  NII technologies identified in this paper:</p>


<ul>
<li>Medical libraries, medical schools, and reference labs across the U.S. will develop large data warehouses of medical specialty image and video data (hematology, cytology, surgical, diagnostic, etc.) for reference, education, and advanced training.  Heterogeneous computer systems at major medical schools and hospitals will be joined via wide bandwidth data networks to share and update this valuable information.  Using intuitive visual inquiry and navigation computer interfaces, physicians and students will routinely access this national data resource to remain informed about the best, most successful medical practices.<br>



<li>Secure medical information networks will revolutionize the provision of daily care.  Private physicians, dentists, clinics, HMOs, hospitals, nursing homes, and other health facilities will be linked directly to insurance companies and government agencies in a highly secure, heterogeneous records management system.  Millions of standardized transactions per day for claims, payments, and logistics will be created and transmitted across this network -- dramatically reducing paperwork, loss, waste, and delays that plague the healthcare data processing infrastructure today.  Healthcare workers will be able to instantly determine the status of claims and electronic fund transfer payments for which they are authorized.<br>

<li>Medical dictation and transcription will be revolutionized by new user interface technologies, such as speech recognition systems with dozens of custom vocabularies for particular medical specialties (radiology, cardiology, pathology).  Doctors on rounds in the hospital will dictate to and make corrections on an electronic tablet -- a speech-enabled, portable computer with handwriting recognition and wireless connection to the hospital's clinical information system.  Turnaround time on patient reports will go from hours (or days) to minutes.
<br>


<li>Electronic "charts" and clinical information systems will provide the physician and the hospital or HMO staff with a single view of the text and data gathered about the patient from all sources while in the facility -- including the admitting clerks, doctors, nurses, monitoring equipment, operating room, specialty labs, pharmacy, dietitian, and social workers.  Complete, accurate, up-to-the-minute data from all the departments servicing the patient will improve the quality of care and reduce errors resulting from missing or incorrect information.

<br>

<li>Advancements in high-performance, affordable multimedia technologies and development of easy to use systems will enable the delivery of customized healthcare education to patients.  Users will be able to access information "on-demand" about topics such as AIDS, pre-natal care, smoking, and lung cancer, using interactive video (with questions and answers).  On-demand video would also provide in-home treatment information, thus enabling more comfortable and lower cost home treatment in place of frequent outpatient or emergency room episodes.  In an emergency, a doctor could "demand" video to his home, office, or another location to receive information or image data on an ill-patient.

<li>Wireless networks and powerful portable computers will enable emergency workers to access medical information during a natural disaster and assist in coordinating relief activities, evacuation, medical supplies, and triage.

</ul>

<p>To help achieve these and other potential benefits of  NII technologies, CSPP recommends that the private sector, with complementary government support, invest in research to meet the following nine technology goals:</p>

<ul>

<b>1. Scalability: </b>The  NII must be able to grow in many dimensions as the number of network users and access points increases, as the demand for greater and expanded capacity grows, and the heterogeneity of the NII components and user requirements increases.<br><br>

<b>2.  lnteroperability: </b>The NII will be comprised of many interconnected, diverse systems, applications, and services.  These systems must be interoperable -- able to communicate with each other so users do not have to make major adjustments to account for differences in different products or services.<br><br>



<b>3. Robustness of Networks: </b>The  NII will be composed of a large number of communications networks that are interconnected to form a synergistic internetwork which must be reliable, dependable, and available at needed bandwidths on demand.<br><br>



<b>4. Security and Authentication: </b>As the  NII grows, a vast amount of information will	be collected, transmitted, stored, and manipulated electronically.  This information must	be protected against unauthorized access, tampering, and misuse, consistent with the needs of the applications and the desires of the user.  New policies will also be needed to ensure the protection of privacy rights in the digital information era.<br><br>



<b>5.  Integrity and Robustness of Data Storage: </b>As vast quantities of data become available on-line, businesses, governments, and individuals will increasingly rely on being able to have timely access to accurate information.  This will require information providers to be able to ensure round the clock access to information and to protect against natural disasters, terrorist attacks, and system failures.<br><br>



<b>6.	Database Technology:  </b>NII applications will require efficient and effective methods	to access, create, share, search, manage, and manipulate very large amounts	of distributed and diverse forms of information.  This will require information management, processing, and searching capabilities at a scale heretofore not possible.<br><br>



<b>7.	Multimedia Technologies: </b>The convergence of telecommunications, broadcast, cable, and computing technologies offers the promise of a new way of information processing and communication.  With this new "multimedia technology" people will be able to access information and communicate in video, voice, text and data formats.  Multimedia services will be essential to a number of  NII applications, such as collaborative work by people in remote locations, work-at-home, distance learning, and telemedicine, as well as home shopping and interactive entertainment.<br><br>



<b>8.  Ease of Use: </b>The services provided by the NII will require user interfaces that are easy and natural to use by users with varied backgrounds and competency levels.  Graphical user interfaces, handwriting recognition, voice recognition, touch screens, and intelligent agents will help make the  NII easy to learn and use.<br><br>



<b>9.	Affordability and High Performance: </b>To be widely used, the  NII will require very	high performance technologies that are, at the same time, affordable.  Over the last	decade, many of the underlying technologies that will enable  NII applications, including high speed networking, high performance computers, and very fast microprocessors, have been improving at orders of magnitude rates, driving large increases in performance at lower cost.  These rates of increase must be sustained, and in some cases accelerated, to obtain the performance rates and affordable costs that will make NII technologies widely accepted.

</ul>

<hr>

<h2><a name="recommendations">RECOMMENDATIONS FOR TECHNOLOGY DEVELOPMENT AND R&D INVESTMENT</a></h2>



<p>The further advancement of the above  NII technology goals will require industry leadership and federal R&D funding support.  In the following section, CSPP identifies, for each goal, the critical technologies necessary to achieve the goal and the priority research areas appropriate for federal funding support.</p>


<hr>
<h2><a name="scalability">Scalability</a></h2>

<p><b>A.	Technologies Needed to Achieve the Goal</b></p>
<ul>
<b>1.	Network Topology </b>-- The enhanced  NII will grow to provide ubiquitous connectivity to a large proportion of the general population.  Research is needed on how users will connect to the  NII, particularly as wireless access to networks grows, and how the connection mechanisms and architectures will expand to accommodate new users as the NII grows.  The network topology of the  NII will have important effects on the management of the networks that make up the infrastructure.
<br><br>


<b>2. Addressing </b>-- Each user of the  NII will require a unique address (or name), analogous in some ways to a telephone number.  A location independent method for finding users will be needed, along with "directory information" services.<br><br>



<b>3.	Forwarding </b>-- Since users are likely to access computing resources through	the NII from a variety of locations and also while mobile, mechanisms must be	provided to forward user data and messages to wherever the user is currently accessing the  NII.  Ideally, this will be handled transparently by the addressing scheme.  The addressing scheme should be targeted toward people and services, rather than physical places.
<br><br>


<b>4.	Applications </b>-- As technology advances and users' needs change, new NII applications will evolve.  This will require software that allows application development independent of the underlying infrastructure.  This software should provide bandwidth-independent interface paradigms, so that an application will provide the same basic functionality over links with widely varying bandwidth, with additional features available at higher bandwidths.  For example, an application might provide an iconic or still-picture interface over a low-bandwidth interconnect, but full-motion video over an interconnect capable of providing the necessary bandwidth.  The capability to construct applications independent of the underlying network protocols will also be important.<br><br>



<b>5.	Physical </b>-- Much work is needed to ensure that the NII's various transmission media, including, for example, fiber networks, All Optical Networks, wireless networks, cable television systems, and telephone service ISDN connections, will work seamlessly together, will accommodate new media, technologies, and applications as they become available, and will extend to new users.
<br><br>


<b>6. Name and Directory Services </b>-- Services will be required to locate resources and services available through the NII, particularly as the  NII grows, becomes more heterogeneous, supports greater user mobility, and adds new services.  Providers of new products and services will want information about the availability of such products to be easy to find by users.
<br><br>


<b>7. Distributed Information System Architecture </b>-- The NII will be a distributed information system of unparalleled proportions, in terms of numbers and types of users and uses, overall scale, complexity, and sheer volume of information.  Improvements are needed in techniques for architecting such large, complex systems to work efficiently, including how functionality should be apportioned in the infrastructure.  This should include how the multitude of distributed services -- such as transaction management, storage management, query management and execution, security, billing, administration, and others will efficiently and effectively interact to meet user needs.
<br><br>
</ul>

<p><b>B.  Scalability Research and Development Funding Priorities</b></p>

<p>Scalability research that would benefit from government support includes the development of techniques to synchronize network resource databases that are distributed among many organizations; architecting databases to maintain coherence and reliability when network configurations (which these databases affect) change; techniques for providing services to an ever-increasing number of users, including work on directory and locator services; and development of software to support the evolution of common NII services.  Understanding how to build a scaleable NII requires knowledge of the practical problems encountered when the size of the infrastructure grows dramatically.  This can be best addressed through testbeds that provide information services to many users.  Scalability of databases is very important and is covered in the Database section of this paper. </p>
 
<p>The government, with private sector input, can complement industry R&D efforts on scalability by investing in research in the following areas:</p>

<ul>

<b>High Priority</b><br>
Large scale testbeds of heterogeneous components and technologies<br><br>



<b>Medium Priority</b><br>
      Directory and location services<br>
     Addressing<br>
     Common software environment/interfaces
</ul>

<hr>
<h2><a name="interoperability">Interoperability</a></h2>

<p>The enhanced  NII will consist of many different physical components,including:	information appliances, from smart televisions and portable wireless computers	to high-end workstations and supercomputers; communications networks using a variety of technologies -- cable, telephone, wireless, satellite, and others; and databases and information services, such as government documents and data, libraries, private bulletin boards, interactive games and shopping, public service information and government services, education programs, and medical information.  These different pieces of the  NII will be built, supplied, and maintained by hundreds of different vendors, as well as by individuals and government agencies.  lnteroperability -- the ability of different systems to work together -- at key locations in the  NII will ensure that these components will work together and communicate with each other.  This will allow any user to get the information he needs and communicate with the people he needs to, as easily, quickly, and transparently as he can with today's telephone system, and any provider of information to make it available through the NII. </p>
 
<p>As described in CSPP's February, 1994 paper, Perspectives on NII Interoperability, achieving an interoperable  NII requires an industry-led strategy to ensure that the specifications for certain interfaces at critical locations in the infrastructure are open. </p>
 
 
 
<p><b>A.     Technologies Needed to Achieve the Goal </b></p>
 
<p>While interoperability is best addressed by the private sector, government support for research on new testing techniques will help accelerate the private sector's adoption of open interfaces.  For example, to guarantee that NII components work together smoothly and seamlessly, research is needed on improved techniques to test and verify interoperability of interface implementations.  A neutral forum in which industry could demonstrate the interoperability of such implementations would help increase end user confidence that various NII components will work together. </p>
 
<p><b>B.	lnteroperability Research and Development Funding Priorities </b></p>
 
<p>Federal investments in research in the following areas will complement private sector efforts to develop open NII interfaces.</p>


<ul>
<b>High Priority</b><br>
	Interoperability demonstration forum<br><br>

<b>Medium Priority</b><br>
	Test methodology<br>
      lnteroperability certification techniques
</ul>
<hr>
<h2><a name="robustness">Robustness of Networks</a></h2>

<p><b>A.     Technologies Needed to Achieve the Goal</b></p>
<ul>
<b>1.	Network Management </b>-- The NII will be made up of many interconnected, interdependent networks using a variety of technologies.  This will require new techniques for network management to ensure the different networks work together.  With vast quantities of data, applications, and services on-line, businesses, governments, and individuals will increasingly depend on being able to access such information in a timely manner.  This requires dependability, from the requester through the networks to the server and back, for all critical NII services.<br><br>
<ul>
<i>a.	Network Planning </i>- The operation of networks changes as the load imposed	by users changes.  Increased network load may lead to failure of a network	that was stable at a lower level of usage.  Being able to track and analyze long term network trends is critical for the reliability and stability of large internetworks.  Today's network management tools are aimed at detecting faults and correcting malfunctions in stand-alone networks, and are not capable of collecting and analyzing the large amounts of data that will be required to support the internetworks that make up the  NII as it evolves.  Methodologies must be developed for collecting and abstracting relevant data and using it as input in simulation- and analytical-based predictive capacity planning tools.<br><br>



<i>b.	Integration of Networks </i>-- Current network management systems practices focus on using monitoring devices, such as bridges, routers, and subscriber attachments, with emphasis on conveying the device-oriented data to the network management console.  The ability to control a network's operations is typically limited to setting individual device parameters.  As the size and complexity of a network increases, the management task grows more complex, and the device-oriented method must be replaced by an integrated system view that takes into account the load placed on the network by mobile users.  As the  NII evolves and network management challenges grow more complex, systems should be able to respond to a wide variety of situations automatically, without human intervention.  Additionally, presentation services for network management data must be developed that include methods for visualizing and interpreting the management data generated from extremely large internetworks.  These services will provide a means to understand internetwork operational trends and identify management actions required for proper internetwork operation.
<br><br>


<i>c.	Network Operations </i>-- The current state-of-the-art for network management must be expanded to include methodologies and tools for dealing with the network management issues encountered in extremely large internetworks, which include multiple, distributed, autonomous domains and multiple, cooperating managers and interdomain management by multiple, mutually suspicious managers.  These tools must address synchronization and conflict resolution issues between multiple managers.</ul>
<br>
<b>2.	Engineering a More Reliable lnternetwork</b>
<ul>
<i>a.	Network Design </i>-- The  NII will include an extremely large internetwork of both wired and wireless networks.  Methodologies and tools are needed to assist network designers in designing reliable and robust network interconnects in order to produce internetworks that will meet specified reliability and robustness criteria.<br><br>

<i>b.	Policy Routing Algorithms </i>-- The NII's internetwork will be comprised of dissimilar domain types.  For example, one domain may provide for low latency guaranteed delivery, while another may provide slower, unguaranteed handling of traffic.  Methods and techniques must be developed to reconcile these differences so that traffic generated in one domain requiring a specific class of service (e.g., bandwidth or protocol) can be handled, delivered to, or through, another domain with dissimilar abilities.  Policy routing is important to ensure reliability for two reasons.  First, the behavior of the networks that comprise the  NII should be repeatably predictable when users attempt to route between two dissimilar domains.  Second, due to outages of communication links and nodes, it may be necessary to transparently reroute traffic on an alternate path through domains that have very different characteristics.<br><br>

<i>c.	Engineering Protocols and Routing Algorithms </i>-- The internetworks of the NII will grow and change over time.  Tools and methods will be needed to provide a high level of assurance that the components of the NII will function correctly when they are connected in the  NII internetwork environment.  Improved methods for specifying protocols and designing, implementing, validating and verifying protocol implementations applied to interdomain routing protocols and algorithms are needed to increase the reliability and availability of the components of the  NII.<br><br>

<i>d.     Reliable Protocols and Routing Algorithms </i>-- Research is needed to design protocols and routing algorithms that provide reliable service in the face of planned or unplanned network changes (topological and operational).  These protocols and routing algorithms must: be able to rapidly respond to changes in the network topology that are caused by either component failures or by reconfiguration of the internetwork; be able to accommodate the requirements of the mobile network user, such as connections implemented on physical circuits that may not be permanent or physically reliable; be designed to be manageable; interface with network management systems and provide data that describes the state of the internetwork; and be able to make use of redundant paths in networks in order to provide enhanced reliability as well as load balancing.<br><br>

<i>e.	Hardware Dependability Technology </i>-- Research is required to determine how transients affect logic and memory circuits, and how VLSI scaling will affect transient error rates.  Improved computer aided design (CAD) tools to ensure design correctness, new design-for-test methods, and on-line techniques to detect errors before they can corrupt the data are needed.  In addition, high quality resilient power, perhaps including new battery technologies, could benefit from additional research.<br><br>


<i>f.	Software Dependability Technology </i>-- With new  NII services and applications being developed, software engineering research is needed in areas of software fault modeling, design test, and verification of the NII services for the ability to tolerate arbitrary failures, fault recovery and discovery.</ul><br></ul>

<p><b>B.	Network Research and Development Funding Priorities</b></p>

<p>The federal government can help the private sector advance the reliability,
availability, dependability, and robustness of networks by focusing research in the
following areas:</p>
<ul>
<b>High Priority</b><br>
	Network interconnection methodologies and tools<br>
      Reliable protocols and routing algorithms<br><br>

<b>Medium Priority</b><br>
     Tracking and analyzing long term network trends<br>
	Network management methodologies<br>
     Reliable network connections</ul>
<hr>
<h2><a name="security">Security and Authentication</a></h2>

<p><b>A.	Technologies Needed to Achieve the Goal</b></p>

<p>Many of the technologies needed to provide the security people will need for their	NII applications already exist.  However, many of these technologies are available only in high security environments to protect the nation's most sensitive and classified information.  Making these technologies available for public use, along with reducing their cost, will significantly improve the security of information available through the  NII.  For technologies that are not currently available, research investments are needed to enable secure systems to access information, protect user identity, provide message encryption, and guarantee reliability of networks.</p>
<ul>
<b>1.	Access to Information</b>
<ul>
<i>a.	Controls </i>-- At present, access to information, communications, and computing resources is usually controlled by a combination of electronic and physical barriers, such as passwords and access to computer rooms, data centers, and buildings.  One computer's access to another is usually controlled primarily by the static structure of the underlying communication network.  These available systems of access control result in an inflexible and insecure network.  New technologies that would improve access controls include: 1) a family of international standards for 'smart cards' or other personal tokens to allow challenge and response authentications and to eliminate the passage of plain text passwords over the NII; and 2) similar cryptographic techniques for computer to computer access control.<br><br>

<i>b.	Auditing </i>-- Technologies will be necessary to record sufficient information about transactions or other events in a manner that will establish accountability for a later study of the records.  Often, it is difficult to select the correct events to audit or to analyze the audit trail once it has been collected, particularly if the system attempts to do real time intrusion detection.  Auditing is further complicated by the need to guarantee that the audit trail is not itself a threat to user security or privacy.</ul>

<b>2.	Identity Protection</b>
<ul>
<i>a.	Anonymous Transactions </i>-- With the adoption of electronic delivery of services, there will be increased demand for the ability to conduct anonymous transactions to protect the privacy rights of individuals and to protect against fraudulent users who might use anonymity to their advantage.  For example, an individual casting his electronic vote in a popular election will need to be guaranteed that his anonymity and security against fraud are protected.  Present techniques for both digital money and voting are cumbersome and fail to capture the precise qualities of more traditional forms.  Protocols for both anonymous voting and digital money are active topics of research in security and need to be improved.<br><br>

<i>b.	Authentication of Identity and Data </i>-- In many transactions, the identity of an individual or computer must be identified in the course of communication or computing.  Excellent cryptographic techniques for identity authentication are readily available, though not widely deployed.  Authentication is also necessary to determine that data, such as digital signatures, have not been altered in ways that change the meaning of the data.  Digital signatures can guarantee that the signed object has not been altered.  It is often difficult, however, to determine whether a person has signed his name to something more complex than just the intended message.  With authentication of digital signatures, the identity of a signator must be established so that a third party, not involved in the transaction, can be convinced of the signature identity and the signator cannot later deny having made his signature.  Data authentication will become more difficult as the NII fosters use of complex services, such as interactive simulations, as means of interpersonal communication.  Currently, digital signature schemes suitable to most computer communication applications are available, though not yet widely deployed.</ul>


<b>3.	Encryption</b>
<ul>
<i>a.	Message Traffic </i>-- Sensitive information may need to be encrypted so that	messages cannot be understood or produced by anyone who does not possess the secret keys.  Cryptographic keys function very much like passwords.  The keys are pieces of information with no intrinsic value that control access to valuable information.<br><br>

The public availability of cryptographic systems suitable for message encryption varies with speed:<br>
<ul>
<li>at 1 0 megabits	good
<li>at 1 00 megabits	fair
<li>at 1 gigabit	poor
<li>at 10 gigabits	non-existent
</ul>
Within the U.S., the most popular choice for message encryption is the Data Encryption Standard (FIPS 46) or multiple applications of this standard. However, this system is generally not exportable, which often makes reliable message encryption unavailable in international communications.<br><br>

<i>b.     Public Key Technology </i>-- Public key technology allows for the construction of cryptosystems controlled by corresponding pairs of keys that permit a message to be encrypted for authenticity or privacy independently.  Public key cryptography provides a flexible and secure mechanism for negotiating and transmitting keys used in electronic mail and interactive communications.  To guarantee secure communications, key management is essential in placing suitable keys in the possession of various pieces of cryptographic equipment.<br><br>

The current number theory based methods for encryption appear very strong.  The actual parameter sizes in use and proposed for many applications are too small for long term security.  The performance of current systems (in both size and speed) makes them unsuitable for some applications and the mathematical diversity of current systems is undesirably low.  A single breakthrough in discrete logarithms or integer factoring would be disastrous.  Consequently, it is important to develop additional methods based on different fields of mathematics.</ul>



<b>4.     Secure and Reliable Networks</b>
<ul>
<i>a.	Secure Computing </i>-- Users of the NII must be confident that the hardware and software perform as specified and cannot be undermined by untrusted programs or interacting resources.  More specifically, a user or system administrator must be able to guarantee that a security policy in a workstation, server, or network cannot be altered by another user.  All known techniques for demonstrating that cryptography programs of even modest complexity perform as intended are extremely expensive.  As a result, guarantees are limited to elementary security properties of essential programs so that a disaster will not occur if there is a malfunction in another part of the system.  Unfortunately, even this has proven ineffective and does not guarantee diverse kinds of correct functions required in many commercial applications.<br><br>



<i>b.	Strength and Security Assessment </i>-- Attacks to defeat a security system are often costly.  Users assess the security and strength of a crypto system through a combination of formal methods and penetration attempts.  The public community has had substantial success recently in developing cryptanalytic methods for strength assessment, but lacks confidence in any system that has not been studied for several years.  It is believed that there is no rigorous theory of resistance to cryptanalysis available anywhere in the world.  Presently, there does not exist a method for customers (individual or corporate) to protect themselves against trap doors installed, for whatever reason, by the suppliers.<br><br>


<ul>
1) Tamper Resistance -- Tamper resistant equipment must be built that can resist reverse engineering and operate unattended while concealing its operating parameters (often cryptographic keys) and perhaps its design.  Assessment of the tamper resistance of chips and other hardware is by and large an art proprietary to companies in the physical security or smart card businesses.  The quality of such assessments is open to debate.  Various techniques for building tamper resistant chips or packaging equipment in tamper resistant containers have been proposed, but none is readily available to the commercial security equipment designer.
<br><br>


2)	Electromagnetic Shielding -- Electromagnetic shields must be developed to protect information in computer and communication systems from being radiated or conducted to outsiders along unintended paths.  Assessment of the exploitability of electromagnetic emissions or the signal contamination depends largely on development of specialized test equipment and is virtually non-existent in the public domain.  An elaborate technology code named TEMPEST is employed by the military, but this technology is secret and its products have generally been more expensive, heavier, and bulkier than comparable unshielded equipment.  A public theory of electromagnetic shielding for security purposes, that could provide the basis for deciding how much shielding is required in commercial equipment, is lacking.</ul></ul>
</ul>


<p><b>B.    Security and Authentication Research and Development Funding Priorities</b></p>

<p>Because security technology has undergone extensive development in both the public and private sectors, many of the basic security mechanisms needed for the National Information Infrastructure already exist.  Nonetheless, there is a wide gap between our present situation and the tools we need to provide users with the security they will need for various NII applications.  The federal government can help close this gap by funding, in close cooperation with the private sector, research in the following areas.</p>

<ul>
<b>High Priority</b><br>

Development of security assessment methodology<br>
Efficient methods for anonymous transactions<br>
Super-high-speed cryptosystems<br>
Worldwide interoperable secure systems</ul>
<hr>

<h2><a name="integrity">Integrity and Robustness of Data Storage</a></h2>

<p><b>A.    Technologies needed to achieve the goal</b></p>
<ul>
<b>1.	New Storage Media and Devices </b>-- The evolution of the  NII will fuel enormous growth in the quantity of on-line data.  Today's storage devices are unlikely to be economic or provide adequate performance given the magnitude of growth in information.  Research should be focused on the development of new kinds of storage media and devices.  Particular focus should be given to improvements in cost per byte, higher storage density, and intrinsic reliability through the elimination of moving parts.  Consideration should be given to the development of hierarchical storage systems that migrate less frequently accessed data to slower, more cost effective storage media/devices over time.  Further research is needed on the extension of storage techniques such as holographic and molecular storage technologies.<br><br>



<b>2.	Size and Performance </b>-- The management of very large databases, on the order of petabytes (1 OA 12 bytes), represents a significant challenge for physical storage management techniques such as indexing, archiving, dumping/loading, reorganizing, partitioning, and sorting, as well as strategies for data retention and periodic deletion.  New data organization and query processing strategies will be needed to provide users with easier ways to locate data.  To accommodate databases that grow in size and usage over time, it will be important to devise scaleable systems, such as those that employ hierarchical storage strategies and multiprocessing approaches that can grow with needs to accommodate huge data sets, complex requests, and large numbers of users.  To avoid loss of data through media deterioration/volatility, tests must be devised and deployed for automatic monitoring of storage media, with alerts issued when it is necessary to migrate data to newer media.  To facilitate the administration of large scale databases, knowledge-based techniques must be devised to enable systems to be self-administering, e.g., by performing self-monitoring of activities and access patterns, self-indexing, and self-partitioning and reorganization.<br><br>



<b>3.	System Configuration and Maintenance </b>-- Even with today's specialized, high availability systems, scheduled down time is required to update key software.  Systems also require down time to deal with addition, deletion or backup of critical data.  Such down time will be poorly tolerated as the NII becomes a critical component of business and individuals' lives, with round the clock availability a necessity.  Research should be directed towards developing ways to maintain system access in the face of inevitable configuration and backup requirements.  Particular emphasis should be given to the problem of on-line upgrade of the operating system and other critical components.  Highest levels of availability will only be achieved through a systematic elimination of single points of failure and the need to change system components, software or configuration through planned outages.  Research should be directed towards eliminating these causes of system outage.<br><br>

<b>4. Multimedia Servers and Database Systems </b>--  NII databases will have to allow for efficient searching as well as delivery of high volumes of multimedia information, including handling combined coded and non-coded information.  The scheduling algorithms used in today's databases are optimized for most transaction throughput, and will not be adequate for multimedia servers, where audio and video information must meet real-time playback constraints.  Many applications will also require queries based on information content rather than coded indices.<br><br>



<b>5.	Aging Effects on Long-Term Storage </b>-- Although some information can be thought of as short lived, that is, having a finite useful life, the majority of information has long lasting value.  Once committed to data storage, information must continue to be safely stored for the foreseeable future.  Although typical storage devices such-as magnetic and optical disks have become more reliable, research is needed to understand the effects of aging and environmental impact on different media types.  Research in this area should also focus on the development of new storage media with stable and long lasting properties for information storage.  Given current limitations on media life, research should be conducted on the prediction of data loss and how and when to copy or upgrade information.  Models describing the long term characteristics of media degradation should be developed and incorporated into the long term storage strategy.<br><br>


<b>6.	High Speed Archiving Techniques </b>- As the volume of on-line data increases and availability requirements approach 100% up time, today's mechanisms for archiving and making backup copies of information will become too slow.  The majority of today's on-line archival techniques require either that data is maintained in a read-only state or captures updated information to deal with change.  As the NII evolves, the ability to access the state of information at a particular time will become a requirement.  Archiving evolving data will become common place.  Research is needed to develop new techniques and approaches to achieve data capture of large quantities of data and strategies for dissemination as needed.  Research is also required to achieve rapid access to archived data through storage hierarchies and other techniques.<br><br>



<b>7.  Protection From Malicious Corruption </b>-- Significant impact to businesses and individuals will result if information in the NII is corrupted through malicious intent.  While physical and logical computer security can address these concerns to some degree, accurate and high performance techniques are required to facilitate real-time monitoring of information and to enable the immediate freezing of access upon detection of corrupted data in order to prevent decisions or actions being based on altered information.<br><br>

<b>8. Protection From Natural Disasters and System Failures </b>-- Perhaps the only viable approach to dealing with natural disasters and large system failures is redundancy of storage in widely separated geographic areas.  Specific research is needed to facilitate high speed, distributed mirroring of information while maintaining data integrity and accessibility.</ul>



<p><b>B.	Data Storage Research and Development Funding Priorities</b></p>

<p>Research on data storage should be directed toward architecture and system management strategies and how these interact with user models and data "popularity." Selected focus should also be given to material physics and storage mechanisms where expertise exists or could be developed or expanded.  Federal funding, with private sector input, should be targeted in the following areas.</p>


<ul>
<b>High Priority</b><br>
	New storage media<br>
     Size and performance of storage media<br>
     System configuration and management issues<br><br>

<b>Medium Priority</b><br>
	Long term storage<br>
      Protection from malicious corruption<br>
      Protection from natural disasters<br>
	High speed archiving techniques<br>
      Multimedia servers and database systems</ul>
<hr>
<h2><a name="database">Database Technology</a></h2>

<p><b>A.	Technologies Needed to Achieve the Goal</b></p>
<ul>
<b>1.	Integration and Distribution </b>-- A current pressing need in and across industries is to provide integrated and ready access to independently developed and autonomous data systems.  The problem of enabling a company or an industry to gain such access is commonly called the "legacy problem." Virtually every major business and government agency suffers from the legacy problem, and solutions to it have the potential to dramatically improve operational efficiencies of these organizations.<br><br>



The capability to provide point-to-point access to distributed information is well in hand.  However, the ability to correlate and semantically integrate information from multiple sources must be devised, to free each individual user from the burden of performing such integration manually.  This capability should include the ability to seamlessly integrate information from multiple sources, multiple data models, and multiple data formats, e.g., records, text, images, audio, multidimensional sensor data, and many others.  Research is needed on devising a multi-database capability, which will enable users to develop, maintain, and efficiently use a single "logical view" of multiple databases, obtain a consistent view of the data, and have transparent access to the underlying multiple sources.<br><br>


<b>2.	Intelligent Information Systems </b>-- Research is needed to develop enriched information systems that can: process, reduce, abstract and fuse data to make it more useful; represent, manipulate, and search approximate and/or fuzzy information; use semantic information to dramatically improve query performance; and apply rule-based reasoning within and across information systems to derive answers to queries (some applications of the latter have been called information dredging or mining).  In addition, capabilities must be devised for pattern recognition on data-rich forms of information, including images, multidimensional data, and voice segments, to greatly improve users' ability to find such information without exhaustive search.<br><br>

<b>3.	Mobile Computing/Computer Appliances </b>-- Technology advancements are needed to support mobile information devices or appliances in the synchronization of information between the mobile device and the source, and the ability to modify it in either or both places; caching strategies for efficient interoperation; small and specialized database management systems (DBMS) engines especially tuned for use on a portable computer; and easy and possibly transparent administration of mobile databases for lay users.<br><br>

<b>4. Multimedia Database Management </b>-- Multimedia data places quite different demands on a database management system than traditional record-based data.  Although today's multimedia servers have built-in data management systems tailored to these large volumes of information, they do not allow for index-based searching common to relational database systems, nor do they scale to handle the large volume that will be available through the NII.  For example, what does it mean to update an image?  Does it mean total replacement, or can one modify or enhance just part of the image?  If the latter, how is such an update expressed, and how is the image structured in storage to permit such an operation?  Also needed will be new query optimization, concurrency control, and transaction management techniques to support efficient use and sharing of multimedia data.<br><br>



<b>5.	Data Modeling and Representation </b>-- The more expressive a data model	is, the better able it is to capture the semantics of an application.  DBMSs	that support rich (object-oriented) data models seem best suited to a number of important services in the  NII, including information integration, meta-data repositories, dictionaries, and directories.  Experiments with object oriented DBMSs for such NII applications should be conducted, and their capabilities extended.  To free users from having to know the precise terms used in databases relevant to the query, capabilities should be developed for the semantic normalization of queries.  This capability would map query terms, using something similar to a thesaurus.  To facilitate data organization and presentation, techniques for data summarization and abstraction will be needed to capture high-level descriptions of documents, scientific data, and various collections of related items, including multimedia.  Finally, development of information representation and communication standards will become increasingly important for efficient use of the NII.  The standards must cover data models, query languages, electronic data interchange representations and protocols for all types of information, including documents, text, drawings, video, audio, and every other abundant form of information.<br><br>

<b>6. Customization for Specialized Applications </b>-- It is not feasible for any single database engine to anticipate and provide the necessary functionality to efficiently store, access, search, and manipulate the diverse forms of information available through the NII.  Research is needed on tool kits and piece parts to facilitate easy construction of specialized database management engines for multimedia and other diverse forms of information.  Such kits should provide for appropriate and customizable storage structures, search, update capabilities, query optimizer construction, concurrency control and transaction management.<br><br>
</ul>
<p><b>B.    Database Research and Development Funding Priorities</b></p>

<p>The government, with private sector input, should focus database R&D support in the following areas:</p>
<ul>
<b>High Priority</b><br>
      Integration and distribution<br>
	Intelligent information systems<br><br>

<b>Medium Priority</b><br>
	Synchronization of information for mobile computing<br>
	Multimedia database management<br>
	Data modeling/representation<br>
      Distributed information system architecture</ul>
<hr>

<h2><a name="multimedia">Multimedia Technologies</a></h2>

<p><b>A.     Technologies Needed to Achieve the Goal</b></p>
<ul>
<b>1. Common Software Environment </b>-- Research is needed to develop common platforms and a common software environment within which multiple multimedia applications can function and be linked.  This is necessary so that entrepreneurs can write applications for the common software environment, rather than developing applications software repetitively for each distinct operating environment.<br><br>



<b>2. Display Technology </b>-- Advances are needed in display technology, combining high resolution and proper color-rendition with lightweight, space saving display screens.<br><br>



<b>3. Switching and Transport of Multimedia Signals </b>-- While significant bandwidth to support multimedia is available (or can be deployed) within the fiber-optic networks of many telecommunications transport providers, current network switching capabilities are limited in their ability to handle the varying combinations of information units that will arise in multimedia applications.  Emerging switching and transport techniques based on Asynchronous Transfer Mode (ATM), for example, are aimed at providing support optimized for multimedia applications.  However, significant work needs to be done to develop "call control" and signaling techniques best suited to multimedia.  Industry needs to continue R&D and deployment of multimedia switching and transport technology.<br><br>

<b>4. Compression </b>-- Multimedia has a unique set of compression problems as one moves through the various media formats -- full motion video, image and text.  Full motion video transmissions can tolerate greater amounts of data loss than can transmissions of images, which, in turn, can tolerate greater losses than text transmissions.<br><br>
</ul>

<p><b>B.	Multimedia Research and Development Funding Priorities</b></p>

<p>Government support for private sector research in the underlying technologies to enable the development by industry of multimedia applications for the NII should be focused in the following areas:</p>
<ul>
<b>High Priority</b><br>
	Display technology<br>
      "Call control" and signaling of multimedia<br>
	Common software environment<br><br>

<b>Medium Priority</b><br>
	Compression</ul>
<hr>
<h2><a name="ease">Ease of Use</a></h2>

<p><b>A.	Technologies Needed to Achieve the Goal</b></p>
<ul>
<b>1. User Interfaces </b>- Research is needed to develop context-sensitive interface agents that are adaptable to individual styles of interaction with computers.  These agents will use models of the task, in conjunction with the user's and the appliance's capabilities, to determine what information to present, when to present it, and how to best present it; as well as how to best receive information and direction from the user.<br><br>

<b>2.	Media Models and 1/0 Techniques</b><br><br>
<ul>
<i>a.	Voice and Audio Processing</i>: Voice/audio processing is an important natural	interface application.  New voice/audio features are needed to match features available with current text processing.  More natural quality and affordable speech synthesis (with personal characteristics) systems are needed.
<br><br>


<i>b.	Pen-based systems: </i>Pen-based systems, such as Personal Digital Assistants or Personal Communicators, have recently been introduced as portable commercial products.  They are based on electromagnetic digitizer or resistive digitizer technologies and have mostly hand printing (as opposed to handwriting) recognition capabilities.  Pen-based systems technology has emerged as the new input medium supplementing keyboard for mobile applications.  Greater robustness in handwriting recognition capabilities of these systems is needed.  New techniques, such as "inking," which is a new data type that uses vector-based bit-map storing of chronological pen-specific stroke information such as pen's starting and ending-points, velocity, pressure, and color, are emerging to address this need.<br><br>

<i>c.	Touch and Gesture</i>: Research is needed to improve touch and gesture input techniques, which will be used for many  NII applications (particularly in applications that use virtual reality).</ul>

<b>3. Information Navigators and Visualizers </b>-- Workable navigation techniques with user-friendly interfaces are needed to help users access complex, widely distributed data in multiple formats.  Building a system that allows NII users to easily find the sources of information they are looking for is a challenge in itself, and the additional constraints of low cost and fast response create an important and difficult problem.  Advanced user interfaces to information resources will require new database access and data rendering techniques.  Advanced software will be needed to construct and maintain physical and logical databases, including integrated views of multiple databases.  New capabilities that help the user to browse data and formulate queries will be essential.  Research is also needed on ways to specify or otherwise construct user interest profiles and the infrastructure to continuously monitor selected sources and route matching information to the user.</ul>

<p><b>B.	Ease of Use Research and Development Funding Priorities</b></p>

<p>The private sector is investing heavily in research on technologies needed for a user friendly NII.  In addition to research on the following technologies, the federal government can support these efforts by increasing its investment in the development of personnel skilled in cognitive engineering or human factors.  Such professionals are needed to transform user cognitive and physical needs into easy to use product designs.</p>
<ul>
<b>High Priority</b><br>
      Voice input/output<br>
	Pen based input<br><br>

<b>Medium Priority</b><br>
      Information navigators and visualizers
</ul>
<hr>

<h2><a name="affordability">Affordability and High Performance</a></h2>

<p><b>A.	Technologies Needed to Achieve the Goal</b></p>
<ul>
<b>1. High Resolution Display Subsystems </b>-- Affordable high resolution displays will enable a multitude of new  NII applications and greater access to the NII.  High resolution display subsystems are needed that will support full motion video and provide image quality approaching that of printed material.  Mobile appliances will need displays of similar quality.  Also, the display architecture/standard must be scaleable, extensible, and open to allow display units, with higher/lower values of resolution, rates, and color, to produce a reasonable image.
<br><br>


<b>2.	High Speed Networking </b>-- In local area networks, many applications, such as video conferencing and client-server computing, require bandwidths of a few megabits per second (on a non-shared basis).  Other applications, however, such as designers using CAD/CAMs, will require much higher bandwidths.  The very high speed local area networks (LANS) (several hundred megabits per second) will be used for backbone LAN and supercomputer/high performance workstation interconnections.
<br><br>


<b>3.	Optoelectronics </b>-- Additional research on optoelectronic technologies will lead to the development of high capacity, lower cost, and low-maintenance transmission systems which will support the aggregation of multimedia applications and the provision of affordable bandwidth across a wide area.
<br><br>


<b>4.      All-Optical Networks </b>-- Advancements in All-Optical Networks (AONS) will increase the availability of low cost telecommunications capacity.<br><br>


<b>5.	Wireless Technologies </b>-- One of the critical technologies needed to realize the  NII goal of communication with anyone, anywhere, and any time is wireless technology.  Hand-held Personal Communicators capable of fax, electronic mail, voice and data communication through wireless medium have just appeared in the market, but are still not commonly affordable.  Today's cellular voice communication is mostly based on analog technology, but is gradually evolving to digital technology which improves spectrum efficiency and security.  Work is needed to increase the transmission speeds of wireless data networks.<br><br>

<b>6.	Interactive Video Technologies </b>-- Interactive video applications will be one of the major attractions of the NII.  Improvements in several technologies will be key to making interactive video affordable at adequate performance levels, including connection mechanisms that provide low-cost, simple interfaces with adequate bandwidth, and local processing and memory to meet the delivery constraints of real-time data at low cost.<br><br>

<b>7.	Computer-aided Software Engineering Tools </b>-- Advanced software engineering tools will be necessary to enable vendors to create affordable applications and content for the NII.  Today's software engineering techniques are adequate for addressing the creation of large scale applications, but have not been tested with a community of users as large, and applications as diverse, as those that would make up the NII.
</ul>


<p><b>B.	Affordability and High Performance Research and Development Funding Priorities</b></p>



<p>The federal government, with private sector input, should invest in research in the following areas to accelerate the development of affordable, high performance  NII technologies.</p>
<ul>
<b>High Priority</b><br>
	High resolution display subsystems<br>
	High speed networking<br>
      Optoelectronics<br><br>

<b>Medium Priority</b><br>
      Wireless technologies<br>
	Interactive video technologies<br>
      All-optical networks<br>
	Computer-aided software environment</ul>
<hr>

<h2><a name="conclusion">CONCLUSION</a></h2>

<p>The NII is well on its way to becoming a reality.  The Administration and Congress are committed to addressing a number of policy issues that are inhibiting private sector investment in and deployment of new technologies.  In the meantime, significant research is being conducted by both the public and private sectors on an array of underlying technologies needed for a successful NII.  This paper is intended to provide guidance for federal policymakers as they develop R&D budget priorities for the HPCC and other research programs so they can best complement private sector research.</p>

<hr>
<hr>
