<html>
<head><title>Ensuring Interoperability</title>
<h2 align=center>
Perspectives on the
National Information Infrastructure:
Ensuring lnteroperability

Computer Systems Policy Project
February 1994
</h2>
<hr>
<p>
TABLE 0F CONTENTS</p>
<p>
<a href="#executive">Executive Summary<br> </a>
<a href="#background">Background: From Vision to Reality<br></a>
<a href="#interoperability">Interoperability in the NII<br></a>
		<ul><a href="#an">An Essential Element<br></a>
		<a href="#advancing">Advancing NII Goals<br></a>
		<a href="#critical">Critical NII Interfaces<br></a>
		<a href="#principles">Principles for a Strategy on Interoperability</ul></a>
<a href="#cspp">CSPP Recommendations<br></a>
	<ul><a href="#action">Action Agenda for Industry<br></a>
	<a href="#agenda">Agenda for Government Support</ul></a>
<a href="#appendix">Appendix: Critical Interfaces For Interoperability in the NII<br></a>
		<ul><a href="#appliance">Appliance to Network<br></a>
		<a href="#to">Appliance to Application<br></a>
		<a href="#application">Application to Application<br></a>
		<a href="#network">Network to Network</ul></a>
</p>
<hr><h2>
<a name="executive>EXECUTIVE SUMMARY</a></h2>

<p>The concept of an improved and enhanced National Information Infrastructure (NII) has captured the American imagination.  Over the last several years, various industries, including the computer industry, have devoted significant time to outlining a vision for the NII - what could it and should it do? </p>
<p>Now, with a vision for the NII firmly in place, attention has shifted to how industry and government can work together to make that vision a reality.  CSPP believes interoperability is the key. </p>
<p>In this report, CSPP proposes an industry-led strategy to ensure interoperability in the NII, and proposes that the government support this strategy by following industry's lead and by working with industry to reach the interoperability goals for the NII.  CSPP is not suggesting an architecture for the NII.  Instead, CSPP has identified critical points in today's infrastructure that </p>
<p>must be	interoperable if the NII vision is to be successfully implemented.  The interfaces identified by CSPP fall into four categories:</p>
<ul>
1.	Appliance to Network: the interface between an information appliance and a network service provider;<br><br>
2.	Appliance to Application: the applications programming interfaces (APIS) between an information appliance and emerging NII applications;<br><br>
3.	Application to Application: the protocols that one NII application, service, or system uses to communicate with another application service or system; and<br><br>
4.	Network to Network: the interfaces among and between network service providers.
</ul>
<p>Ensuring openness of the interfaces identified by CSPP will help advance critical NII goals.  In particular, open interfaces at the recommended locations will:</p>
<ul>
<li>allow users and providers to transmit information smoothly throughout the NIT;
<li>enable wide access by users and providers of information and services; and
   <li>stimulate competitive markets for NIT products and services.
</ul>
<p>The members of CSPP are prepared to work, through the appropriate standards bodies, to advance the openness of those interfaces that are within the computer industry's responsibility.  For inter-faces that fall within the responsibility of other industries, such as the local access provider interfaces, CSPP encourages those industries to develop similar strategies to ensure interoperability through the adoption of open, interoperable, and interconnected interfaces. </p>
<p>Finally, CSPP has identified a set of principles to help guide the industry led effort to achieve an interoperable NII and recommends that the government work with industry to facilitate reaching the interoperability goals for the NII.</p>
<hr>

<p><b><a name="background">BACKGR0UND :</a><br>
FROM VISION TO REALITY</b></p>


<p>Over the last several years, fewer issues have captured the American imagination more than the National Information Infrastructure (NII).  In fact, the concept of an improved and enhanced NII has become a primary focus for many industries including the computer, telecommunications, software, and entertainment industries.  It has also become a priority for policymakers in Congress and the Administration.  Legislation to accelerate industry's NII efforts has been introduced in both the Senate and the House of Representatives.  The Clinton Administration, which has made the NII a cornerstone of its technology policy agenda, is examining a range of important NII-related policy issues, including privacy, intellectual property protection, and widespread access. </p>
<p>To date, NII efforts have focused mainly on defining a vision for the NII -- what is it and what should it do in the future'?  CSPP, for example, believes that by enhancing and integrating four essential components: 1) communications networks; 2) computers and information appliances; 3) information; and 4) people, the NII will create a whole new way of learning, working, and interacting with others.  The NII will link together public and private institutions and resources, from schools and businesses to libraries and laboratories.  More importantly, it will link together individuals, from senior citizens and students to healthcare professionals, manufacturing managers, and business people.  It will allow all Americans to take advantage of our nation's rich resources in information, communications, and computing technologies.  It will revolutionize the way individuals relate to one another by enabling them to work together and access, generate, store. process, transmit, and receive text, data, audio, images, video, and multimedia anywhere, at any time.  Distance, location, time, and language barriers will disappear as the NII evolves.  This vision is consistent with those articulated by other industries and by the Clinton Administration. </p>
<p>Now, with a vision for the future NII largely defined, work on the NII has shifted to how industry and government can work together to turn the vision into reality.  The news over the last several months has been replete with announcements of companies and industries joining together to design, build, or provide services over the NII.  While these alliances involve various entities -- both public and private -- and address different aspects of the NII, there is a common theme: the private sector is making the NII a reality. </p>
 
<p>The private sector's role in the NII is to:</p>
<ul>
<li>develop and make available the services, products, networks, information, and applications that will constitute the NII;
 <li>   continue to invest in NH-related research and development;
    <li>lead the development of standards for interoperability
<li>create an inter-industry forum on interoperability,,
<li>fund precommercial testbeds; and
<li>work with government to refine the NII vision and develop policy ground rules.  
</ul>
<p>As the private sector leads the way, the federal government has an important role to play as a catalyst and stimulator of private sector efforts.  CSPP believes the federal government can best support private sector efforts by:</p>
<ul>
<li>refining and promoting the vision for the NII and developing a government-industry-public interest partnership to oversee its implementation;

<li>funding research and development on precommercial technologies;

<li>investing in precommercial demonstration projects in socially beneficial areas such as education, healthcare, manufacturing, and access to government information and services;

    <li>making government information easily accessible electronically;

<li>supporting an industry-led strategy to ensure interoperability;

<li>implementing a political and regulatory climate that encourages the development of new technologies and enables competitive markets; and

<li>coordinating public and private action to address complex policy issues such as widespread access to the NII, privacy, security, carrier liability, intellectual property protection, and affordability.
</ul>
<hr>
<h2><a name="interoperability">INTEROPERABILITY IN THE NII</a><br>

<a name="an">AN ESSENTIAL ELEMENT</a></h2>

<p><a href="job04.html">Key Terms</a></p>
<p>As envisioned. the future NII will integrate and build upon many different existing and emerging physical components.  These include: 1) communications networks using a variety of technologies-cable systems, telephone networks, data networks, including the Internet. wireless technologies, satellite systems, and others; 2) computers and information appliances, from smart televisions and portable wireless computers to high-end workstations and supercomputers; and 3) information in the form of databases, information services, and creative content, such as government documents and data, libraries, private information services and bulletin boards, interactive games and shopping, public service information and government services, education programs, and medical information. </p>
<p>The NII will also rely heavily on human resources and support services that will enable users to conduct business, locate, access, and retrieve information from remote databases, transmit multimedia documents, be billed and pay for services used, authenticate the information in the documents accessed, ensure security for stored and transmitted data, and track and pay for the use of copyrighted information. </p>
 
<p>Because these different aspects of the NII are being built, supplied, and maintained by hundreds of different vendors, as well as by individuals and government agencies, interoperability - the ability of different systems to work together - is essential. </p>
<p>Today, a lack of interoperability in our nation's information infrastructure presents minor inconveniences.  For example, setting up a video conference may require searching for compatible conferencing equipment.  Sending or receiving a document through electronic mail may require use of translation software or involve significant editing by hand.  In the future,, however, a lack of interoperability at key locations in the NII will have much more serious consequences - it may prevent users from obtaining essential information or making critical communications altogether. </p>
<p>Interoperability at key NII interfaces, both domestically and internationally, will ensure that existing and new NII components work together as easily, quickly, and transparently as the components of today's telephone system.  Equally important, interoperability will enable anyone to provide information or information services through the NII.  An NII that is interoperable at key interfaces will help create an infrastructure that is ubiquitous. interactive, and accessible to all users and service providers.</p>
<h2>
INTEROPERABILITY  IN THE NII<br>
<a name="advancing">ADVANCING NII GOALS</a></h2>
<p><a href="job05.html">Key Terms</a></p>


<p>Interoperability is not a luxury - it is an essential element for meeting many of the goals that have been articulated for the NII. In particular, an NII that is interoperable at key locations will:    </p>
<ul>
1.<i> Allow users and providers to transmit information smoothly throughout the NII</i><br>.  In a highly interoperable NII. a high school student in Montana will be able to use research resources located anywhere in the country and simultaneously discuss that research with students at distant schools.  A business traveler will be able to use a wireless computer to retrieve files from the office, edit the file on screen with colleagues, and to send and receive documents from the airport, airplane, or hotel room. If a vacationer falls ill, the local doctor will be able to quickly access the patient's up-to-date and complete medical record, and consult in real time with the patient's regular doctor and specialists from other cities. An entrepreneur with an innovative idea for a special interest on-line bulletin board will be able to reach all of the users who may be interested in accessing the bulletin board.  With open interfaces at the critical locations for information appliances, communications networks, and databases, all of these things, and much more, will be possible.<br><br>

2.	<i>Enable wide access by users and	 providers of information and services</i>.<br>
Interoperability will help ensure that the NII will be accessible to the broadest number of people - both users and vendors of products and services. An NII that is interoperable at critical interface will enable providers of information and information services and products, such as specialized bulletin boards, locator services, and libraries, to make them available through the NII to anyone who wants to use them, regardless of the type of information appliance the user has, the communications networks the information has to travel to reach the user, or where and how data is stored.  Users will not be limited to a particular vendor's products or certain services to receive or send the information they want. Users will be able to access the NII through computers at public libraries or schools as easily as those who access it from home or work.  <br><br>

3.	<i>Stimulate competitive markets for NII products and services</i>.<br>  An NII that is interoperable at critical interfaces will promote greater competition in NII products and services. In today's marketplace, competition is critical in driving innovation and technology advances. With an interoperable NII, any vendor or independent provider of information will be able to plug a product or service into the NII and reach all potential users of the product or service. Since users will be able to select from a wide range of products and services that best meet their needs, sellers will have to compete with each other to win customers.  With open specifications at key interfaces, all providers of NII products and services will know what is expected and what is necessary for their products and services to interoperate with the rest of the infrastructure. Thus, small companies will be able to make their NII products and services available as easily as larger companies, generating additional competition. A wide range of vendors and open interfaces at the key locations will give users the freedom to change products, services, vendors, and technologies as their needs change or as new technologies become available.
</ul>
<h2>
INTER0PERABILITY IN THE  NII<br>
<a name="critical">CRITICAL  NII INTERFACES</a>
</h2>
<p><a href="job06.html">Key Terms</a></p>

<p>In the Appendix, CSPP has identified several key NII interfaces that Must be a priority for an industry-led strategy to ensure interoperability and openness in the NII.  The list is not intended to be definitive or exhaustive, but merely a starting point for dialogue.  Further, the members of CSPP are prepared to work, through the appropriate standards bodies, to advance the openness of those interfaces that are within the computer industry's responsibility.  For interfaces that fall within the responsibility of other industries, such as the local access provider interfaces, CSPP encourages those industries to develop similar strategies to work through their appropriate standards bodies to ensure interoperability through the adoption of open, interoperable, and interconnected interfaces. </p>
<p>The interfaces in the Appendix are examples of interfaces in today's information infrastructure that must be open in order for information and services to flow smoothly from-n end to end in the NII.  The interfaces in the Appendix were selected based on two criteria: 1) they are located at critical points in the infrastructure, and 2) they are not moving to openness quickly enough.  CSPP believes these interfaces are key, high leverage points in the NII which can enable or catalyze the development and interworking of a broad array of existing or new products and services by multiple competing providers and users.  As the N-H grows and evolves, the private sector should use these criteria to evaluate new interfaces to be sure they meet the desired degree of openness. </p>
<p>The key NII interfaces identified in the Appendix fall into the following four categories. </p>
<p>The	Appendix includes specific examples of each.</p>
<ul>
1.	<i>Appliance to Network: The interface between an information appliance and a network service provider.  </i><br>Open interfaces at these points will allow users of the NII to attach any type of information appliance (such as computers, television set top boxes, smart telephones, or other intelligent consumer appliances) to the local access provider's network.<br><br>

2. <i> Appliance to Application: The Applications Programming Interfaces (APIS) between an information appliance and emerging NII applications, such as multimedia applications, telephony, database access, and X.400</i>. <br>Open APIs will enable developers of NII applications, such as interactive videogames, remote database access, and electronic publishing, to make them available to any user regardless of the type of information appliance the user has.<br><br>

3.  <i>Application to Application: The protocols that one NII application, service, or system uses to communicate with another application, service or system</i><br>.  These would include for example, communications between different mail messaging systems or between database query programs and databases.  Open interfaces between different implementations of NII information systems, services, and applications that allow the systems, services, and applications to "communicate" with each other will enable users to generate and receive information in various formats and media without having to make special adjustments to translate between different implementations. <br><br>

4.  <i>Network to Network: The interfaces among and between network service providers</i><br>.  They include interfaces between different local communications service providers, Such as telephone companies and cable companies; interfaces to local companies' networks at key points and to intelligent switching software; and interfaces between local service providers and long distance carriers and enhanced service providers.  Open interfaces at certain key network points, as noted in the Appendix, will ensure that users have maximum choice in their selection of and access to network and information services and that information providers can reach all users.  This will also ensure the proper conditions for competition.</ul>
<hr>
<h2>INTEROPERABILITY  IN THE NII<br>

<a name="principles">PRINCIPLES FOR A STRATEGY ON INTEROPERABILITY</a></h2>
<p><a href="job07.html">Key Terms (Open or Closed)</a></p>
<p><a href="job08.html">Key Terms (Proprietary or Nonproprietary)</a></p>
<p><a href="job09.html">Key Terms (Standard)</a></p>

<p>As the private sector develops, deploys, and upgrades the components of the infrastructure, it must also take the lead to ensure that the NII is interoperable.  This will require innovative thinking and bold action, from both a technical and policy perspective, to ensure that the infrastructure of the 21st century best meets the needs of all its potential users.  CSPP has identified the following set of principles to help guide the industry-led effort to achieve an interoperable NH. CSPP believes the government's role should be to work with industry to facilitate reaching the interoperability goals for the NII.</p>
<ul>
1. <i>Open Interfaces Are Essential </i>- Open interfaces at critical NII locations will allow the smooth transfer of information throughout the system.  Thousands of interfaces, both open and closed, exist in today's information infrastructure.  Many more will exist as the NII evolves.  If the interfaces at critical locations, such as those identified in the Appendix, are open, the diverse components of the NII will be able to work together so that users can communicate and interact easily and transparently.<br><br>

2.  <i>Industry-Led Standards Are Critical </I>- Industry must lead the development of standards for interoperability.  Users of the NII are increasingly demanding that products and services interoperate so they can access the resources they need.  In markets that are competitive, market forces will generally result in interoperable and open interfaces among key NII products and services.  Customers and other providers will have multiple choices with whom to interconnect, so there are incentives for providers to define open interfaces and to disseminate standards, resulting in maximum interoperability without a need for government intervention.  Development of standards for key interfaces in competitive markets should be entirely industry-led and industry-implemented, driven by market forces and user requirements.<br><br>



3.  <i>Government Has a Role in Regulated Franchised Markets </i>- In regulated franchised markets which are not yet fully competitive, some government stimulation and intervention may be necessary to ensure interoperability.  Without competition, there is limited incentive for providers of franchised monopoly products or services to open the interfaces they control to third parties.  In some cases, this may require the government to identify requirements for interconnection and to specify certain critical interfaces that must be open.  As a last resort, the government may have to require these traditionally regulated franchised monopoly industries to establish interoperable and open interfaces.<br><br>



4.  <i>Interoperability Fosters Competition </I>- Interoperability will promote competition among technologies, providers, and media, leading to the greatest choices, lowest prices, highest value, and maximum innovation.  Interoperability, by making the NII accessible to the greatest number of competing providers, will improve the availability and affordability of products and services, value for price, and competitive rather than exclusive offerings.  This will stimulate demand for NII-related products and services, thus building volume and driving affordability.
<br><br>

5. <i>Minimize Government Intervention </i>- In competitive markets, government intervention should be kept to the minimum level necessary to achieve public policy goals, such as ensuring access by users and providers, reliability, privacy, and freedom of speech.<br><br>

6. <i>Government Must Promote Competition </i>- In traditionally regulated franchised monopoly markets, government policies should be designed to move the markets toward competition by encouraging market openness and interoperability.  This can be achieved by eliminating barriers to entry and exit in local communications markets, requiring standardized, open interfaces to unbundled components to enable interconnection; and removing safeguards and line of business restrictions as soon as meaningful competition is achieved.  Eventually, only those regulations that are necessary to achieve specific public policy goals noted above should remain.<br><br>

7.  <i>Broad Access is Key </i>- Everyone should have the opportunity to access the NII at some level.  Different people have different needs for communications services, information appliances, and information resources at different times, as well as different skill levels and abilities.  A definition of the NII services everyone should be able to access must be developed and new approaches to providing access to underserved populations will have to be explored.  For instance, libraries and schools, which have long been places where people acquire information and develop skills, are two examples of locations at which a reasonable selection of appliances and access to advanced NII services and information resources could be made available.  Other points of access might include non-profit organizations, chambers of commerce, and neighborhood business associations serving small businesses.  Public access points may also provide places for training people in the use of the NII and coaching them on its use thereafter.  Further, people at some sites may be NII intermediaries for those who need NII-based services but are incapable of accessing them.<br><br>

8.  <i>Government Must Ensure Access When Necessary </i>- In cases where market forces do not make the NII widely accessible, there is a role for federal, state, and local governments in ensuring access to the NII.  Where it is agreed that users should have access to certain NII services - such as, for example, government services and information - subsidies may be needed to make access to the NH components affordable to certain users.  Where subsidies are needed to offset the cost of using the NII, suppliers of NH components should not be required to subsidize users.  Subsidies should be provided by governments directly to institutions, such as libraries or schools, that will make the appropriate NII components publicly available to users, or perhaps directly to users to access on-line information services.  Developing a workable strategy to meet these needs will require the cooperation of NII providers and the federal, state, and local governments.  The means of providing such subsidies to points of access and people who warrant them will have to be developed in such a way that it can evolve in parallel with the NII without inhibiting its advance or distorting competition.<br><br>

9.	<i>Ease of Use Must Be a Priority </i>- NII components intended for use by the general public should be easy to use; correspondingly, people should be adequately trained and educated to use the NII to meet their needs.  Accessibility could be enhanced if user interfaces provide a consistent set of basic procedures to perform tasks across a wide range of applications and platforms, including the development of standardized procedures for locating information, such as an electronic version of "yellow pages;" standard procedures for retrieving information from widely distributed sources; and standard document presentation forms that are able to support multimedia formats.  It is important, however, that such procedures provide a basic way of accessing information and contain sufficient interface specification information to permit vendors to offer advanced easier-to-use user interfaces.</ul>
<hr>

<h2> <a name="cspp">CSPP RECOMMENDATIONS</a><br>
<a name="action">ACTION AGENDA FOR INDUSTRY</a></h2>
<p>1. <b> Establish Cross-Industry Forum </b>- The private sector should establish a cross industry open forum to monitor the development by standards bodies of open, critical NII interfaces.  The forum should: 1) lead the development of a roadmap that identifies critical interfaces within the NII, including those in the Appendix-, 2) assess the degree of interoperability and openness of each critical interface on an ongoing basis; 3) identify goals and milestones for achieving maximum interoperability and openness where needed; 4) evaluate progress toward meeting those goals and milestones; and 5) update the list of critical interfaces as necessary. </p>
 
<p>2. <b>Facilitate Quick Adoption of Open NII Interface Specifications </b>- Industry members of standards bodies and other forums that address NII interface specifications should commit to ensuring that proposed standards are considered and decided upon as quickly as possible in order to accelerate the acceptance and adoption of open NII interface specifications by users and vendors.  The development and implementation of voluntary, industry-developed interoperability standards for the critical NII interfaces should be accomplished through existing industry-led groups, including ANSI-accredited standards bodies, with appropriate collaboration and input from other independent industry forums, such as the ATM Forum and the Telecommunications Operations Forum.  Industry should encourage coordination among these groups, when appropriate, such as the current effort to establish a liaison between ISO/IEC JTC- I and the Internet Society to lead to the ultimate goal of harmonization between their architectures.  In all cases, efforts should be made to accelerate the approval process to the extent possible, in both the domestic and international domains. </p>
 
<p>3. <b>License Proprietary NII Technologies on Reasonable Terms </b>- When a developer of an NII system proposes proprietary technologies for incorporation in critical NII interface standards, the developer of the technology should be prepared to license the technology on reasonable terms and conditions, demonstrably free of discrimination. </p>
 
<p>4.  <b>Fund and Participate in Testbeds and Demonstration Projects </b>- In partnership with the federal government, companies should fund and participate in precommercial testbeds and demonstration projects that will accelerate the development and adoption of interoperable and open NII interfaces.</p>
<hr>

<h2>CSPP RECOMMENDATI0NS<br>

<a name="agenda">AGENDA FOR
GOVERNMENT SUPPORT</a></h2>

<p>1. <i>Develop Milestones</i>-The government should work with industry to develop realistic milestones for open NII interfaces and monitor progress by industry in meeting those milestones. </p>
 
<p>2. <i>Promote Industry-Developed Interoperability Standards </i>- The government </p>
<p>should promote the adoption of industry-developed standards for interconnection and interoperability through government purchases of NII-related equipment and services. </p>
 
<p>3. <i>Support U.S. Industry's Standards Interests in International Bodies </i>- The government should continue its critical support for U.S. industry's standards interests in international standards forums sponsored by treaty organizations, e.g., the International Telecommunications Union, where the U.S. government represents U.S. interests.  The federal government must explicitly recognize the importance of U.S. leadership in standards and ensure that a U.S. industry perspective is accurately and forcefully represented in global standards bodies sponsored by treaty organizations. </p>
 
<p>4. <i>Fund Testbeds and Demonstration Projects </i>- The government should fund, in partnership with industry and users'. precommercial testbeds and demonstration projects to test and develop interoperable and open NII interfaces. </p>
 
<p>5. <i>Remove barriers to competition in franchised monopoly communications markets. </i></p>
 
<p>6.<i> Eliminate safeguards and regulations applicable to traditionally regulated franchised monopolies as meaningful competition is achieved</i>. </p>
 
<p>7. <i>Develop Definitions of Essential NII Services and Resources </i>- In conjunction with state and local governments and public interest groups, the government should develop definitions of essential NII services and resources that all Americans should have the ability to access, and a plan to ensure some minimum level of access/availability for such essential NII services.</p>
<hr>

<h2 align=center><a name="appendix">APPENDIX</a></h2>

<h2>CRITICAL INTERFACES FOR<br>
INTEROPERABILITY IN THE  NII<br>

OVERVIEW</h2>

<p>Interoperability is an essential element in transforming today's information infrastructure into a National Information Infrastructure (NII) that will be a primary resource for the future.  With the Information Age upon us, the ability to quickly and efficiently generate and exchange information, technology, and ideas is the key to increased economic prosperity, improved quality of life, and global competitiveness in a range of industries. </p>
<p>CSPP has identified the following four categories of interfaces between and among information appliances, NII applications, information services and network service providers: 1) Appliance to Network; 2) Appliance to Application; 3) Application to Application; 4) Network to Network.  With interoperability at these critical NII interfaces, both domestically and internationally, CSPP believes industry can develop and deploy an NII that will most effectively and efficiently serve the needs of its users.  In addition, interoperability at these key junctures in the NII will enable the broadest possible range of applications based on the most extensive information provided by the greatest variety of vendors.  Interoperability will promote competition and create new opportunities for the development of products and services we cannot even begin to imagine today.</p>
<center><img src="1.gif"></center><br>
<hr>
<h2 align=center>
CRITICAL INTERFACES FOR
INTEROPERABILITY IN THE  NII</h2>

<h2>Category #1<br>
<a name="appliance">APPLIANCE TO NETWORK</a></h2>
<p><a href="job014.html">Goals and Benefits</a></p>

<p><b>APPLIANCE TO NETWORK </b>- Interface between information appliance (including computers and set top boxes) and local access provider (including telephone company, cable television service provider, competitive access provider, wireless systems, and other service providers. </p>
 
 <center><img src="2.gif"></center>
 
<p><b>Current Status: </b>Today, some network interfaces are not open, so users cannot connect any information appliance to any network. </p>
 
 
<p><b>Recommended Industry Action: </b>The computer, communications (including telephone and cable), and consumer electronics industries should work through standards bodies to define open network interfaces where they do not exist.</p>

<h2>
Category #2<br>
<a name="to">APPLIANCE TO APPLICATION</a></h2>

<p><a href="job015.html">Goals and Benefits</a></p>
<p><b>APPLIANCE TO APPLICATION </b>- Application programming interface (API) between information appliance (platform) and emerging NII applications, such as  telephony, database access, multimedia applications, and X.400. </p>
 
 <center><img src="3.gif"></center>
 
<p><b>Current Status: </b>APIs for new NII applications such as telephony, X.400, multimedia. and others, are being defined by standards bodies.  However, slow progress is hampering the introduction of  new products. </p>
 
<p><b>Recommended Industry Action: </b>Industry should expedite development of open APIs for NII applications, especially multimedia. through computer information processing, and communications industry standards bodies and industry associations, such as X3, IEEE, Interactive Multimedia Association, Multimedia Communications Forum, Telecommunications Information Network Architecture, other computer, consumer electronics, telecommunications, and cable television industry consortia, and JTC-1.</p>


<h2>
Category #3<br>
<a name="application">APPLICATION TO APPLICATION</a></h2>
<p><a href="job016.html">Goals and Benefits</a></p>


<p><b>APPLICATION TO APPLICATION </b>- Information systems/service interfaces which are the interfaces between different NII applications, systems, and services, such as electronic mail, voice messaging, database access, and electronic publishing. </p>
<p>Examples of current NII services/systems for which action is needed to establish open inter-faces are provided below.  In the future, this category of interfaces will become increasingly important as technologies evolve and new capabilities become available. </p>
<center>
<img src="4.gif"> <br>
<img src="5.gif"></center>

<p><b>Current Status: </b>While standards for many of today's services and systems are evolving, difficulties remain.  For example, X.400, the electronic mail messaging standard, is not widely implemented because of its complexity; today's voice messaging systems are generally closed, so a recipient of a voice message cannot forward it or broadcast it to someone on a different system; several standards exist for describing printed text and images in databases; and common standards for providing and accessing databases are not yet widely implemented.  Standards need to be defined and adopted for today's applications that can accommodate evolution to new systems and services, such as multimedia applications of electronic mail, electronic publishing, and database access. </p>
 
<p><b>Recommended Industry Action: </b>The computer, communications, and information industries need to work through their respective standards bodies and industry associations, such as X.3, IEEE, OSI Implementor's Workshop, the Electronic Mail Association, the Information Industry Association, the Association of American Publishers, Society of Motion Picture and TV Engineering (SMPTE), Audio Engineering Society (AES), SQL/Access Group, X/Open, the Intenet Society, ITU-T, and JTC-1, and other appropriate forums, to simplify current standards and promote their adoption, and to develop standards where ones do not exist for new multimedia and other NII applications.</p>



<h2>Category #4<br>
<a name="network">NETWORK TO NETWORK</a></h2>
<p><a href="job018.html">Goals and Benefits</a></p>

<p>NETWORK TO NETWORK - Local access provider interfaces.  Local access providers include telephone, cable, wireless, and competitive access providers.  "Advanced Intelligent Network" is the FCC's term for the centralized computers and databases used to store network intelligence, includes Service Control Points, Signal Transfer Points, Stored Program Control switches, Service Management System'.  Service Circuit Nodes, and Intelligent Peripherals.</p>
<center><img src="6.gif"></center>
<ul>

4a - Interface between different Local Access Providers Switching Offices.<br><br>

4b - Interface between Local Access Provider and lnterexchange Carrier (IXC) or Enhanced Service Provider (ESP).<br><br>

4c - Interfaces between AIN and alternative service providers.
</ul>
<p>Current Status: While progress has been made in defining and opening some interfaces, local access networks are not yet fully open.</p>

<p>Recommended Industry Action:  Access providers should work through their standards bodies and industry organizations to develop and support open interface specifications for the interfaces identified.  Potential bodies to address these interfaces include T1, other communications industry forums, TIA, and ITU-T.</p>
