<html>
<head><title>The Need for Fundamental Reform</title>
<h2 align=center>Perspectives on Export Control Policy:
<br>
The Need for Fundamental Reform
<br></h2>
<hr>
<p>TABLE OF CONTENTS</p>

<p><a href="#executive">Executive Summary</a><br>
<a href="#exports">Exports: The Key to U.S. High-Technology Competitiveness</a><br>
<a href="#current">The Current Export Control Regime: A Threat to U.S. High-technology Competitiveness</a><br>
<a href="#need">The Need for Long-Term Export Control Reform</a><br>
<a href="#cspp">The CSPP Approach: Striking the Necessary Balance</a><br>
<a href="#recommendations">Recommendations for a New U.S. Export Control Regime</a><br>
<a href="#conclusion">Conclusion</a></p>
<hr>
<a name="executive">EXECUTIVE SUMMARY</a>

<p>The Administration, Congress, and U.S. high-technology exporters all agree that the export control system must be changed.  The current system was created over 40 years ago to impede the economic and military development of the "Communist Bloc." It has not been updated to reflect the  dramatic geopolitical changes that have unfolded over the past few years and it cannot keep pace with rapid advances in technology.  As a result, the U.S. export control system is now a serious impediment to U.S. competitiveness. </p>
 
<p>The Computer Systems Policy Project (CSPP) supports a rational export control system that efficiently meets national security objectives without imposing unnecessary adverse effects on the nation's economy.  Today, a sound economy is absolutely essential to preserving the nation's global military superiority.  This means that the U.S. export control system must carefully balance military superiority, economic strength, and technological leadership -- the interdependent facets of national security. </p>
 
<p>CSPP has developed a balanced approach to export controls that will enable the government to meet its legitimate objectives while allowing U.S. industry to maintain its economic competitiveness in export markets.  The CSPP proposal applies only to commercial items -- it does not deal with military hardware or munitions.  Finally, CSPP has chosen to address only substantive issues of export control, not the important organizational and management issues that will emerge with any new approach to export control policy. </p>
 
<p>CSPP recommends that the new U.S. export control regime:</p>
<ul>
1 . Focus on the major security challenges of the coming decade: preventing proliferation of weapons of mass destruction and missile delivery systems, and combating the spread of international terrorism;<br><br>

2.     Rely on multilateral control arrangements to the maximum extent possible,
employing unilateral controls only in exceptional circumstances;<br><br>

3.	Impose licensing requirements only on products or technologies that are required for the proliferation of weapons of mass destruction or missile delivery systems -- not on those that simply contain cutting-edge technology;<br><br>

4.	Specifically identify the export control targets (countries and end-users); and
<br><br>
5.	Recognize that exports are essential to the economic security of the United States, and that exports of commercial items, particularly information technology products, contribute to the development of market economies and democratization.</ul>
<hr>
<h2><a name="exports">EXPORTS: THE KEY TO U.S. HIGH TECHNOLOGY COMPETITIVENESS</a></h2>

<p>High-technology industries, like the computer industry, must grow globally or die.  Today, the markets for computer products and services are worldwide, as are the industry's customers and competitors.  As a result, exports are vital.  In fact, more than sixty percent of the computer industry's revenue is derived from sales to customers outside the U.S. </p>
 
<p>High-technology companies must also be quick to market with new, innovative products.  The average life cycle of today's computer technology is under eighteen months.  More dm seventy percent of the U.S. computer industry's 1992 revenue came from products that did not exist two years earlier.  This figure is expected to exceed eighty percent by 1995. </p>
 
<p>The bottom line: U.S. high-technology industries must be able to quickly export their most innovative products to be successful in the global marketplace.</p>
<hr>
<h2><a name="current">THE CURRENT EXPORT CONTROL REGIME: A THREAT TO U.S. HIGH TECHNOLOGY COMPETITIVENESS</a></h2>

<p>The current export control regime poses a real threat to U.S. high-technology competitiveness by preventing U.S. high-technology companies from quickly exporting their most competitive products.  As a result, U.S. companies are unable to effectively exploit their competitive position in global markets.  For example, in 1993, outdated computer export licensing requirements threatened to delay delivery of leading edge U.S. computer products based on a new generation of microprocessors.  In addition, an obsolete definition of 'supercomputer' imposed extraordinary export restrictions on U.S. computer systems readily available on the world market. </p>
 
<p>On September 29, 1993, the Administration took bold and decisive action to temporarily address these issues and avert a pending high-technology export crisis.  Working with industry, the Administration crafted a plan for short-term export control relief that eliminated unnecessary controls on the export of U.S. computers to countries not engaged in proliferation activities or international terrorist activities. </p>
 
<p>Once implemented, the Administration's plan will significantly benefit the U.S. economy.  U.S. computer companies will be able to export tens of thousands of computers made by U.S. workers that would have otherwise been controlled. </p>
 
<p>The Administration's plan will also help ensure that limited government resources are devoted to better policing those exports that directly contribute to proliferation and terrorism.  The plan will also temporarily eliminate an unmanageable flood of export license applications at the Commerce Department for products that are widely available from other sources around the globe.</p>
<hr>
<h2><a name="need">THE NEED FOR LONG-TERM EXPORT CONTROL REFORM</a></h2>

<p>The Administration's September 29 action signaled an important shift in U.S. export control policy, acknowledging that in today's global economy, the export control system must simultaneously balance the nation's security needs and its economic objectives. </p>
 
<p>The President's action was positive and necessary, but it was only a "stop gap" measure taken to address problems created by an export control system that is fundamentally flawed and badly out of date.  Major flaws in the current system include: 1) unilateral U.S. controls, which often impose crippling restrictions on U.S. companies while foreign competitors operate unhampered in the international market; 2) restrictions that do not take into account the diffusion of technology throughout the world; and 3) controls based on the level of technological sophistication of a product or technology rather than on whether it is required for the proliferation of weapons of mass destruction or missile delivery systems.  The idea that a product or technology is necessarily a more significant proliferation concern if it contains advanced technology is unfounded: the United States, as well as other nuclear powers, developed nuclear weapons without using today's advanced technology.  In fact, Congress' Office of Technology Assessment (OTA) recognized in a September, 1993 report that high performance computers "are not required to design first generation fission weapons." </p>
 
<p>As the Administration and Congress work to reauthorize the Export Administration Act, the time is right for fundamental reform.  Without it, the United States will be forced to address the system's flaws through repeated short-term fixes in the midst of pending export crises.  A crisis management approach prevents appropriate and thorough consideration of critical issues.  The United States needs a new export control system that provides the certainty and stability that America's exporters need to compete effectively in the global market.</p>
<hr>
<h2><a name="cspp">THE CSPP APPROACH: STRIKING THE NECESSARY BALANCE</a>
</h2>
<p>The Computer Systems Policy Project (CSPP) has developed a balanced approach to export control policy that will enable the government to meet its legitimate objectives while allowing U.S. industry to maintain its economic competitiveness in export markets.  The CSPP proposal applies only to commercial items -- it does not deal with military hardware or munitions.  Finally, CSPP has chosen to address only substantive issues of export control, not the important organizational and management issues that will emerge with any new approach to export control policy. </p>
 
<p>CSPP's recommendations are based on the following key principles.</p>
<ul>
<i>1 . Exports are critical to U.S. economic security.</i>
Exports create U.S. jobs.  Exports also generate revenue that companies reinvest in the research and development essential to maintaining technological superiority over foreign competitors.  Today, unemployment and the erosion of our technology base are as serious a threat to the United States as a hostile military power.<br><br>

<i>2. Trade encourages the development of market economies and democratization</i>.
This is particularly true for the information technology industry, which provides the products and infrastructure that are essential to the operation of market economies and that encourage the free exchange of ideas and information.  Today's global economy demands that we encourage economic development in all nations, excepting those few that threaten international stability.<br><br>

<i>3. Export controls should only be used to meet the following critical national objectives:</i><br>
<ul>
<li>to prevent the proliferation of weapons of mass destruction and missile delivery systems;

<li>to enforce multilateral sanctions designed to compel adherence to international norms of behavior; and
<li>to deter terrorist activity.
</ul>
<i>4. The system must focus on "controllable " products and technologies</i>.
This requires recognizing the broad diffusion of technology and the rapid speed at which it advances.  The export control system should aim to control only those products and technologies that are not widely available from uncontrolled sources.<br><br>

<i>5. The export control regime should focus on chokepoints -- those products and technologies that are required for the proliferation of weapons of mass destruction or missile delivery systems.</i>

Focusing controls on proliferation chokepoints will ensure that the government effectively uses its limited resources to meet the nation's proliferation goals.  It will also help prevent unnecessary adverse effects on U.S. exporters of commercial products.  Burdensome export licensing requirements on products and technologies that are not critical for proliferation prevent U.S. industries from being first to market with the most innovative commercial products.  As a result, legitimate trade opportunities are lost without accomplishing any important national goals.<br><br>

<i>6.	Export controls must normally be multilateral</i>.

In most situations, export controls must be multilateral to be effective.  Unless the United States has a monopoly over a particular technology, unilateral controls are simply symbolic.  What is worse, they essentially hand markets over to foreign competitors.<br><br>

<i>7.	The system should be "positive" and transparent</i>.

To facilitate compliance by U.S. exporters, the government must clearly identify the targets of control and the reasons for control.<br><br>

<i>8.	Export controls should be employed only as part of a comprehensive economic, political, and  diplomatic strategy</i>.

Export controls will be effective only if employed in conjunction with other remedies available to the government and the international community.  In a vacuum, export controls are likely to harm U.S. exporters and do little to advance legitimate U.S. objectives.
</ul>
<hr>
<h2><a name="recommendations">RECOMMENDATIONS FOR A NEW U.S. EXPORT CONTROL REGIME</a>
</h2>
<p>In accordance with the principles outlined above, CSPP recommends that the U.S. implement a new export control system based on the following three-tiered structure.</p>
<ul>
1.	<b>Tier I </b>consists of. products and technologies that are required for the proliferation of weapons of mass destruction or missile delivery systems.  The government will have discretion to require prior approval for the export of these 'choke point" products and technologies.<br><br>

2.	<b>Tier II </b>consists of commercial products and technologies not essential to proliferation.  Export of these products and technologies will be restricted only in narrowly defined circumstances.<br><br>

3.	<b>Tier III </b>contains products and technologies with no connection to proliferation activities.  There will be no restrictions on their export.
</ul>
<b><p align=center>Tier I<br>
"Choke Point" Products and Technologies</p></b>

<p>Identifying "Choke Point" Products and Technologies.  A product or technology will be categorized as a Tier I item only if rigorous technical analysis determines that there is a direct and substantial link between the product or technology and proliferation activity.  To be classified as a "choke point' product or technology, the item must be required for the proliferation of weapons of mass destruction or missile delivery systems.  In other words, a "choke point" product or technology is something without which proliferation activity cannot occur.  A high level of technological sophistication alone will not justify classification as a Tier I item. </p>
 
<p>To ensure the integrity of the classification process, the government must provide for substantial input from industry and academia.  Furthermore, the government must ensure that classifications of products and technologies as 'choke points" are regularly reviewed so those that no longer meet the criteria for categorization as a Tier I item can be quickly decontrolled. </p>
 
<p>Controls on "Choke Point" Products and Technologies.  The government will be able to require prior approval of Tier I exports to specified countries.  However, these controls will normally be allowed only if they are part of an effective multilateral control regime.  Effective multilateralization requires full participation by all countries that are a source of the product or technology. </p>
 
<p>In addition, export controls on "choke point' products and technologies may only be imposed if the item is controllable.  This means that a feasible method must exist to prevent the product or technology from reaching the export control target.  As the OTA has recognized, a product or technology cannot be controlled if:</p>
<ul>
1.	it is available from non-controlled sources; or
<br><br>
2.	it can be replaced by a similar and reasonably available non-controlled substitute.
</ul>

<p>Minimizing Unilateral Controls.  The U.S. should rely on multilateral control arrangements to the maximum extent possible, employing unilateral controls only in the following limited and exceptional circumstances.</p>
<ul>
1.	Pending Multilateralization.  The U.S. may impose a temporary unilateral U.S. control, with multilateralization required within six months.  The purpose of such controls will be to obtain broad-based participation, with the government providing incentives for other countries to join in the U.S. led controls.  The multilateralization must be effective; that is, it must include full participation by all countries that are a source of the product or technology in question.  If efforts at multilateralization fail within six months, however, the unilateral controls will be discontinued.<br><br>

2.	Sole Source.  Unilateral controls will be allowed on a product or technology for which the United States is the only source of supply.  This is the only situation in which unilateral controls can possibly be effective.  However, the government will have to make a specific finding that this requirement for unilateral controls has been met.  Upon reasonably sufficient evidence that a new source of supply is set to enter the market, the unilateral controls will be discontinued.<br><br>

3.	Terrorist regimes or entities.  Unilateral controls on "choke point" products and technologies may be imposed on identified terrorist regimes or entities if the U.S. determines such controls will deter terrorist activity.
</ul>

<p>Minimizing Re-export Controls.  Controls on re-export of Tier I items to countries that are not part of the relevant multilateral regime will normally be allowed only if they are applied by all members of the regime.  Unilateral re-export controls will be allowed only in the three situations described above -- pending multilateralization, U.S. sole source, and terrorist regimes or entities.</p>

<b><p align=center>Tier II<br>
Commercial Products and Technologies</p></b>

<p>This category includes all products and technologies that do not meet the "choke point" criteria, in other words, are not essential to proliferation activity.  Exports of Tier II products and technologies will not be subject to prior government approval or export licensing.  However, the government may prohibit their export to any specifically identified country or end-user that is subject to a multilateral embargo or is determined by the United States to be a terrorist regime or entity.  Re-export controls will be similarly limited. </p>
 
<p>In those instances in which the export of Tier II products and technologies are controlled, the following framework will apply.</p>
<ul>
1.	The government will issue and maintain an explicit list of embargoed countries and end-users.
<br><br>
2.	Exporters will be responsible for export screening to ensure that they do not make prohibited exports.
<br><br>
3.	Exporters will be prohibited from exporting to any end-user who the exporter knows to be involved in prohibited proliferation or terrorist activities.  However, the standard is actual knowledge.  The responsibility of investigation to determine proper targets of export controls belongs with the government, not the private sector.
</ul>
<b><p align=center>Tier III<br>
Unrestricted Products and Technologies</p></b>

<p>Tier III includes all products with no direct connection to proliferation activities.  These products will not be subject to any controls whatsoever, regardless of destination.  For example, humanitarian items, such as medicine, food, and educational material, do not directly contribute to proliferation efforts.  Restricting exports of such benign items cannot meaningfully contribute to any of the goals of an export control regime.</p>
<hr>

<h2 align=center>CSPP PROPOSAL:<br>
A New U.S. Export Control System</h2>

<p>"<b>CHOKE POINT PRODUCTS AND TECHNOLOGIES</b><br>
Government May Impose Export Licensing Requirements</p>
<ul>
	<li>Includes only products and technologies shown, through technical analysis, to be "choke points" for proliferation activity.
	<li>An item will not be controlled under Tier I if it, or a substitute, is available from a non-controlled source.
	<li>Controls will normally be imposed only if multilateral.
	<li>Unilateral controls will be allowed only if-
<ul><li>1.	multilateralization is pending within six months;
<li>2.	the United States is the sole source of the product or technology; or
<li>3.	the controls are imposed against a terrorist regime or entity.
	</ul>
</ul>
<p><b>COMMERCIAL PRODUCTS AND TECHNOLOGIES</b></p>

<p>Uncontrolled Except for Multilateral Controls and<br>
Unilateral Controls Aimed at Terrorist Regimes and Entities

</p>
<ul><li>	Includes all other commercial technology except items in Tier ]III.
	<li>Government must issue and maintain a detailed list of prohibited export destinations.
	<li>Exporters are responsible for screening exports against the control list.
	<li>Exporters will be prohibited from exporting to any end-user if the exporter has actual knowledge that the end-user is involved in prohibited proliferation or terrorist activities.
</ul>

<p><b>UNRESTRICTED PRODUCTS AND TECHNOLOGIES</b></p>

<p>No Restrictions to Any Destination</p>
<ul>
	<li>Includes all products with no direct connection to proliferation activities.
	<li>These can be items to meet basic human needs and other designated benign items.
</ul>
<hr>
<h2 align=center><a name="conclusion">CONCLUSION</a></h2>

<p>The world has changed significantly since the U.S. export control system was created over forty years ago.  From a national security perspective, the Cold War is over.  In its place, we are confronted with the specter of international terrorism and the proliferation of weapons of mass destruction and missile delivery systems.  From an economic perspective, markets, customers, and competitors are increasingly global, and national economic security has become essential.  Balancing these changes demands bold reform of U.S. export control policies. </p>
 
<p>Government and industry must work together to craft a new export control regime that will help prevent the proliferation of weapons of mass destruction and missile delivery systems, and curb international terrorism, while fostering U.S. competitiveness in global markets.</p>


<hr>
