<html>
<head><title>Information Technology's Contribution to Health Care Reform</title>
<h2 align=center>
Information Technology's Contribution<br>
to Health Care Reform<br>

April, 1993
</h2>
<hr>
<p><b>Executive Summary</b></p>

<p>Healthcare costs are rising at an g rate.  In 1993, healthcare will cost the United States $900 billion - 14% of Gross Domestic Product.  Without a change in current spending practices, healthcare expenditures will rise to more than 18% of GDP by 2000 
and 22% by 2010.  One immediate result is that millions of Americans do not have access to health care services because they cannot afford health insurance or they have inadequate coverage.  The Computer Systems Policy Project (CSPP) believes that by sign
ificantly increasing the application of information technology to our healthcare delivery system, we will be able to provide greater access to high-quality health care services at reduced costs for all Americans. </p>
 
<p>A healthcare information infrastructure will provide a foundation for improving healthcare information management, which can be applied throughout the healthcare system, from billing and payment to delivery of services by medical experts.  The healthca
re information infrastructure will include a network of interconnected, interoperable, multi-speed communications networks; medical information resources; computers and information appliances; and people able to access the information they need, when they
 need it.  The infrastructure will be based on regional community health infrastructures, which will provide services to individuals, hospitals, physicians, HMOs, emergency or ambulatory care centers, employers, and payers. </p>
 
<p>Nationwide adoption of an integrated healthcare information infrastructure will require joint public-private sector efforts to overcome a variety of human, organizational, economic, societal, and technological challenges, including: economic feasibilit
y; professional and organizational adaptation to new technologies; development and adoption of standards; reimbursement mechanisms for using information; and legal barriers, such as liability and ownership of data.  Some of the technology challenges inclu
de data capture, retrieval, and distribution; data access and delivery; data storage; integration; communication technologies; and data presentation. </p>
 
<p>CSPP believes these barriers can best be overcome through regional and interregional demonstration projects in the following areas:</p>
<ul>
	<li>Computerized Patient Records;
	<li>Telemedicine;
	<li>Application of Outcomes Information; and
      <li>Computer Aided Medicine.
</ul>

<p>These demonstration projects, when scaled to the level of nationwide implementation, would realistically test the viability of various technologies and the costs and benefits of their application in healthcare settings. </p>
 
<p><b>The Value of Information Technology to Healthcare Reform </b></p>
 
<p>The major healthcare challenge for the United States as we close the 20th century will be to increase the quality and access to healthcare services while reducing the overall cost of delivering those services to all Americans.  Healthcare reform is a l
arge and multifaceted endeavor for which there is no 'silver bullet'.  It is, rather, a complex set of problems that will require equally complex choices that can favorably impact quality, cost and access and that are sustainable over an extended period o
f time. </p>
 
<p>The Computer Systems Policy Project (CSPP) believes that new information management techniques and the application of information technologies win provide the opportunity to improve productivity, quality, and cost control in care delivery, health manag
ement, education and research, security of health-related information, and reimbursement.  CSPP recommends implementing a joint public-private sector effort to significantly increase the information technology investments made by major healthcare stakehol
ders, to accelerate nationwide deployment of a healthcare information infrastructure. </p>
 
<p>In his Economic Plan for America, President Clinton announced a major initiative to create an Information Infrastructure Technology Program in healthcare, education, manufacturing, and libraries.  CSPP applauds this recognition of the important contrib
ution that advanced information technology can make in healthcare and recommends that a healthcare information technology coordination function be included as part of the National Economic Council's task force on information infrastructure This should pro
vide a focal point for consulting with private sector experts in information technology; healthcare professional organizations and user groups that represent the broad array of stakeholders in the healthcare delivery and management, consumer groups, and r
esearch institutions. </p>
 
<p>The essential elements of the healthcare information infrastructure will include: a network of interconnected, interoperable, multi-speed communications networks connecting regional community health infrastructures; information resources, such as onlin
e medical databases and patient histories; computers and information appliances; and people -- both medical professionals and consumers - who are able to use the technologies.  Community health infrastructures will provide information services to individu
als, hospitals, physicians, HMOs, emergency or ambulatory care centers, employers, and payers locally.  Healthcare consumers and providers must be confident that medical data is correct, complete, and up to date, and that it is not provided to unauthorize
d users or used for unauthorized purposes.  Services available might include:</p>
<ul>
	<li>authorized access to computer-based lifetime patient records;
	<li>medical plan enrollment data;
	<li>medical eligibility criteria;
	<li>coordination of benefits information;
	<li>physician credentialing data;
	<li>authorization of care services;
       <li>patient monitoring and testing data;
	<li>financial settlement services; and
       <li>secure patient medical information.
</ul>
<p>Through nationwide links, medical research and outcomes assessment 
data could be aggregated and made available to local and regional 
users.  Ultimately, the community infrastructures would be linked, both 
locally and nationally, to payers, suppliers, pharmaceutical companies, 
employees, and party databases, as well as support systems for public 
sector quality assessment, clinical research, and education. </p>
 
<p>Pieces of this information management structure exist in the healthcare system today, and should be the foundation of the integrated and automated healthcare system of the future.  Today's healthcare system is a fragmented set of players.  Information 
technology can provide the thread that weaves the disparate pieces together into an integrated and seamless system of high-quality, low-cost, widely accessible care. </p>
 
<ul><i><li>Quality</i> </ul>
 
<p>As advanced and sophisticated as clinical care is in the U.S. today, most diagnostic and therapeutic decision-making is still executed based on the knowledge and experience of individual clinicians and care teams responsible for the patient.  That know
ledge resides principally in the clinicians' minds and may be augmented by journals, papers, and conferences they may have attended.  By providing access to complete patient histories and current patient information, along with online medical libraries, o
utcomes data, medical literature, and even consulting specialists, clinicians will be able to make decisions in real-time with the benefit of the entire range of medical knowledge available.  This access to a broad range of up-to-date information will res
ult in higher quality clinical decisions, which will generate higher quality outcomes.  By tracking and analyzing outcomes data, higher quality information to support clinical research and medical education can be gathered and made available consistently,
 nationwide. </p>
 
<ul><i><li>Cost</i> </ul>
 
<p>Better access to medical information by healthcare practitioners and consumers can reduce excessive or redundant tests, procedures, and visits to doctors' offices and hospitals.  For example, on-line patient medical information will provide practitione
rs with all current medical information about a patient, including complete test result information, eliminating the need to order tests that may be redundant.  Automated practice guidelines and protocols will deliver lower cost treatment options to clini
cians.  The higher quality care that results will tend to reduce the length of stay in hospitals.  Hospital efficiency will be improved through better education of clinical support resources.  Automated medical charting with voice-to-text conversion and h
andwriting-to-text conversion win ensure timely completion of medical records, ensuring higher quality of information input.  Computerized records of clinical transactions will speed the billing process, while providing complete data for patient/provider 
billing.  Higher quality clinical outcomes should help reduce malpractice premiums, which in turn should reduce the incidence of defensive medicine.  This is consistent with a 1992 Arthur D. Little, Inc. study which concluded that annual healthcare costs 
can be reduced by at least $36 billion through nationwide application of certain information technologies. </p>
 
<ul><i><li>Access </i></ul>
 
<p>Access to care is complicated by geographic, cultural, and economic factors.  Many areas of the U.S. -- both urban and rural - do not have sufficient numbers or types of healthcare practitioners.  In particular, the lack of specialists and diagnostic e
quipment prevents many people from receiving adequate diagnostic and treatment services.  Cultural factors, such as unfamiliarity with the English language, prevent many Americans from receiving adequate healthcare services.  In addition, cultural factors
 sometimes inhibit people from seeking medical intervention until a medical condition reaches very serious stages of advancement.  The lack of health insurance, as well as inadequate healthcare coverage, prevents millions of Americans from obtaining healt
hcare services.  Many Americans must choose between purchasing healthcare services and basic living items, such as food, shelter, and clothing.  Information technologies can help overcome these types of barriers to access through telemedicine and other ap
plications. </p>
 
<p><b>Barriers to Adoption of a Health Care Information Infrastructure </b></p>
 
<p>To achieve the promise of healthcare information technology, a variety of technological, human, organizational, and economic barriers must be overcome. </p>
 
<ul><i><li>Economic Feasibility </i></ul>
 
<p>Information technology has the potential to significantly improve the quality of, and access to, clinical treatment in the U.S. and to reduce administrative costs.  However, questions remain regarding how to fund its widespread implementation and the c
ost savings that are possible from such implementation.  The Center for 
Healthcare Information Management (CSPP has recommended developing 
mechanisms for various stakeholders (the federal government, other insurers, patients, vendors, and healthcare institu
tions) to share in the costs of development and implementation of computer-based patient records.  CSPP recommends establishing pilot projects that will test such mechanisms by demonstrating the economic and technological feasibility of large-scale implem
entation of information technology in healthcare settings. </p>
 
<ul><i><li>Professional Adaptation </i></ul>
 
<p>Healthcare providers have concerns about the impact of technology on their professions.  For example, physicians may perceive that their autonomy as clinical decision makers will be reduced by automation which enables implementation of protocols of car
e or outcomes research.  In addition, physicians may resist the necessary relearning and changes in procedures needed to adapt to using the new technologies.  Some nurses are concerned about technology substituting for nursing staff.  Finally, physicians 
and nurses may have reservations about the organizational implications of hospital administrators mandating automation without regard to the risks it poses for their professions.  Addressing these issues, will be no less challenging than commercializing t
he sophisticated technologies described later in this paper.  Demonstration projects that involve medical professionals can help better identify potential issues and possible solutions. </p>
 
<ul><i><li>Information Technology Standards </i></ul>
 
<p>Standardized communications formats and interoperable networks are essential to connect patients and caregivers within community health networks and to connect the community networks in a unified and fully integrated national system.  To exchange data 
among providers, insurers, researchers and consumers, standard data formats and definitions will be needed.  Such standards will be best developed and adopted through regional and interregional demonstration projects led by private sector stakeholders. </
p>
 
<ul><i><li>Lack of Reimbursement Mechanisms for Using Information </i></ul>
 
<p>A major obstacle to the adoption of information technology in healthcare is the lack of an appropriate mechanism for reimbursing providers for the cost of sharing information in treatment delivery.  Several problems exist: the U.S. healthcare system do
es not explicitly recognize the monetary value of health information; the collection and handling of patient data is viewed as a cost, but it is a cost that may not be reimbursable to the patient or the physician under today's compensation mechanisms; and
 delivery of treatment via the use of telemedicine is not reimbursable under present federal and state policies.  Demonstration projects that show the value of healthcare information will highlight the need to develop new reimbursement practices to take a
dvantage of new technologies. </p>
 
<ul><i><li>Legal Barriers </i></ul>
 
<p>A number of legal barriers are inhibiting the widespread adoption of information technologies by the healthcare community, including issues about the ownership and appropriate use of patient information as well as liability for the misuse of informatio
n.  These are complex issues that need to be examined carefully by the fun range of affected stakeholders.  CSPP applauds efforts by the Computer Patient Record Institute (CPRI) and other groups to develop recommendations on these issues. </p>
 
<ul><i><li>Technology Challenges </i></ul>
 
<p>The healthcare information infrastructure of the future will link providers, payers, and patients in an automated, interconnected healthcare system which provides reliable, secure access to authorized users anywhere and at anytime using a range of acce
ss methods -- voice, data, multimedia.  To achieve this vision, further research is needed on leading edge technologies for the entry, storage, communication, and presentation of multimedia information.  The Information Infrastructure and Technology Act o
f 1993, currently being considered by the Senate as Title VI of S.4, would authorize funds for research in these technologies.  In addition, though many of these technologies are already being demonstrated, they have not been integrated seamlessly through
out the healthcare system and have not been demonstrated on a scale large enough to support the nation's healthcare delivery system.  Large scale demonstration projects in the areas suggested in Section III are necessary to integrate the technologies into
 the healthcare system and identify specific additional research and scalability challenges. </p>
 <ul>
<b>1. Data Capture, Retrieval, and Distribution </b>- Healthcare practitioners frequently require mobility, are often in environments that are hostile to electronic equipment, and will not use an automated system if it requires more time to do a task than
 it takes to do it manually.  Fundamental to the success of the healthcare information infrastructure is the ability to capture information when and where it is generated and to retrieve and distribute that information when and where it is needed.  This w
ill require advancements in technologies for voice recognition input, handwriting recognition input, natural language understanding, pen-based computing, and portable information appliances. <br><br>
 
<b>2. Data Access and Delivery </b>- Healthcare practitioners must be able to locate the information they need very rapidly, and consumers of healthcare information must be able to find medical and cost information quickly and easily.  This will require a
pplication of state of the art technologies in both distributed database and information filtering technologies.  Intelligent agents will be needed to help users formulate queries and filter the responses. <br><br>
 
<b>3. Data Storage </b>- The U.S. healthcare system includes:<br>
<ul>
	<li>5,892 short stay hospitals
	<li>1,033,881 short stay beds
	<li>539,228 physicians
	<li>1,648,000 registered nurses
      <li>1,487,000 nursing home or personal care residents
</ul><br>
For every thousand beds, a large hospital generates about 3 gigabytes of image data per day; emerging technologies such as 3D magnetic resonance imaging have the potential to generate 20-40 megabytes of data for a single test.  The requirements for data s
torage and retrieval technology are already large and growing with the current uses of information technology.  In the future, the widespread application of information technologies in 1.3 billion patient contacts per year will, coupled with federal and s
tate laws that require certain kinds of medical information to be stored for a minimum of 25 years, will require significant advancements in information storage and retrieval technologies to handle that data efficiently and effectively. <br><br>
 
<b>4. Integration </b>- Given the pluralistic nature of the U.S. healthcare environment, the information stored throughout the system will be based upon a heterogeneous set of storage and retrieval technologies.  Leading edge technologies will be needed t
o integrate this heterogeneous information base so it works as one seamless system. <br><br>
 
<b>5. Communications Technologies </b>- Delivery of multimedia healthcare information when and where it is needed will require an information infrastructure that includes interconnected, interoperable networks that provide adequate levels of security, pri
vacy, and reliable transmission.  Mobile communication appliances will be essential elements throughout the healthcare information infrastructure. 
 <br><br>
<b>6. Presentation </b>- Presentation of healthcare information to a wide variety of users, with a wide range of computational skills and information needs, is a major challenge.  Emerging technologies, such as data mining tools, 'information agents,' voi
ce-to-text conversion, non-destructive compression algorithms, and interactive two-way video over local area and remote wireless networks, will find application as the need to quickly and unambiguously grasp the significance of a wide range of healthcare 
information becomes commonplace.  Visualization tools and virtual reality are already being applied in both surgical training and certain kinds of treatment. 
 </ul>
<p><b>Representative Demonstration Projects </b></p>
 
<p>Projects that demonstrate, on a regional and interregional basis, the application of information technology to healthcare would highlight the potential benefits of information technology in increasing access, improving quality, and reducing costs.  Whi
le there is consensus that information technology will result in substantial cost savings, demonstration projects can quantify the magnitude of the savings in a way that is scaleable to nationwide implementation. </p>
 
<p>Furthermore, demonstration projects can provide vehicles to overcome the technological and non-technological barriers to widespread implementation of the information technologies, by furthering research, testing the viability of various technology solu
tions, and catalyzing their adoption by important stakeholders.  To be effective, demonstration projects must be of sufficient scale and variety to give competing technologies a fair trial and to be credible when scaled to the level of a nationwide health
care delivery system.  Projects should be based upon national and international consensus healthcare information technology standards which are being developed to support the healthcare information infrastructure.  This way, the demonstration projects wil
l both drive and test the emerging standards. </p>
 
<p>Demonstration projects in the following areas will help accelerate the adoption of information technologies in healthcare.  While a number of projects are currently ongoing in each area, additional efforts should build on the progress currently being m
ade.  The automation of billing and claims reimbursement will be an important means of reducing indirect costs of healthcare in the future, and should use national and international standards where they are available. </p>
 
<ul><i><li>Computerized Patient Records </i></ul>
 
<p>The National Academy of Sciences' Institute of Medicine's Committee on Improving the Patient Record concluded after an 18 month study that the Computer-Based Patient Record (CPR) is an essential technology for improving the quality of healthcare while 
reducing costs.  The committee recommended that both the public and private sectors should expand their support for the CPR and CPR system implementation through research, development, and demonstration projects. </p>
 
<p>The CPR is an integrated information system designed around an electronic database of patient information with links to medical knowledge bases, such as the National Library of Medicine.  The patient information is generated by clinicians and care prov
iders as a result of interaction with patients during care episodes and represents all of the care episodes during a patient's lifetime.  This way, practitioners will have easy access to the most up-to-date health information, such as test results, allerg
ies, and family history.  Treatment decisions based on higher quality information are likely to result in better outcomes and lower costs.  Focused demonstration projects would demonstrate the value of the CPR and instruct users how to implement systems c
ost effectively. </p>
 
<p>CSPP recommends that funds be allocated as part of healthcare policy reform efforts for a set of demonstration projects that will accelerate progress towards national implementation of CPR technology. The demonstration projects should be at least regio
nal in scope and should involve multiple healthcare providers and multiple vendors using a variety of technologies, building upon emerging national and international consensus standards.  The demonstration projects should include as key elements the devel
opment of standards for privacy protection and the quantification of the economic viability of computerized patient records. </p>
 
<ul><i><li>Telemedicine </i></ul>
 
<p>Telemedicine is the extension of medical information from its major source, the hospital, to the physicians in surrounding areas and beyond.  Through telemedicine, caregivers in areas lacking the full range of healthcare providers will be able to consu
lt with experts; improve or maintain their education; share medical records, x-rays, ultrasound images, and monograms; and monitor and treat patients in their homes without the need for extensive travel.  Less travel, with better monitoring to detect prob
lems early, will reduce healthcare costs dramatically while providing patients with access to higher quality care.  For example, Michael McDonald, chairman of Communications and Computer Applications in Public Health, stated in testimony before the House 
Subcommittee on Science, that homebased telemedicine could save $15 - 20 billion per year by allowing health professionals to monitor and interact with patients remotely via telemedicine systems that merge computer, video, and telecommunications technolog
ies. </p>
 
<p>CSPP recommends allocating funds to demonstrate, on a large scale, the underlying technologies for telemedicine, including high capacity network connections, by linking primary care physicians in rural areas with other providers throughout the nation. 
 While telemedicine has been successfully demonstrated many times in recent years, demonstration projects will address the barriers to accelerating its deployment.  The telemedicine demonstrations should include both teleradiology, which is the ability to
 share x-ray information with others, and which can be done now, and telepresence, which permits a practitioner to look at 3-dimensional images built from two-dimensional x-rays and manipulate the devices as if they were located in the room with the patie
nt. </p>
 
<ul><i><li>Application of Outcomes Information </i></ul>
 
<p>Outcomes research, accessible databases, and user friendly information for consumers will help healthcare providers, payers, individuals, and communities make better healthcare decisions that will reduce costs and enhance the quality of service.  Too o
ften, consumers make healthcare decisions in a vacuum.  Decisions made without adequate information result in unnecessary trips to doctors' offices and emergency rooms, an inability to compare prices and services offered, and postponing care until it has 
reached a crisis stage.  Michael McDonald estimates that personal health information systems -- even if used only 25 % to 35 % of the time - could save $40-60 billion per year in the U.S. by helping healthcare consumers make more informed choices. </p>
 
<p>CSPP recommends funding projects to demonstrate how regional healthcare information infrastructures designed to serve the needs of healthcare stakeholders can help forge collaborative care partnerships that would be outcomes-driven.  Care would be deli
vered and evaluated by quality and cost together, enabling decision-making to be guided by outcomes rather than procedures.  Interregional healthcare links could help measure and calibrate the mobile character of our population and the dynamic nature of h
ealthcare. </p>
 
<p><b>1. Aggregating Data </b>- Aggregating the data stored in individuals' computerized patient records would increase the quantity and quality of information that researchers and practitioners use to determine which treatment protocols lead to the best 
health outcomes.  For example, Pennsylvania's coronary artery bypass graft surgery project has made aggregated medical information available to consumers, payers, and providers. </p>
 
<p>CSPP recommends funding a demonstration project that would include development of standard formats for collecting, storing, and reporting cost, quality, and outcomes information.  From this data, consumer report cards can be produced to bridge the medi
cal information knowledge gap in communities. </p>
 
<p><b>2. Information Dissemination and Education</b> - Once the aggregation process has begun, the benefits to individual consumers and other payers can take root.  Community outreach programs similar to local recycling campaigns can focus attention on de
veloping more informed health care consumers.  Cable television, home computer networks, and public health initiatives, connecting local departments of health, libraries, and physicians' offices, are all mechanisms that can be used to educate the public. 
</p>
 
<p>Once available and broadly disseminated, information will foster knowledgeable consumers, enhancing prevention, wellness, self-we, and early intervention.  With this additional knowledge, consumers will be able to avoid unnecessary trips to emergency r
ooms and doctors' offices, and people will be able to select among providers offering the best and most appropriate services at the lowest prices. </p>
 
<p>CSPP recommends funding a demonstration project designed to bring health information to people with the same ease that sports, entertainment, financial, and other types of consumer information are brought into peoples' homes.  Convenient consumer acces
s to understandable healthcare information will contribute significantly to changes in individual behavior that are necessary to recast the nation's healthcare profile. </p>
 
<ul><i><li>Computer Aided Medicine </i></ul>
 
<p>The application of computing technologies to medical procedures can help reduce the cost of performing many of those procedures while increasing the likelihood of positive outcomes.  For example, with high-performance computers, surgeons can construct 
three-dimensional images of the human anatomy. These images can then be rotated on a computer screen, examined from all angles, and used to plan surgical treatments and design prosthetic replacements.  CSPP recommends-,ids funding demonstration projects i
n the following areas to examine the cost effectiveness of commercial application of high performance computing to surgical practice.</p>
<ul>
1. Develop a system for simulating multiple interacting physiologic systems -- in essence, a whole body simulation.  The proposed system would permit both forward modeling to simulate physiologic processes and reverse modeling in which data collected from
 a single individual is used to construct a specific model for that individual.<br><br>

2. Develop a system of computer-aided decision support, including the use of artificial intelligence for diagnosis and treatment.<br><br>

3. Develop robotic surgery systems enabling distant, as well as traditional, surgical interaction.<br><br>

4. Develop advanced imaging technology supporting enhanced image presentation and manipulation.<br><br>

5.     Develop 3D modeling systems to aid in craniofacial and orthopedic treatment.</ul>

<p><b>Conclusion</b> </p>
 
<p>A wide variety of information technologies are being applied successfully in other industries to reduce cost and increase productivity and quality.  Applying those technologies to the delivery of healthcare services can help alleviate the tremendous pr
essure on the healthcare system, By s g administrative and management processes, using telemedicine to make healthcare more widely accessible, providing complete and up to date patient and medical information to practitioners when and where they need it, 
and making better use of high performance computing technologies, the healthcare industry -- and American healthcare consumers - can reap the benefits of the Information Age.</p>

<hr>
</html>
</DOC>
