<html>
<head><title>The CSPP Agenda for the 103rd Congress</title>

<h2 align=center>Perspectives on U.S. Technology and Trade Policy:<br>
The CSPP Agenda for the 103rd Congress<br>
October 1, 1992</h2>
<hr>
<p><b>TABLE OF CONTENTS</b></p>
<ul>
<li><a href="#executive">Executive Summary</a>
<li><a href="#introduction">Introduction</a>
<li><a href="#industrys">Industry's Role</a>
<li><a href="#governments">Government's Role</a>
<li><a href="#cspp">CSPP Recommendations for the 103rd Congress</a>
 <li><a href="#one">Recommendation #1: Take Action to Increase the Nation's Return on the Federal R&D Investment</a>
 <li><a href="#two">Recommendation #2: Expand the Research Agenda of the High Performance Computing and Communications Program</a>
 <li><a href="#three">Recommendation #3: Create a New National Technology Challenge: A National Information Infrastructure for the Future</a>
 <li><a href="#four">Recommendation #4: Implement Policies to Open Market and Expand Trade</a>
<li><a href="#five">Recommendation #5: Enhance the Ability of U.S. Companies to Compete Globally
<li><a href="#appendices">Appendices</a>
 <ul>Appendix A: U.S. Corporate R&D by Industry<br>
 	Appendix B:  U.S. Corporate R&D by Industry - Percent of Sales<br>
 	Appendix C:  Share of R&D Spending by U.S. Industry Sector<br>
 	Appendix D:  Share of R&D Spending by U.S. Industry Sector<br>
	Appendix E: Total R&D Spending - United States<br>
	Appendix F: U.S. Federal Government R&D Funding Trend
</ul></ul>
<hr>
<p><b><a name="executive">Executive Summary</a></b></p>

<p>The computer industry was borp in America over half a century ago.  The industry's progress since then is an impressive example of an American success story.  Over the years, U.S. companies have grown and developed in America and have contributed significantly to the overall economic health of the country.  At the same time, they have gained a competitive edge and leadership position in what is now a global industry. </p>
 
<p>The success of the past, however, does not guarantee similar success in the future.  The American computer industry is in the midst of an international competitive struggle.  To maintain and improve its world leadership position, the U.S. computer industry must address the combined challenges presented by: 1) fierce competition; 2) increasingly shorter product life-cyclesand 3) foreign governments' support for their domestic computer industries. </p>
 
<p>The chief executives of thirteen leading American computer companies, the members of the Computer Systems Policy Project (CSPP), recognize that the primary burden for meeting those challenges and seizing new opportunities rests with each company.  As a result, CSPP's member companies are taking independent actions to: 1) maintain a steady investment in R&D and innovation; 2) focus on commercialization; 3) emphasize quality; 4) compete globally; and 5) educate their work force. </p>
 
<p>Nevertheless, the U.S. government also has a role to play.  Through its policies and practices, the government can create a supportive public policy climate and set an appropriate national tone that facilitates the industry's ability to succeed.  In addition, the government can provide a research foundation for industry to build upon by continuing its commitment to basic research and focusing more attention on commercially relevant R&D. </p>
 
<p>To that end, CSPP recommends the federal government take the following actions during the 103rd Congress to bolster economic performance and build a solid technology and trade policy foundation for the future:</p>
<ul>
	<li>Take Action to Increase the Nation's Return on the Federal R&D Investment;
 <li>Expand the Research Agenda of the High Performance Computing and Communications Program;
 <li>Create a New National Technology Challenge: A National Information Infrastructure for the Future;
 <li>Implement Policies to Open Markets and Expand Trade; and
	<li>Enhance the Ability of U.S. Companies to Compete Globally by Modernizing and Strengthening U.S. Antidumping Law and Modernizing the U.S. Export Licensing System.
</ul>

<p><b><a name="introduction">Introduction: The U.S. Computer Industry</a></b></p>

<p><b>Made in America </b>- The success of the computer industry is an example of the American entrepreneurial spirit at work.  The computer industry was born in a university laboratory less than half a century ago.  A ballroom-sized invention performed in minutes calculations that until then took dozens of people days to compute.  Through American ingenuity and a commitment to continuously increasing efficiency, those same calculations are now performed in moments on computers that can fit in the palm of your hand or in your shirt pocket. </p>
 
<p>Today, computers and computer technologies are a pervasive and strategic element in the competitive marketplace.  With power and speed once unimaginable, computers are on the desks and in the briefcases of scientists, students, and business people in virtually every industry.  They are essential to the efficient production and operation of products from automobiles to airplanes and to the efficient functioning of businesses from grocery stores to banks. </p>
 
<p><b>Global Success </b>- Perhaps more than any other industry in the United States, computer systems producers, and the high technology industry of which it is a part, are highly integrated into the global market system.  In fact, there is quite possibly no other sector of the U.S. economy that contributes so much to, and depends so heavily upon, international markets for its domestic as well as its international success. </p>
 
<p>In 1991, CSPP companies had worldwide revenue in excess of $140 billion, almost 60% of which was derived from outside North America.  As information technology continues to develop into the 21st century and its value is realized around the world, the importance of overseas markets will continue to grow. </p>
 
<p><b>Future Outlook </b>- The successful companies of the future will be globally competitive companies that provide seamless solutions to business problems and emphasize quality systems development and service.  More and more, the real value of the computer industry is more than just manufacturing-based- it is knowledge-based as well.  The industry's value-added, and the best prospect for ensuring its future success, is the technology used to power its products and the applications designed for those products.  Moreover, the industry adds value through the jobs it provides, not only in manufacturing, but in high-quality, highpaying, knowledge intensive jobs in engineering, R&D, sales, marketing, and services, including repair, maintenance, and development of applications. </p>
 
<p><b>Challenges</b> - To be counted among the successful companies of the future, U.S. computer companies must have access to global technology and a presence in markets around the world.  Moreover, they must address various challenges presented by: 1) fierce competition; 2) increasingly shorter product life-cycles; and 3) foreign govemments' support for their domestic computer industries.</p>
<ul>
	<li><b>Fierce Competition</b>.  The rapid pace of technological advancements and the computer industry's success in domestic and global markets make it one of the most fiercely competitive U.S. industries.  Because technology and innovation are the primary products of the industry, and because there is no monopoly on either, there is always room for a new idea and a new company advancing that idea.  The result is constant competition not only from foreign competitors, but from domestic rivals as well.
	<li><b>Increasingly Shorter Product LifeCycles</b>.  In such a competitive environment, the speed with which any given company can bring a new product to the market increasingly determines the success or failure of multi-million dollar investments and the maintenance or loss of thousands of jobs.<br><br>

Typically, companies that manufacture computer systems derive half their revenue from products that did not exist two years earlier.  These incredibly short product lifecycles demand that the computer industry continuously develop new products based on innovative technologies.  In addition, it demands increasingly efficient production as newer products impose price pressures on older designs which become quickly obsolete.  As a result, research and development (R&D), the industry's primary resource in developing new technologies and processes, has always been and continues to be the foundation upon which the success of the industry is built.

	<li><b>Foreign Governments' Support for Their Computer Industries</b>.  The synergy between investment in R&D and the success of high technology industries is widely recognized by our international competitors.  Much of the competition the U.S. computer industry faces from its foreign competitors comes from the degree of support foreign governments provide their domestic industries.  This support is not just financial.  It also includes foreign governments' commitments to setting national technology priorities and identifying and developing technologies of strategic importance to the economic wellbeing of the country.
</ul>
<hr>
<p align=center><b><a name="industrys">Industry's Role</a></b></p>

<p>Clearly, the primary responsibility for meeting the challenges posed by the competitive domestic and international environment rests with each company.  In response, American companies continue to: 1) invest steadily in R&D and innovation; 2) focus on commercialization; 3) emphasize quality- 4) compete globally; and 5) educate their work force. </p>
 
<p><b>Invest Steadily in R&D and Innovation </b>-  The computer industry, like all corporate America, is in the midst of one of the most difficult economic periods in recent memory.  Nevertheless, our industry increased its R&D spending in 1991.  The U.S. semiconductor and computer industries invested $18.6 billion in R&D, more than any other single industrial sector (see Appendix A).  As a percentage of sales, the semiconductor and computer industries' investment in R&D was 8.7%, more than double the average for spending by all U.S. industry (see Appendix B).  Overall, the broader electronics industry, including computers, accounted for 3 1 % of all industrial R&D spending.  Of that, the semiconductor and computer industries' spending alone accounted for 24% of all industrial R&D spending (See Appendices C and D). </p>
 
<p><b>Focus on Commercialization </b>-Recognizing that the development of new technologies is only the first step, U.S. computer companies continue to expend significant efforts on turning those technologies into marketable products.  Companies are working to bring various corporate departments such as research, development and marketing together early to speed the commercialization process; forming strategic alliances with other companies and universities-, and capitalizing on the resources at the nation's federal laboratories.  For example, this past spring, the CEOs in CSPP and the Secretary of Energy, Admiral James D. Watkins, signed a model Cooperative Research and Development Agreement (CRADA) designed to boost collaborative research efforts between the U.S. computer industry and the Department of Energy's (DOE) National Laboratories. </p>
 
<p><b>Emphasize Quality </b>-Delivering quality products to their customers has made the industry competitive and will keep the industry competitive for the long-term.  As a result, the computer industry has made quality a top priority by emphasizing internal programs and practices designed to ensure quality, beginning in the research phase and continuing through the development, manufacturing, delivery, and service phases. </p>
 
<p><b>Compete Globally </b>- The computer industry has become one of the most competitive industries overseas by developing products that capitalize on available technology from around the world and that respond to the needs and expectations of its global customers.  Overseas markets are the fastest growing markets for the computer industry.  Gross revenue from sales by the U.S. computer industry is approaching $200 billion, with almost 60% of those revenues derived from sales abroad.  According to export figures featured in the June 29, 1992 issue of Fortune Magazine, six CSPP companies currently account for over 13% of all exports generated by the top 50 exporters in the country.  The global success of the industry provides the constantly growing revenue base it needs to fund critical R&D.  While almost 60% of the industry's revenues come from overseas, 61% of the industry's employees are located in the United States, and 90% of the industry's research and development is conducted here. </p>
 
<p><b>Educate the Work Force </b>- The computer industry depends on technically proficient workers to design and develop new products, manufacture quality products, and design, install and use applications for computer technologies.  To ensure an on-going, steady supply of skilled workers, computer industry companies have instituted and continue to expand their own worker training and education efforts.  In addition, computer companies continue to participate in and establish programs to attract young students to careers in math, science, and engineering.  In total, CSPP companies spend over $2.25 billion per year to educate and train those they employ and to reach out to future generations of employees. </p>
 <hr>
<p align=center><a name="governments"><b>Government's Role</b></a> </p>
 
<p>While the primary burden for competing successfully rests with industry, the federal govemment has a clear role to play.  The government must implement supportive technology and trade policies and set an appropriate national tone that allows U.S. companies to innovate, create, and compete. </p>
 
<p><b>Technology </b>- The federal government has always had a role in investing in research on technologies critical to its mission needs.  Govemment research was, for example, instnnnental to the early beginnings of the computer industry.  Its role is just as cr-ucial today. </p>
 
<p>In 1991, total U.S. R&D spending, both public and private, was $151 billion (see Appendix E).  U.S. government spending accounted for nearly half that total at $66 billion, which was more than that of all of our major competitors' goverm-nents combined.  Despite the fact that this is a significant amount, there is room for improvement. </p>
 
<p>For the last several years, about 60% of the govemment's R&D spending has been devoted to defense research (see Appendix F).  Given world developments over the last few years, now is the time for the goverm-nent to work with industry to increase the focus of the federal R&D investment on commercially relevant research.  In addition, the government should work with industry to be sure public and private R&D spending priorities are more complementary.  For example, while 24% of private industry spending was devoted to computer-related R&D in 199 1, the U.S. govemment allocated only 2% of its R&D budget to computer-related R&D (see Appendices C and D).  During the same time, the goveniments of our international competitors recognized the importance of R&D in computing technologies and are investing billions of dollars in multi-year projects such as the Real World Computing Program and Teletopia Project in Japan; RACE, ESPIRIT and EUREKA in Europe; and the POLIKOM Project in Germany.  Better aligning U.S. government and private sector R&D spending priorities would improve the nation's return on its R&D investment and would provide the country with a stronger research base. </p>
 
<p><b>Trade </b>- Through its trade policies, the U.S. government can either help or hinder the ability of U.S. companies to compete.  To help companies compete, U.S. trade policies must recognize the global nature of the industry and the global nature of technology, and be designed to foster the flow of technology and products. </p>
 
<p>While this country has historically advocated policies that encourage open trade, other countries have not.  For example, the European Community created high tariffs to protect their computer and computer component industries.  The result was a decline in the competitiveness of the companies and a reduction in their global business.  If the goal is a healthy, vital computer industry, trade policies must not create artificial borders and boundaries. </p>
 <hr>
<p align=center><a name="cspp"><b>The CSPP Recommendations for the 103rd Congress</b></a> </p>
 
<p>On the following pages, CSPP offers a series of specific recommendations to improve the federal government's technology and trade policies in the 103rd Congress.  Taken together, these recommendations can help improve the ability of the computer industry to compete and bolster the country's domestic economic situation and international competitive position. </p>
 
<p>Nevertheless, the following recommendations will not have the desired effect unless they are complemented by the enactment of long-term policies to improve the overall business climate in the United States and to build a stronger U.S. educational system.  CSPP maintains a limited agenda focused on technology and trade policy issues.  As a result, CSPP's member companies work on business and education issues through a variety of other trade and professional associations, CSPP encourages the government to work with those organizations to create a sound business climate and policy framework that will enable the following specific recommendations to improve our economic performance and help provide the necessary technology and trade policy foundation for the future:</p>
<ul>
 	<li>Take Action to Increase the Nation's Return on the Federal R&D Investment',
 	<li>Expand the Research Agenda of the High Performance Computing and Communications Program-,
 	<li>Create a New National Technology Challenge: A National Information Infrastructure for the Future:
	<li>Implement Policies to Open Markets and Expand Trade; and
	 <li>Enhance the Ability of U.S. Companies to Compete Globally by Modernizing and Strengthening U.S. Antidumping Law and Modernizing the Export Licensing System.
</ul>
<hr>

<p><b><a name="one">Recommendation #1</a></b></p>

<p align=center>Take Action to Increase the Nation's<br>
Return on the Federal R&D Investment</p>

<p>To help improve national economic performance, the return on the federal research investment must be increased by making it more relevant to the private sector.  CSPP recommends that the government work with industry to:</p>
<ul>
	 <li><b>Increase the Allocation of Funds to Commercially Relevant Technologies: </b>In addition to continuing its strong support for basic research, the federal government should work with industry to reallocate, over the next four years, $5-$10 billion more per year of its total R&D budget to research on pre-competitive, generic technologies.  This can be accomplished in part by:<br>
<ul>
1.	Developing and implementing model Cooperative Research and Development Agreements (CRADAS) that meet the needs of different industries, making it easier for companies to enter into collaborative research efforts with the govemment's research laboratories; and<br><br>

2.	Setting aside a portion of government laboratories' budgets for industry-driven cooperative research projects.</ul><br>

	<li><b>Improve Federal R&D Budget Review Mechanisms and increase Industry Involvement: </b>Budget crosscuts (summaries of major federal research initiatives that cut across the budgets of several different agencies) have proven very usefw in assessing federal spending on various research projects.  CSPP recommends that the government continue working with the private sector to develop and refine crosscuts of federal spending on generic technologies that can contribute to the improved economic competitiveness of the U.S. Furthermore, private sector advisory panels should be created such that they allow fWl participation by industry representatives in setting federal R&D priorities.

	<li><b>Improve Government Incentives for U.S. R&D: </b>In today's global marketplace, promoting American innovation is critical.  The U.S. government can enhance the incentive for U.S. companies to increase their spending on domestic R&D by making the R&D tax credit permanent and by permanently resolving the 861-8 research allocation issue by regulation.  CSPP urges the government to demonstrate its commitment to a healthy and vital U.S. R&D enterprise by taking immediate action on these two important issues.
</ul>
<hr>

<p><b><a name="two">Recommendation #2</a></b></p>

<p align=center>Expand the Research Agenda of the High
Performance Computing and Communications Program</p>

<p>U.S. research on high performance computing and communications (BPCC) is a significant and critical undertaking by the federal government.  CSPP believes BPCC technologies have the potential to provide the country with the foundation for an infrastructure that will help improve America's quality of life for the 21st century and beyond. </p>
 
<p>To date, CSPP has strongly supported Administration and Congressional BPCC initiatives and applauds the government's creation of a new, improved management structure for the current B:PCC Program.  As CSPP has advocated, the new structure provides a clear mechanism, which draws on private sector expertise, to coordinate, manage, and govern the implementation of the initiative.  In addition, CSPP is pleased Congress is considering legislation that will begin to move the BPCC effort to a new level. </p>
 
<p>CSPP believes that federal and private investments in BPCC technologies will be maximized by increasing the focus on how current research on BPCC technologies can benefit individual Americans and businesses.  To that end, CSPP recommends that the government enhance and expand the BPCC research agenda to:</p>
<ul>
	<li>Provide the Foundation for an Information and Communications Infrastructure of the Future: The BPCC Program includes research to deploy a high-speed research and education network (NREN).  CSPP believes this research can be leveraged to provide the foundation for a much broader communications and information infrastructure for the future.  That broader infrastructure would not only bring the benefits of BPCC technologies to bear on scientific and engineering problems, but on difficult social and economic problems as well.  To that end, CSPP recommends that the government fund the current BPCC research program at the level in the budget request and allocate additional funds for research needed to enable a broader communications and information infrastructure for the future.

	 <li>Bring the Benefits of HPCC Technology to Individual Americans in Health Care, Education and Lifelong Learning, and Manufacturing: The federal government is committed to promoting a healthier, more educated, and more productive citizenry, and to improving the productivity and quality of the nation's manufacturing enterprise.  CSPP recommends that the government and private sector work together to be sure @CC technology helps meet these goals.  Specifically, CSPP recommends the government expand the BPCC budget in FY '94 to include funds within the Departments of Health and Human Services and Education, and at the National Institute of Standards and Technology, to begin research needed to solve problems in health care, education, and manufacturing, respectively.  In addition, CSPP recommends allocating additional funds to the current HPCC agencies (National Science Foundation, Defense Advanced Research Projects Agency, National Institutes of Health, the Department of Energy, and others as appropriate) to expand their efforts in these areas.

	 <li>Create Technology Demonstration Projects: CSPP also recommends that the federal government work with relevant industry groups, future user groups, research and educational institutions, and state and local governments to develop technology demonstration projects to test the ability of an advanced communications and information infrastructure to support applications in health care, education and manufacturing.  Government support for such demonstration projects will help drive private sector investments in developing and producing applications.  In a separate paper to be released this fall, CSPP will provide more detail about the research needed in each of the areas and will suggest possible technology demonstration projects.
</ul>
<hr>
<p><b><a name="three">Recommendation #3</a></b></p>

<p align=center>Create a New National Technology Challenge:<br>
a National Information Infrastructure for the Future</p>

<p>The U.S. faces a challenge that is as significant as the challenge we faced when Sputnik was launched in 1957.  The current challenge is to enhance our future prospects for economic prosperity, an improved quality of life, and our global competitive leadership.  Meeting this new challenge will require the same level of national cooperation and commitment that led us to win the space race. </p>
 
<p>As we enter the Information Age, our best resource is our ability to create and exchange information, technology, and ideas.  Today, we have an edge.  The U.S. leads the world in its communications infrastructure and in the development of supercomputers and important computing and software technologies.  In addition, the BPCC Program will provide a critical, initial research foundation.  However, this is not enough.  We must elevate and accelerate our effort.  The United States needs to make a national commitment to capitalize on our leadership position and build upon the research foundation provided by the EPCC Program to create a new national information infrastructure for the future. </p>
 
<p>Creating a new national information infrastructure will require improving upon and linking together current communications, information, and human resource capabilities.  More importantly, it will require developing new capabilities to enable broad access to a variety of public and private information resources and enable transmission of text, images, and video to anyone, anywhere, at any time.  To realize the comprehensive information infrastructure of the future, CSPP recommends that the federal government work with industry to:</p>
<ul>
	 <li>Make the Drive for a National Information Infrastructure the New National Technology Challenge: The President and Congress should challenge American industries, universities and laboratories to form a public/private partnership to create the new information infrastructure.  The goal should be to immediately begin implementing a nationwide high speed communications and knowledge infrastructure capable of bringing the benefits of computing and communications technologies to bear on social and economic areas of widespread concern such as health care, education and lifelong learning, and manufacturing.

	 <li>Adopt an Industry/Government Vision and Milestones to Measure Progress: The government should work with industry, academia, potential users, and other interested parties to develop a vision for the future computing, communications, and information infrastructure, and a set of milestones to measure progress toward reaching that common vision.  CSPP is currently working to develop our industry's vision of a future information infrastructure and plans to issue a report in mid-1993 that will describe that vision and the steps we believe are necessary to move the country toward that vision.

	 <li>Address Public Policy, Political, and Regulatory Issues: A widely accessible, reliable, and useful national information infrastructure based on fair and open competition will require addressing a range of networking policy issues from interoperability, security, and broad access to copyright protection and availability of federal information.  During the 103rd Congress, the federal government should establish fora where these and a myriad of other relevant public policy issues can be addressed by experts from a range of industries, potential users and consumers, and the federal government.  CSPP also recommends that federal and state governments work with industry to ensure that various political and regulatory hurdles preventing the implementation of an information infrastructure are addressed in an open, timely, and systematic manner.

	 <li>Effectively Manage the Public/Private Partnership to Foster Commercialization: The government should encourage the near-term implementation of the new information infrastructure by- 1) facilitating access to and ensuring compatibility/interworking among multiple private and public networks- 2) investing in precompetitive technologies needed to make the national information infrastructure possible, including addressing interoperability and human factors issues; and 3) assisting disadvantaged users in obtaining access to the information infrastructure.
</ul>
<hr>

<p><b><a name="four">Recommendation #4</a></b></p>

<p align=center>Implement Policies to Open Markets and Expand Trade</p>

<p>To be competitive, U.S. high technology industries need access to the major markets of the world to earn the returns needed to sustain capital investment and critical research and development.  CSPP recommends that the U.S. government continue its commitment to opening markets around the world to U.S. goods and services by creating effective multilateral and bilateral agreements that focus on results, not managed trade.  Specifically, CSPP recommends that the government:</p>
<ul>
	 <li>Successfully Conclude the Uruguay Round of Trade Negotiations: The most important step that the United States can take to improve market access worldwide is to strengthen the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade (GATT).  Since open markets are one of the principal benefits of an effective multilateral system, the U.S. government should make every effort to successfully conclude the current negotiations on the Uruguay Round of trade negotiations.  In particular, CSPP urges the government to be sure the final agreement includes a reduction in the very high European Community tariffs on computer parts and semiconductors.

	 <li>Implement an Effective North American Free Trade Agreement: CSPP actively supports actions to open markets around the world, CSPP urges the government to implement the NAFTA because it recognizes the realities of the global marketplace and will promote the growth and expansion of markets for U.S. computer products in Mexico and Canada.

	 <li>Implement the Japan Public Procurement Agreement: The U.S. government also should focus on bilateral market access initiatives.  In particular, the U.S. government should seek aggressive implementation of the January 1992 agreement by the Japanese government to open its public sector computer market to foreign products.  This agreement is critical because it directly addresses a significant problem: CSPP found that while foreign computer manufacturers have established a major share position in Japan's private sector mainframe market (41%); the foreign share of the Japanese national government mainframe market is only 0.4%. CSPP urges the U.S. government to continue working with the computer industry to define the most appropriate mechanisms for measuring progress under this agreement.

	 <li>Continue Efforts to Broaden U.S. Companies' Access to the Japanese Semiconductor Market: In accordance with the 1991 Semiconductor Trade Agreement with Japan, C SPP urges the U.S. government to continue working to ensure that Japan continues progress toward an open market for U.S. semiconductors.
</ul>
<hr>

<p><b><a name="five">Recommendation #5</a></b></p>

<p align=center>Enhance the Ability of U.S. Companies to Compete Globally</p>

<p>The ability of U.S. computer companies to compete globally is critical to the future health and vitality of the industry.  The U.S. government should work with industry to be sure its policies and practices do not act as a disincentive to global competition.  In particular, CSPP recommends that the U.S. government:</p>
<ul>
	 <li>Modernize and Strengthen the U.S. Antidumping Law: Modernizing and strengthening the U.S. antidumping law is a major trade policy priority for CSPP for two reasons: 1) CSPP members are highly integrated into the global trading system, sourcing from and selling to every major market in the world.  Our ability to compete globally is significantly affected by the antidumping law in the U.S. and foreign countries; and 2) effective antidumping law is one element of the high technology business environment necessary to nurture a healthy U.S. high-technology enterprise.<br><br>

CSPP believes antidumping law should be an effective remedy for injuriously unfair pricing, no more and no less.  Above all, CSPP believes antidumping law should be balanced and should not interfere with ordinary business practices, particularly practices vital to maintaining a strong U.S. high technology industry.  CSPP outlined its initial position on antidumping law reform in its May 1990 report, " Perspectives on Market Access andAntidumpingLawReform." CSPP recommends that the U.S. government begin working with industry to modemize and strengthen the U.S. antidumping law to reflect the realities of the current global marketplace.<br>

	 <li>Modernize the U.S. Export Licensing System: To be effective and to prevent negative effects on U.S. industry, government regulations must keep pace with the rapid rate of technological advancements.  CSPP is concerned that technological change is outpacing U.S. government export control policy.
<br><br>
Export control regulations based on older generations of technology may actually create or subsidize foreign competitors by reducing or eliminating the ability of U.S. companies to compete in viable markets.  For example, the performance threshold for supercomputers as currently defined by U.S. export control regulators is so low that it currently includes systems that perform at less than 1% of the speed of the top of the line machines.  As a result, even single chips used in desk-top workstations are, in some cases, currently defined as supercomputers.  Prohibiting U.S. exports of these chips does not protect a particularly high-level technology, it simply restricts U.S. sales.  In another example, the government is currently seeking to control the export of software with encryption capabilities.  This software is heavily in demand and widely available throughout the world.  Limiting exports of products with these features simply places U.S. companies at a disadvantage by prohibiting U.S. companies from selling their products overseas.  It does not control this technology.<br><br>

CSPP recommends that the U.S. government, working with industry, regularly and systematically revise its export regulation definitions to reflect the most recent technological developments.  Moreover, any controls over the export of computer technology should be multilateral, not unilateral, in nature.<br><br>
</ul>
<hr>

<p align=middle><b><a name="appendices">APPENDICES</a></b></p>
<ul>
