<html>
<head><title>Increasing Industry Involvement</title>
<h2 align=center>
PERSPECTIVES ON U.S. TECHNOLOGY POLICY, PART II:<br>
INCREASING INDUSTRY INVOLVEMENT<br>

February 26, 1991</h2>
<hr>

<p><b>EXECUTIVE SUMMARY</b></p>

<p>The following paper is designed as an update on the CSPP technology policy effort.  Since issuing our initial technology assessment in July, 1990, we have continued to analyze, study and evaluate the challenges confronting our industry. </p>
 
<p>We have concluded that the cooperative R&D investments by the private sector and governments worldwide demand a new level of cooperation between industry and government in the United States. </p>
 
<p>CSPP has established CEO-level working groups to develop specific plans that will improve the economic return on the national R&D investment by:</p>
<ul>
1. Improving federal R&D budget review mechanisms through industry input;<br><br>

2. Implementing the High Performance Computing and Communications Initiative; and<br><br>

3. Increasing the interaction between industry and the federal laboratories.
</ul>
<p>We urge other industries that depend on research and technology advancements to conduct their own internal technology assessments.  Further, we encourage them to work to improve their own competitive positions by increasing their involvement in federal R&D priority-setting. </p>
 
<p>At the same time, the Administration and Congress should begin working with a wide range of industries, both individually and through cross industry efforts such as the Council on Competitiveness' National Technology Priorities Project, to increase the focus of government-funded R&D on critical pre-competitive, generic technologies. </p>
 <hr>
<p align=center><b>BACKGROUND</b> </p>
 
<p><i>The Computer Systems Industry </i></p>
 
<p>Computer systems technologies and products increase productivity in a variety of sectors.  In fact, it is difficult to think of significant technical advances over the past two decades that have not relied on computer systems.  The computer systems industry is, clearly, a building block for other high technology industries. </p>
 
<p>Computer systems products are necessary and critical components of virtually all modern manufacturing and service industries, from communications systems and business equipment to medical and scientific instrumentation and consumer electronics.  In addition, development and operation of most of the sophisticated weapons systems in the U.S. arsenal would be impossible without computer systems and electronic components. </p>
 
<p><i>The Initial CSPP Technology Assessment </i></p>
 
<p>The Computer Systems Policy Project (CSPP) began its technology policy work over a year ago with a detailed, internal assessment.  For the first time, the industry's chief technologists worked together to examine how the industry could best define and address the technology issues and public policy areas that affect our success.  We began by answering three crucial questions: what are the technologies that are critical to the competitiveness of the U.S. computer systems industry?; what is the relative U.S. position in these technologies compared to our foreign competitors?; and what is the future prognosis for these technologies in the U.S.? </p>
 
<p>The result of our assessment was mixed.  In our report entitled <i>Perspectives: Success Factors in Critical Technologies</i>, which was released in July 1990, we identified 16 technologies critical to the success of the computer industry, and concluded that the U.S. still leads the world in half (mostly software-related technologies).  We also concluded, however, that the U.S. lags the rest of the world in the other half (mostly capital-intensive technologies). </p>
 
<p>Our chief technologists then projected the U.S. position in these technologies five years into the future, and concluded that the performance of U.S. industry in all sixteen technologies will erode without positive action.  As a result, we took our analysis one step further and identified 15 factors upon which success in these technologies depends - the levers which could, if improved, reverse the trend toward erosion of our competitive strength. </p>
 
<p>For each technology, we identified which of the 15 factors could help improve performance in that technology.  This correlation between success factors and critical technologies indicated three of the success factors -- skilled personnel, the general business environment, and research and development -- cut across a majority of the technologies and, if improved, could significantly increase the U.S. competitive position in the broadest possible range of the critical technologies. </p>
 
<p><i>Developing the CSPP Agenda </i></p>
 
<p>In recent years, private industry has addressed skilled personnel, business environment and R&D policy issues.  Of the three, its efforts in the area of R&D policy have been somewhat less focused.  Therefore, CSPP has concentrated its initial technology policy strategy on R&D policy -- specifically, on improving the U.S. research and development investment. </p>
 
<p>Nevertheless, skilled personnel and business environment issues are critical to the success of the computer industry and most other technology industries.  In fact, without a well-educated work force and a business environment conducive to investment, industries like ours cannot undertake the research and development efforts needed to make the technological advancements that will prevent further erosion of our technology base, let alone improve our position. </p>
 
<p>Acknowledging this, CSPP member companies are devoting substantial attention and resources to increasing the pool of skilled personnel and improving the U.S. economic climate, both independently and through our industry trade associations.  We wholeheartedly support and actively join the efforts of other associations in advocating policy changes that would improve these areas.  Statements of principles in support of ongoing activities which CSPP endorses appear in Appendices 1 and 2. </p>
 
<p>It is important to note that fully addressing the technological challenges facing the computer systems and other industries will require policy improvements in more areas than R&D, human resources and the business environment.  In fact, these are only a few of the pieces of a much bigger puzzle.  Accordingly, CSPP members have begun, and will continue, to take independent steps within our individual companies to improve our competitive position by improving quality and increasing efficiency.  In addition, using our critical technology assessment as a guide, CSPP member companies have undertaken independent, internal efforts to improve U.S. performance in each of the sixteen technologies, independent of government-industry activities.  Further, CSPP will continue to explore ways in which the industry can work together to strengthen its position in critical technologies.</p>
<hr>

<p align=center> <b>INCREASED INDUSTRY GOVERNMENT COOPERATION: </b><br>
A STRATEGY TO IMPROVE THE EFFECTIVENESS OF
THE FEDERAL R&D INVESTMENT</p>

<p>As we began the search for solutions to the technological challenges confronting our industry, we reviewed the role of government investment in R&D in the U.S. and other countries.  Our assessment of global R&D spending patterns, presented in Part I of this report, <i>The Federal R&D Investment</i>, provided a useful starting point for developing our policy recommendations. </p>
 
<p>It was clear from our analysis that while the total amount of federal R&D spending is substantial, its bias toward defense development leaves limited funds and focus available for pre-competitive, generic technology R&D.  This bias is particularly noteworthy when compared with the R&D spending of the Japanese and European Community governments.  In order to improve the nation's ability to compete in the technologies essential to its future economic and military security, we believe the focus of U.S. federal R&D must address these global realities.  CSPP believes the first step toward this objective is to expand the role of the private sector in setting priorities for government R&D investment. </p>
 
<p><i>A Good Beginning </i></p>
 
<p>Last fall, the Administration issued a report on U.S. Technology Policy which was a first and welcome step in the right direction.  The report, signaling an evolution in position, acknowledges a role for the government in technology policy, stating that the Administration is prepared to work with industry on critical, pre-competitive, generic technologies.  More recently, President Bush called for increased investments in research and development in high technology in his State of the Union Address.  The Administration's Fiscal Year 1992 budget proposal reflects this shift in priorities by increasing spending on applied R&D by $1.5 billion, or ten percent, including funds for a high performance computing and communications network, the Department of Commerce's Advanced Technology Program, new initiatives in advanced materials R&D and continued support for SEMATECH. </p>
 
<p>CSPP is ready and willing to work with the federal government to maximize the return on the nation's investment in these and other technology research efforts.  Specifically, CSPP recommends that the government and the computer systems industry take the following steps together to improve the effectiveness of the nation's R&D investment:</p>
<ul>
1. Improve the mechanisms for reviewing federal R&D spending, including increased industry input in setting federal R&D priorities;<br><br>

2. Implement the High Performance Computing and Communications Initiative, including a national network capable of bringing the benefits of computing to every household and school in the nation; and<br><br>

3. Increase the interaction between industry and the federal laboratories, including private sector advice on laboratory R&D priorities, aimed at improving the economic return on the national R&D investment.
</ul>
<i>A Cooperative Strategy for Success</i>

<p>By working together, U.S. industry and government can improve the effectiveness of the federal R&D investment by re-focusing spending on those pre-competitive, generic technologies with known commercial relevance.  To increase industry input, CSPP specifically recommends a cooperative government-industry strategy to:</p>
<ul>
<b>Improve R&D Budget Review Mechanisms Through Industry Input </b>-- The Administration and Congress must develop a better sense of how its $76 billion investment in R&D is being spent.  As a starting point, CSPP urges the Administration and Congress to develop a comprehensive summary of the federal R&D budget, including detailed summaries -- budget crosscuts -- of agency efforts on initiatives related to developing generic technologies.  This would provide a means by which the private sector and the government could review and adjust spending priorities to meet the nation's changing research needs.<br><br>

CSPP is pleased that the Office of Management and Budget (OMB) is providing budget summaries that cut across agencies in several key areas, including high performance computing, and is considering developing similar information for other research areas, including materials research.  CSPP recommends that crosscuts be done for other important technology areas as well, including electronics and information technologies.<br><br>

By including industry perspectives, the effectiveness and usefulness of these budget summaries can be improved.  We urge the Administration and Congress to ensure that industry is a partner not only as the crosscuts are developed, but also as they are evaluated.  Once crosscuts are available, strategies can be developed, with industry participation, to bolster investment in certain areas or to shift priorities where necessary within the parameters of current spending levels.  This should be an on process, not a one-time event.<br><br>

To facilitate this, CSPP has established a working group, including CSPP CEOs, company technologists and policy experts, willing to work with Administration representatives to develop and refine the materials summary.<br><br>

Further, we have established a CEO-level working group to investigate the legal and regulatory barriers that may impede or inhibit the private sector participation needed to make the federal R&D priority-setting process more effective.  We will report the results of our analysis, including recommendations for any necessary changes, later this year.<br><br>

<b>2. Implement the High Performance Computing and Communications Initiative </b>- CSPP recommends fully funding the Administration's High Performance Computing and
Communications (HPCC) Initiative, including implementing, in conjunction with academia and the private sector, a National Research and Education Network.  This effort is critical to provide the research infrastructure required to maintain our nation's leadership in basic research, and to expand our capability to perform the applied research which moves basic science closer to commercial use.  In addition, the HPCC will be instrumental in helping achieve the national education and work force training goals established for the 21st century.<br><br>

CSPP will support this effort through a long-term project to identify possible future applications of a network that will enhance the quality of life and economic competitiveness of the nation.  Computer and networking technology can help solve problems and realize opportunities in American homes, factories, universities, workplaces and classrooms.  We have established a CEO working group to identify innovative network applications, the technological advances needed to accomplish them, and the best ways to describe the applications' benefits to the public.<br><br>

Further, CSPP has committed to work with the Administration to review the HPCC budget crosscut and examine the relevance to the computer industry of the research being conducted as part of this initiative.  Later this year, CSPP will provide recommendations to improve federal spending under the initiative.<br><br>

<b>3. Increase Industry Laboratory Interaction </b>- The Federal government spends billions each year on R&D in federal labs, three-fifths of which goes to defense programs.  Much of that R&D, properly focused, could be substantially more useful to the computer industry than ft is today.  CSPP believes that the nation's return on the federal lab investment can be enhanced by increasing private sector input into lab activities and shifting some labs' research priorities to include generic technologies that have commercial potential.<br><br>

Implementing these shifts will require a long-term joint effort by the government and industry.  CSPP recommends that OMB begin working with the private sector to develop ways to include industry input in laboratory R&D priority-setting and in ongoing laboratory research activities.<br><br>

CSPP has established a CEO-level working group to recommend ways to improve the federal laboratories' contributions to the national R&D effort, including developing funding mechanisms for joint industry-lab projects of interest to the private sector; identifying potential and current laboratory research projects and research areas that could benefit the computer industry; and identifying research areas that lend themselves to budget crosscut analysis.  The results of that work, along with recommendations, will be issued later this year.</ul>
<hr>
<p align=center><b>CONCLUSION</b></p>

<p>Improving U.S. technology policy is a long-term process that cannot be addressed by any one organization or any single set of recommendations.  It is, nonetheless, an essential process given the cooperative R&D investments by the private sector and governments worldwide. </p>
 
<p>Improving U.S. technology policy requires a long-term commitment and a series of changes by industry and government over time.  Whether as independent CEOs or as an industry, the members of the Computer Systems Policy Project are committed and involved.  We hope our perspectives and those of other high technology industries will help to strengthen U.S. technological leadership now and in the future.</p>
<hr>

<p><b>APPENDIX 1
</b></p>
<hr>
<p align=center><b>CSPP STATEMENT OF PRINCIPLES:<br>
SKILLED PERSONNEL</b></p>

<p>The computer industry depends on technically proficient workers to design and develop new products, to manufacture quality products, and to design, install and use applications for computer technologies.  Without an adequate supply of scientists, engineers, and mathematicians, the computer industry, its suppliers, and its users cannot develop or implement the technological advances we need to ensure our economic and military security. </p>
 
<p>Recent studies confirm that the United States is not producing enough technically proficient workers to meet the future needs of U.S. industry, including the computer industry.  In "Workforce 2000," the Hudson Institute projects a shortfall of 400,000 B.S. graduates by the year 2000.  The Bureau of Labor Statistics estimates that there will be 1.2 million new positions in programming available by the year 2000, but only 1.7% of college freshmen are currently majoring in technical subjects.  The number of Americans receiving engineering degrees has been dropping since 1986, while the number of engineering jobs is growing 25% per year. </p>
 
<p>While a skilled workforce is critical to the success of the computer industry, the challenges facing the U.S. educational system are far greater than any single organization can combat alone.  Rather than proposing new education programs to address the projected shortfall, CSPP will concentrate its resources in support of ongoing efforts. </p>
 
<p>First and foremost, CSPP supports the six national education goals adopted by the President and the fifty state governors in February, 1990, and private sector efforts to achieve those goals, such as the Business Roundtable and the National Center on Education and the Economy. </p>
 
<p>CSPP, as a group and through its member companies, will build upon existing efforts and programs to complement the efforts of other groups in providing the means to meet the President's national education goals by:</p>
<ul>
<li>Continuing and expanding individual CSPP member companies' training and education efforts;

<li>Participating in and establishing innovative programs to attract young people to careers in math, science and engineering;

<li>Supporting increases in the numbers of federally-funded predoctoral science and engineering fellowships and traineeships; and

<li>Issuing interim reports as appropriate to inform the government and other interested parties of the needs for skilled personnel, as well as potential means for meeting those needs.
</ul>
<hr>
<p><b>APPENDIX 2</b></p>
<hr>
<p align=center><b>CSPP STATEMENT OF PRINCIPLES:<br>
THE BUSINESS ENVIRONMENT</b></p>

<p>The cost and patience of capital and the structure of the U.S. business environment play an important role in determining the extent to which the U.S. computer industry can make the investments it needs to maintain its long-term viability.  Developing new technologies, and bringing new products that use them to the market, requires high levels of funding and long-term management time horizons.  These conditions are more readily justified both when the comparative cost of capital is low enough to help offset the long payback periods, and when investors are willing to endure the short-term variations in earnings that may occur while long-term R&D efforts mature. </p>
 
<p>The twin goals of cheaper and more patient capital will be achieved in an economic environment that is both pro-saving and pro-investment.  Pro-saving policies are those that expand the pool of funds available for investments; pro-investment policies -properly structured -- help to direct those funds toward longer-term investments in R&D and manufacturing. </p>
 
<p>In addition, U.S. companies are often unable to take advantage of economies of scale, interrelated technologies, flexible manufacturing options, product integration, and other benefits of  joint manufacturing to which their vertically integrated competitors have access.  Pooling plant and capital enables companies to share risks in expensive projects. </p>
 
<p>CSPP supports federal economic policies that will increase the national saving rate, reduce the tax-affected cost of capital and permit sharing manufacturing risks.  Specifically, CSPP supports: </p>
 
<p>Sound fiscal management by the U.S. government to reduce the budget deficit, which would reduce the cost of capital for all American companies and improve the climate for investment, regardless of country to country differences in capital costs:</p>
<ul>
<li>Reducing the budget deficit through spending cuts;

<li>Consumption taxes, if new taxes are necessary, to encourage saving and investment;

<li>Increasing the patience of capital through indexing the capital gains rate to encourage longer holding periods for investments;

<li>Reducing the cost of performing complex R&D, by making permanent the R&D tax credit, permanently revising the allocation rules for attributing domestic R&D expenditures to foreign income, and permitting total R&D equipment costs to be expensed in the year of purchase; and

<li>Extending the 1984 National Cooperative Research Act to include joint manufacturing.
</ul>
<hr>
