<head><title>The Federal R&D Investment</title>
<h2 align=center>
PERSPECTIVES ON U.S.  TECHNOLOGY POLICY, PART 1:<br>
THE FEDERAL R&D INVESTMENT<br>

February 26, 1991
</h2>
<hr>
<p><b>INTRODUCTION</b></p>

Since its creation in 1989, the CEOs, chief technologists and policy experts of CSPP's member companies have devoted significant time to studying and evaluating the technology challenges that face the computer systems industry.  With the help of Bain & Company, this effort included preparation of the following charts and graphs which describe current R&D investment trends and practices in the United States and other countries.  One specific goal in compiling this information was to identify how the U.S. federal R&D investment affects technologies critical to the computer systems industry and to compare that with how R&D investments in other countries affect computer related technologies.

We found that the U.S. federal investment in R&D is significant but that the return on this investment could be enhanced by refocusing the federal government's research priorities to include pre-competitive, generic technologies with commercial relevance.  The U.S. government allocates a greater percentage of its R&D investment to defense research than do the governments of our competitors.

Further, we found that the federal government's research priorities do not match the priorities of the private sector at a time when the private sector now drives technology advances in this country.  Consider, for example, that while the computer industry conducts more R&D than any other industrial sector (21% of the total U.S. private sector investment), the government allocates only a small fraction (2% of the total federal R&D investment) of its investment to computer-related technologies.

This information is particularly significant when compared to the R&D funding practices of our international competitors.  Computer-related technologies are a focus, through direct funding or other means, of the governments of technologically competitive nations.

Based on this data, we have outlined an initial set of technology policy recommendations in <i>Perspectives on U.S. Technology Policy, Part II: Increasing industry Involvement</i>.  In short, CSPP's recommendations provide a strategy for better focusing the federal R&D investment in pre-competitive, generic technologies that will help industry meet international competitive challenges by increasing industry involvement in federal R&D priority setting.  By working together, industry and government can improve the nation's return on the total R&D investment and help meet the international challenge to this country's technological strength.
<ul>
<li><a href="1.html">Graph 1</a> - Total R&D Spending - United States
<li><a href="2.html">Graph 2</a>  - Total R&D Spending - Japan & EC
<li><a href="3.html">Graph 3</a>  - U.S. Federal Government R&D Funding Trend (Defense Versus Non-Defense)
<li><a href="4.html">Graph 4</a>  - Government - Industry R&D Mix (1989)
<li><a href="5.html">Graph 5</a>  - Total Government R&D Spending (1979-1989)
<li><a href="6.html">Graph 6</a>  - Non-Defense Government R&D Spending (1979-1989)
<li><a href="7.html">Graph 7</a>  - U.S. Corporate R&D By Industry (1989)
<li><a href="8.html">Graph 8</a>  - U.S. Corporate R&D By Industry - Percent of Sales (1989)
<li><a href="9.html">Graph 9</a>  - Share of R&D Spending By U.S. Industry Sector (Preliminary Estimate: 1989)
<li><a href="10.html">Graph 10</a>  - Computer Related R&D By Government
<li><a href="11.html">Graph 11</a>  - Computer Equipment Market Share*
<li><a href="12.html">Graph 12</a>  - U.S. computer systems Trade Balance
</ul>
</html>
