<hr>

<p align=center><b><a name="intro">INTRODUCTION</a></b></p>

<p>The complex process of designing and building today's information processing systems is dependent on two very intricate sets of relationships. </p>
 
<p>The first set of relationships exists among and within a diverse group of industries.  These include: computer systems, software, tool and test equipment, semiconductor manufacturing and peripherals and components. </p>
 
<p>The second is an intricate set of interrelationships among a number of complex technologies. </p>
 
<p>Weakness in one or more industries or technologies can materially affect the strength of the computer systems industry - and of many other industries that today are increasingly dependent on computers and computer-related technologies. </p>
 
<p>The purpose of this study is twofold:</p>
<ul>
	<li>To identify the critical "success factors" which profoundly affect the ability of the U.S. computer systems industry to compete in the development of innovative technologies well into the 21st century; and

	<li>To examine and report on the strength of the technologies that the U.S. computer systems industry has identified as critical to its health.
</ul>

<p>The CEOs initiated this ground-breaking report on technology public policy recognizing that the industry itself must take action to meet many of the challenges posed in the report.  By the end of 1990, CSPP expects to complete an analysis of public policies that will have a major impact on the critical success factors and the critical technologies.  At that time, CSPP will offer specific recommendations on the role of industry and government to the Administration and Congress. </p>
 
<p>The Computer Systems Policy Project, which was organized in 1989, is an affiliation of eleven CEOs from the computer systems industry.  CSPP's long-term objective is to inform policy makers of the critical concerns facing the computer systems industry and to provide ongoing information and data to help illuminate public policy issues over the next few years.</p>
<hr>
<p align=center><b><a name="hist">HISTORICAL PERSPECTIVE</a></b></p>

<p>For 30 years the United States has led the world computer systems industry in output, investment, employment, R&D, innovation and new product development.  The industry is a vital component of America's economy, directly employing more than half a million people.  Virtually every other sector of the U.S. economy, including defense, is dependent on its products.  In 1989, the computer industry:</p>
<ul>
	<li>Shipped $164 billion in hardware, software and services;
	<li>Employed 587,000 workers in the U.S. and a similar number abroad in the production of hardware, software and in the provision of services; and
	<li>Exported $22.4 billion in computer equipment, six percent of total U.S.
exports,
</ul>
<p>Even these statistics understate how deeply American computers have penetrated the world economy.  Few aspects of business or industry remain untouched by the "computer revolution." Computer systems are far more than productivity engines. They are automating, expanding and reshaping virtually every aspect of business and altering the fundamental nature of work. </p>
 
<p>Although U.S. companies continue to dominate the world computer equipment and software markets, they find themselves in an intensely competitive environment.  While American companies' share of world computer system sales fell from 81% to 61% between 1983 and 1989, Japan's s share rose from 8% to 22% and Europe's share grew from 10% to 15%. </p>
 
<p>U.S. computer systems manufacturers have maintained worldwide market leadership in vital industry sectors, including networking, software and supercomputers, to a considerable degree because of their ability to develop innovative technologies.  Continued leadership in emerging technologies is especially important today because these technologies will provide the basis for the world's manufacturing and service industries well into the next century.  And foreign competitors are vigorously pursuing extensive R&D efforts in every key technology. </p>
 
<p>The overall vigor of the industry also depends on factors other than technology.  These include ease of use, marketing strength, quality of field support and the installed customer base.  In all of these, the U.S. continues to excel.</p>
<hr>
<p align=center><b><a name="cspp1">CSPP'S TECHNOLOGY ASSESSMENT</a></b></p>

<p>CSPP has produced a carefully researched report on what the best technology minds in the industry - its chief technologists - believe to be essential to the future.  The technologists have identified "levers" (or catalysts) which will enhance U.S. performance in many technologies. </p>
 
<p>These technologists have identified fifteen "critical success factors" that profoundly affect the U.S. computer industry's ability to compete successfully in key technologies.  In addition, the technologists identified 16 "critical technologies" upon which America's computer industry will depend into the next century. </p>
 
<p>The technologists reported that the United States is maintaining its competitive lead in the technologies that stress creativity and human factors and are less capital intensive.  These include software engineering, applications technologies and computer (processor) architectures. </p>
 
<p>The technologists also concluded that the U.S. lags in capital-intensive technologies such as ultra-large-scale integration (ULSI) fabrication equipment and facilities, microelectronics and manufacturing.  However, they were optimistic that the U.S. has the ability to significantly improve its current performance in the key technologies. </p>
 
<p>The technologists found a very strong correlation between certain technologies and certain of the success factors.  Critical success factors that cut across a number of important technologies include capital investment, state-of-art manufacturing, quality, applied research and development, basic research and skilled personnel. </p>
 
<p>By the end of the year, CSPP expects to propose to the Administration and the Congress a public policy agenda to address the success factors have the greatest impact on the technologies critical to the U.S. computer systems industry. </p>
 
<p>On a preliminary basis, however, CSPP's technologists reported a clear correlation between certain public policies and a number of key success factors.  High-impact public policy sectors include: cost of capital and tax strategies; education; federal research, development and manufacturing policies and support. </p>
 
<p>CSPP will work with other business and industry groups to develop a broad consensus that cuts across technology and industry lines.  For example, the Council on Competitiveness will apply a methodology similar to CSPP's in its current examination of the competitive viability of nine key U.S. industries, including computers.</p>
<hr>
<p align=center><b><a name="cspp2">CSPP'S TEAM OF CHIEF TECHNOLOGISTS</a></b></p>

<p>Massive investments in the multi-billion dollar range are made in new technology every year by the eleven U.S. computer manufacturers whose CEOs make up CSPP.  Each enterprise's technology investment decision relies extensively on the judgment of its chief technologist. Collectively, the technologists comprise America's best thinking regarding the direction of technology and its effect on the computer industry.  These technologist include: </p>
 
<p>Larry Tesler, Vice President Advanced Products, Apple; Christopher J. Gintz, Director of Technology, Planning and Development, Compaq; Don Powers, Vice President and General Manager, Control Data; Jim Sundet, Chief Logic Design Engineer, Cray Research; Dr. Samuel H. Fuller, Vice President, Corporate Research, Digital; Dr. Frank Carrubba, Director of Hewlett-Packard Laboratories, Hewlett-Packard; Dr. John A. Armstrong, Vice President for Science and Technology, IBM; Lowell Deckard, Assistant Vice President of Technology, NCR; William Joy, Vice President, Research and Development, Sun Microsystems; Steve Wierenga, Director, VLSI Technology, Tandem; and John Wise, Vice President & Chief Technical Officer, Unisys.</p>
<hr>
<p align=center><b><a name="cspp3">CSPP'S METHODOLOGY</a></b></p>

<p>The chief technologists met in Palo Alto, California and Houston, Texas.  At these meetings the technologists identified the most relevant "success factors" which will determine how effectively the U.S. can compete in technologies that are essential to the development and production of future generations of competitive computer systems.  From a wide range of technologies, the technologists then isolated those which are most critical to the future competitiveness of the industry. </p>
 
<p>The technologists utilized a procedure known as Quality Function Deployment (QFD) to correlate the relationships between technologies and critical success factors.  They also evaluated the importance of each technology and summarized their evaluations in terms of a numerical value on a pre-determined, ordinal scale. </p>
 
<p>The resulting data were tallied and all technologies above a predetermined value were defined as critical to the industry's competitiveness.  Additional analysis further isolated 8 of the 16 that were re-examined to validate the overall numerical results. </p>
 
<p>As the charts in this report show, the chief technologists assessed the U.S. computer industry's present competitive position versus the rest of the world.  Then, for each technology, they also agreed on where the U.S. industry is headed against its offshore competition under 1) current course and speed and 2) under optimal circumstances.  The technologists were in consensus that in every technology, the U.S. continues to have the ability to significantly improve its current competitive position. </p>
 
<p>CSPP's chief executive officers met in June, 1990 and unanimously endorsed the findings of the chief technologists.  The findings presently are being examined by an independent group of highly-respected experts in the technology industry.</p>
<hr>
<p align=center><b><a name="crit1">CRITICAL SUCCESS FACTORS: DEFINITIONS</a></b></p>

<p>The critical success factors were grouped in three categories: business environment research and development; and people and culture.  Seven of the factors were identified as especially important.  These appear in boldface at the beginning of each category:</p>

<p><i>Business Environment</i>:</p>
<ul>
	<li><b>Capital Investment</b>: The availability of long-term capital resources necessary to build and sustain the infrastructure required to research, develop and produce competitive products.

	<li><b>Critical Mass</b>: The large scale and structure required to research, develop and produce competitive products.

	<li><b>Large Market Size</b>: The significant market size required to sell these exceedingly complex products at a profit.

	<li><b>Intellectual Property Protection</b>: The worldwide system of laws that protects proprietary interests in all forms of intellectual property, including inventions, works of authorship, trademarks and trade secrets.

	<li><b>Standardization and Standards</b>: Common specifications that simplify compatibility of products and services.

	<li><b>Reduced Risk for Large Emerging Markets</b>: Availability of early, sheltered markets - such as government procurements -- in which emerging technologies can be tested before they are demonstrably viable in the competitive marketplace.  This may be required because of immaturity of the technology or a current lack of cost effectiveness.  Establishment of these markets sometimes requires participation by multiple companies and government in demonstration projects.
</ul>
<p><i>Research Development and Manufacturing</i>:</p>
<ul>
	<li><b>State-of-the-art Manufacturing</b>: Manufacturing facilities that include the most advanced tools and techniques, including CAD, CIM, flexible manufacturing and robotics.

	<li><b>Applied Research and Development</b>: Research and development focused toward
specific commercial product areas, systems and applications.

	<li><b>Basic Research</b>: Exploration of fundamental scientific phenomena not directly related to direct product development.
</ul>
<p><i>People and Culture</i>:</p>
<ul>
<li><b>Quality</b>: Excellence that pervades every aspect of the business process, including research, development, manufacturing, sales, administration, delivery, installation and service.  This results in world-class competitive products.

	<li><b>Exceptional People/Skilled Personnel</b>: Availability of high-quality, well-trained personnel at all levels.

	<li><b>Research, Development and Manufacturing Linkages</b>: Concurrent involvement in the product development process by research, development and manufacturing specialists leading to timely and cost-effective commercialization and incremental product improvement.

	<li><b>Cooperation by Business, Academia and Government</b>: Joint activities that focus, draw upon and combine the uniquely individual resources and strengths of each sector.

	<li><b>Private Sector Cooperation</b>: Joint activities within industry that enable sharing of resources and risk.

	<li><b>Cultural Characteristics</b>: A wide range of factors contributing to sub-optimal performance of American industry, such as close-in investment horizons, quarter-to-quarter financial perspectives, disdain of manufacturing and the declining quality of education.
</ul>

<a name="grap"><a href="1.gif">Critical Success Factors (Graphic)</a></a>
<hr>
<p align=center><b><a name="crit2">CRITICAL TECHNOLOGIES</a></b></p>

<p>A critical technology is examined on each of the following 16 pages.  For each technology
the report provides the following:</p>
<ul>
	<li>A definition of the technology;
	<li>A list of the critical success factors that impact the technology; and
	<li>The competitive position of the U.S. computer systems industry:
<ul>
		<li>Versus foreign competitors today in implementing the 16 critical technologies: ahead; lead rapidly diminishing; behind; losing;

			<li>In five years measured against the same competitors if the U.S. industry and its competitors both continue at current course and speed; and

			<li>In five years under optimum conditions.  This will require maximum possible development of the technologies by the U.S. and assumes the critical success factors and public policies are optimized.
</ul><br>
The critical technologies that CSPP has identified are:<br><br>
<ul>
<li>Database Systems
<li>Processor Architecture
<li>Networks & Communications
<li>Human Interface
<li>Visualization
<li>Operating Systems
<li>Software Engineering
<li>Application Technology
<li>Displays
<li>Hard Copy Technology
<li>Storage
<li>Manufacturing Technology
<li>Integrated Circuit Fabrication Equipment
<li>Microelectronics
<li>Optoelectronics
<li>Electronic Packaging
</ul>
</ul>
<hr>
<p align=center><b><a name="data">DATABASE SYSTEMS</a></b></p>

<p>DEFINITION: Database technology is essential to computer-based information management.  Key elements of database technology include data representation, storage, retrieval and update, semantic modeling and interpretation and the maintenance of integrity.</p>

<p align=center>HIGH-IMPACT CRITICAL SUCCESS FACTORS:</p>
<ul>    
<li>People: Skilled Personnel
</ul>
<p align=center>MEDIUM-IMPACT CRITICAL SUCCESS FACTORS:</p>
<ul>
<li>Quality
<li>Applied Research and Development
<li>Collaboration with Academia, Government and Business
<li>Basic Research
<li>Standardization and Standards .
<li>Intellectual Property Protection
</ul>
