<p align=center><b><a name=""proc>PROCESSOR ARCHITECTURE</a></b></p>

<p>DEFINITION: The instruction set portion of the computer processor describes the bit-level definition of the data and the instructions the machine can process.  The instruction set defines the machine-executable portions of the interface to which software is assembled, compiled and linked.  Instruction sets can be organized into different types of architectures such as Complex Instruction Computer Systems (CISC), Reduced Instruction Set Computing (RISC), superscalar, wide-word, multi-processor and massively parallel.</p>

<p align=center>HIGH-IMPACT CRITICAL SUCCESS  FACTORS:</p>
<ul>
	<li>Applied Research and Development
	<li>Basic Research
     <li>People: Skilled Personnel
</ul>

<p align=center>MEDIUM-IMPACT CRITICAL SUCCESS FACTORS:</p>
<ul>
	<li>Capital Investment
	<li>Critical Mass
	<li>Large Market Size
	<li>Quality
	<li>Collaboration with Academia, Government and Business
    <li>Intellectual Property Protection
</ul>
<p align=center>POSITION OF U.S. COMPUTER INDUSTRY VS.  WORLD:<br>

PROCESSOR ARCHITECTURE</p>
