<hr><hr>
<p align=center><b><a name="summ">SUMMARY</a></b></p>

<p>CSPP has completed the first phase of its ground-breaking report on U.S. technology.  It has identified 15 critical "success factors" that will determine whether the U.S. computer industry can retain or regain a lead in 16 "critical technologies" essential to the future success of the industry. </p>
 
<p>The U.S. currently leads the world in highly creative technologies such as software engineering, applications technologies and computer architectures.  It is lagging other countries in capital-intensive technologies such as ultra-large-scale fabrication equipment and facilities, microelectronics and manufacturing. </p>
 
<p>Although the overall competitiveness of the U.S. computer industry depends on many factors, the key success factors are especially relevant to the U.S. leadership in the critical technologies.  These factors include:</p>
<ul>
<b>Business environment</b>: Capital investment; critical mass; large market size;
and intellectual property protection;<br><br>

<b>Research, development and Manufacturing</b>: State-of-the-art manufacturing; applied research and development; basic research; and linkages among research, development and manufacturing;<br><br>

<b>People and Culture</b>: Skilled personnel; quality; and cooperation among business, academia and government.<br><br>
</ul>
<p>The next phase of CSPP's technology project is to identify public policies that will most directly strengthen the "success factors," thus the critical technologies, into the 21st century.  CSPP expects to complete this phase of the project by the end of 1990.  At that time it plans to propose its public policy agenda to the Administration and Congress,

</p>
