</ul>
<hr>
<p><b><i>Policy Proposals on Trade:<br>
Market Access and Antidumping Law Reform</i></b></p>

<p><i><a name="trade">TRADE POLICY OVERVIEW</a></i></p>

<p>The Computer Systems Policy Project (CSPP) has identified two interrelated public policy areas as top priorities for our focus: trade and technology.  This paper is the first in a series of CSPP public policy proposals regarding trade and technology. </p>
 
<p>Computer systems producers and other high-technology companies are highly integrated into the global trading system.  Perhaps no other sector of the U.S. economy contributes so much to, and depends so heavily on, America's ability to compete internationally.  This sector therefore has a substantial stake in the growth and openness of world markets and in the effectiveness and fairness of international rules of trade. </p>
 
<p>These objectives can be best achieved by the negotiation of comprehensive and substantive agreements in the Uruguay Round of Multilateral Trade Negotiations.  Such agreements must be promptly and effectively implemented by a strengthened GATT and by the United States and other GATT members.  CSPP also supports progress in a wide range of other international initiatives: reform of the export control system, resolution of international monetary and debt problems, the evolution of the European Community's Single Market, expanded trade and investment with Eastern Europe and the Soviet Union, and tax policies that promote international competitiveness. </p>
 
<p>CSPP has selected market access and antidumping law reform as two trade policy issues that require particular attention now.  This paper addresses each of these issues in turn. </p>
 <hr>
<p>MARKET ACCESS </p>
 
<p>Computer systems producers recognize that we may need, on occasion, bilateral government-negotiated market-access agreements.  Such agreements may be necessary to supplement our own competitive efforts and the more open markets that result from an effective multilateral system.  Because of the increased use of Section 301 and Super 301, CSPP has a special interest to ensure the development and implementation of an approach to market access that is effective and properly balanced. </p>
 
<p>CSPP proposes a dynamic market-access approach that uses specific criteria and contextual factors to define goals and that adjusts those goals as conditions change.  Our four-step process (i) identifies those markets that require bilateral market-opening initiatives, (ii) establishes, through bilateral negotiations, specific actions to be taken to achieve an open market by a date certain, (iii) periodically applies measures of progress, and (iv) uses government imposed sanctions carefully when necessary.  We oppose a government guarantee of market share.  We advocate, instead, steady and measurable progress toward open markets. </p>
 
<p>ANTIDUMPING LAW REFORM </p>
 
<p>Computer systems producers also have a special interest in antidumping law reform.  Antidumping laws are being applied increasingly here and abroad to high-technology products.  This increased application has highlighted a number of problem areas for computer systems producers and other high-technology companies.  These and other issues related to the use of antidumping laws are receiving significant attention in the Uruguay Round. </p>
 
<p>The prime objective of antidumping law reform must be the adaptation of the laws to the global trade realities of the 1990s.  Such adaptation means, on the one hand, enhancing the capacity of the laws to deter multiple offenses and circumvention and, on the other hand, sharpening the focus of the laws on pricing practices that are both unfair and injurious.  The four parts of CSPP's approach are: (i) realistic cost calculations to determine whether there is unfair pricing, (ii) deterrence of injuriously unfair pricing, (iii) measures to combat circumvention of antidumping relief, and (iv) recognition of marketplace realities.  CSPP believes that these antidumping law reforms, which build on the reforms enacted in 1988, would enhance the international competitiveness of American systems producers and other high-technology industries.</p>
<hr>
<a name="market2"><p align=center>CSPP Policy Proposal Summary<br>
MARKET ACCESS</p></a>

<p>Market Access for High-Technology Industries Must be a Prime U.S. Trade Policy Objective. </p>
 
<p>A More Effective Multilateral System is the Most Important Instrument for Achieving Open Markets. </p>
 
<p>The Time has Come for a Fresh, More Effective Bilateral Approach to Complement Multilateral Market-Access Efforts. </p>
 
<p>The New Approach Must Emphasize Results, Not Promises. </p>
 
<p>Market Access Must Mean Greater Opportunities for Competitive Products, Not Managed Trade. </p>
 
<p>A Dynamic Four-Step Process, Using Specified Criteria and Contextual Factors, Is Critical:</p>
<ul>
<li>Identify Markets in which Multilateral Efforts Have Failed to Provide Real Opportunities for Competitive Products.

<li>Establish, through Bilateral Agreement, Specific Actions to Achieve Open Market by Specific Date.

<li>Measure Progress toward Open Market by Periodically Reassessing, Under the Then Current Circumstances, the Opportunities for Competitive Products in the Market.

<li>To Spur Progress, Use Government Imposed Sanctions that are Carefully Designed to Achieve Maximum Effect in Closed Market and Minimum Damage to U.S. Industries.
</ul>
<hr>
<a name="market3"><p align=center>CSPP Policy Proposal<br>
MARKET ACCESS</p></a>

<p>Open foreign markets are crucial to the competitiveness of the American high-technology industries: the makers and marketers of computer systems, semiconductors, semiconductor manufacturing and testing equipment, peripherals, and software.  High-technology companies cannot earn the returns needed to sustain capital investment and research and development if they are foreclosed from reaching customers in major markets of the world.  CSPP therefore strongly supports market access as a prime objective of U.S. trade policy. </p>
 
<p><i>The most important step that the United States can take to improve market access worldwide is to strengthen the GATT</i>, for open markets are one of the principal benefits of an effective multilateral system.  Bilateral market-access initiatives are a mechanism to resolve particular bilateral problems.  Such initiatives must be viewed as discretionary supplements, not mandatory alternatives, to multilateral efforts.  When the U.S. Government and the American business community do need to resort to bilateral initiatives, they should fashion an approach to opening markets that complements the GATT.  Within this multilateral context, the time has come for both government and business to take a fresh look at bilateral market-access initiatives. </p>
 
<p><i>Basic to CSPP's approach to bilateral market-access is our emphasis on results</i>.  Results are not "expectations" or commitments or sanctions.  Results are sales made, market shares gained, and revenues received.  The market access approach that we propose is one that can achieve results. </p>
 
<p>We are firm in our emphasis on results, but <i>we are also firm in our opposition to managed trade</i>.  We neither need nor want government guarantees of market share.  What we need and want are opportunities to compete.  CSPP's policy proposal on market access is intended to focus bilateral efforts on making opportunities to compete a reality for America's high-technology industries. </p>
 
<p>CSPP's approach to bilateral market-access initiatives departs sharply from static approaches in which the market-access goal is established at the outset as a fixed numerical target.  CSPP advocates, instead, a dynamic process that refocuses the market-opening initiative as products, technologies, and markets change.  By defining goals in dynamic terms and by continually reassessing the conditions that promote or retard access to a particular market, CSPP's approach can be an effective complement to multilateral efforts. </p>
 
<p>Specifically, <i>CSPP proposes a four-step process that, in turn</i>, (i) identifies markets in which multilateral efforts have failed to provide real opportunities for competitive products, (ii) establishes, through bilateral negotiations, specific actions to be taken in order to achieve an open market by a date certain, (iii) measures progress toward an open market at regular intervals, and (iv) applies government imposed sanctions if necessary to secure results.  Although the goals, actions, measures of progress, and sanctions would differ from one market-access initiative to another, the process would be consistently followed.  This process would apply to all markets that are believed to foreclose competitive opportunities for foreign businesses and that remain closed despite multilateral efforts. </p>
 
<p><i>The first step of the process is to identify markets that require a bilateral market access initiative</i>.  CSPP recommends that the U.S. Government, in consultation with relevant industries and other interested parties, establish specific criteria at the outset to assess whether a given foreign market is closed.  The criteria would be used to measure deviations from an open market and the contextual factors would be used to adjust any such measured deviations according to changing product, technological, or market conditions. </p>
 
<p>Examples of possible criteria are:</p>
<ul>
<li>the difference between the share that U.S. electronics companies have achieved in the public sector market of a given country and their market share in that country's commercial sector;

	<li>the difference between the market share that U.S. electronics companies have achieved in a given country and their share in other countries of comparable technological or economic development; and 

	<li>the difference between gross sales levels or gross sales increases that U.S. electronics companies have achieved in a given country with a given sales effort and the levels or increases they have achieved in countries with similar markets that have had similar sales efforts.
</ul>

<p>Examples of possible contextual factors are:</p>
<ul>
	<li>the U.S. industry's sales effort in the foreign market;
	<li>the competitiveness of U.S. products in the foreign market in terms of availability, specifications, performance, and quality;

	<li>the state of the global economy and of the foreign market's economy; and

<li>occurrence of strikes or other extraordinary disruptions in the foreign market or in other markets used for comparisons.
</ul>
<p><i>If the criteria and contextual factors, taken together, indicate that the particular foreign market is not open to competitive products, then, as a second step, a market opening initiative is launched.  </i>The U.S. Government would negotiate a bilateral agreement with the foreign government to achieve an open market by an agreed date.  The agreement would set forth specific actions to be undertaken by the governments and industries involved to open the foreign market on schedule.  The agreement would also clearly articulate the criteria and contextual factors that the U.S. </p>
 
<p>Govermment used to determine that the foreign market is closed and that it would use periodically to measure progress during the term of the agreement. </p>
 
<p><i>The third step is to measure progress toward an open market at regular intervals</i>.  Ordinarily, progress should be measured by undertaking anew the analysis that underlay the original decision that the market was closed.  For example, the U.S. Government, in consultation with its foreign counterpart and with domestic industries and interested parties, might annually calculate gross sales levels and increases, market shares, and other criteria and compare the range of these results with those of the previous year.  Both the extent of the differential, if any, and the trend in that differential could then be used to assess progress, taking into account such contextual factors as U.S. sales efforts, quality of product offerings, and other market developments. </p>
 
<p>The analysis may find that, because of the introduction of a new U.S. product since the market-opening initiative began, the U.S. share of an open market would be higher than had originally been expected; or, the analysis may find that a worldwide recession accounts for the lack of an increase in gross sales in the foreign market in question.  In any event, progress would be measured not by fixed milestones nor by straight-line interpolations between beginning and ending points.  Rather, the process would respond dynamically to changes in products, markets, and technologies that enhance or detract from U.S. competitiveness in the market in question. </p>
 
<p><i>If the periodic measures of progress show that inadequate progress is being made, theta as a fourth step, government imposed sanctions should be considered to secure results</i>.  Sanctions must be carefully tailored to achieve maximum leverage on the closed market with minimum disruption of American businesses.  In designing sanctions, the U.S. Government should confer with domestic interested parties and should avoid sanctions that undermine the competitiveness of the very industries to which the foreign market is closed. </p>
 
<p>CSPP believes that this dynamic four-step process can result in more effective market-opening initiatives.  By identifying closed markets, establishing specific courses of action, measuring progress toward open markets, resorting if necessary to carefully crafted government imposed sanctions, and adapting the market-access initiative to changing circumstances, the CSPP process can achieve greater access for the competitive products of America's high-technology industries. </p>
 
<p>We welcome the active support of the U.S. Government in launching this process.  The U.S. Government has a critical and constructive role to play in initiating the assessment that identifies market-opening needs, in negotiating effective bilateral agreements, in timely and fairly measuring progress, and in applying sanctions if progress is not forthcoming.  CSPP strongly believes, however, that the U.S. Government should be the guarantor only of the fairness and transparency of the process itself-, the results must be the work of the American business community.  If accorded real opportunities to compete, we are confident that the results will reaffirm the vigorous competitiveness of America's high-technology industries.</p>
<hr>

<a name="anti1"><p align=center>CSPP Policy Proposal Summary<br>
ANTIDUMPING LAW REFORM</p></a>

<p>The Antidumping Laws Constitute a Powerful Weapon in the Trade Policy Arsenal. </p>
 
<p>CSPP Supports Strong Antidumping Laws that are Effective Remedies for Injuriously Unfair Pricing, No More and No Less. </p>
 
<p>To be Effective, the Laws Must Reflect the Commercial Realities Facing America's High-Technology Industries. </p>
 
<p>In Particular, CSPP Proposes Four Antidumping Law Reforms to Recognize Four Commercial Realities:</p>

<p>1. Proposal for Realistic Cost Calculations:</p>
<ul><li>High-Technology Industries are Characterized by High Capital investment, Rapid Product Introduction, and Short Product Life-Cycles.

	<li>Antidumping Cost Calculations Should Take Account of the Forward Pricing that Results from These Characteristics.
</ul>
<p>2. Proposal for Enhanced Deterrence:</p>
<ul><li>Dumping, Properly Defined, is Becoming a More Common Practice in Certain Foreign High-Technology Sectors.

<li>Multiple Offenders, Carefully Defined, Should Face More Stringent Remedies.
</ul>
<p>3. Proposal to Combat Circumvention:</p>
<ul><li>As More Countries Gain the Capability to Assemble High-Technology Components, More Companies Can Circumvent Application of Antidumping Relief by Relocating Assembly Operations.
<li>Provisions to Combat Circumvention Should be Strengthened.
</ul>
<p>4. Proposal to Recognize Marketplace Realities:</p>
	<ul><li>Decisiomnakers in Antidumping Cases Need Better Information and Standards in Applying the Antidumping Laws to High-Technology Industries.

<li>Revised Definitions of like Product, Suspension of Duties in Cases of Shortage, and Participation of Industrial Users in Antidumping Cases Would Better Reflect Marketplace Realities.
</ul>
<hr>

<a name="anti2"><p align=center>CSPP Policy Proposal<br>
ANTIDUMPING LAW REFORM</p></a>

<p><i>Reform of the antidumping laws is a major trade policy issue</i>.  As the Uruguay Round of the GATT negotiations enters the home stretch, the debate over reform of the GATT Antidumping Code and of the corresponding national antidumping laws has become intense.  Proposals have been made by the EC, the Nordic countries, Australia, Japan, Hong Kong, Korea, Canada, and the United States.  Within the United States, several major business groups, including AEA, SIA, and ECAT, have taken positions on the reform of the antidumping laws.  Furthermore, the implementation of the antidumping provisions of the Semiconductor Trade Arrangement has focused attention on the effect of the antidumping laws on high-technology companies. </p>
 
<p>For CSPP, reform of the antidumping laws is a high priority for two reasons.  First, CSPP members are highly integrated into the global trading system, sourcing from and selling into every major market in the world.  Our businesses may be significantly affected by changes in the antidumping laws of the United States and of foreign countries.  Second, effective antidumping laws are one element of the business environment necessary to nurture a healthy U.S. high-technology sector.  CSPP therefore has a substantial stake in the current debate over the antidumping laws. </p>
 
<p><i>The CSPP position on antidumping law reform is rooted in the principle that the antidumping laws should be effective remedies for injuriously unfair pricing, no more and no less</i>.  Therefore, antidumping law reform should above all be balanced.  It should enhance the deterrent capability of the laws and prevent circumvention of antidumping relief. But reform should also sharpen the focus of the antidumping laws, so that they do not impair ordinary business practices, particularly practices common to the high-technology sector.  The antidumping laws should encourage fair competition, not stifle it. </p>
 
<p><i>CSPP's recommendations for antidumping law reform include four elements </i>that together constitute a balanced approach.  The four elements are: (1) realistic cost calculations to determine whether there is unfair pricing; (2) deterrence of injuriously unfair pricing; (3) measures to combat circumvention of antidumping orders, and (4) recognition of marketplace realities.  These four elements are interrelated and together constitute an integrated approach.  CSPP does not support any one of these elements without the others.  The four elements are:</p>
<ul>
1. Realistic Cost Calculations to Determine Whether There is Unfair Pricing:<br><br>
<ul>
	<li>Revise GATT Antidumping Code and U.S. Laws;

<li>Expressly Permit Pricing Below Average Unit Costs during Introductory Period;

<li>Expressly Permit Allocation of Capital and R&D Costs over Product Life Cycle; and

<li>Require Product-Specific Determination of Introductory Period and Life Cycle.
</ul></ul>
<p>An essential element of every U.S. antidumping case is the Commerce Department's determination whether a product is being priced below "fair value" -whether, in short, it is being dumped.  In some cases, "fair value" is calculated according to the prices at which the product is sold in its home market.  But when the Commerce Department finds that the product in question is being sold "below cost" in the home market, it constructs a value for the product based on certain required minimum levels of costs and profit and deems that value to be the "fair value" for the product.  If a product is priced at less than this "fair value" in the United States, the Commerce Department concludes that dumping is occurring. </p>
 
<p>This procedure for constructing value can pose problems for high-technology companies.  Among the defining characteristics of a high-technology product are the high level of capital investment and research and development that the product embodies and the necessity to bring the product to market at the earliest possible moment, even if in some cases full-scale commercial production and yield cannot immediately be achieved.  The burden of high initial costs. and the pace of technological competition combine to create a distinctive pricing pattern for high-technology products, including semiconductors. </p>
 
<p>It is commonplace in a competitive market for the manufacturers of such products to offer a new product, for an introductory but not a sustained period, at a price below average unit costs.  As commercial levels of production and yield are attained, both costs and prices fall rapidly, with prices finding a market acceptance at a level above average unit costs.  Then the margin of price above cost enables the producer to recover not only manufacturing costs but also research and development costs and capital costs.  This pricing practice, which anticipates higher volume and lower unit costs over a product's life cycle, is known as "forward pricing." </p>
 
 
<p><i>The ability to engage in forward pricing is crucial if high-technology companies are to take advantage of product innovation</i>.  If introductory prices had to cover all costs - especially those initial unit costs associated with product introduction -- then new products would often be too expensive to gain the market acceptance that, successively builds demand, drives production, lowers unit costs, and thereby makes possible the recovery of costs and the generation of funds for further innovation.  Much of the competitive advantage of "being there first" would be lost because of inflated introductory prices.  Particularly handicapped would be those very U.S. firms - in such high-technology fields as logic chips and computers -- that currently have technological advantages over foreign competitors.  Therefore, it is crucial that the treatment of costs for purposes of determining whether dumping is occurring be such as to permit forward pricing, where that is the relevant industry's normal business practice. </p>
 
 
<p><i>Currently, realistic cost calculations are not assured</i>.  Although U.S. antidumping regulations permit recovery of costs over "a reasonable period of time," the Commerce Department exercises considerable discretion in defining that period.  The Commerce Department also exercises discretion in determining which costs are allocable over an entire product life cycle and which are allocated to a shorter period, and in determining how to allocate non-product-specific R&D.  Furthermore, the Commerce Department often ignores the reality that the full cost of bringing a new product to market cannot be done during initial production periods, when low production levels and product yields are common.  The GATT Antidumping Code does not specifically address the forward pricing and cost allocation issues. </p>
 
<p><i>To make cost calculations realistic, revision of the U.S. antidumping laws and of the GATT Antidumping Code is necessary</i>. </p>
 
<ul><li>The laws and Code provisions on cost calculation should expressly permit pricing below average unit costs during an introductory period of low yield and production. 
 
<li>Furthermore, they should expressly permit allocation of capital and R&D costs over the life cycle of the product.
 
<li>Whenever a product is subject to an antidumping investigation, the investigating agency should make a product-specific determination of the appropriate introductory period and life cycle. </ul>
 </ul>
<p>In this manner, the recognition that forward pricing is an ordinary, and not unfair, business practice can be integrated into the determination whether dumping is occurring.</p>
<ul>
2. Deterrence of Injuriously Unfair Pricing:
<br><br><ul>
	<li>Sharply Define "Multiple Offender."
	<li>Expedite Antidumping Investigations of All Multiple Offenders.
	<li>For Second Offense, Assess Antidumping Duties Back to Date of Initiation of Investigation.
	<li>For Third Offense, Assess Antidumping Duties Back to as Much as Two Years Before Date of Initiation, with Foreign Producers Liable for Pre-Initiation Duties.
	<li>Revise GATT Antidumping Code Accordingly.
</ul></ul>

<p>One of the principal complaints about the existing antidumping laws is that their remedies are too little and too late.  The 1988 Omnibus Trade Act did provide for abbreviated procedures in cases involving short-life-cycle products that have been subject to repeated dumping violations by the same firm -- a so-called "multiple offender." But more can be done to strengthen deterrence, provided there is a realistic cost calculation to determine whether there is dumping. </p>
 
<p>First, the notion of "multiple offender" should be more sharply defined. violations in the same country within an eight-year period involving dumping margins of 50 percent or more with respect to related products by a firm's parent, its subsidiaries, and any affiliates over which the corporate family exercises effective control, should all be criteria to determine whether a firm is a "multiple offenders" Related products would be those produced by similar processes under similar circumstances for similar end-uses; there would be a rebuttable presumption that products within the same four digit Harmonized Tariff Schedule classification are related. </p>
 
<p>Second, antidumping investigations should be expedited when multiple offenders are involved, regardless of the life cycle of the product imported. </p>
 
<p>Third, in the case of certain multiple offenders (two offenses), antidumping duties should be assessed back to the date on which the antidumping investigation was commenced; somewhat more limited retroactivity is currently permitted only upon a showing of "critical circumstances" -- a surge of injurious imports and either a history of dumping of the product in question or knowledge by the importer that dumping was occurring. </p>
 
<p>Fourth, in the case of certain other multiple offenders (three or more offenses), antidumping duties should be assessed retroactively for up to two years prior to the filing of the petition, with foreign exporters rather than U.S. importers being responsible for payment of any duties for the period before the antidumping investigation commenced. </p>
 
<p>It is critical that the concept of "multiple offender" be carefully defined.  Foreign countries often look to U.S. antidumping laws as a model, and an overly expansive or vague U.S. concept of "multiple offender" may be adopted by foreign countries whose antidumping laws do not offer the transparency and due process of U.S. law.  Ideally, the foregoing measures to enhance deterrence should be incorporated in a revised GATT Antidumping Code so that multilateral rules on deterrence are consistent.</p>
<ul>
3. Measures to Combat Circumvention of Antidumping Relief:
<br><br><ul>
	<li>Monitor Effectiveness of Present U.S. Law.

	<li>Add to GATT Antidumping Code Anti-Circumvention Measures on Parts and Components.

	<li>Add to GATT Antidumping Code Measures against Third Country Dumping.
</ul>
</ul>
<p>The increasing internationalization of sourcing and production can facilitate circumvention of antidumping relief For example, when a finished product is subject to an antidumping duty, the product's components may be imported instead, with minor assembly operations shifted to the country imposing the antidumping duties.  The 1988 Omnibus Trade Act authorized the Commerce Department to extend an existing antidumping order on a finished product to that product's parts and components assembled in the United States or third countries; it also authorized the International Trade Commission ("ITC") to monitor imports of downstream products.</p>

<p><i>Several additional steps should be taken both in the United States and at the GATT</i>.</p>
<ul>
	<li>The effectiveness of the current law on parts and components should be monitored and, if necessary, enhanced to ensure that slight modifications of a product or a shift of minor assembly operations cannot circumvent the law.

	<li>Anti-circumvention measures relating to parts and components should be included in a revised GATT Antidumping Code.

	<li>Third countries should be encouraged, through the GATT Antidumping Code, to enforce their own antidumping laws against firms that use those countries as dumping grounds for components, which are then assembled and exported.
</ul>

<p>The details of all of these anti-circumvention measures must be carefully considered and articulated, lest the cure be worse than the disease.  For example, anti-circumvention efforts should not go so far as to permit countries to impose local content requirements as a condition of settling antidumping cases.</p>
<ul>
4. Recognition of Marketplace Realities:
<br><br><ul>
	<li>Define "Like Product" So That Antidumping Relief Cannot be Imposed on Imported Product for which There is No Competitive Domestic Product.

	<li>Permit Deferral or Prompt Suspension of Antidumping Duties on Products in Short Supply, with Resumption of Duties Once Domestic Supplies Become Adequate.

<li>Accord Industrial Users the Right to Participate in Antidumping Proceedings and Comment on Those Legal and Factual Questions of which They have Particular Knowledge and Interest.
</ul></ul>

<p>Often the realities of the U.S. marketplace that are of particular concern and familiarity to U.S. industrial users are overlooked or misunderstood in antidumping proceedings.  For example, adequate recognition of the availability and quality of supplies should be an integral part of every antidumping investigation but that is not always the case. </p>
 
<p>Recognition of marketplace realities should be enhanced in three ways.  <i>First, the definition of like product" should include consideration of the availability, specifications, performance, and quality of the domestic product </i>that is "like" the imported product: if no domestic product is truly competitive in these respects, then there is no "like product" and no antidumping relief is warranted. </p>
 
<p><i>Second, the antidumping laws should permit the deferral or prompt suspension of antidumping duties in cases of domestic supply shortages</i>, with the duties re-imposed as soon as adequate domestic supplies resume. </p>
 
<p><i>Third, industrial users should have the right to participate </i>in antidumping proceedings and comment on those legal and factual questions on which they have particular knowledge and interest, such as the scope of the investigation, the definition of like product, and the existence of short supplies.</p>


<a name="conc"><p><b>Conclusion</b></p></a>

<p>The use of bilateral market-access initiatives and the reform of the antidumping laws may enhance or undermine the international competitiveness of America's high-technology industries.  CSPP's proposals in these two areas of trade policy would contribute positively to America's ability to compete at home and abroad.  CSPP's market access approach leverages rather than ignores the dynamics of international trade, thereby promising more realistic and effective U.S. efforts to open foreign markets to U.S. high-technology products.  CSPP's proposed antidumping reforms adapt the rules of fair trade to the complex realities of sourcing, manufacturing, and marketing high-technology worldwide today.  Together, these two initial CSPP proposals on trade reflect our conviction that American high-technology industries will compete -- and compete successfully -- in an open and fair global trading system.</p>

<hr></html>
</DOC>
