<html><head><title>Amelio Bio</title></head>

<body background="../images/bkground.gif" link="#003399" vlink="#cc3366">

<center><font size=+4>Dr. Gilbert F. Amelio</font></center>

<hr align=center width=50%>

<TABLE>
<TR>
<TD><img src="images/dot_clr.gif" hspace=10></TD>
<TD>
<strong>DR. GILBERT F. AMELIO<br>
<a href="http://www.apple.com">Apple Computer, Inc.</a></strong><p>
<img hspace=4 vspace=4 align=right src="images/temp.gif"><dd>Dr. Amelio, 52, is chairman of the board and chief executive officer of Apple Computer, Inc.  He was appointed to this position in February 1996, after having joined the board of directors in 1994.
<dd>Before Apple, Dr. Amelio was chairman of the board, president, and chief executive officer of National Semiconductor Corporation.  He led the company through a financial transformation that has resulted in record earnings for the past two years.  He was also responsible for repositioning National from a broad-line chip-maker into a company focused on analog and mixed-signal processes for the moving and shaping marked segments.
<dd>A graduate of Georgia Institute of Technology with a bachelor's, master's and Ph.D. in physics, Dr. Amelio is an IEEE Fellow and holder of 16 patents.  He is co-inventor of the industry's first charge-coupled device which is used in most video cameras produced today.  In 1991, he received the Masaru Ibuka Consumer Electronics Award for his work in the development of charge-coupled devices.  He is the co-author with Bill Simon, Ph.D., of the book, "Profit from Experience: The National Semiconductor Story of Transformation Management," which outlines and documents the transformation of National from 1991 to 1995 as well as the future vision of the company.
<dd>Prior to joining National Semiconductor, Dr. Amelio was president of Rockwell Communications Systems.  He is a director of Pacific Telesis, and serves as vice chairman on the board of governors of the Electronics Industry Association (EIA).  He served as a member of the executive roundtable for the University of California Irvine and chairman of the board of directors for the Semiconductor Industry Association from 1993 to 1994.  He is also a member of the Business-Higher Education Forum and the Wingspread Group on Higher Education.
<dd>Before joining Rockwell, Dr. Amelio served as general manager of Fairchild Camera and Instrument Corporation's Microprocessor division, and also as vice president and general manager of Fairchild's MOS Products Group.
<dd>Dr. Amelio began his career at Bell Laboratories, assigned to the Device Development department.  Since then, he has accumulated more than 30 years of high tech industry experience in research, engineering, marketing, finance, product development, wafer fabrication and assembly.
<dd>Dr. Amelio is a past member of the board of trustees of the Georgia Tech Research Corporation and past member of the university's National Advisory Board.  He served as board chairman in 1985-86 during Georgia Tech's centennial year.</TD>
<TD><img src="images/dot_clr.gif" hspace=10></TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>

