<html><head><title>Palmer Bio</title></head>

<body background="../images/bkground.gif" link="#003399" vlink="#cc3366">

<center><font size=+4>Robert B. Palmer</font></center>

<hr align=center width=50%>

<TABLE>
<TR>
<TD><img src="images/dot_clr.gif" hspace=10></TD>
<TD>
<strong>ROBERT B. PALMER<br>
<img hspace=4 vspace=4 align=right src="images/temp.gif"><a href="http://www.digital.com">Digital Equipment Corporation</a></strong><p>
<dd>Robert B. Palmer, 55, became president, chief executive officer and a member of the Board of Directors of Digital Equipment Corporation in October of 1992.  He was elected chairman in May 1995.
<dd>Palmer joined Digital in 1985 and became vice president, Semiconductor Operations the following year.  In 1989 he was appointed vice president, Semiconductor and Interconnect Technology.  He became vice president, Manufacturing and Logistics in 1990; and in early 1992, his responsibilities were further expanded as vice president, Manufacturing, Logistics and Component Engineering.
<dd>Prior to Digital, Palmer served as executive vice president of Semiconductor Operations at united Technologies Corporation.  He joined United Technologies in 1980, when it acquired Mostak Corporation, a company Palmer co-founded in 1969 with a group of fellow engineers from Texas Instruments.
<dd>Palmer's technical accomplishments at Mostek include the development and implementation of a TTL-compatible (transistor-transistor logic) MOS Integrated circuit production process.  Palmer shares a patent awarded for this groundbreaking work, which has been recognized by the Semiconductor Equipment Manufacturing Institute as one of the most significant technology developments in the Integrated circuit industry.
<dd>Palmer is a past member of the Board of Directors of SEMATECH; the Semiconductor Industry Association; the Semiconductor Research Center; the Microelectronics and Computer Technology Corporation in Austin, Texas; the Microelectronics Center of North Carolina; the Massachusetts Technology Park Corporation; and Electronics Design, Inc.  He is currently Chairman of the Computer Systems Policy Project, a member of the Board of Directors of AlliedSignal, Inc., and a member of the Board of Trustees of the Cooper Institute for Aerobic Research.
<dd>A native Texan, Palmer earned a bachelor of science degree in mathematics with high honors (1962) and a master of science degree in physics (1965) from Texas Tech University.</TD>
<TD><img src="images/dot_clr.gif" hspace=10></TD>
</TR>
