</DOCHDR>
<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Sidebar: Impediments to the GII</TITLE>
<body background="../images/bkground.gif" link=003399 vlink=cc3366>
</HEAD>

<BODY>

<H2>IMPEDIMENTS TO THE GII</H2>
<P></P>
The Global Information Infrastructure (GII) holds out the promise of a world-wide, interactive communications and information system, through which a Global Digital Common Market may be created.  However, this potential can be achieved only if laws and regulations seek to foster, rather than inhibit, the growth of the GII.  The most significant today are in five key areas:
<P></P>

<OL>
<LI>Trade and Market Entry Restrictions.  National laws that have the effect of preventing the delivery of services via the GII or that restrict local consumers' choice of networks, technologies or products will distort the GII's development.  Commercial practices that differ substantially from international norms also can act as barriers to global business and limit a country's integration into the GII.
<P></P>
<LI>Security.  Users of the GII -- whether engaged in commerce or other personal or professional transactions -- will require mechanisms to validate the source and authenticity of communications, and to prevent unwarranted intrusions into confidential exchanges and to safeguard electronic financial transactions.  Encryption technology offers solutions to many of these concerns, but international use of this technology is limited by national security laws.  Failure to meet consumers' needs for encryption technology will defeat the GII and digital common market.
<P></P>
<LI>Privacy.  Security concerns are particularly acute in the case of confidential data.  There is no common understanding between countries regarding what data may be collected and distributed by third parties, how data should be protected, how it can or should be shared across borders, or how individuals can act to prevent the spread of unauthorized or inaccurate personal information.  These questions are pivotal for global enterprises and for citizens.
<P></P>
<LI>Copyright Protection.  Copyright -- the primary means of defining and protecting original expressions of information -- is critical to the economic use of the GII.  The GII will flourish only if proprietors can use it as a distribution channel without risking loss of their goods.  There is a need for clear legal protections related to copyrighted material transmitted on the GII.  Also, mechanisms, including encryption, which limit the risk of unauthorized reception need to be evaluated.  At the same time, attempts to protect copyright that focus on technologies, rather than on acts of infringement, are inherently risky. The responsibility for implementing and enforcing copyright protections cannot be placed solely on the manufacturers of information technology products.
<P></P>
<LI>Interoperability.  The GII, and the global digital common market, require that the multiple networks within countries, and a myriad of alternative digital appliances are able to  connect and operate seamlessly.  Industry and the open marketplace can accomplish this  but governments must enable industry to do so through pro-competitive public policies.



</BODY>
</HTML>

</DOC>
