<html>
<title>Key Terms</title>
<p>KEY TERMS</p>
<hr>
<p>As CSPP began to address the issue of interoperability in the NII, it became clear that there were several terms that needed to be clearly defined to ensure understanding and consistency of meaning throughout our discussions.  Because those terms and definitions are an important resource in understanding this report and the need for interoperability, they are provided throughout this section.</p>
<a href="report6.html">Return to the Main Report</a>
</html>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>WT04-B17-183</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA086-000620-B039-289</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://www.cspp.org:80/reports/report6/job05.html 198.69.128.8 19970122040846 text/html 1037
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: Netscape-Communications/1.12
Date: Wednesday, 22-Jan-97 04:13:29 GMT
Last-modified: Thursday, 07-Dec-95 18:23:24 GMT
Content-length: 844
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<html>
<title>Key Terms</title>
<p>KEY TERMS</p>
<hr>
<p><b>INTEROPERABILITY</b> is the ability of two or more given systems (for the purposes of this paper, "systems" includes devices, databases, networks, or technologies) to interact in concert with one another in accordance with a prescribed method in order to achieve a predictable result. </p>
<p>Interoperability allows diverse systems made by different vendors to communicate with each other so users do not have to make major adjustments to account for differences in products or services. </p>
<p>lnteroperability implies compatibility among systems at specified levels of interaction, including the physical.  This compatibility is achieved through specifications for the interfaces between systems.</p>
<a href="report6.html">Return to the Main Report</a>
</html>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>WT04-B17-184</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA086-000620-B039-312</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://www.cspp.org:80/reports/report6/job06.html 198.69.128.8 19970122040855 text/html 1485
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: Netscape-Communications/1.12
Date: Wednesday, 22-Jan-97 04:13:39 GMT
Last-modified: Thursday, 07-Dec-95 18:23:26 GMT
Content-length: 1291
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<html>
<title>Key Terms</a>
<p>KEY TERMS</p>
<hr>
<p>An <b>INTERFACE</b> is a connection between two systems that is specified in physical (electrical or mechanical) and/or logical (message format and exchange procedure) terms.  The interface specification provides the information and technical parameters for how systems communicate with each other, but should be limited to that information necessary to enable communications between the systems, leaving the expression of implementations and the remaining product design to the creative abilities of competitive suppliers. </p>
<p>Some examples of common interfaces include the interfaces between the electric power system in the home and a television power cord; televisions and videocassette recorders (VCRs); standard-size nuts and bolts; telephone jacks and telephones; and computers and modems. </p>
<p>Equipment which meets the interface specifications should be able to interconnect and interoperate across the interface.  For example, a videocassette recorder can interoperate with any U.S. television sold today and the electrical source in the residence, and a fully interoperable remote control will work with both the VCR and the television.</p>
<a href="report6.html">Return to the Main Report</a>
</html>
</DOC>
