</DOCHDR>
<html>
<title>Key Terms</title>
<p>KEY TERMS </p>
 <hr>
<p>Interfaces can be <b>OPEN OR CLOSED</b>.  An interface is physically and logically open if its specifications are readily available to all vendors, service providers and users, and if such specifications are not revised without timely notice or public process.  Interfaces critical to the interoperability of the Nil should allow manufacturers or vendors to provide, in compliance with reasonable licensing terms and conditions, if any, equipment or software to meet the interface specifications. </p>
<p>For instance, if the specification for the interface between a 35mm camera and film is open, manufacturers can build products that are compatible with both sides of the interface.  For example, film manufacturers such as Kodak and Fuji can both produce film that works with any brand of camera, and camera manufacturers can make cameras that can accept any brand of film. </p>
<p>In tne Nil, open multimedia standards, for example, will permit content providers and applications publishers to create programs that work together on one side of lie multimedia standard interfaces, as well as permit hardware manufacturers to produce multimedia engines on the other side of the interface to display that content and work with the applications.  While open interfaces at critical points in the Nil are important for enabling interoperability, it is also important to maintain the intellectual property rights of expressions of implementations as a key incentive for industry to develop advanced technologies and applications.</p>

<a href="report6.html">Return to the Main Report</a>
</html>
</DOC>
