Content-length: 1113
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<html>
<title>Key Terms</title>
<p>KEY TERMS </p>
 <hr>
<p>An open interface may or may not be a STANDARD interface.  Standard interfaces are those which are formally recognized by a national, regional, or international standards body. </p>
<p>Many interfaces, both open and closed, are not formally recognized as standards, but may be widely used and adopted by an industry.  These are known as "de facto" standards.  Thus, open interfaces may involve proprietary or nonproprietary technologies, and may or may not be formally standardized. </p>
<p>When an interface is formally standardized, strong public participation in the evolution of the standard is essential.  The standard specification must be published, controlled, and supported in terms of changes to the relevant documentation by an independent organization. </p>
<p>Other factors that </p>
<p>contribute to the success of standards are that their specifications are well written and multi-vendor, and promote portability, scalability, and interoperability.</p>

<a href="report6.html">Return to the Main Report</a>
