<html>
<title> Strathcourier - April 1996</title>
<body>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#000088" VLINK="#ff0080" TEXT="#f5f50c" LINK="#8888ff" ALINK="#ff8888" >

<h2>Nurturing tall poppies....</h2>
<p>
<i>"Tall poppies need a chance to grow"</i> was a headline in the Brisbane Courier-Mail in January.  The article continued, <i>"Australia has long prided itself on its egalitarianism.  This attitude, while working against the development of an unwelcome class system, has also tended to hold back many with the potential to achieve excellence.  If Australia is allowed to make its mark on the world it needs to promote and create opportunities for its best and brightest.  This is particularly important when those people are young..."</I>
<p>For the overwhelming majority of young people, education is the key to their future.  Two main  ingredients are required - access to the best instruction and motivation to reach their personal best.  I am delighted that our Year 10 students are undertaking one VCE unit this year and over three-quarters of Year 11 are studying a Unit 3/4.  Strathcona girls have  access to the best instruction  and the majority have a determination to succeed.  This is reflected in the 1995 VCE results of which we are very proud.<br>
As has often been the case in the past, our top students proved again that it is possible to complement  outstanding achievement with the fullest participation in school life.  They accepted leadership responsibilities and provided fine role models for younger students.  We congratulate every member of the Class of '95.<br>
(Mrs) Ruth E Bunyan<br>
Principal<p>
<center><img src="leaders.gif"><br><b>1996 School Leaders</b><br>
Vanessa Davidson (Deputy Captain), Lee Brewster (Captain), and Megan Fricke (Deputy Captain). </center><p>

<html>

<H2>Realisation of Potential</H2><P>
The 1995 VCE results were outstanding  and brought great pleasure to the girls of strathcona and their teachers.<br>
All girls were awarded the Victorian Certificate of Education<br>
The dux of the school was Christine Shih.  Her TER of 99.85 included full marks in mathematical methods and physics, and a distinction in university enhancement mathematics.  Christine was offered a place at Oxford University to read physics, but accepted her first choice of a combined science/medicine degree at the University of Melbourne. <p>
<center><B>A Comparison Of Recent Years</B><p>
<img src="table1.gif"><P>
A scaled study score of 42+ means that the students is in the top 5%<br>
The number of subjects with scores >42 was 21 (out of 28)</center><P>
<H2>Rewarding Excellence</H2><P>
<b>The Jean Lovegrove Award</b><br>
In 1995, Dr Austin Lovegrove endowed the school with the inaugural jean Lovegrove Award for Dux of the School in memory of his mother, Jean Bell Lovegrove (nee Austin).  Mrs Lovegrove was School Captain and Dux of the School in 1926 and later served as President of the Old Strathconians' Association.  She spent many years doing voluntary charity work, devoting her later life to the care of the sick and elderly.  Her standard of excellence and generous spirit are remembered in the Jean Lovegrove Award<p>
<center><img src="shih.gif"><p>
<b>Christine Shih receiving the inaugural Jean Lovegrove Award from <br> Dr Lovegrove</center><p>
<center>
<img src="watts.gif"><p>
<b>Jane Watts receiving the Monash Prize for Academic Excellence in Year 11, 1995 from Dr Peter Tutton, Reader in Anatomy, Monash University.</b><p></center>
<P>
<h2>Achieving in many ways...</h2><p>
<b>Congratulations to so many students who have achieved excellence.</B><br>
<b>Janette Lewis</b> (Year 10) - one of four Australian students to win a BHP National Science Award.<br>
<b>Heidi Leonard</b> (Year 12) - a 1995 Premier's VCE Award for Dance Styles.<br>
<b>Leah Watterson</b> '95 - a $300 scholarship for having the highest TER score for students entering the Business Management Course at Monash, Caulfield.<br>
<b>Rebecca Wilson</b> (Year 11) - the Swannie Debating Award as the best debater in all age groups in the Victorian Schools' Debating Competition.<br>
<b>Rosemary Lee</b> (Year 11) - selected for the Victorian section of the Physics Olympiad Training Squad.<br>
<b>Hannah Clarke</b> (Year 11) - highest marks in the State in the Australian Schools' Science Competition.<br>
<b>Jessica Pigot</B> '95 - equal first prize in the National Languages Festival (four other girls gained honourable mentions).<br>
<b>Monica Teh </b> '95 - was a prize winner in the National Competition to design a logo for the Education Network Australia (EdNa).<br>
<b>Elisha Willis</b> '95 - highest award in the Adeline Genee International Ballet Competition for selected 15 - 18 year old dancers in London.<br>
<b>Joanna Knight </b> (Year 12) - represented Victoria in the National Schools Constitutional Convention in Canberra. <br>
<center>
<img src="triathlon.gif><br><b> Year 12 students Margaret Fricke, Kate Dalrymple and Andrea Frankpitt who won the under 17 teams event (girls) at the BP Triathlon</b> <p>
