<html>
<title>Strathcourier - April 1996 </title>
 

<body>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#000088" VLINK="#ff0080" TEXT="#f5f50c" LINK="#8888ff" ALINK="#ff8888" >
<h2>Sowing the seeds.....</h2>
<p>
<h3>Career education</h3><P>
<center>
<img src="career.gif><br>
<b><i>Mrs Catherine Symons and Mrs Merrill Buller helping  Georgina Anderson (Yr11) in the careers Room. </b></i>
</center><br>
Given the nature of today's job market, career education is increasingly important.  Students are faced with complex decisions about tertiary courses, career paths and future employment.<br>
Mrs Catherine Symons is Strathcona's VCE Coordinator and Careers Counsellor.  Mrs Symons' dual role allows her to work alongside students as they explore ideas about careers and select VCE courses of study.    She believes that career pathways should be developed alongside academic programs.  She says,"There will be little unskilled work in the twenty-first century.  Today's students will need to be excellent communicators  and great team players.  They will need broadly based  education that enables them to be flexible enough to cope with continuing  workplace change."<br>
While university courses are the destination of most of our students, Mrs Symons believes that  there are many other interesting options.  She says, " There are now vocational links into many degree courses.  There are opportunities for work placements, and TAFE options provide a broad skill base for employment."<br>
Technology is playing a significant  role in career education.  Computer programs such as  Job and Course Explorer (JAC) have been used for some years.  Tertiary institutions  have introduced hot lines to provide information on courses.  The Internet is also becoming a source of career data.  It is being  used by the Department of Employment, Education and Training (DEET) to provide information for students.<br>
At Strathcona the careers framework encourages students to focus on their personal interests.  Compiling a resume, undertaking work experience, listening to visiting speakers and attending interview evenings are some of the activities persued by students in years 9 to 12.  A great deal of personal development occurs during these years and students are encouraged to view the future with confidence and optimism.<br>
The VCE Australian Studies Course in year 10 is taken by all students.  All students complete a research project about a career, course or business that interests them.   In addition, each student in year 10 completes a work experience placement.  As part of this task they are required to write letters of application and phone prospective employers, under the guidance of the Careers Secretary, Mrs Merrill Buller.  Mrs Buller says, "The girls are very excited  when they are offered a placement.  It gives them tremendous self confidence."<br>
Mrs Symons notes that in recent years significant  emphasis has been placed on the skills that will be needed beyond school.  She says, "Excellent communication skills, leadership, enthusiastic teamwork and responsibility and part of Strathcona's ethos.  We set out to develop self esteem, a willingness to contribute to the wider world and a love of learning.  We are also working very hard to develop creativity, independence and the belief that every strathcona student can be a tall poppy in Australia's future."<P>
<center><img src="carli.gif"><br>
<b><i>Work Experience student Carli Dawes (Year 10) at Tullamarine Airport.</center></b></I>
<p>
<h3>Skills for the future</H3><br>
<b>Enterprise and teamwork are skills that are highly valued in the workforce.  There are many ways of developing these skills beyond the careers program.</b><br>
In March, 22  Strathcona students from Years 8-11 were Australian role models for an international project on teenagers organized by the <i>National Council for Education Technology</i> in the UK.<br>
Our students worked from 7.30am to 8.30pm  with 200 students located British Telecom's training headquarters in Stone, Staffordshire.  Their task was to produce a multimedia project on <i>Teenage girls - past, present and future.</i><br>
Stephanie Mills said,"We wanted to emphasise that girls are innovative leaders, creative users of technology and confident about Australia's future.  It was a great opportnity!"<p>

<center><img src="ncet.gif"><br>
<b><i>Strathcona students working on their multimedia presentation during the NCET Project.</b></i><br>

