<html>

<head>
<title>CAMI - The Journey of Hope</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<h1 align=center>The Journey of Hope</h1>
<hr>
<p><font size=4><i>There is a place for the families and loved ones of those suffering from severe 
mental illnesses.&#160; A place to share and grow.&#160; A place to learn. </i></font></p>
<p><font size=4><i>We offer answers to individuals and family members asking for understanding, 
information or just sincere support.&#160; These answers come from others who have 
walked the same path before us.</i> </font></p>
<h1 align=center><font size=4>Ten Principles of Support</font></h1>
<ol>
<li><font size=4>We acknowledge and accept the fact that someone we love has a mental 
illness. </font></li>
<li><font size=4>We accept that we have no control over this illness or the individual with 
the illness.&#160; We have control only over our own actions and thoughts. </font></li>
<li><font size=4>We release all feeling of guilt concerning this mental illness for we are not to 
blame for the illness or its effects. </font></li>
<li><font size=4>We understand and acknowledge that the mental illness has had an impact 
on all of our relationships. </font></li>
<li><font size=4>We forgive ourselves for the mistakes we have made and we forgive others 
for wrongs we feel have been committed against us. </font></li>
<li><font size=4>We choose to be happy and healthy.&#160; We choose to return to a healthy focus 
on ourselves. </font></li>
<li><font size=4>We keep our expectations for ourselves and for our mentally ill loved one at 
realistic levels. </font></li>
<li><font size=4>We believe that we have inner resources which will help us with our own 
growth and will sustain us through crisis. </font></li>
<li><font size=4>We acknowledge the strength and value of this support system and we 
commit ourselves to sustaining it for our benefit and the benefit of other 
families. </font></li>
<li><font size=4>We acknowledge that there is a higher power to whom we will turn to 
nurture and strengthen our ability to release those things we cannot control. </font></li>
</ol>
<hr>
<p><font size=4>The Journey of Hope...</font></p>
<hr>
<p><font size=4>Research studies indicate that 40-65% of adults with severe and persistent mental 
illness either reside with their families or receive primary care-management from 
their families.&#160; The ability of family members to provide a benign, 
understanding, and predictable environment for their ill relative is a key factor in 
the capacity of the ill family member to stabilize and remain in the community.&#160; 
The <i>Journey of Hope</i> not only provides education and skill training for families 
who must cope with the difficulties of their ill relatives, it also gives them the 
practical and emotional support to sustain themselves in the role as primary 
caretakers in the community mental health system. </font></p>
<p><font size=4>There are two components to the <i>Journey of Hope</i> - an education element and a 
support group element.&#160; Together they provide maximum benefit to the family 
member.&#160; Families are strongly encouraged to take advantage of both. </font></p>
<p><font size=4>The <i>Journey of Hope</i> family education program is a 12-week course for relatives 
and friends of individuals with severe and persistent mental illness.&#160; Those 
attending need not be AMI members, but are encouraged to join a local affiliate.&#160; 
The curriculum focuses on three major psychiatric illnesses: schizophrenia, 
bipolar disorder, and major depression.&#160; It emphasizes the clinical treatment of 
these illnesses and teaches the knowledge and skills family members need to 
cope more effectively with the ill relative.&#160; The courses are taught by trained 
AMI family member volunteers in a team teaching approach. </font></p>
<p><font size=4>The <i>Journey of Hope</i> support group program is an on-going support structure 
for families and friends.&#160; Again, family members are trained to facilitate these 
groups.&#160; They provide family members with an opportunity to reinforce coping 
skills and to seek emotional support and practical help from other family 
members.&#160; Based on Ten Principles of Support, the groups guide efforts of 
individuals to help themselves and each other.&#160; In this family-to-family support 
group, families learn they are not alone; that there is hope; that there is 
information; and that individual family member experience is a powerful tool for 
help when shared with others. </font></p>
<hr>
<p><font size=4>Twelve Educational Modules</font></p>
<hr>
<ol>
<li><font size=4>Learning about feelings, learning about facts </font></li>
<li><font size=4>Introduction to schizophrenia: diagnosis, critical periods </font></li>
<li><font size=4>Introduction to depression and bipolar illness: diagnosis and causes </font></li>
<li><font size=4>Basics about the brain </font></li>
<li><font size=4>Problem-solving skills workshop </font></li>
<li><font size=4>Medication review </font></li>
<li><font size=4>What it's like to be mentally ill: empathy workshop </font></li>
<li><font size=4>Communications skills workshop </font></li>
<li><font size=4>Relative groups and self-care </font></li>
<li><font size=4>Rehabilitation </font></li>
<li><font size=4>Advocacy: fighting stigma </font></li>
<li><font size=4>Certification and celebration </font></li>
</ol>
<hr>
<p><font size=4>Class and Support Group Information</font></p>
<hr>
<ol>
<li><font size=4>The <i>Journey of Hope</i> programs are currently offered throughout California. 
Training sessions are conducted yearly for volunteers who are willing to 
teach the 12-week education classes or facilitate a support group for two 
years.&#160; Affiliates or communities who want to offer the <i>Journey of Hope</i> in 
Oregon can send trainees free of charge. </font></li>
<li><font size=4>The implementation of the <i>Journey of Hope</i> education classes in a local 
affiliate involves an intensive 22 hour weekend training of two-person 
teams from at least four affiliates.&#160; These family teams are then prepared to 
offer the program in their own community.&#160; The course can be offered to a 
group of 15 to 20 family members. </font></li>
<li><font size=4>Training is also provided for support group facilitators.&#160; The education 
classes can self-select facilitators, or volunteers can be recruited from other 
members of the local affiliate.&#160; The intensive training for the facilitators is 17 
hours. </font></li>
<li><font size=4>Communities now offering support groups are invited to send volunteers to 
the <i>Journey of Hope</i> facilitator training.&#160; The training includes the skills and 
principles that help family members and friends cope with the mental illness 
of a loved one. </font></li>
<li><font size=4>The nationwide <i>Journey of Hope</i> began as a joint effort between the 
Alliance for the Mentally Ill organizations in Louisianna and Vermont.&#160; 
Donna Mayeaux and Behavioral Health, Inc.&#160; from Baton Rouge, Louisiana 
provided the support group model.&#160; Joyce Burland, Ph.D., a clinical 
psychologist and family member from Vermont, compiled and wrote the 
material for the 12-week education classes.&#160; Donna and Joyce also conduct 
training sessions for state-wide trainers of facilitators and family educators 
on a yearly basis. </font></li>
</ol>
<h2 align=center>For the locations Journey of Hope Family Education 
classes are held within California:</h2>
<div align=center><center>
<pre>
California Alliance for the Mentally Ill
1111 Howe Ave., Ste. #475
Sacramento, Ca.  95825
(916) 567-0163
BrianJOH@aol.com

For information about Journey of Hope in California:

Brian Jacobs,
Program Director
203 Argonne Ave., B-104
Long Beach, Ca. 90803
(310) 438-4174
FAX (310) 434-6019
EMail: <a href="mailto:BrianJOH@aol.com">BrianJOH@aol.com</a>
</pre>
</center></div>
<h2 align=center>Outside California</h2>
<div align=center><center>
<pre>Journey of Hope
P.&#160; O.&#160; Box 2547
Baton Rouge, LA  70808
(504) 343-6928
<hr></pre>
</center></div>
<div align=center><center>
<pre>[<a href="./cami.html">CAMI</a>]</pre>
</center></div>
<p align=center><a href="http://www.susanville.com"><img src="/graphics/stest.gif" border=0 align=bottom width=54 height=54></a></p>
</body>

</html>
