<h1 align=center><tt>AMI NEWSLETTER</tt></h1>
<p align=center><strong><tt>The Alliance for the Mentally Ill of Santa Clara County</tt></strong></p>
<table width=100%>
<tr><td width=50%><pre><strong><tt>August 1996</tt></strong></pre>
</td><td width=50%><div align=right>
<pre><strong><tt>Volume XXI No. 8</tt></strong></pre>
</div>
</td></tr>
</table>
<p align=center><em><strong><tt>A Grass Roots Organization</tt></strong></em></p>
<h2><tt>Potluck Picnic at Cupertino Memorial Park to Replace August General Meeting</tt></h2>
<tt>
<p>
Gourmet main dishes, salads and sinful desserts are on the menu for AMIs annual picnic Friday evening, August 16 at Memorial Park in Cupertino. The potluck supper, to be served promptly at 6 PM, replaces the August General Meeting.
</p>
<p>
The park is located next to the park Senior Center opposite De Anza College at Stevens Creek Boulevard and Mary Avenue. Parking is available at the Senior Center Parking lot.
</p>
<p>Picnickers are asked to bring one main dish, salad or desert large enough to serve 8 to 10 people. AMI will supply soft drinks, paper plates, napkins and eating utensils. Please call Mary Lou Filice, at 408-723-4842, to let her know what you plan to bring. Every body is welcome to come, play and help celebrate summer is finally here!
</p>
</tt>
<h2><tt>October Mental Illness Awareness Week Theme is <i>is "Open your Mind, Mental Illnesses are Brain Disorders"</i>
</tt></h2>

<tt>
<p>Planning is currently underway for AMI-SCCs participation in Mental Illness Awareness Week 1996 (MIAW) which will be observed nationally, starting Sunday October 6, 1996. We want to increase awareness that mental illnesses are physical illnesses and (with access to treatment and adequate in-community support) that people with brain disorders can live productive lives, at much lower total cost to families and the community. We have a packages of NAMIs MIAW how to information, artwork, and handout materials, with suggested themes for each day. AMI-SCC also has much free material giving the facts of mental illness care and offering direct practical help for families and clients.</p>

<p>To get public attention on MIAW in the first full week in October, AMI-SCC needs many more volunteers, starting now to: 1) Prepare and send out news releases to Newspapers and letters to local organizations, 2) Distribute AMI material to libraries, schools, health centers and other local public places, 3) Contact radio and television stations, offering 30 second announcements, personal interviews, etc. and 4) make follow up phone calls  and presentations to receptive organizations.</p>

<p>If you can help, please call the AMI-SCC Office, 408-280-7264, or in North Santa Clara County, call Ann Sloan, 415-85 </p>
</tt>	
<h3><tt>COUNSELORS AND CONSUMERS DESCRIBE PEER COUNSELING AND SUPPORT GROUPS EXPERIENCES
 AT AMI GENERAL MEETING HELD JUNE ll, l996 <i> By Cole Buxbaum </i></tt></h3>
<tt>
<p>The main message from all presenters was that consumers can play a significant role in helping themselves and each other to cope with their problems, to acquire skills and to get into work or other meaningful activities, through peer counseling and self help support groups.</p>
<p>Fred Vater, a volunteer counselor with the County ACCESS program described his support group. Vater started the group this year with the mission of getting clients together to interchange information dealing with the job market and related problems.  To be in his group people must be working, going to school, or actively seeking work. They cannot have a substance abuse problem, and must be identified as a client of the county or of a contract team.</p>

<p>Subjects such as interviewing techniques, working hours, bureaucratic impediments to be conquered, and issues of confidentiality between co-workers, including medication, are all addressed in weekly meetings, with the group setting its own agenda.  At present, there are seven members who meet at the County Central Mental Health Center near Valley Medical Center at 6:30-8:00 P.M. on Mondays, and they are seeking additional people.  "Looking for work is tough", explained Vater and our people can use as much help as they can get in getting job opportunities and work related coping skills. For more information, call Mr. Fred Vater at 408-885-6229.</p>
<p>Alice Washington, Peer Counselor, and Paul Ernst, Coordinator of Volunteers at Miramonte Mental Health Services, discussed their program and its accomplishments. Paul Ernst, explained that Miramonte is a private non-profit mental health agency in Palo Alto helping mentally ill clients in North Santa Clara County, including parts of San Jose. He has been with Miramonte for seven years, working with volunteers for five years, starting with volunteer peer counselors, fifty-five years or older, who are trained to work with clients sixty or older. To date, he has trained over l00 peer counselors who can go into a clients home for weekly one hour visits.  Forty are still active.</p>
<p>In addition to the above Senior Peer Counselors, there are Adult Peer Counselors, who are younger people like Alice Washington, who have experienced emotional difficulties and are interested in helping others with similar concerns.  Washington began by saying that initially she didnt think she would be able to perform the task, but after one year she was doing it and training others with great satisfaction. She learned the skills of active listening. Her self esteem and knowledge of  the therapeutic relationship has increased.</p>
<p>She now teaches a class to other clients seeking the same rewards in helping others.  To date she has taught eight trainees and looks forward to more.  To get this peer counseling training, one must be a client of Miramonte.  In answer to a question, Washington explained that she interacts with the vocational program at Miramonte that helps clients find and keep jobs.  She is also the co-editor  of the "Community Alliance Times" published bi-monthly at Miramonte, discussing  all issues of interest to consumers, ranging from available activities, womens and mens group issues, coping strategies and insurance coverage and legislation.</p>
<p>Paul Ernst said their Peer Counseling is done at the Miramonte Discovery Center, l429 Grant Road, Mountain View, 4l5-6l7-l769.  He meets with the counselors on a weekly basis.  There is no training fee charged  to the volunteers in either the Senior or Adult Peer Counselor group, with the proviso that they volunteer to help others for at least one year for Senior group and six months for the Adult group.</p>
<p>Linda Bell, Director of the Mental Health Association (MHA) came with seven clients to relate their support group and life experiences in frank and vivid terms, with their striving to achieve and maintain an active life. Linda Bell said MHA is a non-profit agency like AMI, but with no member dues funding.</p>
<p>Bell is celebrating her tenth anniversary this month, offering support and guidance to individuals primarily with bipolar disorders and major depressions, and a few with a schizo-affective diagnosis.  Patients come alone or with family members to her the Mood Disorder Groups at Stanford and in San Jose.</p>

<p>Marguita began by explaining that she entered  a deep depressive state after losing a close relative. She was hospitalized three times, when there was a concern about self mutilation or of harming others.  Her husband loyally visited her twice a day, and offered strong support.  They have just celebrated their 50th wedding anniversary.  She joined Linda Bells group five years ago and has been very grateful for their acceptance and caring.</p>
<p>Jody was diagnosed with a bipolar disorder eleven years ago, going through four manic-depressive psychosis and "lots of depression". Three generations of  her family has had individuals with bipolar illness.  It was very difficult for her to accept her own diagnosis, leading to periods of abstinence from medication and relapse. Unfortunately she observed that people in the medical profession, and she is a nurse, have a particularly difficult time with acceptance. Linda Bells group is a place where she can open up and laugh, without the necessity of hiding, and can make real lasting relationships.</p>
<p>Barbara, after fifteen years of therapy and groups, was finally diagnosed with a bipolar II disorder.  Her perception had been that she was different from others and felt isolated, despite the fact that she got college degrees and worked.  She took herself off medication and had suicidal impulses and ideation.  Linda Bells group has given her a chance to participate in learning how to manage the condition through medication and sharing. She now has recovery but still no cure.</p>
<p>David was essentially untreated for five years from l962 on. Prior to that, he obtained degrees in biochemistry and computer work. Two years ago he discovered that he had bipolar illness.  His brother suffers from a schizoaffective disorder, and his wife has Obsessive Compulsive Disorder. Coming to the group there is  the "wonderful sense that we are not alone", with hope that a cure will still be found. </p>
<p>Carolyn, had her first psychotic episode at age 28 and then diagnosis of manic depression. Carolyns younger sister was first diagnosed as schizophrenic and then re-evaluated to bi-polar.  Several members in her family suffer from these illnesses, including her mother.  Carolyn became a nurse at age 20 in an attempt to understand why "Her world fell apart" begining with her first episode.  Linda Bell helped her, she says, as one would "pick up a piece of something floating on the ocean".</p>
<p>Beth deals most of the time with major depression; however, "some medications trigger a switch in her mood into a manic state and alternating rapidly between the two".  Her diagnosis was major depression ten years ago, altered to bipolar seven years ago. She has been hospitalized about seven times with three sessions of Electro Convulsive Therapy (ECT), that have been very effective and probably saved her life from suicidal impulses".  She is trained as a scientist and does part time writing assignments. She is grateful  to have places like the Mental Health Associations groups.</p>

<p>Karin had a suicidal and alcoholic mother; with two sisters on lithium.  "It was hell living in that house".  But she attended college, obtained an electrical engineering degree and worked for over ten years before she then became uncontrolled and diagnosed with a bipolar disorder.  The Stanford Mood Disorder Group was accepting, and not judgmental. Karin said, "without Linda there would be no group, and without a group there would not be some of us".
</p>
Note:	The monthly schedule for the Mood Disorder Groups and other client self help groups can be found each month in the AMI Newsletter on page one, towards the bottom of the left hand column. For further regarding AMI's Mood Disorder Groups and other client self help groups, please call Linda Bell at 408.294.4991.

<h2><tt>Update: Jail Diversion</tt></h2>
<p><em><tt>by Erika Toth, AMI Vice President</tt></em></p>
<p><tt>
	Our County Board of Supervisors approved by a unanimous vote a $241,000 budget addition for FY 1996-97 for a Mental Health Jail Diversion Program. This will fund a one year pilot program. It will cover only key central areas of our County: Downtown San Jose, East San Jose and the McKinley area of San Jose. These have been identified as target areas of high incident rates for potential diversion in law enforcement encounters.
	A new Mobile Mental Health Crisis (MMHC) Team will be created under Jo Gampon, Director of Adult MH Services. The staff are being recruited now and the MMHC Team is expected to be operational sometime in October 1996. The San Jose City Sobering Station will be enlarged to allow for a "cool-down" period for persons in crisis, to hopefully avoid being booked into jail. Also, a daytime drop-in program will be made available for the homeless mentally ill in Downtown San Jose.
	The above represents only a start.  Supervisor Bealls Steering Committee will continue to meet and monitor the Jail Diversion Program. The Program must demonstrate success and cost effectiveness in order to get renewed (or increased) funding next year. Because our ultimate goal is a County-wide Program to include juveniles as well as adults, the committee is also beginning to assess the catastrophic lack of services available to juveniles with mental illness in Juvenile Hall.
	I will keep you updated on our progress.
<b>FOR FAMILY INFORMATION AND HELP REGARDING LOCKED FACILITIES, JAIL AND POLICE ISSUES, contact Erika Toth, 408-370-7021, Chair of AMIs Forensic and Locked Facilities Liaison Committee.</b>
</tt></p>

<h2><tt>MEGAN GEORGE WILL HOLD A SERIES OF CLASSES ON MENTAL ILLNESS FOR RELATIVES</tt></h2>
<p><tt> 
	Megan George, LCSW, will lead a four week series of family educational classes on mental illness, beginning September l8, for relatives of mentally ill persons. She will present the series in conjunction with AMI-SCC.  The classes will include the theories of mental illness, psychiatric medications, legal issues, resources for the mentally ill, and parents perspectives.  A fee of $l0 is charged for class supplies and to provide books and video tapes for a lending library.
	The class is limited to 20 and will meet for two hours, from 6 to 8 PM, on two Wednesday evenings in September and October at El Camino Hospital, 2500 Grant Road, Mountain View. The dates and meeting rooms are: Sept. l8, Rm. B; Sept. 25, Rm. A; Oct. 2, Rm. B, and Oct. 9, Rm. A.	<b>For more info. and attendance space, please call Megan at 4l5.969.7337.</b>
</tt></p>

<hr>
<blockquote>
We want to express our deep sympathy to Ted Berndt and his two sons on the loss of Nancy Berndt, wife, mother, and long time AMI member, due to a stroke on June 30th.  The familys wants all memorial donations in her memory to be sent to AMI-SCC at 1060 Minnesota Ave., Suite 7, San Jose, CA 95125.  We will miss her smiling face at our meetings and her steadfast support.
</blockquote>
<hr>

<h2><tt>StarFires URIEL House is Open     <i>by Michael Whitney</i>
</tt></h2>
<p><tt>
The new StarFire program supports those with mental illnesses, as they recover from substance abuse. Their mental illness is stabilized through work with a MH  Service Team case manager and doctor. They concurrently learn techniques to control substance abuse.  StarFires Uriel House, to provide a dual diagnosis, sober living environment, opened June 1, 1996. The first client was a female, who moved in on the Fourth of July.  Other clients in the San Jose State area were invited to a Bar B Que, where they met and had hot dogs and hamburgers.  At this writing, there is still one more female bed space and five male bed spaces available.  Then a waiting list will be formed and maintained.
	The main support in helping to open Uriel House has come from individual AMI members, the AMI-SCC Organization, local clergy and interested mental health staff.  Thanks very much for all the donations of time, money and furnishings. All we need now is some on-going assistance, bedding, sheets and two single beds to become fully operational.  <b>To help out or to interview for placement, call 408.279.1003.</b>

</tt></p>
