<p align=center><em><strong><tt>A Grass Roots Organization</tt></strong></em> </p>
<h2><tt>New Adult Mental Health Programs to be discussed at 
AMI&#146;s November General Meeting</tt></h2>
<p><tt>Three special new Service Teams and a second ACCESS operation will be 
discussed at. AMI&#146;S Monthly General Meeting. November 12 at the Hewlett 
Packard Auditorium, 5301 Stevens Creek Blvd. in the City of Santa Clara. The 
Meeting is open to the public. We open at </tt><strong><tt>7:00 PM</tt></strong><tt>, with everyone sharing 
information and welcoming new-comers. At </tt><strong><tt>7:30</tt></strong><tt> President Erv Dean will chair a 
short information discussion on AMI affairs, mental health services and Local, 
State or Federal news. The program begins at </tt><strong><tt>8:00</tt></strong><tt> </tt></p>
<p><strong><tt>Mobile Mental Health Team: Lewis Pollard</tt></strong><tt>, Health Services Supervisor. This 
specialty team (previously known as the Jail Diversion Team) will be comprised 
of 5 mental health professionals who will work in concert with the San Jose 
Police Department to find alternatives to incarceration for mentally ill 
individuals. The primary goal is to link mentally ill individuals who are in 
crisis or at risk of incarceration to the mental health system of care, 
including both residential and outpatient programs. This pilot project is only 
funded through June 1997 and for the high need downtown San Jose area.</tt></p>
<p><strong><tt>Young Adult Transitional Outpatient Service Team:</tt></strong><tt> Kim Flatmo, Health Services 
Supervisor. The Young Adult Transitional Service Team was developed to address 
the special needs of the mentally ill young adult transitioning from youth 
services to adult services. Transitional youth between the ages of 17-24 have 
been identified as an under-served population that requires resources and 
treatment philosophies from both the youth and adult mental health systems. 
The team is located at the Fairoaks Mental Health Center site.</tt></p>
<p><strong><tt>ACCESS II:</tt></strong><tt> Meg Paris, Health Services Supervisor. This program provides 
telephone screening and referral for Alcohol and Drug Services, as well as 
Mental Health Information and Referral. This is a joint venture between the 
Department of Drug and Alcohol (</tt><strong><tt>D A</tt></strong><tt>) and Mental Health (</tt><strong><tt>M H</tt></strong><tt>) Departments. The 
program provides a D A and M H central 24-hour telephone information and 
referral service to simplify consumers&#146; efforts to obtain information 
regarding available County resources.</tt></p>
<p><strong><tt>Homeless Service Team:</tt></strong><tt> Kitty Palmer, Health Services Supervisor. The Homeless 
Service Team is comprised of interdepartmental staff from Mental Health, Drug 
and Alcohol, Public Health, and Social Services Agency, coordinating services 
from these and other County departments to provide comprehensive aid to 
homeless mentally ill clients. This is a three year grant awarded to Santa 
Clara County from HUD. The team is located at the Downtown Mental Health 
Center site.</tt></p>
<h2><tt>President's Corner</tt></h2>
<p><strong><tt>Supervisors Race:</tt></strong><tt> the competing four candidates in the November County 
Supervisor elections, two for District 3 (now Supv. Gonzales) and two for 
District 5 (now Supv. McKenna) were all invited to speak at our October AMI 
General meeting. </tt><strong><tt>Barbara Koppel</tt></strong><tt> indicated six weeks before the October General 
meeting that her schedule would not permit her to speak at the Meeting and 
there was no aid who could appear for her (lack of interest?). On the day of 
the Meeting </tt><strong><tt>Patricia Sausedo</tt></strong><tt> called to say she was not feeling well and could 
not attend.</tt></p>
<p><tt>This left us with </tt><strong><tt>Joe Simitian</tt></strong><tt> and </tt><strong><tt>Peter McHugh</tt></strong><tt>, who came at considerable 
personal effort on their part. Simitian and McHugh each talked to us for about 
45 minutes, taking questions and showing real compassion for AMI families and 
clients coping with mental illness and County services. Each indicated a 
knowledge of County M H and wanted to know AMI-SCC member&#146;s experience and 
concerns. McHugh said he would support having a M H paid Family Advocate or 
Ombudsman.</tt></p>
<p><tt>If you favor a candidate for Supervisor, please contact him or her as an AMI 
member. They all need to know about our personal experience coping with family 
members or close friends who are receiving County services related to mental 
illness. AMI members, who can establish a personal supportive relationship 
with a candidate, can help him or her to get elected. Then you can continue to 
help them be a good Supervisor for M H.</tt></p>
<p><tt>Ericka Toth also announced at the Meeting that </tt><strong><tt>Eugene Hyman</tt></strong><tt> has been very 
helpful to the Jail Diversion effort and is worthy of your support for 
Superior Court Judge.</tt></p>
<h3><tt>Health Merger Put on Hold</tt></h3>
<p><tt>The proposed merging of the Alcohol and Drug Dept. with the Mental Health 
Dept. into a Behavioral Health Services Dept. per a March letter from then 
Dept. Directors (Bob Martinez and Robert Garner) was put on hold Sept. 25, 
1996 by a letter from Robert Sillen, Executive Director, Santa Clara Valley 
Health and Hospital System.</tt></p>
<p><tt>A recent review by Soleng Tom and Robert Garner indicated that: 1. There was 
no outside mandate driving the merger., 2. There are significant differences 
in their service systems, in their funding, mandates and client populations. 
3. The shared dual diagnosed populations are a fairly small percentage of the 
total and a number of joint service projects between the Departments have been 
developed for those dual diagnosed. 4. With both Departments , as well as the 
Hospital, initiating comprehensive managed care systems, there is at present 
not enough time or staff resources to plan and develop a new department. </tt></p>
<p><tt>Sillen&#146;s letter concludes &#147;We will develop and monitor those services which 
address the dual diagnosed and we will watch with interest the development and 
operation of two or three behavioral health organizations created by mergers 
between private mental health and drug and alcohol providers.&#148;</tt></p>
<p><tt>With the merger set aside, Sillen will now proceed to recruit and appoint a 
permanent M H Director.</tt></p>
<h3><tt>FDA Approves Olanzapine (Zyprexa)</tt></h3>
<p><tt>The Food and Drug Administration&#146;s approval on Oct. 1, 1996 of Eli Lilly &amp; 
Co.&#146;s Olanzapine under its brand name Zyprexa could help patients with 
schizophrenia who haven&#146;t responded well to existing medications. Dr. Alan 
Schatzberg of Stanford has high hopes for Zyprexa since it is chemically 
similar to Clozapine (Clozaril) but is expected to have less side effects. 
&#147;It&#146;s a potential breakthrough of tremendous magnitude.&#148; said Schatzberg, 
although he cautions that Zyprexa has not yet been adequately compared in 
testing with existing medications</tt></p>
<p><tt>Lilly has shipped Zyprexa to wholesalers and some pharmacies should now have 
supplies. The wholesale price for a 60-day supply has been quoted at $387. Dr. 
Gary Viale, head of the County&#146;s Psychiatric Pharmacy, said he is waiting for 
more test data on the drug before stocking it.</tt></p>
<h3><tt>Marty Craig, AMI Treasurer, Moving to Monterey</tt></h3>
<p><tt>Marty Craig can no longer continue doing her excellent volunteer work as our 
AMI Treasurer. She does our accounts using Quicken on her home IBM type 
computer (also on our AMI Office computer). It can also be done by hand in a 
ledger and takes about 6 to 8 hours work a month either way, per Marty and 
Jack Birnbaum, the prior treasurer. Any volunteers?</tt></p>
