<h2><tt>INFORMATION ON SCHIZOPHRENIA AND CURRENT TREATMENT 
RESEARCH WAS PRESENTED AT AMI SCC GENERAL MEETING 
HELD SEPTEMBER, l996 </tt></h2>
<p align=center><em><tt>By Cole Buxbaum </tt></em></p>
<p><tt>Dr. John Brooks, M.D. and Ph. D., senior resident psychiatrist in the 
department of Psychiatry and Behavioral Science at Stanford University School 
of medicine, working for Dr. Ira Glick, has been conducting a number of 
research studies on new antipsychotic medications. In his talk Dr. Brooks 
described Schizophrenia and the early antipsychotic medications, comparing 
them to the more recent Clozapine and Risperidone, and then discussed the 
newest medications close to approval for use by the United States Food and 
Drug Administration.</tt></p>
<p><tt>Dr. Brooks described schizophrenia is a chronic illness that is usually marked 
by bizarre delusions and auditory hallucinations, referred to as positive 
symptoms, and decreased social interaction and flattening of affect or lack of 
expression, known as negative symptoms. Schizoaffective disorders involve some 
of these, with a mood component as well. Prior to 1952, the only treatment 
available was long term institutionalization and physical restraint.</tt></p>
<p><tt>With the approval of Thorazine in 1952, some medical treatment was possible 
for delusions and auditory hallucinations, making it possible to reduce the 
period of institutionalization in many cases. Unfortunately, the drug was 
marked by a number of undesirable side effects, including movement disorders, 
making it difficult to convince patients to comply. In addition, it did 
nothing to treat the negative symptoms, making them worse in some cases. The 
mechanism for action of this and other later antipsychotics for a number of 
years, was primarily to block one of the neurotransmitter receptors; D2 - 
Dopamine.</tt></p>
<p><tt>In the late 1980&#146;s a newer atypical drug, Clozaril, was approved in the US, 
which targeted (in addition to the Dopamine receptor) the Seratonin 5HT2 
receptor. It has been remarkably effective for many patients, but had the 
unfortunate side effect in about one percent of patients of a sudden marked 
decrease in their white blood cell count, (agranulocytosis) affecting their 
immune system adversely. This currently requires weekly blood testing to 
continuously monitor all patients, increasing the difficulty and cost of use. 
Drooling and constipation are some of the other frequent side effects of the 
drug, making it more difficult for patients to comply. Researchers then began 
to work on substances that model the benefits of Clozaril without some of it&#146;s 
undesirable side effects. This resulted in the release in 1993 of the drug 
Risperidone made by Janssen Pharmaceutical. Risperidone, in addition to 
treating the positive symptoms, produced a marked improvement in negative 
symptoms, in some patients, as does Clozaril, but without the risk of 
agranulocytosis and weekly blood tests. This, as well as a lower price, 
results in a lower total cost for the medication, but still well above that of 
the older more typical antipsychotics, such as Thorazine and Haldol. There is 
also some incidence of orthostatic hypotension (dizziness on standing up) and 
of sedation, but a much lower risk of Parkinsonian like symptoms than 
Thorazine, except in higher doses.</tt></p>
<p><tt>In answer to a question regarding the number of patients that have gone 
successfully from Clozaril to Risperidone, Dr. Brooks explained that this 
would &#147;in some ways be an unfair trial,&#148; since, in general, Clozaril has been 
reserved for patients who are even more refractory to treatment, because of 
its side effect profile requiring blood testing.</tt></p>
<p><tt>A new antipsychotic, Olanzapine (Zyprexa - released by the US FDA on Oct. 1, 
1996 after this presentation) is modeled after Risperidone in that it targets 
both Seratonin and Dopamine neurotransmitter receptors. Olanzapine has been 
proven as effective as Haldol, but with very little evidence of movement 
disorders, such as Parkinsonian like rigidity, or akethesia (restlessness). 
Patients who have previously had movement disorders appear to improve with 
Olanzapine. Dry mouth, drowsiness and occasional anxiety are some side 
effects.</tt></p>
<p><tt>A Seratonin imbalance is often associated with depression, according to Dr. 
Brooks, and selective Seratonin re-uptake inhibitors such as Prozac and Paxil 
also relieve this. However, some seratinergic receptors feed into Dopamine 
receptors; so by blocking the seratinergic pathways you also block Dopamine. 
He explained that by blocking Dopamine through the seratinergic pathways you 
leave fewer side effects than in direct blockage, as by Thorazine.</tt></p>
<p><tt>Seroquel (Quetiapine) is another new drug, similar to Clozapine, that has a 
high affinity for seratinergic receptors but a mild affinity for dopaminergic 
receptors. It has fewer side effects and a lower incidence of movement 
disorders than conventional antipsychotics. There is only a moderate 
improvement in negative symptoms as compared to Risperidone and Clozaril, but 
appears to have a lower incidence of movement disorders than does Risperidone, 
when the latter is given at higher doses of 16 mg per day. Agitation, 
somnolence and mild constipation are some side effects.</tt></p>
<p><tt>The last new drug discussed was Sertindole, where FDA approval is also 
pending. It also targets seratinergic and dopaminergic receptors, but has a 
very low incidence of constipation and dry mouth. It has a long half life, and 
can be given once a day, making for better compliance on the part of the 
patient. There have been no observed movement disorder side effects. There is 
some increased heart rate and slight weight gain.</tt></p>
<p><tt>A question was raised that even though in the short term these newer drugs 
haven&#146;t shown a significant incidence of movement disorders, such as tardive 
dyskinesia , how do we know that they won&#146;t appear with long term use? Dr. 
Brooks explained that we can&#146;t be sure. However he feels that at higher doses 
Risperidone may give rise to movement disorders with a greater incidence than 
Seraquel or Olanzapine.</tt></p>
<p><tt>The direction that research seems to be going, according to Dr. Brooks, is to 
target dopamine through seratonergic pathways to decrease side effects, 
increasing compliance and consequently reduced hospitalization. </tt></p>
<p><tt>In answer to a question regarding akathesia or drug related restlessness, with 
Risperidone as compared to the other drugs discussed, Dr. Brooks said that it 
is lower in all of the newer drugs, including Risperidone, except in some 
patients at higher doses. There are a few who experience it even at low doses, 
however.</tt></p>
<p><tt>Regarding a question on the duration of a patient trial on one of the new 
drugs, Dr. Brooks felt that generally results should appear within 6 weeks of 
achieving a therapeutic dose, although it could take somewhat longer in 
certain cases.</tt></p>
<p><tt></tt>&nbsp;</p>
</body>

</html>
