<title>AMI December</title>
</head>

<body>
<h1 align=center><tt>AMI NEWSLETTER</tt></h1>
<p align=center><strong><tt>The Alliance for the Mentally Ill of Santa Clara County</tt></strong></p>
<table width=100%>
<tr><td width=50%><pre><strong><tt>December  1996</tt></strong> </pre>
</td><td width=50%><div align=right>
<pre><strong><tt>Volume XXIV No. 11</tt></strong> </pre>
</div>
</td></tr>
</table>
<p align=center><em><strong><tt>A Grass Roots Organization</tt></strong></em> </p>
<h2><tt>Holiday Potluck Party features friendship and good food with 
entertainment by Linda Bell&#146;s Group</tt></h2>
<p><tt>AMI-SCC&#146;s annual holiday supper Party will be held the same as last year at Mc Naught Hall of 
the St. Francis Episcopal Church, 1205 Pine Ave., corner of Pine and Newport Avenues, in the 
Willow Glen area of San Jose. On </tt><strong><tt>Tuesday Dec. 10 at 6:00 PM</tt></strong><tt>. Following the supper, to be 
served promptly at 6:30, Linda Bell&#146;s group will lead us in holiday music and song. Plan to 
bring a hot dish, a salad or a dessert with serving spoons for 6 to 8 people. Please call Mary 
Lou and Peter Filice at 408-723-4842 to learn what is needed most. Sodas, hot drinks, cups, 
plates, and eating utensils will be provided. It is a fun time of the year and gives us all a 
chance to get to know others with a common interest in a festive setting. So mark your 
calendar now while you are thinking of it. You will be glad you did!</tt></p>
<h2><tt>November 1 &amp; 2 CAMI Conference Was a Big Success</tt></h2>
<p><tt>Well over 500 people attended the annual statewide CAMI Conference held this year at the San 
Francisco Marriott Hotel next to the Bay just South of the S. F. Airport. Over 30 AMI-SCC 
members were at the Conference plus 30 County Spanish speakers attended a three hour Spanish 
language workshop. All attendees were able to get much new and helpful information</tt></p>
<p><tt>Among the major presentations given the first morning in the Grand Ballroom was an hour 
presentation by Samuel Keith, MD, Chairman, Dept. of Psychiatry, University of New Mexico, 
entitled: Schizophrenia Treatment and Pathophysiology: Our Past , Present and Future. Dr. 
Keith stressed the results of the last decade of brain research, leading to the development of 
much better medications, large scale patient testing and the demonstration of their 
effectiveness in the control of delusions, psychosis and other symptoms.</tt></p>
<p><tt>A second hour presentation was by Terence A. Ketter, MD, Chief of the Bipolar Disorder Clinic, 
Stanford University School of Medicine. His informative talk was entitled: Recent Research in 
Brain Imaging and Treatment of Mood Disorders. We hope to have him speak at a monthly General 
meeting early in 1997, so you can hear him directly. </tt></p>
<p><strong><tt>Lori Schiller</tt></strong><tt> is the author of the book, &#147;</tt><strong><tt>The Quiet Room</tt></strong><tt>&#148; about her experiences, suffering 
from the disease called Schizophrenia. Many felt she gave an inspiring hour and a half 
presentation in the Grand Ballroom entitled: With Hope Comes Miracles. She eloquently 
described how she came back to reality after hitting rock bottom, being very delusional and 
hearing voices. With a change to the medication Closaril and through suppressing/ignoring the 
residual symptoms, she has become a productive, essentially normal functioning person again.	
The final speaker the second day in the Grand Ballroom was </tt><strong><tt>E. Fuller Torrey, MD</tt></strong><tt>, Clinical and 
Research Psychiatrist, Washington, D. C. Dr. Torrey, the author of best seller &#147;</tt><strong><tt>Surviving 
Schizophrenia, A Family Manual</tt></strong><tt>&#148; has a new book just published entitled: </tt><strong><tt>&quot;Out of the Shadows&quot;</tt></strong><tt>. 
He gave a rousing closing speech where he urged all of us to: (1)Work hard toward eliminating 
the public misinformation about Neurobiological Brain Disorders (NBD)., (2) Achieve parity for 
private and public treatment of NBD equal to that for other long term illness, and (3) 
Increase funding for continued research, more low cost housing and disability rehabilitation 
toward fuller employment.</tt></p>
<h3><tt>First CAMI Conference Spanish Language Workshop</tt></h3>
<p><strong><tt>Alejandro Kopelowicz</tt></strong><tt>, Mental Health Director, at San Fernando Mental Health Center, Mission 
Hills, California, was the main speaker in the Spanish Language Work Shop at the CAMI 
Conference. </tt><strong><tt>Arturo Uribe</tt></strong><tt> and </tt><strong><tt>Maria Gil</tt></strong><tt>, Mental Health Specialists, from Community Companions, 
San Jose, were also speakers. </tt></p>
<p><tt>Thirty persons from Santa Clara Co. departed from the Community Companions parking lot. 
Transportation was provided by Santa Clara Co. Mental Health Dept.. Organizations represented 
from our county were Community Companions, Centro de Bien Estar (Gardner Clinic), Avenues to 
Mental Health, Guadalupe Support Group and AMI-SCC.	</tt></p>
<p><tt>Coordinating this first CAMI Conference all Spanish language workshop on mental illness 
information for Santa Clara Co. Latinos, were Soleng Tom, MD, and Maria Fuentes from the SCC 
Mental Health Dept.; Rebecca Woolis and Arturo Uribe from Community Companions; and Eleanor 
Reza and Luisa Perez, members of AMI-SCC. </tt></p>
<p><tt>A total of fifty-five persons were present, coming from four AMI Affiliates: San Bernardino, 
Sonora, Kern, and Santa Clara Counties.</tt></p>
<h2><tt>President's Corner with Erv Dean</tt></h2>
<p><strong><tt>Santa Clara Co. Supervisors Race:</tt></strong><tt> Good News! </tt><strong><tt>Peter McHugh</tt></strong><tt>, for District 3 (to replace Supv. 
Gonzales) and </tt><strong><tt>Joe Simitian</tt></strong><tt>, for District 5 (to replace Supv. McKenna) were both elected in the 
November election. Both came to speak at our October AMI General meeting and showed real 
compassion for AMI families and clients coping with mental illness and County services. They 
both indicated a knowledge of County Mental Health and wanted to know more about AMI-SCC 
member&#146;s experience and problems. McHugh said he would support having a M H paid Family 
Advocate or Ombudsman to represent clients and their families to County service providers.</tt></p>
<p><tt>Supv. </tt><strong><tt>Mike Honda</tt></strong><tt>, was also elected to the State Assembly. His replacement as Supervisor has 
not yet been determined. This will mean that three of the five County Supervisors will be new 
starting in 1997, a year with expected major changes in M H services.</tt></p>
<p><tt>They will all need to know more about our personal good and bad experiences coping with family 
members or close friends who are receiving County services related to mental illness and what 
can be done to make County services even better. We have a Complements/Complaints Form in the 
Office to use to communicate with M H Management and their bosses.</tt></p>
<p><tt>AMI members, who have (or can establish) a personal relationship with their Supervisor, can 
help him or her be a more informed and effective Supervisor. Please call the AMI-SCC Office if 
you are interested in coordinating your efforts with other AMI members</tt></p>
<p><tt>Ericka Toth also announced at the General Meeting that </tt><strong><tt>Eugene Hyman</tt></strong><tt> has been very helpful to 
the Jail Diversion effort and is worthy of your support for Superior Court Judge. We are 
pleased that he was also elected.</tt></p>
<h3><tt>Planned Lifetime Assistance Network (PLAN) </tt></h3>
<p><tt>For Plan or current services information call the AMI-SCC Office at 408.280.7264 or Erv Dean 
at 415.494.0347. Privately paid supplemental services can also be very helpful on a short term 
basis, to initially assess at-home situations or in-community supports and to suggest 
alternatives available to unlock impasses in getting better private or County M H services. 
For PLAN Service Providers: In North County -Call Linda Wohlsen at 415.617.8340. In Central &amp; 
South Co.-call Diana Solves, 408.261.7777.</tt></p>
<h3><tt>Time to Renew Your Annual AMI-SCC Memberships</tt></h3>
<p><tt>We are a California Non-profit, your dues paid in 1996 can be deducted from your income tax. 
Almost all of AMI-SCC funds come from member dues and donations. We forward about a third of 
your dues to CAMI &amp; NAMI to fund them also. Please establish AMI-SCC as your favorite charity 
for your donations at work or directly donate to help AMI do more, if you can. Our major 1997 
goals are to reach more people who should be members and get clients better medications and 
housing.</tt></p>
<h3><tt>Direct Assistance to Adult Clients </tt></h3>
<p>A new clothes closet for donation of clothes for clients is now open at 1080 Minnesota (next door to our AMI-SCC Office) 
and now renamed Nikkis&#146; Place.</p>
<h4 align=center>The Alliance for the Mentally Ill of Santa Clara County </h4>
<h4 align=center>&amp; </h4>
<h4 align=center>The Mental Health Association of Santa Clara County</h4>
<p align=center><font size=3><em><tt>Both ask your help in making the 1996 Holidays a success for mentally ill individuals of all 
ages. You can provide a holiday gift for someone who otherwise might not receive one. </tt></em></font></p>
<p align=left>There are more than 5,000 mentally ill people of all ages in Santa Clara County who are not living in a home environment but 
are in institutional or treatment settings. You can help them celebrate the holidays by providing gifts to prove that somebody 
cares. Suggested gifts:</p>
<p align=center><em><tt>cosmetics, perfumes, combs, brushes, shampoo, soaps, tooth brushes, toote paste, wallets, 
purses, small address books, small note pads, stuffed animals, playing cards, stationery, 
socks, slippers, scarves, gloves, caps, bathrobes, night wearsweat shirts or T-shirts (not in 
colors red or blue) head set radios, calculatorscandy, cookies</tt></em></p>
<p align=left>Gifts should not be wrapped, but wrapping paper and bows are welcome. Plastic, rather than glass containers are preferred. 
All gifts are given directly to people in need who are in psychiatric hospitals and other treatment programs. </p>
<p align=center><font size=3><em><strong><tt>These are the county&#146;s forgotten people. Together we can remember them!</tt></strong></em></font></p>
<p align=center>Gifts or donation checks may be brought to the AMI Office, 1060 Minnesota Avenue, Suite 7, San Jose, CA 95125, or to 
the AMI Holiday Potluck Party at 6:00 PM, Tuesday, December 10 in McNaught Hall of St. Francis Episcopal Church, 
1205 Pine Avenue, corner of Pine and Newport Avenues, in the Willow Glen District of San Jose.</p>
<p align=center><em><strong><tt>Checks should be made out to and mailed to the:</tt></strong></em></p>
<p align=center>Mental Health Association, P.O. Box 18340, San Jose, CA 95158. </p>
<p align=center>All contributions are tax-deductible as allowed by law. For more information call Mary Lou Filice (408-723-4842).</p>
