<head>
<title>AMI October</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body>
<h1 align=center><tt>AMI NEWSLETTER</tt></h1>
<p align=center><strong><tt>The Alliance for the Mentally Ill of Santa Clara County</tt></strong></p>
<table width=100%>
<tr><td width=50%><pre><strong><tt>October 1996</tt></strong></pre>
</td><td width=50%><div align=right>
<pre><strong><tt>Volume XXV No. 10</tt></strong></pre>
</div>
</td></tr>
</table>
<p align=center><em><strong><tt>A Grass Roots Organization</tt></strong></em> </p>
<h2><tt>County Supervisor Candidates to Speak at October 
General Meeting</tt></h2>
<p><tt>Competing candidates running for the Board of Supervisors will be the 
speakers in our General Meeting featured program starting at 8:00 PM on 
Tuesday, Oct. 8, 1996. They include Patricia Saucedo and Peter Mc Hugh 
running for District Three supervisor and Joe Simitian running for 
District Five supervisor. Simitian&#146;s District Five opponent, Barbara 
Koppel was invited but declined to attend due to another engagement. The 
candidates will speak about their goals and what their plans are relative 
to mental health care. </tt></p>
<p><tt>The Monthly General Meeting is held at Hewlett Packard&#146;s Auditorium, 5301 
Stevens Creek Blvd. in the City of Santa Clara. See the map to the right. 
The Meeting is free and those interested are always invited to attend. </tt></p>
<p><tt>It starts at 7:00 PM, with greeting each other and welcoming newcomers. 
At 7:30 we begin a current information session on AMI efforts, local 
health services and pending legislative actions related to mental health 
care.</tt></p>
<h2><tt>October is Mental Illness Awareness Month - End 
the Stigma</tt></h2>
<p><tt>Our Anti-Stigma Committee headed by Ann Sloan, Grace Johnston and Herb 
Slavin is in high gear. They have Mental Illness fact sheets on key 
topics, four different 7 to 14 minute videos, posters, pamphlets, buttons 
and a model short speech for a typical half hour presentation to any 
interested group. They need your help as a group contact person to help 
schedule a presentation at your church, club, coffee klatch, or work 
place. If you have contact with a group which could benefit from a 5 to 
30 minute information session, please call Grace Johnston at 415.968.9337 
or Herb Slavin at 408.531.0932.</tt></p>
<p><strong><tt>The AMI-SCC Office hours have been reduced to 10AM-2PM, work days.</tt></strong></p>
<p><tt>Diana Trawinski, the main stay of our office, had a minor stroke in mid 
August, affecting her ability to speak and swallow. She is recovering at 
the Court Yard Care skilled nursing facility, 340 Northlake Dr., San Jose 
(Near Winchester &amp; Saratoga). Call there at 408.249.0344 for more 
information.</tt></p>
<p><tt>We are looking for an AMI member to be a part-time paid replacement for 
Diana as our Office Manager and Volunteer Coordinator until she recovers. 
Please call Florence Rosen at 408.266.8646 or Erv Dean at 415.494.0347, 
if you know someone who would be interested in filling the position or 
who could help as a temporary transition volunteer at the office.</tt></p>
<h2><tt>President's Corner</tt></h2>
<p align=left><strong><tt>County Supervisors:</tt></strong><tt> Both District 3 (Supv. Gonzales leaving) and District 
5 (Supv. McKenna leaving) have two candidates for election in November 
(our speakers at the October General Meeting -Page 1). Please contact the 
candidates for your district as an AMI member to let them know of your 
experience with the mentally ill. Try to assure that they and their staff 
know how the County Mental Health (M H) Program is working and how it 
could be even better for the whole county.</tt></p>
<p align=left><tt>You can get AMI information brochures and a Resource Handbook covering 
how County M H services are currently provided from the AMI Office. 
Anti-Stigma fact packs are available from our committee (Page 1). A 
personal working relationship with a candidate can help them be fully 
informed about family M H care and help them to get elected. </tt><tt><u>Remember 
County Supervisors have direct authority over County M H treatment, 
especially in their own district and a continuing relationship can be 
helpful to all parties.</u></tt></p>
<p align=center><strong><tt>Collaboration between M H and Religious Organizations</tt></strong></p>
<p align=center><em><tt>by Cole Buxbaum</tt></em></p>
<p><tt>In the Psychiatric Rehabilitation Journal of Boston, Jeff Walters, MD and 
Bernard Neugeboren, PhD, describe the important role that religious 
institutions can have in helping those &#147;who are struggling to cope with 
the devastating isolation of mental illness&#148;. &#147;Successful collaboration 
between consumers, churches, synagogues and M H providers can achieve 
such patient benefits as expanded services, increased client 
normalization, facilitated discharge, and decreased stigmatization,&#148; 
according to the authors. They say that consumer social clubs linked with 
religious institutions and mental health agencies, addressing the needs 
of mental health consumers living in a community, have been very 
effective.</tt></p>
<p><tt>&#147;There are often regularly scheduled weekly meetings for the activity 
group or club at the church or synagogue facilities. The congregation&#146;s 
minister, priest or rabbi frequently serves as a co-leader with an out 
patient staff member and trained volunteers.&#148; A club of this type can 
provide social support for family members and consumers, who also receive 
clinical treatment from community-based mental health services.</tt></p>
<p><tt>The authors say that barriers to implementing such partnerships are 
numerous but not insurmountable and &#147;care needs to be taken to identify 
shared goals and overcome difficulties&#148; in the different organizational 
structures. </tt></p>
<p><tt>Reference: Neugeboren, 8 (1991), Organization, Policy and Practice in 
Human Services. New York, Haworth Press.</tt></p>
<p><strong><tt>Editors Note</tt></strong><tt>- Three examples of monthly group meetings at churches in 
Santa Clara Co. are given on our page 1. They are the two AMI Caring 
Groups, one at the Foothills Congregational Church in Los Altos and one 
at the Catholic Guadalupe Church in East San Jose (which families and 
consumers attend) and the Mood Disorder Group at Christ Episcopal in Los 
Altos. There are also a few urban ministry operations in the County. So 
it can be done!</tt></p>
<p><tt>With one out of five County families directly affected by someone with a 
serious brain disorder, why do you suppose there are not more religious 
groups providing some M H help in a County of 1.6 million people? The 
CAMI Journal on Religious Outreach, 1992 Volume 3 number 4 is available 
at the AMI Office. It provides an overview of the subject, pointing out 
that Religious Organizations are second only to public schools in 
educational activities, have family/individual outreach and help as an 
important objective, but are often way behind the times on mental 
illness. Perhaps their leaders and membership do not realize they have 
AMI members in the organization.</tt></p>
<p><tt>Could it be they seldom hear from one of the members of their 
congregation on the latest facts on brain disorders and how to 
collaborate with service providers in their community? Here is a place 
where you can make a difference. See if you can arrange with your 
religious organization for one of our 20 Anti Stigma volunteer speakers 
to meet with your outreach leader or group in October or November (See 
page one for where to start.)</tt></p>
<p><tt>Deadline to order NARSAD cards is November 1 The NARSAD brochure and 
order form enclosed with this Newsletter must be returned to the AMI-SCC 
Office, 1060 Minnesota Ave., #7, San Jose, CA 95125 by November 1 to be 
included in our Holiday card order. </tt></p>
<p><tt>NARSAD Artworks is a non-profit organization which pays mentally ill 
artists established rates for their work and sends its profits to NARSAD 
to help fund their research grants for outstanding researchers in mental 
illness.</tt></p>
<h2><tt>How Family and Friends Can Help Someone Who 
Resists Taking Medications</tt></h2>
<p align=center><em><tt>By Ronald J. Diamond, M.D.</tt></em></p>
<p align=center><em><tt>Reprinted from</tt></em><tt> </tt><strong><tt>Relapse</tt></strong><tt>, </tt><em><tt>a Yale University magazine</tt></em></p>
<p><tt>The concept of &#147;treatment-resistance&#148; (i.e. won&#146;t take medications) 
assumes that a psychiatrist&#146;s decision about what is good for a patient 
is correct and that there is something wrong with a patient who resists 
the help offered.</tt></p>
<p><tt>It is equally likely, however, that something is wrong with the treatment 
being resisted: Treatment resistance may mean that we want to sell 
something that our patient does not want to buy.</tt></p>
<p><tt>Studies have shown that patients more readily comply with treatment and 
have an improved outcome when they form a collaborative therapeutic 
alliance with their family and therapists. To foster this alliance, both 
need to show more interest in the person&#146;s aspirations and discuss how 
taking neuroleptic medication may help them to meet their own goals. A 
good place to start is by seriously listening to what they say that they 
want for their lives rather than starting by telling them what they 
should do.</tt></p>
<p><tt>It is important to take seriously what a specific client wants, no matter 
how unreasonable it may initially seem. For example, if a patient wants 
to be an astronaut, I can tell him that&#146;s ridiculous or we can discuss 
steps he might take toward attaining this goal. The first strategy closes 
off conversation, while the second opens doors to further 
communication.</tt></p>
<p><tt>Although becoming an astronaut may be an unrealistic goal for someone 
with mental illness, discussing it can help promote intermediate steps 
like taking meds.</tt></p>
<p><tt>Forming a collaboration is not easy. It can take time. I had one patient, 
for example, who refused to talk and refused medication. When I asked her 
what she wanted, she said, &#147;to eat.&#148; So every few weeks we went out to 
lunch. She accused me of trying to bribe her to talk. I acknowledged that 
we both got something out of the lunches..she got to eat and I got her to 
talk. Over the next year she agreed to take her meds and has been doing 
so ever since. We collaborated. Lunch every few weeks was less costly and 
time-consuming than traditional approaches.</tt></p>
<p><tt>Patients will be more likely to take meds if they believe it will improve 
their quality of life. Side effects may deter people from taking meds if 
they see no hope for ever living independently, even with meds.</tt></p>
<p><tt>If a patient believes that meds will allow one to hold a job or socialize 
with friends, they may find the side effects worth tolerating.</tt></p>
<p><strong><tt>Ten tips to reach people resisting medicine </tt></strong></p>
<blockquote>
<p><tt>1. Put treatment in the context of the patients&#146; lives. Be 
concrete about what they will gain by taking meds.</tt></p>
<p><tt>2. Start with the patient&#146;s own agenda. Take seriously what 
they say they want for their lives.</tt></p>
<p><tt>3. Be concerned about whether patients follow through with 
agreed-on treatment plans. Ask specific questions designed to 
open up dialogue rather than put them on the defensive.</tt></p>
<p><tt>4. Involve patients as much as possible in decisions about 
their treatment. Provide information about treatment options 
and resources that patients can use to solve problems and 
enhance their lives.</tt></p>
<p><tt>5. Make sure patients, their families and involved agencies are 
kept informed about the treatment options and plans. Be 
sensitive to the agendas and prejudices of these people and try 
to work with them.</tt></p>
<p><tt>6. Try to involve friends, families, landlords, clergy and 
others as confidentiality allows and as it fits into the 
patient&#146;s own goals and agendas. People in support systems 
exert considerable influence in patient&#146;s decisions.</tt></p>
<p><tt>7. Be willing to be tenacious when necessary. Be flexible about 
how you can engage patients. If they decline meds, focus on 
&#147;safe&#148; topics first.</tt></p>
<p><tt>8. If warranted, connect medication compliance with continued 
community involvement. If necessary, try linking medication use 
with activities the patient needs such as obtaining spending 
money.</tt></p>
<p><tt>9. Accept the fact that some patients refuse treatment or parts 
of treatment despite all efforts. Offer what you can--be it 
bowling or lunch. Patients may be more willing to comply with 
treatment once a relationship is established.</tt></p>
<p><tt>10. Plan for anticipated crises. Use them to build trust. 
Following through on promises will strengthen the therapeutic 
alliance.</tt></p>
</blockquote>
</body>

</html>
</DOC>
