<body>
<h1 align=center><tt>AMI NEWSLETTER</tt></h1>
<p align=center><strong><tt>The Alliance for the Mentally Ill of Santa Clara County</tt></strong></p>
<table width=100%>
<tr><td width=50%><pre><strong><tt>June 1996</tt></strong></pre>
</td><td width=50%><div align=right>
<pre><strong><tt>Volume XXII No. 6</tt></strong></pre>
</div>
</td></tr>
</table>
<p align=center><em><strong><tt>A Grass Roots Organization</tt></strong></em></p>
<h2><tt>Groups Leaders and Consumers to Discuss Training and Support at 
AMI June General Meeting</tt></h2>
<p><tt>Group Leaders and Consumers in training and support groups will be featured at AMI&#146;s General 
Meeting on June 11 at Hewlett Packard Auditorium, 5301 Stevens Creek Blvd. in the City of Santa 
Clara. Paul Ernst, Mira Monte&#146;s leader of Consumer Peer Counseling training, along with trainees, 
will describe their experiences in learning to do volunteer and paid counseling work. Linda Bell, 
Director of the Mental Health Assoc., and Fred Vater, an ACCESS Counselor, along with 
participants in their Support Groups, will also discuss their respective programs and 
experiences. AMI&#146;S Monthly General Meeting is held at the Hewlett Packard Auditorium, 5301 
Stevens Creek Blvd. in the City of Santa Clara. The doors open at 7:00 PM, with everyone sharing 
information and welcoming new-comers. At 7:30 President Erv Dean will chair a useful information 
session on local mental health operations plus State and Federal plans and programs.</tt></p>
<h2><tt>Help! Help! Help!</tt></h2>
<p><tt><u>Additional volunteers are really needed to sustain AMI services as follows:</u></tt></p>
<p><tt>1. AMI Office phone responders to give callers information on public or private mental health 
care resources and AMI experience in coping with mental illness. Office phone help is needed for 
two to four hours, 10 AM to 5 PM, one or more days a week, or at home in early evening hours if 
possible.</tt></p>
<p><tt>2. AMI Office or at home computer word processing or editing to help get this AMI Newsletter and 
other materials printed and mailed monthly.</tt></p>
<p><tt>3. Helping with the set up and hosting of monthly AMI General Meetings, or with the special 
August picnic or December pot luck parties. </tt></p>
<p><strong><tt>Participation is fun, fulfilling and makes you a better consumer also! </tt></strong></p>
<p><tt><u>For more information, please call Diana at the AMI Office or anyone below:</u></tt></p>
<p><tt>Erv Dean, President: leads on Monthly Newsletter, AMI Office committee, General Meetings, and 
Legislative Committee. 415.494.0347. </tt></p>
<p><tt>Sharon Roth, First V P: Housing &amp; Rehabilitation, Caring &amp; Sharing, and Speaker&#146;s Bureau 
Committees 415.299.3331. </tt></p>
<p><tt>Erika Toth, Second V P: Mental Health Board / Subcommittees and Confined Care (Medical or Jail). 
408.259.5000, Ext. 2578. </tt></p>
<p><tt>Philip Carter, Third V P: Liaison with Private M H Providers, Other Private Organizations, and 
Fund Raising Events. 415.856.9375</tt></p>
<h2><tt>President's Corner</tt></h2>
<p><tt>Immediate County Mental Health Concerns: As discussed in the May AMI Newsletter, there are two 
immediate Santa Clara County Mental Health (M H) concerns: (1) The County annual Fiscal Year 
Budget is to be approved in June for implementation July 1, 1996 and (2) Two County Supervisor 
positions are up for election in November.</tt></p>
<p><tt>Budget: The current County Mental Health (M H) budget proposal now includes a net reduction of $2 
million from this year&#146;s budget and is under review by higher County Administration for 
submission to the County Supervisors. Acting M H Director, Dr. Soleng Tom, was asked last month 
to prioritize all M H programs for possible additional M H cuts. At the same time he was asked to 
indicate where extra funds would be used if they were available. The Supervisors recently asked a 
formal Request for Proposal be prepared for a private provider to bid to provide Alcohol And Drug 
services. We feel that these actions indicate the County Supervisors are concerned with further 
possible budget reductions at the State and Federal levels plus the impact of mandated Managed 
Care of all health services. These concerns may be making them considerably more flexible about 
services and program performance/ outcome oriented. AMI Members need to keep informed about plans 
and progress in these areas and not bashful in letting their district&#146;s supervisor know how their 
constituents want them to vote.</tt></p>
<p><tt>Supervisors: In the November General election two new County Supervisors will be elected. Both 
District 3 (Supv. Gonzales vacating) and District 5 (Supv. McKenna vacating) each have two 
candidates vying for election. As indicated in the March AMI Newsletter, we feel all these four 
remaining candidates could be effective County Supervisors.</tt></p>
<p><tt>Each AMI member in these two districts needs to let both of their candidates know as soon as 
possible of our hard earned knowledge and experience with the mentally ill. We want to be assured 
that they know how the County M H Program is working and what it would take to make it even 
better.</tt></p>
<p><tt>A good AMI working relationship with each candidate can help them be fully informed about family 
M H care, help them be elected and assure they are an effective Supervisor when elected. To 
coordinate your Supervisor contact efforts with other AMI members, please call the AMI Office or 
Rod Pence (408) 779-7477, Chairman of our legislative committee. Remember County Supervisors have 
direct control over what County M H treatment is available anywhere at any time in the County.</tt></p>
<p><tt>Further changes in Interim M H Administration: </tt></p>
<p><tt>In an April 30 letter to all M H Providers, Soling Tom, Interim Director of the M H Dept. 
announced the interim appointment of two people to additional responsibilities. Josie Romero was 
given the additional responsibility of managing all ten of the Contract Adult Service Teams. 
While this adds to the Older Adult service teams she continues to manage, the letter said the 
change was not to be an expansion of the Older Adult Division, but was an attempt to have a more 
equitable distribution of Dept. work loads. Nancy Pena, Ph.D. (in addition to continuing as the 
Director of the Family &amp; Children&#146;s Services Division) is now also the Interim Deputy Director of 
the entire M H Dept., directly under. Soleng Tom, MD. Nancy will delegate some of her F &amp; C 
Division tasks to other F &amp; C staff to balance her workload. The interim appointments will be in 
place until further decisions concerning the implementation of the System Redesign Concept and 
the proposed Drug/Alcohol and M H merger are made.</tt></p>
<p><tt>Federal Health Care Reform Bill S. 1028: This very important health legislation passed 100 to 
zero in the U. S. Senate with the Domenici-Wellstone amendment to end discrimination against all 
M H treatment in private insurance nationwide included. The House passed similar legislation 
without the M H amendment. Both are now re-numbered to HR 3103 and both Senate/House appointees 
to a conference are being selected to resolve the differences.</tt></p>
<p><tt>NAMI and all AMI levels including individual AMI members are being very active in continuing to 
support passage of the amended legislation. A form letter was passed out at our last general 
meeting for attendees to sign and mail. Please send them in.</tt></p>
<p><tt>Many in the misguided Insurance and Business community are now stepping up their opposition to 
the Bill and its M H amendment, claiming estimates of additional costs from bygone years will 
ruin them.</tt></p>
<p><tt>Current national estimates of mandating parity for total M H care show a 4.0 percent premium 
increase at maximum. For brain disorder care alone, the national estimates are far lower--2.5 
percent or less. In states that have recently ended insurance discrimination, basically against 
brain disorder care only, such as Texas, Rhode Island, and New Hampshire, actual per month M H 
costs have been between 30 cents and $2.47 per person. None of these monthly insurance costs 
consider the expected offsetting community savings by individual families, businesses or other 
community support or law enforcement groups, incurred when M H is not included in health 
insurance. Doing the right thing has only a minimal overall cost if any!</tt></p>
<p><tt>Please contact as soon as possible your House and Senate representatives (or the presumptive 
Presidential candidates) any way you know how, to let them know a constituent strongly supports 
this bill and its M H amendment and ask them to personally help get it passed.</tt></p>
<p><tt>Contact the AMI Office if you need more information.</tt></p>
<h2><tt>Good Samaritan Health Systems Foundation Funds</tt></h2>
<p><em><tt>by Erika Toth, AMI Vice President</tt></em></p>
<p><tt>Due to the recent purchase of the non-profit Good Samaritan Hospital by the for-profit Columbia 
Health System Corporation, a portion of the assets (acquired through the prior non-profit status) 
has been required to be reserved for public health financing. This has resulted in Columbia 
creating a non-profit Good Samaritan Health Systems (GSHS) Foundation to control and distribute 
the money for public health needs.</tt></p>
<p><tt>On May 14, 1996, I attended the first of several public hearings planned to be held by the GSHS 
Foundation and the County Supervisors on what should be done with the estimated 56 to 72 billion 
dollars available in the Foundation.. I spoke (as only one of two Mental Health advocates) at the 
meeting, representing both AMI-SCC and the County Mental Health Board. I pleaded that our County 
Supervisors gain control and assure distribution of needed money within our Public Health System 
for Mental Health (M H) services.</tt></p>
<p><tt>At the meeting there seemed to be an emerging public lack of trust and public information on how 
much Foundation money there actually was and whether it would be spent on public health care 
needs. There are some indications that the Foundation plans to use the fund only to supplement 
some of the programs of the Columbia Health Systems Corp.. The Foundation seemed less than 
forthcoming on both the total money available and their plans AMI Members need to attend the 
upcoming public hearings, shown in the box below, especially those held in their own Supervisor&#146;s 
area, to advocate for preserving as much of the existing minimal M H services as possible through 
the next fiscal year. The next 1996-1997 FY County M H proposed budget now shows a cut of $2 
million below this year and does not include further cuts being discussed at the State and 
Federal levels. These cuts could severely reduce M H community supports and case management 
services for our loved ones. We should advocate for the use of GSHS Foundation funds in the near 
term as needed to compensate for these cuts and maintain these essential services until County 
revenues improve.</tt></p>
<p><tt>Letters to the California State Attorney General, urging him to see that the Foundation complies 
with all non-profit fund conversion legal requirements, would also be most helpful. You can write 
to him as follows: Daniel Lungren, 1515 K St. No. 511, Sacramento, CA 95814</tt></p>
<h2><tt>FLASH! FLASH!</tt></h2>
<p><tt>Public Invited to Tuesday Evening, May 28, Meeting in San Jose on Mental Health Jail Diversion 
Recommendations.</tt></p>
<p><tt>Supervisor Jim Beal and the Santa Clara County Mental Health Jail Diversion Steering Committee 
are pleased to Announce their &#147;policy recommendations&#148; at a May 28 open community meeting. The 
meeting will be held at the Public Health Center Auditorium, 2220 Moorpark Ave (at the North/West 
corner of Moorpark and Bascom) in San Jose, from 7:00 p.m. to 9:00 p.m. The goal of the diverse 
21 member leadership Committee is to develop a comprehensive County/City system to divert the 
mentally ill from jail for minor offenses by creating a plan that is both fiscally and morally 
responsible. After numerous meetings, researching issues and conducting an intensive public input 
process, policy recommendations have been developed by the Committee. These recommendations will 
be presented to an open meeting of the County Board of Supervisors in the month of June. The 
prior public input has been incorporated into the recommendations, however, your additional 
feedback is needed at both meetings.</tt></p>
<p><tt>Refreshments will be served during the evening meeting. Please RSVP for the evening meeting by 
calling 408-299-3924.</tt></p>
<p><tt>(Editor&#146;s Note: The above actions are even more important now that the current AMI sponsored 
State legislation on diversion of the mentally ill from jail for minor offenses is apparently 
stalled indefinitely due to prosecuting attorney&#146;s disagreements with the bill&#146;s definition of 
&#147;minor offenses&#148; and pleas for local flexibility.</tt></p>
<p><tt>It is our understanding that one of the Committee&#146;s recommendations is to consider a pilot M H 
Crisis Response team (based on a successful Berkeley team model) in the Downtown and East side 
areas of San Jose. This has been sorely needed for several years, both for direct response 
assistance to police and sheriff personnel in crisis cases but also for better training of 
personnel likely to be involved with the mentally ill.)</tt></p>
<h2><tt>PLEASE CONTINUE SENDING IN LUCKY &amp; LONG&#146;S RECEIPTS</tt></h2>
<p><tt>Jean Pence, AMI-SCC Fund Raising Chairperson, recently reported that AMI members have turned in 
over $4,000 in Lucky and Long&#146;s store sales receipts. Please continue to send in these receipts 
to the AMI Office, and encourage friends and neighbors to save or collect them for you for us. 
Final remuneration by points for profit will be awarded to AMI at the end of the year. We will 
report our total fund raising results at that time.</tt></p>
<h2><tt>Support Services Available for Mental Health Clients at 
Community Colleges and San Jose State University</tt></h2>
<p><em><tt>by Diana Trawinski</tt></em></p>
<p><tt>Now is the time for your loved one to consider fall enrollment in a recreational or skills 
building class at local public schools. The seven community colleges in Santa Clara County and 
San Jose State University provide services for mental health clients in their extra service, 
student disability programs. These include priority registration, alternative test taking 
arrangements, smaller group instruction, tutoring, liaison with faculty, etc. Tuition is waived 
at the community colleges for adult consumers with annual incomes below $7600.</tt></p>
<p><tt>AMI-SCC can provide personal support for clients interested in returning to school. The AMI 
Office has volunteers who will visit a campus with clients and assist them in applying for 
admission and registering for their selected classes in the school of their choice. The 
volunteers can assist in applying for tuition waivers and federal grants. They can also connect 
students to school Disability Program Counselors for help in selecting classes and other 
services.</tt></p>
<p><tt>In the past year, twenty clients have contacted the AMI office for assistance and/or information 
about school attendance. We have assisted them in registering for classes at DeAnza, Evergreen, 
Mission, San Jose City College, West Valley, and San Jose State University. The student&#145;s 
results, including student job placement assistance, have been excellent. Arrangements should be 
made soon for attendance this fall.</tt></p>
<p><tt>(Note: AMI Members wanting to assist consumers in this program should call Diana at the AMI 
Office.)</tt></p>
<h2><tt>ANTI-STIGMA COMMITTEE NEEDS HELP</tt></h2>
<p><em><tt>By Ann Sloan</tt></em></p>
<p><tt>Your AMI&#146;s newly formed committee to publicize NAMI&#146;s Campaign to Remove the Stigma October &#145;96, 
needs your help. We need volunteers to present informative M H talks and written materials to 
their business, fraternal, religious group; union affiliations, trade affiliations, etc.--any 
group with which you may be associated. We need your group information to be able to supply 
prepared material for running in your organization&#146;s published newsletters to educate their 
members. We are obtaining/preparing videos for TV spots for all the local stations and tapes for 
radio broadcasts for all the radio stations. We also have an energized group of member/consumer 
volunteers who will help in the distribution of posters and flyers to all libraries, police 
departments, medical centers and hospitals. Our Hispanic members are planning events at senior 
centers and for the Sept. 16, Mexico&#146;s Independence Day Celebrations.</tt></p>
<p><tt>Please join us. We are an energized group and would appreciate your ideas, your help. Our next 
meeting is May 28 at 4:30 PM. Call Ann Sloan for details and if you can help in any way. (415) 
851 2825 (eves., Sat. - Mon.) We are going to erase the stigma of mental illness which is a 
neurobiological illness of the brain. Those afflicted are deserving of all the compassion and 
benefits afforded those with any other illness.</tt></p>
<h2><tt>HOUSING NEEDED FOR CONSUMERS</tt></h2>
<p><em><tt>By Elizabeth Seaman</tt></em></p>
<p><tt>An urgent housing need now exists for four women who are in their thirties to fifties, sharing a 
four-bedroom, three-bathroom apartment in northern Mountain View. The length of their residency 
in this apartment ranges from 2 to 8 years, a very stable group who would like to stay together. </tt></p>
<p><tt>Last year, when the rent was raised to $1500 in February, 1995, Miramonte M H Services absorbed 
the increase, as the women were already each paying half or more of their monthly SSI payments 
($626) for rent. Now the rent is being raised an additional $500 on 30 days notice. Miramonte is 
generously paying the additional amount for one month, so they will have to find a new home by 
June 30. </tt></p>
<p><tt>They can afford to pay together no more than $1300 for rent without a subsidy. Can the members of 
this family find a home that will accommodate all of them or do they have to break up? Their 
relatives help them in whatever ways they can but that does not bridge the gap between their 
income and needs.</tt></p>
<p><tt>If you have any suggestions or offers of below-market-rate housing, or tax deductible direct 
contributions or pledges to Miramonte Mental Health Services to supplement the rent of these 
women and others like them, please contact Karen Wine at Miramonte, (415) 617 1754.</tt></p>
<h2><tt>NEW DUAL DIAGNOSIS PROGRAM IS BEGINNING</tt></h2>
<p><em><tt>by Michael Whitney</tt></em></p>
<p><tt>The StarFire Dual Diagnosis Program is a new Program for clients who have a diagnosis of both 
mental illness and substance abuse. The StarFire group will develop a Dual Community with their 
own dual 12 step meetings, Dual Sponsors and supportive housing. Clients, family members and 
staff, who support dual diagnosis work are invited to help generate the program. A licensed 
boarding house will be the first residential project. Donations of household goods, furniture and 
your expertise are needed. Call Michael Whitney at (408) 294-9347 to help out. Consumers can get 
on the established waiting list now.</tt></p>
<p><tt>A Stanford Dept. of Psychiatry SEROQUEL Study needs patients with schizophrenia or 
schizoaffective disorder for an open, randomized comparison of the investigational antipsychotic 
drug SEROQUEL with usual-care drugs for 52 weeks to determine relative effectiveness. The 
medication will be furnished. All other medical services, hospital care, etc. will be at the 
client&#146;s or carrier&#146;s cost. Call Joy Knapp, study coordinator at (415) 723-6678 for more 
information.</tt></p>
<h2><tt>Advocates for Consumer Legal Rights and for Traumatic Brain 
Injury Improved Care Spoke at AMI April Meeting</tt></h2>
<p><em><tt>By Cole Buxbaum</tt></em></p>
<p><tt>Kyra Kazantzis, Directing Attorney for Mental Health Advocacy Project in San Jose, and Terry 
Stimpson, MS, Rehabilitation Counselor for the Traumatic Brain Injury Advocacy Project in San 
Jose, discussed their programs at the April l996 AMI General Meeting.</tt></p>
<p><tt>Kyra Kazantzis described the Mental Health Advocacy Project (PHAP) as one of four programs of the 
Santa Clara County Law Foundation. As shown in a brochure distributed by Kazantzis, their goal is 
to &#147;empower people identified as mentally or developmentally disabled to live more independent, 
secure and satisfying lives through the enforcement of their legal rights and the advancement of 
their social and economic well-being&#148;. They are an independent state mandated organization. Her 
group, &#147;Patient&#146;s Rights Advocates&#148;, within the Project has five attorneys and a total staff of 
ten, who represent people firstly in civil commitment hearings, when the clients are held 
involuntarily. (The Public Defender handles such cases when criminal action is involved.)</tt></p>
<p><tt>In instances where a person refuses medication, the MHAP represents them before an administrative 
law judge. In all cases, probable cause of rights violation must be found for the MHAP to 
continue to advocate for the person. A second role is that of advocating for a patient or for a 
group of patients in a care facility, if there is evidence of rights violation as found by a MHAP 
attorney. A report is written describing the violations, the law involved, and the measures to 
correct them. A copy is sent to the local mental health director and the state office of 
patients&#146; rights.</tt></p>
<p><tt>Kazantzis distributed a copy of a patients rights information sheet, listing those rights that 
cannot be denied in general and those when hospitalized. Although the right to privacy is 
required for all mental health consumers, it can be compromised, in fact, when the patient is 
hospitalized, when there is good cause. Theoretically a right should be abridged only in the 
least restrictive way. For instance, if a patient is displaying potentially violent behavior 
toward a parent, the care givers may restrict all visits by that parent but permit others to see 
him or her. In answer to a listener&#146;s question, the MHAP is not normally notified of rights 
violations unless a consumer or significant other requests them to investigate.</tt></p>
<p><tt>Housing and benefits are two other areas in which the MHAP can become involved. For instance, 
when SSI has been denied they will handle the appeal. They also do a significant number of 
eviction defense actions in the housing area. In closing, Kazantzis emphasized that, where 
appropriate, they will initiate an action where the consumer is not in a position to call them. </tt></p>
<p><tt>Each year more than 373,000 Americans are hospitalized as a result of traumatic brain injury with 
about l00,000 of these ending with long term injuries profoundly affecting their social and 
business lives. </tt></p>
<p><tt>Terry Stimpson of the Traumatic Brain Injury Advocacy Project began her presentation by asking 
for a show of hands of those who are or have been involved with a person who received a traumatic 
brain injury and five held up their hands. She explained that injuries due to anoxia or brain 
tumor are not included in this class, although the results are frequently similar. A trauma is 
from an external force or blow normally occurring as a result of an accident.</tt></p>
<p><tt>Unfortunately according to Stimpson there has been very little funding allocated in regional 
centers to address this widespread problem. Brain injury results in a wide variety of 
consequences as described in a &#147;Fact Sheet&#148; distributed to the audience, including cognitive, 
physical, and emotional brain disorders. Although there are many problems in common with those of 
the mentally ill, there are no specific public policies to govern the care of the traumatically 
brain injured. When such an injured person displays psychiatric type problems, he or she may find 
access to some public support via the mental health services route. The Kyra&#146;s Mental Health 
Advocacy Project has been a source of some assistance in this area. </tt></p>
<p><tt>The California Head Injury Foundation, a consumer organization affiliated with the National Head 
Injury Foundation, has been in existence since l980. It was founded by family members with a 
board composed of survivors, professionals and family members. Brain injury can range from mild 
to severe, resulting in patients that have many kinds of needs and problems including substance 
abuse. Their aim is to link up with existing resources on the basis of disability. They sit in 
various task forces including the Department of Rehabilitation Task Force and the Mental Health 
Master Plan Council.Santa Clara County alone has over 22 new brain injuries per year. They may 
result in short or long term memory loss, spatial orientation loss, seizures, vision impairment , 
anxiety and depression, mood swings, and other manifestations. Attention and concentration 
problems make it difficult to hold a job. A loving, caring family, social relationships, and good 
care are all important. Although 80% of all brain injuries are not major, they almost all result 
in some long term neurological alteration affecting performance.</tt></p>
<p><tt>Stimpson pointed out that Medi-Cal does not cover brain injured patients and some of the 
resources available to the mentally ill are normally not appropriate to the brain injured. She 
asked that AMI members welcome these brain disabled people, who are not adequately supported 
elsewhere and collaborate with their organizations.(Note: Copies of materials handed out by 
Program Speakers are usually available afterward at the AMI Office.)</tt></p>
<p><tt></tt>&nbsp;</p>
</body>

