<p align=center><em><strong><tt>A Grass Roots Organization</tt></strong></em> </p>
<h2 align=center><tt>SSI &amp; SSDI Eligibility and Financial Benefits Will be 
Presented at AMI&#146;s February General Meeting </tt></h2>
<p align=left><tt>Ellen Holloway, local Claims Representative for Social Security, will be the 
featured speaker for AMI&#146;s General Meeting to be held February 11 at the Hewlett 
Packard Auditorium, 5301 Stevens Creek Blvd. in the City of Santa Clara (See the 
Map below). All our Meetings are open to the general public.</tt></p>
<p align=left><tt>Ms. Holloway will explain the procedures and eligibility rules for applying for 
Supplemental Security Income (SSI) or Social Security Disability Insurance 
(SSDI) financial benefits for our loved ones. Both of these financial assistance 
programs are administered by her Social Security Office. She will also cover the 
many program changes which are occurring. </tt></p>
<p align=left><tt>The Meeting starts at 7:00 PM, with everyone sharing information and welcoming 
new-comers. At 7:30 PM President Erv Dean will chair a short information 
discussion on AMI affairs, mental health services and Local, State or Federal 
news. The featured Program begins at 8:00 PM.</tt></p>
<h2>Please Join or Renew Your Annual AMI-SCC Membership 
Now!</h2>
<p>Our major 1997 goals are: 1. To give you and the public more information on coping with brain disorders, 
2. To reach more people like you who should participate with us as members, and 3. To enhance public 
and private community M H services, including housing. To accomplish movement towards these goals, we 
need more volunteers and more funds for one part time AMI Office and Community Outreach 
Coordinator. AMI-SCC is a volunteer California Non-profit Corporation with a volunteer Board.</p>
<p>Almost all of AMI-SCC, CAMI and NAMI operating funds come from annual local AMI dues and 
donations. If you have not become a new AMI-SCC member (or renewed) after the month of September 
1996, please join or renew now, so that we do not have to go to the trouble and expense of a special 
mailing to you. You can use the convenient form on the back page of this newsletter and help AMI, CAMI 
and NAMI continue working for you all through 1997.</p>
<p>Also please consider making AMI-SCC your designated charity for your donations at work or consider a 
direct donation on our form to help AMI-SCC do more to reduce the suffering of families and ill relatives 
like yours.</p>
<h2>Special Recognition for AMI-SCC Volunteers'</h2>
<p>Special thanks to the following volunteers in the AMI Office:</p>
<p><u>Phone Answerers:</u> Edwina Adoradio, Teddy Avakoff, Ann Barclay, Betty Pfister, Mary Lou Filice and 
Ann Youngman.</p>
<p><u>AMI Newsletter preparation and mailing:</u> Dave Barclay, Delsie Mc Grath, and Pearl Owen. </p>
<p><u>Data Entry:</u> Helen Knisely and Donna Mechanic.And last but not least, the <u>Office Committee Chairperson:</u> 
Florence Rosen. All their efforts are essential to keeping AMI in operation, responding to members and the 
public&#146;s need for information on coping with Neurological Brain Disorders (NBD). Citizenship Required 
for SSI Recipients by August 1997. </p>
<p>Although the Federal Welfare Reform Act was passed to create a new &#147;welfare to work&#148; mandate, the 
largest impact of the legislation--both human and fiscal--will be on recipients of SSI, the federal assistance 
program which helps the aged, blind or disabled. By August 1997, virtually all legal permanent residents, 
who are non-citizens, may be terminated from SSI. In California 41% of SSI recipients are non-citizens. </p>
<p>A special interest of ours are those with NBD who are living in board and cares, since SSI pays for their 
tenancy. Additionally, as Medi-Cal is tied into SSI, it may also be canceled for these folks, if Gov. Wilson 
chooses that option.</p>
<p>Obtaining citizenship normally requires a minimum of 6 months. It is imperative that a concerted effort be 
made to gain citizenship as soon as possible for all non-citizens with NBD. Otherwise more Californians 
with mental illness will be deserted to our streets and jails at great cost to our counties and our overall 
system.</p>
<p>Thanks to Carla Jacobs, CAMI Board Member for this information. Our AMI Office has a copy of her 
Getting Citizenship package by attorneys at Protection and Advocacy.</p>
<p>Carla can be reached at 203 Argonne Ave. B104, Long Beach, CA 90803. Phone 310-438-4174 FAX 
310-434-6019.</p>
<h2>BARBARA ARONS PAVILION EDUCATIONAL SERIES 
FOR WINTER 1997</h2>
<p>2/11/97 6-7PM Evaluation of psychiatric patients. Legal issues and resources in the community for 
patients.</p>
<p>2/25/97 11:30-12:30PM Psychiatric evaluation and treatment in an inpatient setting.</p>
<p>3/11/97 6-7PM Psychiatric diagnoses and treatment.</p>
<p>3/25/97 11:30-12:30PM Families coping with mental illness.</p>
<p>4/8/97 6-7PM Psychiatric medications</p>
<p>4/22/97 6-7PM Services for Hispanic psychiatric patients and their families. Call Megan George at 
408-885-6141 for info.</p>
<h2>Planned Lifetime Assistance Network (PLAN)</h2>
<p>Ask Yourself:</p>
<p>[] Could you use a break, a vacation from worry?</p>
<p>[] Is it difficult for you to spend as much time as</p>
<p>[] you would like with your ill family member?</p>
<p>[] Does he or she need more social contact?</p>
<p>[] Would you like to see your loved one get out more?</p>
<p>Have something meaningful to do?</p>
<p>Find a better place to live?</p>
<p>If you checked any of the above, help is available now.</p>
<p>The PLAN M H Service Provider for Santa Clara and Alameda County clients was changed from the San 
Mateo Lodge to two existing Santa Clara Co. M H Contract Agencies in October 1996. These Agencies 
were consolidated January 1, 1997 into the Alliance for Community Care (ACC).</p>
<p>PLAN and ACC, can provide services to all families who want paid supplemental M H services. ACC 
offers a wider choice of supplemental M H services to better fit individual family / client needs. Their 
services are priced to fit the varying difficulty and time needed for ACC to achieve each family&#146;s near term 
or long term objectives in each situation.</p>
<p>The PLAN Office in Los Angeles, assisted in Santa Clara County by AMI-SCC, will oversee ACC 
PLAN services in six month contract intervals. PLAN is also prepared to help with information on a model 
longer term California Special Needs Trust and to provide Trustee services in accord with a family will and 
trust. For pay as you go services under PLAN with AMI oversight information, call Erv Dean at 
415-494-0347.</p>
<p>Professional, privately paid, short term, supplemental ACC services (prior to signing up for longer term 
services under PLAN) are also available and can be very helpful to families unable to cope with a family 
member&#146;s mental illness. ACC can assist in quickly assessing the short term need and benefits to a family 
by obtaining supplemental at-home services or in-community services beyond the public or private services 
they may or may not have. Brief phone contacts and a visit with Linda Wohlsen at ACC can often identify 
ways to overcome existing roadblocks to getting more effective private or County M H services. For 
further information, phone Linda Wohlsen at 415.617.1751</p>
<h2>Research on Brain Leads to Designer Drugs&#148;</h2>
<p><em>By Daniel Goleman</em></p>
<p><em>Summarized from the New York Times of 11/19/96 by Cole Buxbaum</em></p>
<p>Daniel Goleman, staff writer for the New York Times, wrote a vivid and informative article dealing with the 
latest advances in research and development of psychiatric medications. According to Goleman, many new 
medications may now be found because of progress in neuroscience research, &#147;the fruit of the much 
vaunted 1990 &#147;Decade of the Brain, an initiative by the National Institute of Mental Health.&#148; Until recently 
neuroscientists had thought that there were just one or two variations of each type of brain receptor, the 
proteins in and on brain cells that receive chemical messages, affecting our emotions and thoughts. Now 
they realize there may be a hundred or more variations of a given receptor.</p>
<p>Fifteen different receptors have now been found for seratonin, a neurotransmitter involved in depression; 
five for dopamine implicated in symptoms of schizophrenia; six kinds for norepinephrine, etc.. (Buxbaum 
Note: Neurotransmitters and chemicals are released by nerve cells or neurons to communicate with each 
other. When a neurotransmitter is released, it attaches itself or binds to a receptor in the wall of a nearby 
cell.)</p>
<p>Present psychiatric medications lessen or increase activity of all the receptors for a class of neurotransmitter 
like seratonin indiscriminately and cause unwanted side effects, Goleman said. The next breed of drugs may 
target a specific carrier for a symptom in question and so will offer greater results with fewer side 
effects.</p>
<p>The greatest enthusiasm comes from neuroscientists at pharmaceutical companies, according to Goleman. 
Dr. Steven Paul, head of neuroscience research at Eli Lilly and Company (previously with the National 
Institute for Mental Health) says, &#147;The coming generation of psychiatric medications will be ten times better 
than we have now.&#148;</p>
<p>Goleman says that others are more cautious, such as Dr. Hyman, director of the Mental Health Agency 
who believes, &#147;it&#146;s not just a matter of discovering new receptors to yield new medications but that there is 
lots of basic research to do before we can best use discoveries (such as what circuits they connect with 
and what behavior they regulate) to yield new medications.&#148;</p>
<p>Dr. Edward Bradley, senior vice president for clinical research at Sanofir-Winthrop, Inc., indicates that 
they are already &#147;betting on this strategy.&#148; They have medications specific for seratonin receptors and will 
start testing them in the U. S. by the end of the year.&#148;</p>
<p>Goleman explains that with molecular biology offering the first precise map of receptors, new automated 
methods in chemistry allow production of an array of molecules, systematically adding small pieces to 
concoct huge numbers of subtly different compounds. Rapid fire testing of hundreds of thousands of 
compounds to find any that have a desired effect on target receptors can shrink development time from 
years to months.</p>
<p>Dr. Richard Wienberg, a neuroscientist at the University of North Carolina, however, says that 
&#147;discovering that seratonin has fifteen receptors instead of just two or three is a bit like having a fuse box 
containing fifteen fuses with just two or three labeled, the next step is to determine what circuits all those 
unmarked fuses control.&#148;</p>
<p>The problem, according to Goleman, is that current psychiatric medications are crude in their action. Even 
the most recently introduced drugs such as the new class of psychiatric medications that include Risperdol, 
Olanzapine and Sertindole, &#147;are the last of the older generation because they act at many sites,&#148; said Dr. 
John Tallman, scientific director of Neurogen. For example, Prozac, which reduces depression by 
interfering with the ability of receptors to reabsorb the neurotransmitter seratonin, acts on all the seratonin 
receptors, such as those affecting sexual desire and digestion. </p>
<p>&#147;Wouldn&#146;t it be better,&#148; Dr. Hyman asked, &#147;to target just those seratonin receptors that regulate mood and 
leave alone those for other things like sexual activity?&#148;</p>
<p>Goleman ends his article by saying that the potential use of genetic testing may make it possible to identify 
people with brain patterns most susceptible to a given mental illness long before the disease begins.</p>
<p>In another article is the same issue, Goleman reports that Neurogen Corporation in conjunction with 
Shering-Plough is testing a compound that affects only the dopamine D4 receptor which is thought to be 
involved in cognitive aspects of schizophrenia. In addition Merck Corporation is testing compounds for 
treating depression that target a specific seratonin-2 receptor that is thought to have a role in psychotic 
hallucinations.</p>
<h2>EARL CALKINS MEMORIAL FUND ESTABLISHED</h2>
<p>Earl Calkins, a long time AMI-SCC volunteer and contributor, died peacefully at home on November 23, 
1996, after a long illness. A gentle, kind spirit, he devoted many years of support to the mentally ill and 
their families. He is survived by his wife, Carole (former head of Perma Housing); son William; daughters; 
Dennie, Callie, Marel and grandchildren; Kyle, Karlie, Elizabeth and Phoebe, who will all miss him very 
much.</p>
<p>In lieu of a memorial service, friends were invited on December 5th to a dedication ceremony for a new 
Leo Tolstoy Library established at Community Companions by Carole and a reception. Many 
contributions were made to her Earl Calkins Endowment Fund For the Mentally Ill.. Additional Memorial 
Gifts to the Fund may be sent to the Alliance for Community Care, 2001 The Alameda, San Jose, CA 
95126 or to The Alliance for the Mentally Ill, 1060 Minnesota Ave. San Jose, CA 95125.</p>
<p>Among many other contributions, Earl served with distinction on the AMI-SCC Board as Treasurer from 
December 1985 until March 1991.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
