<p align=center><em><strong><tt>A Grass Roots Organization</tt></strong></em></p>
<h2><tt>Permahousing Merger with Community Companions to be Discussed at AMI July General Meeting</tt></h2>
<p><tt>Mary Williams, Executive Director of Community Companions (CC) and Carole Calkins, Director of the Permahousing Division of Housing for (CC) will explain the merger of their two private non-profit agencies at our AMI Monthly General Meeting to be held on Tuesday evening, July 9th.
	Mary Williams will give us a vision of how her organization and other County, non-profit Mental Health 
contractors expect to handle the next 
12 months and what contractor services
we can expect in the future.
	AMIS Monthly General Meet-
ing is held at the Hewlett Packard Aud-
itorium, 5301 Stevens Creek Blvd. in 
the City of Santa Clara.  The Meeting is 
free and open to the public.  We begin at 7:00 PM, with everyone sharing information and welcoming new-comers.  At 7:30 President Erv Dean will chair a general information discussion on AMI matters, local mental health services and local, State or Federal government actions.
</tt></p>
<h2><tt>Evidence Mounting for Role of Fetal Damage
in Schizophrenia
</tt></h2>

<p><tt>The New York Times, May 28, 1996, carried the above head line on pg. 28 and went on to cite several research studies indicating that in half or more cases of later diagnosed schizophrenia, the seeds of the disorder may actually be sown in the second trimester of a pregnancy.  The research explains why neuroscientists now believe several factors, such as a flu or other viruses, or malnutrition, and/or genetic predisposition can produce abnormalities in fetal brain growth and development in the second trimester.
	Another article in the Los Angeles Times of April 29, 1996 cited research by sibling Meggin Hollister, which showed that a difference in the mothers and the fetuss blood type can also produce this result during pregnancy, when the mother produces allergic antibodies harmful to her fetus.  In this case if the blood type difference is known early, the mother can be given medication to prevent antibody development, preventing the damage.
	Some question these findings saying no symptoms of schizophrenia appear for almost two decades after birth.  A British 43 year study has found subtle childhood differences in those who later developed the disease.  There were no gross abnormalities, but a lifelong delayed maturation of a couple weeks to a few months in their brain function in sitting up or later hand movements, suggest subtle abnormalities in neural development in the cortex..  Autopsies of patients brains also confirm wayward cell development in the cortex, which takes place almost entirely during the second trimester.
</tt></p>
<h2><tt>President's Corner</tt></h2>
<p><tt><b>County Budget:</b> The County Mental Health (M H) proposed budget still included a net reduction of $2 million from this years programs at the time this newsletter went to press on June 16.  Supervisor public budget hearings were to be held the next week.  They were to consider adding about $400 thousand for a one year pilot Jail Diversion project (See below.)
</tt></p>
<p><tt><b>County Supervisors:</b> As you know two new County Supervisors will be elected this November.  One in District 3 (now Supv. Gonzales) and one in District 5 (now Supv. McKenna).  This is the time AMI members in all districts should contact their incumbents and candidates to let them know of your concerns with care for the Countys mentally ill and dual diagnosed.  Assure yourself that they know how the County M H Program is working and what it takes to make it even better.  We can help them be fully informed about effective family M H care.  Please call the AMI Office to let us know of Supervisor contacts and results.  It is often best to visit them with other AMI members.  Please work together and with the AMI Office.
Remember, County Supervisors have direct management control over all County health treatment services in the County.
</tt></p>
<h2><tt>Update: Jail Diversion</tt></h2>
<p><em><tt>by Erika Toth, AMI Vice President</tt></em></p>
<p><tt>On May 28, 1996, the County Board of Supervisors unanimously approved Supervisor Jim Bealls Steering Committees plan for diverting mentally ill persons from jail when minor, non-violent crimes might be charged.  On June 18th, the Board will hold a public hearing and vote on the additional budget allocations required for one year funding of the proposed Jail Diversion Plan.  AMI members were asked at the AMI General Meeting to attend and support approval.

	Supervisor Bealls Steering Committee proposed a one year pilot project that would cover Downtown San Jose, East San Jose and the McKinley area as being a limited, concentrated area of high need.  The Areas Sobering Station would be expanded and a new Mobile Crisis Response Team would be created to assist the Police in evaluating and redirecting minor offenders in crisis to other community programs or placements.  Thus, hopefully, saving the County money by keeping harmless mentally ill people out of jail and providing a better treatment oriented alternative for our loved ones.

	We are most grateful to Supervisor Beall for his leadership and to all the members of his committee for their work and support in developing this plan.  We are also greatly appreciative of the community support we received from KBAY Radio Station and the San Jose Mercury News.  Especially, we thank Melody Peterson, Donna Alvarado and Jim Trotter for their dedicated and compassionate reporting.  And, especially, we thank the Editor.  When we needed it and asked for Editorial support, we received it (June 7, 1996).  We are truly grateful to everyone who helped get this done.
</tt></p>

<h2><tt>Erase the Stigma Committee </tt></h2>
<p><tt>Discrimination in insurance coverage, housing, employment and access to services will not end until we work together to make discrimination socially unacceptable.  Your AMI October 96 Campaign to Erase the Stigma of Mental Illness Committee needs your help NOW! Respond vocally and in writing to every media item you see that unfairly or unrealistically portrays disorders of the brain.  Write letters to the editors of newspapers and magazines, expressing your criticism or approval of their handling of a brain disorder issue. Please send a copy to the AMI Office.  We will see the Northern California Coordinator for the October campaign receives a copy to forward to other AMIs and to NAMI.  If we are successful in this, there are two large donors who will pay the expenses for this national campaign. But they must be able to see the articles in the media that have been generated by the AMIs or individuals who are fighting to end the stigma and discrimination against peoples with disorders of the brain.  Open Your Mind--Mental illnesses are brain disorders that can be successfully treated is the theme.</tt></p>

<h2><tt>Update on Santa Clara County Mental Health
Medications and Associated Client Services 
</tt></h2>
<p><tt>
Mechling also visits the various public and private psychiatric care facilities, including Napa State Hospital to evaluate and coordinate their programs.  Clozapine and Respiridone, being atypical antipsychotics, are more constrained budgetwise than the less costly more typical ones.  Because of this and general County financial considerations, Mechling said that each program has been directed by the Board of Supervisors to develop newer cost and treatment outcome data.
	In closing Dr. Viale reminded us that bipolar illnesses, affect some one percent of the general population and accounts for a very high percentage of suicides.  The average patient doesnt get diagnosed for eight years.  There is hope that some newer anticonvulsant medications will be effective to supplement the present drugs.  Schizophrenia also has a lifetime prevalence of about one percent.  The suicide rate is ten times that of  the general population, a fact that should be made well known.
	Note: We must all lobby to increase the use of these cost effective medications and associated community supports, both to reduce overall County costs and to reduce suffering.
</tt></p>
