<p align=center>
<em><strong><tt>A Grass Roots Organization</tt></strong></em>
</p>
<h2><tt>Current Stanford University Psychiatric Medication Research and Testing to be Presented  at AMI's September General Meeting</tt></h2>
<tt>
<p>John Brooks, M. D. and Ph.D., from the Department of Psychiatry and Behavioral Science, Stanford University School of Medicine, will be the featured speaker for our Public Information Program starting at 8:00 PM on Tuesday, Sept. 10, 1996.  He will speak about the Stanford research studies being conducted there, including late phase testing of newer medications to gain Federal approval for general use.  Specifically, Dr. Brooks will discuss two new medications: 1. Seroquel, for treating patients with Schizophrenia and Schizo-Affective disorders and 2. Depakote, for treatment of patients with bipolar disorder.  He will cover studies of some very new medications also.</p>
<p>AMI'S Monthly General Meeting is held at the Hewlett Packard Auditorium, 5301 Stevens Creek Blvd. in the City of Santa Clara.  The Meeting is free and open to the public.  We begin at 7:00 PM, with everyone sharing information and welcoming new-comers.  At 7:30 President Erv Dean will chair a general information discussion on AMI matters, local mental health services and State or Federal actions.</p>
</tt>
<h2><tt>Back to School on Coping With SeriousMental Illness</tt></h2>
<tt>
<p><b>"Recovering From Psychosis: A Wellness Approach"</b> is a 12 session Mary Moller course on coping with Schizophrenia, Major Depression, and Bipolar disorders which will be taught on Thursday evenings by Phyllis M. Connolly, Ph.D., RN starting Sept. 12, 1996.  Complete details and a sign up form are included in this issue's insert flyer sheet.  It is highly recommended for professionals, family members and consumers.</p>
<p><b>A one day seminar on "Surviving & Thriving Despite Serious Mental Illness"</b> will be given by Christopher S. Amenson, Ph.D. on Friday, October 4, 1996 in Pleasant Hill.  Deadline for pre-registration is Sept. 15,1996.  Dr. Amenson is a highly respected presenter of effective coping with serious mental illness.  Again, complete details and a registration form are included on the back of the insert flyer.  (Note: if more than one registration is wanted, please use your nearest copy machine.)</p>
<p><b>Mark your calendars now to save Nov. 1 & 2 for the CAMI Conference at the S. F. Airport Marriot Hotel.</b>  The best two day seminar you'll ever find anywhere!
</p>
<p><b>Please note the change in AMI-SCC Office hours to 10AM-2PM.</b>  Diana Trawinski, the main stay of our office every work day, has suddenly become ill and is in Kaiser's Santa Teresa Hospital.  Despite our best wishes and prayers, she is not expected to be able to return soon.  She is sorely missed by us all.</p>
</tt>
<h2><tt>President's Corner</tt></h2>
<tt><p><b>Thanks to all of you</b> for what you have been doing to keep yourselves informed and for your work in helping to inform others.  You have helped to make our County's Mental Health care what it is, one of the best informed and most cost effective services anywhere.  Perhaps by lighting this corner of the world, we are doing more than we know to overcome these illnesses. </p>
<p><b>On County Supervisors:</b> As noted in our March and later Newsletters, two new County Supervisors are to be elected this November.  Patricia Sausedo and Peter McHugh are in a runoff in District 3 (now Supv. Gonzales).  Barbara Koppel and Joe Simitian are in a runoff in District 5 (now Supv. McKenna).  See the March issue or call for more candidate information. <u>Remember, elected County Supervisors have direct management control over all County health and welfare services in the County. </u></p>
<p><b>AMI-SCC members should call or write their Supervisor</b> to thank them (as a resident of their supervisor district) for their interest in improving services for the County's mentally ill and dual diagnosed.  We should offer help to keep them informed about effective family M H care. It is best. if you can,  to schedule a visit in September with them or their staff along with other AMI members from your district.  Please try to work together and with the AMI SCC Officers.  The AMI office has member information and useful fact sheets you can use. </p>
<p>A Supervisor action we can thank them for occurred earlier this year, when the they all approved a major County wide five year effort to move toward Comprehensive Performance Management (CPM) with the objective of budgeting measurable County service performance (results) in all departments, rather than for just staff position placement throughout the County.  Several CPM Committees have been set up to document best practices which could enhance performance.  Longer term we may be able to judge the County's Executive/Administration performance by how much of future County annual budgets are based on program dollars with quantifiable results each year. 	</p>
<p>Along with CPM the Supv.'s are also increasing the use of Requests For Proposals (RFP's) as a move toward competitive performance where possible.  In that regard, I hear their RFP, which resulted in the complete transfer of all patients from East Valley Pavilion to Crestwood, has been largely an improvement, based on patient's improved care and treatment results, even with reduced total costs.  Please let me and your District Supervisors and Candidates know what your experience indicates on this and also what you believe would further improve County and Contractor Mental Health care performance. </p>
<p><b>The November General Election is just two months away, and AMI efforts at State and Federal legislation for parity in public and private mental health care after some initial committee success have all recently failed.</b>  Please assure yourselves that your vote goes only to representatives who will support legislation for State and Federal parity in both public and private M H care.  Getting such legislation passed would do more to eliminate discrimination and end stigma than any thing else we could do.
</p>
</tt>
<h2><tt>OPEN YOUR MIND....MENTAL ILLNESSES ARE BRAIN DISORDERS</tt></h2>
<tt>
<p>This is a report on what we doing for the October '96 Mental Illness Awareness Campaign.  The above is NAMI's slogan and a committee of 12 AMI members (apostles?) has been formed.  More volunteers are needed!  The original members are: Ann Sloan, Chair; Herb Slavin and Marie Koerper, Media Publicity; Grace Johnston, Sharon Roth, Barbara Johnson, and Nancy Grippo plus Luisa Perez and Eleanor Reza (for Spanish), Speaker's Bureau; and Diana Trawinski, Virginia Moseley, and Elaine Miller, Display Materials for libraries and other facilities.	
</p>
<p>
The committee has been reviewing, selecting and ordering posters, brochures, videos, 35mm slides and other informational materials for public displays and presentations.  If you know of a public facility, house of worship, business lobby or other place where <u>you </u>could set up an informational display or sponsor an AMI speaker during the first week of October, please call AMI or Ann Sloan, wk. 415.327.0561 or hm. 415.851.2825.</p>
</tt>

<h2><tt>PERMAHOUSING AND COMMUNITY COMPANIONS NEW JOINT ORGANIZATION WAS DESCRIBED BY THEIR DIRECTORS AT THE AMI SCC JULY GENERAL MEETING</tt></h2>
<i>By Cole Buxbaum</i>
<tt><p>Mary Williams, Executive Director of Community Companions, and Carole Calkins, Director of its Permahousing Division, spoke at the AMI SCC July General Meeting.  "This is a wonderful time to be involved in the mental health community," said Calkins, referring to the recent merger of Permahousing into Community Companions.  There have been some internal organizational changes as well as some moves into new quarters.  The larger combined agency will afford backup support for each member and improvements in meeting all the needs of all clients.  Permahousing will still have some clinical services, their key housing services, an intern program in collaboration with San Jose State University, plus Crossroads and Zoe House licensed board and cares.</p>
<p>With Community Companions, they are gaining involvement in employment services, day rehabilitation, case management, a club house, a volunteer jobs program, partial hospitalization, and service teams.  The new combined organization is now a full service entity.  The main office is located at Community Companions, 200l The Alameda, San Jose, CA 95l26, phone number: 408-26l-7777.  The Permahousing Day Program, therapy and counseling will continue at l080 Minnesota, San Jose, CA 95l25.</p>
<p>Mary Williams began by saying that Calkins had initiated the merger by recognizing the benefits of collaboration that would allow Permahousing to concentrate more on housing and related special programs, while strengthening Community Companions capabilities in family services.  "The merger has been very successful as a result of the commitment of all people on both staffs." she stated.</p>
<p>By January, l997 Avenues to Mental Health and Miramonte Mental Health Services will also merge with Community Companions.  She noted that, " The un-named new organization will then be the largest non-profit mental health provider in Santa Clara County.  It will be stronger and will be able to provide leadership to further the values we all hold, while enhancing patient capability and reducing costs."  Also there were over twenty non-profit agencies that contracted with Santa Clara County to provide mental health services.  County administration, wants to reduce the number of contractors, while improving their responsiveness and lowering costs.</p>

<p>Williams emphasized that this collaboration and merger, working closely with the County should strengthen our community mental health system, benefiting the clients and making it less probable that more portions of the system may be contracted to private for-profit corporations.  "We all must be pro-active and informed as we move into managed care", she said, "to make sure that the client's needs are met."</p>

<p>The Permahousing and Community Companions merger was l8 months in the making.  Miramonte Mental Health Services and Avenues to Mental Health have also been working for a year towards their merger.  Seven people selected from each of these organizations are acting as a temporary board of directors, to report to a Chief Executive Officer, still to be selected .  Lynn Farr, Executive Director of Miramonte Mental Health Services, Glen Robertson, Director of Avenues to Mental Health, and Mary Williams are competing to be the new CEO.  They all are committed to the success of the new organization.  Rod Pence of AMI SCC and three other community individuals will be contacted to give input to the CEO selection process.	They are now soliciting ideas for the name of the new entity.  Williams recommended that "behavioral health" should not be the choice, although it seems that many regions of the country are using that as a title for an integrated mental health -substance abuse organization.  AMI members should write to Robert Sillen, Director of Health and Hospital Systems, 2220 Moorpark Ave., San Jose, CA 95l28, making their feelings known on the objectionable aspects of such a name substitute for Mental Health.  Calkins agreed, and added that the term can imply negative intent rather than a biological manifestation.</p>
<p>In answer to a question regarding the possibility of their contracting with Kaiser or other HMO's to supply some outpatient mental health care services.  William's indicated that  Kaiser has already begun a pilot program for outpatient intensive day care with Community Companions initiated by Sharon Roth..  She explained that the new joint entity of Community Companions and Permahousing will be open to additional contracts with other payees, as well as to an expansion of programs from Kaiser.</p>

<p>As the County moves toward integrating Drug and Alcohol Programs with Mental Health (which Sillen seems intent on doing) there will be the opportunity to look at the whole patient, since a large population falls into both categories.  Williams favors this collaboration, provided that certain resources and advocacy for  the mentally ill are preserved.  One process that would be better served is the Jail Diversion Program, which overlaps both categories.  It is important, she said that AMI members become involved in all these changes because "People hear family voices differently from those of paid providers" and they frequently carry more weight.</p>
<p>Mary Williams described the major parts of the combined organization to be as follows:  (l) Five service teams, including psychiatrists, licensed clinical social workers, case managers, and therapists to provide treatment and support 24 hours per day for mentally ill clients.  (A van permits a psychiatrist to go into the field.)  The total case load of all teams is now eleven hundred clients.  (2) Partial hospitalization; including intensive day therapy supported by Medicare funds, to minimize hospitalization.  (3) Day rehabilitation services to promote social and personal skills; Club House, Nikki"s Place, and Crossroads.  (4) Housing (under Carole Calkins) Zoe House and Crossroads Village and six facilities for independent living, plus individual apartments and several board and care homes for interim support.  (5) Housing coordinator (under Carole Calkins and staff) to develop additional housing resources.  (6) Volunteer program; to train clients to help others, and work within Community Companions on various programs.  (7) Employment; Mission Valley Employment (working with the State Department of Rehabilitation) places and trains clients for work and collaborates with Miramonte Mental Health Services, Avenues to Mental Health, and Focus for Work.</p>
<p>If someone needs to be connected with one of the above programs, or wants more information, please call Community Companions at 408.261.7777, or come to a monthly Community Companions, Family Information Night.
</p>
</tt>
