<p align=center><em><strong><tt>A Grass Roots Organization</tt></strong></em> </p>
<h1><tt>New Alliance Offers Full Range of 
Community Care As County Contractor 
and To Private Fee Clients</tt></h1>
<p><tt>On January 1, 1997 three previously independent and diversified County 
Mental Health Contractors will have been consolidated into one larger, 
non-profit organization, the Alliance for Community Care. Through the 
consolidation of Community Companions, Avenues to Mental Health and 
Miramonte Mental Health Services, the Alliance will serve approximately 
5,000 local residents, offering a broader and deeper range of programs 
and services to the mentally ill and their families. The new non-profit 
Alliance, headed by Mary Williams, will have an annual budget of $20 
million, a staff of 430, and 15 residential or outpatient treatment 
facilities. Alliance&#146;s goal is to provide all services needed by clients 
to develop and maintain their ability to live and work successfully in 
the community.</tt></p>
<p><strong><tt>Lyn Farr, Alliance Director of <br>
Clinical Services and Linda Wohlsen, <br>
Supervisor of fee-for-service, will discuss <br>
a broad range of available Alliance <br>
family and client services from 8:00 to <br>
9:00 PM at our Jan. 14 Monthly AMI <br>
Meeting. </tt></strong><tt>They will give examples of how<br>
different services for families / clients could benefit them: All the way 
from crisis intervention to diagnosis and initial treatment plans, to 
PLAN proxy-parenting care for County clients through pay-as-you-go, now 
or by trust after you are gone. (See more about PLAN on page 2.)<br>
Lyn Farr headed Miramonte for several years. Linda Wohlsen has served as 
Miramonte&#146;s vocational counselor and county rehabilitation specialist. 
Wohlsen has a masters degree from San Francisco State University in 
Marriage, Family and Child Counseling, and. was responsible for starting 
Miramonte&#146;s fee-for-service department and recently providing PLAN 
Services.<br>
</tt><strong><tt>The AMI General Meeting doors will open at 7:00 PM at the Hewlett Packard 
Auditorium, at 5301 Stevens Creek Blvd.</tt></strong><tt> in the City of Santa Clara, as 
shown above. A half hour presentation of AMI-SCC news will precede the 
Farr and Wohlsen program presentation.</tt></p>
<h3><tt>Please Renew Your Annual AMI-SCC Membership Now!</tt></h3>
<p><tt>Our major 1997 goals are: 1. To give you and the public more information 
on coping with brain disorders, 2. To reach more people like you who 
should participate with us as members, and 3. To enhance public and 
private community M H services, including housing. To accomplish movement 
towards these goals, we need more volunteers and more funds for a part 
time AMI Office and Community Outreach Coordinator. AMI-SCC is a 
volunteer California Non-profit Corporation with volunteer Board. Almost 
all of AMI-SCC, CAMI and NAMI operating funds come from shared local AMI 
dues and donations. If you have not become a member (or renewed) within 
the last quarter of 1997, please renew now. Please use the member form on 
the back page of this newsletter and help AMI, CAMI and NAMI continue 
working for you all through 1997.<br>
Also please consider establishing AMI-SCC as your charity for donations 
at work or on the form to help all of us do more to reduce the suffering 
of families and clients like yours.</tt></p>
<h3><tt>Planned Lifetime Assistance Network (PLAN)</tt></h3>
<p><tt>The pay-as-you-go PLAN Service Provider for Santa Clara and Alameda 
County clients was changed from The San Mateo Lodge to Santa Clara Co. M 
H Contract Agencies in October 1996. These Agencies have now consolidated 
into the Alliance for Community Care as described on the front page.<br>
PLAN and the new Alliance, starting January 1, 1997 will continue to 
provide PLAN services but with a wider choice of services to better fit 
individual family / client needs and priced to fit the varying difficulty 
and time needed for better results in each situation. Prior and on-going 
PLAN participants were all mailed a letter on December 10, 1996 detailing 
the new service options and payments required to continue to receive PLAN 
services under the new arrangement.<br>
The PLAN Office in Los Angeles, helped locally by AMI-SCC, can oversee 
Alliance implementation of pay as you go PLAN services in six month 
intervals. PLAN is also prepared to help with information on longer term 
California Special Needs Trusts and to provide Trustee services in accord 
with a Will.<br>
Privately paid, Alliance services can also be very helpful to family 
members in assessing their need for other at-home services or 
in-community services. These initial contacts with Alliance can often 
find ways to overcome existing roadblocks to getting more effective 
private or County M H services.<br>
For further information on short term family paid Alliance services, call 
Linda Wohlsen at 415.617.1751. For more pay as you go PLAN or AMI 
oversight information, call the AMI-SCC Office at 408.280.7264 or Erv 
Dean at 415.494.0347.</tt></p>
<h3><tt>Update on After Hours / Weekend / Holiday Service Team 
Coverage by Laurel Mechling</tt></h3>
<p><tt>After regular working hours emergency service (weekdays 5:00 PM -8:00 AM 
and 24 hours on weekends and holidays) is available to all clients 
receiving treatment in Santa Clara County from an Adult or Senior Mental 
Health Service Team. The goal of having after hours services available is 
to provide the appropriate level of care to service team connected 
clients around the clock, 24 hours a day, 365 days each year.<br>
Individuals who are currently receiving services from a Service Team can 
access after hours staff in the following ways:<br>
(1) If an individual is connected to a COUNTY Service Team the 
instructions are to call the ACCESS program at (408) 299-5800. ACCESS 
staff will page the on-call County staff person, who will in turn, assess 
the situation and provide the appropriate level of care or intervention 
deemed to be clinically appropriate.<br>
(2) If the individual is connected to a CONTRACT AGENCY Service Team, the 
individual is directed to call the contract agency&#146;s direct after hours 
service phone line.<br>
(3) If the individual or someone concerned about the individual doesn&#146;t 
know the after hours phone number, call ACCESS to get services or 
referral to a CONTRACTOR after hours number.<br>
Any inquiries / comments / problems relating to any of these services 
should be directed to Laurel Mechling, Mental Health Adult Service 
Division Administration at (408) 885-7575. The AMI-SCC Office also has a 
complements / complaints form for member written service experiences, 
which would let AMI know what is happening. We can forward the signed 
form to Laurel or to Jo Gampon the Adult Services Director, if requested.</tt></p>
<h2><tt>OPPOSITION TO PARITY FOR MENTAL ILLNESS 
TREATMENT IS BASED ON MISINFORMATION</tt></h2>
<h3><tt>Mental Illness Myths Dispelled - 1996 NAMI Fact sheet:</tt></h3>
<p><tt>Myth: Mental illnesses do not affect the average person.<br>
Fact: No one is immune to mental illness. The National Institute of 
Mental Health&#146;s statistics show that five million adults and 7.5 million 
children in America have some form of mental illness in any given year.<br>
<br>
Myth: The cause of mental illness is either poor parenting or poor 
character.<br>
Fact: Mental illnesses like major depression, manic depression, 
schizophrenia, obsessive-compulsive disorder and panic disorder are 
no-fault brain diseases, and can strike in any family.<br>
<br>
Myth: A person experiencing mental illness is possessed by an evil 
spirit.<br>
Fact: Mental illnesses are caused by physical disorders or chemical 
imbalances, not by supernatural forces.<br>
<br>
Myth: There is no effective treatment for mental illness.<br>
Fact: Mental illnesses are brain disorders. Brain disorders can be 
successfully treated, allowing victims of this condition to lead normal 
productive lives.<br>
<br>
Myth: People with mental illnesses cannot work or contribute to society.<br>
Fact: People with brain disorders find effective treatment through 
medicine, therapy, or both. Treatment that works allows people with brain 
disorders to contribute to society. It is the stigma of mental illness 
that prevents people with brain disorders from seeking employment.<br>
<br>
Myth: Mental illness is the same as mental retardation.<br>
Fact : Mental retardation is an intellectual deficit at birth, or a 
result of illness or injury during infancy or childhood. Mental illnesses 
are brain diseases, physical disorders that often strike between the ages 
of 16 and 25.<br>
<br>
Myth: People who have a mental illness are dangerous.<br>
Fact: Most people who have a mental illness are no more violent than 
someone suffering from cancer, diabetes, or any other serious illness. </tt></p>
<h3><tt>More often, they are the victims of violence.<br>
More From the 1996 NAMI Anti Stigma Brochure:</tt></h3>
<p><tt>Yours may be the one out of every five families in the United States that 
is or will be directly affected by a serious brain disorder. Such 
families face an unfair system that still treats them as &#147;less than,&#148; 
&#147;not as important as,&#148; or &#147;not equal to&#148; the rest of Americans. All 
Americans must help end the stigma and discrimination that lingers 
despite the scientific proof that makes them groundless.<br>
<br>
Discrimination against people with brain disorders makes no sense - No 
scientific sense - No economic sense - No political sense. Stigma is 
everywhere, but NAMI (and your local AMI) intends to end it. We have 
launched a five-year effort to challenge negative stereotypes, educate 
the public, confront discrimination and demand fair public policies from 
informed elected officials and policy makers.<br>
<br>
&#147;Doesn&#146;t it cost too much to pay for equal treatment for brain 
disorders?&#148; The better question is, &#147;Doesn&#146;t it cost too much to NOT 
treat them?&#148;<br>
<br>
According to the National Institute of Mental Health, &#147;Estimates based on 
studies of current coverage and utilization suggest that for an 
additional annual cost of $6.5 billion...annual savings in indirect costs 
and general medical services would amount to $8.7 billion. This would 
represent an estimated net economic benefit for the nation of $2.2 
Billion annually.<br>
<br>
For less than the price of a cup of coffee, one can buy a month of mental 
illness insurance benefits equal to those for other medical illnesses.<br>
<br>
AMI&#146;s five year campaign to End Discrimination will close the gaps 
between science and policy. We will demand equal access and treatment for 
a group of people who have been denied their inalienable rights simply 
because they have schizophrenia instead of epilepsy, bipolar disorder 
instead of Alzheimer&#146;s, or major depression instead of Parkinson&#146;s 
disease.<br>
________________________________________________<br>
<br>
Help the Campaign. Talk to your friends and write your representatives. 
Now!</tt></p>
<h2><tt>Recovering From Psychosis: A Wellness Approach 
Class</tt></h2>
<p><tt>This unique 12 week course will begin again on Wednesdays, February 12 
from 3:30- 6:30 PM, and continuing until April 30 at the Alliance for 
Community Care (was Community Companions), 2001 The Alameda, San Jose. 
There is a $45 fee for the required text/manual. Fees per session 
attended are based on a sliding scale ($1-$25 per session), for 
non-professionals according to need and ability to pay. Professionals 
attending for credit will be given 36 contact hours for completion of all 
12 sessions and will be charged $30 per session. Call Nikki Winovich at 
408-261-7777 for registration and additional information.<br>
The 12 week course empowers persons diagnosed with a psychiatric illness 
and their families through an increased understanding of the illness, 
relapses, recovery and rehabilitation. Because the course includes 
individuals with psychiatric illness, families, mental health 
professionals and mental health service providers, an optimal and 
effective learning environment is created. Outcome research, based on a 
large sample of participants involved in the course in the state of 
Washington, indicated a 93.5% decrease in hospitalization needs. 
Satisfaction surveys from participants of the course here in Santa Clara 
County indicate immediate and long term satisfaction and similar positive 
outcomes.<br>
Dr. Phyllis M. Connolly, a certified clinical specialist in adult 
psychiatric/mental health nursing and a professor at San Jose State 
University is the facilitator. She was specifically trained by Mary 
Moller and Millene Murphy, developers of the course and she can be 
reached at 408-924-3144 for additional information. The 12 week course is 
approved for 36 contact hours for nurses., Suite 7, San Jose, CA 95125.<br>
<br>
AMI-SCC Office Changes<br>
AMI Office Coordinator<br>
As most of you know, Diana Trawinski had a stroke last August after the 
AMI picnic. It affected her speaking and swallowing abilities . With 
rehabilitation she is making some improvement and is able to live at 
home. It is not expected now that she will be able, any time soon, to 
resume her nearly half time or more work as the AMI-SCC Office 
Coordinator.<br>
She performed her work at the AMI Office so well and with so much 
dedication that we were hoping that she might be able to return and still 
do. However we have had to come to the realization that there is little 
chance that will happen. So we must seriously seek a replacement for her 
as described in the column to the right. If you or any one you know could 
do the job as described please call and send in a resume&#146;.<br>
<br>
AMI-SCC Treasurer<br>
Marty Craig our very capable Treasurer has transferred from San Jose to a 
better job in Santa Cruz and is in the process of buying a home in 
Pacific grove. Last year she set up our books on an IBM personal computer 
using the financial program Quicken and before that was the Board 
Secretary. All good things come to an end, they say. All we can say is 
</tt><strong><tt>THANK YOU VERY MUCH MARTY FOR ALL YOUR HELP!</tt></strong><tt><br>
Fortunately, Herb Slavin has computer skills and has agreed to be our new 
Treasurer for the remainder of our fiscal year. Welcome aboard Herb.</tt></p>
<h3><tt>Needed: An Office Operation and Outreach Coordinator</tt></h3>
<p><tt>The Alliance for the Mentally Ill of Santa Clara County is seeking an 
individual to coordinate the work flow of its office and to supervise its 
volunteer staff. AMI-SCC is a volunteer non-profit organization of family 
members of people with mental illness. We provide support for families, 
public information and education about mental illness and advocacy for 
improved services for people with psychiatric disabilities (brain 
disorders).<br>
Duties will include coordinating the work flow of the office, supervising 
the volunteer staff, assisting the Board of Directors with outreach and 
fund raising projects and providing information to families and the 
community about services available for the mentally ill in Santa Clara 
County.<br>
Desired qualifications include:<br>
1. Experience and abilities to organize and coordinate office activities.<br>
2. Ability to work well with volunteers and to delegate work.<br>
3. Flexibility, initiative, detail oriented and a willingness to learn.<br>
4. Computer literacy, typing ability and good telephone skills.<br>
5. Knowledge of mental illness, AMI and the County public and private 
mental health system and services.<br>
The position is part-time, 20 hours per week (four hours per day, 10 AM - 
2 PM, Monday through Friday). The salary is $9 per hour to start, raising 
to $10 after 3 months.<br>
Please send resum&eacute;s to:<br>
AMI/Job--AMI-of Santa Clara County<br>
1060 Minnesota Ave., Suite 7,<br>
San Jose, CA 95125<br>
The last date to send resum&eacute;s is January 15, 1997. Interviews will be 
conducted as received, with those individuals whose skills seem to be the 
most qualified.<br>
For further information, please call the AMI office at 408-280-7264 or 
Erv Dean, President, at 415-494-0347.<br>
<br>
Office Operation and Outreach Coordinator Tasks:<br>
1. Operate answering machine, copier, and FAX machine.<br>
2 Answer phones, read and sort mail.<br>
3 Provide office support for AMI Board Members.<br>
4. Assign tasks to office volunteers.<br>
5. Help with monthly Newsletter and its mailing.<br>
6. Maintain membership data base, and correspondence.<br>
7. Keep calendars and schedules current.<br>
8. Continue to develop office procedures.<br>
9. Help to organize functions and events.<br>
</tt></p>
<h3><tt>PREMATURE DISCHARGE FROM CONFINED CARE</tt></h3>
<p><strong><tt>Maria Montez Fink</tt></strong><tt>, AMI Member and new Co-Chair of the Mental Health 
Board&#146;s Patient&#146;s Rights Committee invites family representatives to 
