<h2><tt>New County Mental Health Programs Described at 
November, 1996, General Meeting of AMI-SCC</tt></h2>
<p><tt>By Cole Buxbaum<br>
<br>
Three exciting new Santa Clara Department of Mental Health Service Teams 
and a behavioral Gateway Program have been started to improve problem 
Mental Health (M H) services, according to Pablo Garcia, Adult M H 
Services Manager, who led the speakers at the November, 1996, AMI General 
Meeting.<br>
Kitty Palmer, Health Services Supervisor in the Downtown M H Center 
specializes in problems of the County&#146;s homeless mentally ill. She wrote 
a grant proposal to H.U.D. last year requesting $2.4 million to begin a 
multi-service Homeless Team.. It was approved and will provide a full 
array of needed services focused on homeless disabled individuals in the 
County with Mental Health as the lead agency. The M H Team will promote 
more collaborative homeless efforts with Drug and Alcohol, and Public 
Health Departments, plus Social Services and the Veterans Administration. 
More rental subsidies and a post hospitalization component are included 
in the funding.<br>
The Team will service the homeless population who live on the streets or 
other inappropriate places and those staying in emergency shelters, who 
are disabled, mentally ill, have alcohol and drug abuse problems or the 
dual diagnosis of mental illness and substance abuse, or AIDS, or Post 
Traumatic Stress Disorder.<br>
Transitional Housing now has rental subsidies for 28 beds, with residents 
paying up to one third of their income. Emergency Housing Consortium has 
given the Homeless Team 25 additional bed spaces and Julian Street Inn, 
35 more.<br>
A new post-hospitalization shelter will offer a clean, safe environment 
for homeless individuals requiring on-going care after release from 
emergency rooms or a hospital. The plan is for a two-week stay. A public 
health nurse has been assigned.<br>
The Homeless Team will have a total of 11 members, including a public 
health nurse, a rehab counselor, a social worker from adult protective 
and social services, and a part time physician, plus 2.5 positions 
contracted through the VA.<br>
Referrals to the Homeless Team are through the emergency shelters or by 
contacting the Homeless Team Supervisor, Kitty Palmer, 408-299-8657.<br>
Lewis Pollard, recently the Supervisor of the East Valley Mental Health 
Department, is now Supervisor of the new Mobile M H Team at ACCESS. His 
new Team is a pilot project to help divert mentally ill people with minor 
offenses away from incarceration in the jail system in collaboration with 
City of San Jose police. The target group consists of those who have 
committed a minor offense or nuisance misdemeanor, such as trespassing, 
disturbing the peace, or not paying for public services. The Mobile M H 
Team is funded until July first for three people per day (one during the 
day and two on the evening shift) seven days a week. The team will be 
staffed by social workers with masters degrees, licensed clinical social 
works or MFCC&#146;s. The organization will be operated by the County Mental 
Health Department as a unit of their ACCESS (Acute Crisis Care and 
Entrance to System Services) program.<br>
In answer to questions, Pollard said, &#147;The Mobile M H Team will attempt 
to contact family members or others in the clients&#146; support system as 
needed and as appropriate,&#148; Also regarding location, he said, &#147;The team 
will spend most of its time with police radio contact cruising Central 
and East San Jose streets. It remains to be seen whether they will have 
time for inside work as well.&#148;<br>
Pollard observed that it would be impractical to relate at first to all 
of the County&#146;s police districts so they are beginning in San Jose&#146;s 
highest need areas and will try to set up procedures to work with the 
local police, street people and the public there.<br>
As to the number of people who potentially could be diverted from jail, 
he estimates that from 500 recent arrests made in a three day period, 
including approximately 60 misdemeanor arrests, about 34 could have been 
diverted. These are people whose behavior would usually lead to an arrest 
but if linked with Mental Health could avoid jail. Pollard&#146;s number is 
408-885-6210 for more information exchange if needed.<br>
The traditional M H approach in dealing with younger clients consists of 
separating those under 18 years of age from adults (18 or over). The two 
groups have very different guidelines for M H services. Young adults 
frequently need something in between. A committee was set up two years 
ago to study transitional M H services under the co-chairmanship of Jo 
Gampon, Adult Services Director, and Nancy Pe&ntilde;a, Ph.D., Family and 
Children&#146;s Director, including contract and other agencies serving the 
population. Their work has resulted in forming a new group, called The 
Young Adult Transition Team (YATS) which will be led by Kim Flatmo, 
Health Services Supervisor, at the Fair Oaks M H Center, 408-733-2760.<br>
Along with Kim Flatmo as Supervisor, YATS has a staff of five 
professionals. Key characteristics required of the team members are 
understanding young persons&#146; problems and enjoying working with them. The 
team&#146;s goals are to, &#147;Stick by you to help you think about your options 
about medications, friendships, recreations and leisure, money benefits, 
health, housing, school work and family.&#148; A young person would not be 
included in YATS unless he or she has no connected family, has housing 
problems and no resources. <br>
Garcia added that the YATS has been talking to the Social Security 
Administration about addressing the problem of transition coverage for 
young people going from the hospital or jail to the community. He 
contacted Congresswoman Zoe Lofgren for help and hopes that AMI will help 
here as well.<br>
The Department of Alcohol and Drug Services has been moving to a managed 
care model to maximize its resources and render broader behavioral care. 
Meg Paris, Ph.D., Health Services Supervisor, described a new program 
which will be a collaborative effort between M H and Drug and Alcohol to 
provide a single point of entry into the managed health care system for 
adults with behavioral problems who need help. It will be called the 
Gateway Program. </tt></p>
<p><strong><tt>The Gateway Program under Julianna Brooks, MSW</tt></strong><tt> has been established to 
provide Chemical Dependency telephone information on County services and 
screening for referral to County resources for drug and alcohol treatment 
and education. It will also serve as a central data collection unit of 
callers seeking such information and treatment.<br>
</tt><strong><tt>The Chemical Dependency Screening and Referrals will operate five working 
days a week, from 8 AM to 10 PM and can be reached at (408) 885-5790. 
</tt></strong><tt>Case Managers will handle the most difficult cases. Four clinical 
positions are funded, with one being a transferee from the ACCESS 
program.</tt></p>
<p><tt>All the staff will be Alcohol and Drug people, where the funding comes 
from, rather than Mental Health.<br>
</tt><strong><tt>General Chemical Dependency information collection and services 
information will operate on a 24-hour basis, seven days a week and can be 
reached at (800) 488-9919</tt></strong><tt> with roll over to ACCESS 24 hour services 
between 10 PM and 8 AM or on holidays and weekends.</tt></p>
</body>

</html>
