<head>
<title>CAMI - The JOURNAL</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align=center>&#160;<img src="../../graphics/jourhdr.jpg" align=bottom width=504 height=96></p>
<p align=center><em>If you wish to order back issues of THE JOURNAL, they are available from </em><a href="./cami.html"><em>CAMI</em></a><em> for $5 or 
$7 depending on whether they are in black and white or color.</em><b> Mail check to:</b> 1111 Howe 
Avenue, Suite 475 Sacramento, CA 95825-8541 (916) 567-0163 </p>
<p align=left><a href="http://www.mhsource.com/hy/j11.html"><strong>SCHIZOPHRENIA</strong></a><em>: a look at the most devastating of all thought disorders plus theories on 
treatment and cause</em><strong> </strong></p>
<p align=left><strong>HOUSING</strong><em>:the best housing options for persons with mental illness, and a look at consumer 
choices</em></p>
<p align=left><strong>REHABILITATION</strong><em>: various 'rehab' theories and the benefits of meaningful work, and the 
raising of expectations</em></p>
<p align=left><a href="http://www.mhsource.com/hy/j14.html"><strong>DEPRESSION</strong></a><em>: how it feels to be the victim of unpredictable mood disorders, and a review 
of the famous and creative persons who have been afflicted</em></p>
<p align=left><strong>VIOLENCE</strong><em>: untreated and acting out, at a time when the pendulum has swung in favor of 
civil liberties, persons with mental illness are often more dangerous; so many are in prisons</em></p>
<p align=left><a href="http://www.mhsource.com/hy/j22.html"><strong>ALCOHOL AND DRUG ABUSE</strong></a><em>: both appear to make persons with mental illness worse, 
but why, then, aren't professionals cross-trained so that disciplines aren't always in 
conflict, further victimizing the ill?</em></p>
<p align=left><strong>SYSTEM CHANGE</strong><em>: a few hopeful signs that the dysfunctional, under funded mental 
health systems are being reorganized with a focus on outcomes</em></p>
<p align=left><strong>BRAIN RESEARCH</strong><em>: a glimpse into the realm of scientific inquiry that is permitted today 
via astounding new technologies and determined researchers</em></p>
<p align=left><a href="http://www.mhsource.com/hy/j31.html"><strong>SIBLINGS</strong></a><em>: the impact oon the brothers and sisters of persons with mental illness</em></p>
<p align=left><strong>CLIENTS</strong><em>: experiences with brain disorders are shared with genuine openness and 
vulnerability by persons who have survived the trauma and the stigma</em></p>
<p align=left><strong>PROVIDERS</strong><em>: professionals express concern about the inadequacies of their training to 
deal with the realities of the system in which they must work</em></p>
<p align=left><strong>RELIGIOUS OUTREACH</strong><em>: clergy, many of whom have family members with 
schizophrenia or affective disorders, urge fellow religious leaders to become better 
informed</em></p>
<p align=left><strong>MEDIA</strong><em>: the media creates and perpetuates distortions, biases, and fears as they trivialize 
and wildly fictionalize behaviors of persons with mental illness</em></p>
<p align=left><strong>DOES ANYTHING WORK</strong><em>: a new kind of teaming of professionals and those who receive 
services and their families, supports risk taking for the &quot;members&quot; in the community</em></p>
<p align=left><strong>VETERANS</strong><em>: special concerns of veterans who have mental illness, and their families' 
plight, and the VA agenda for research and service</em></p>
<p align=left><strong>ARTS</strong><em>: participating in &quot;the arts&quot; proves uniquely beneficial on many levels</em></p>
<p align=left><a href="http://www.mhsource.com/hy/j51.html"><strong>ETHICS</strong></a><em>: who looks out for the patient involved in neurobiological research?</em></p>
<p align=left><strong>RELATIONSHIPS</strong><em>: exploring friendships, intimacy and sex for persons with mental illness</em></p>
<p align=left><a href="http://www.mhsource.com/hy/j53.html"><strong>RECOVERY</strong></a><em>: a vision of what life can be after psychiatric diagnosis</em></p>
<p align=left><strong>CHILDREN &amp; ADOLESCENTS</strong><em>: with NBD face unworkable laws, inadequate schooling, 
and even the threat of parental abandonment in order to get publicly funded services</em></p>
<p align=left><a href="http://www.mhsource.com/hy/j61.html"><strong>OBSESSIVE-COMPULSIVE DISORDER</strong></a><em>: a morbid, frightening thoughts, fear of dirt and 
touching, bizarre rituals and repetive behaviors make up this fouth most common 
psychiatric disorder</em></p>
<p align=left><a href="http://www.mhsource.com/hy/j62.html"><strong>BIPOLAR</strong></a><em>: exploring the mood disorder once called manic-depression, the treatments for 
it, and experiences of people who have it</em></p>
<p align=left><strong>SELF HELP</strong><em>: as a powerful step on the road to recovery</em></p>
<p align=left><strong>ADA</strong><em>: hope in the workplace for persons with mental disabilities</em></p>
<p align=left><a href="http://www.mhsource.com/hy/j71.html"><strong>MANAGED CARE</strong></a><em>: is it merely rationing care to increase private sector profits?</em></p>
