<DOCHDR>
http://www.susanville.com:80/home-n-garden/crafts/barbie.html 165.227.192.28 19970216112207 text/html 5853
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Date: Sun, 16 Feb 1997 11:22:26 GMT
Server: Apache/1.1.3
Content-type: text/html
Content-length: 5682
Last-modified: Mon, 03 Feb 1997 00:09:33 GMT
</DOCHDR>
<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//IETF//DTD HTML//EN">

<html>

<head>
<title>Barbie Sweater Patterns</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<h1 align=center><img src="/graphics/Knitting1.JPG" align=bottom></h1>
<p align=center><font color="#000000"><em>All three sweaters (the embroidered sweater dress, cropped cable pullover, and striped 
pullover) can be made from the same basic pattern with minor alterations.</em></font></p>
<h2 align=center><font color="#000000">Materials</font></h2>
<h3 align=left><font color="#000000"><font size=4>Yarn</font></font></h3>
<p align=left><font color="#000000">J. &amp; P. Coats Knit-Cro-Sheen (100 yards) from Coats &amp; Clark (P.O. Box 27067, Greenville, 
SC 29616), 1 ball each #46A Rose, #10A Canary and #168 Jade.</font></p>
<h3 align=left><font color="#000000">Needles</font></h3>
<p align=left><font color="#000000">Size 2 knitting needles, or size to obtain gauge. Sewing needle.</font></p>
<h3 align=left><font color="#000000">Notions</font></h3>
<p align=left><font color="#000000">5 stitch holders. Matching sewing thread. Small metal snaps.</font></p>
<h2 align=center><font color="#000000">Directions</font></h2>
<h3 align=left><font color="#000000">Gauge</font></h3>
<p align=left><font color="#000000">15 stitchs and 17 rows = 2&quot; (in St st using two strands of yarn held together). To save time take 
time to check guage.</font></p>
<h3 align=left><font color="#000000">Front and Back</font></h3>
<p align=left><font color="#000000"><em>(made in one piece)</em> With 2 strands of yarn held together, cast on 40 stitches (except where 
noted). Work even in St st (k1 row, p1 row) for length indicated in individual directions; end with 
a WS row. <strong>Raglan shaping:</strong> k9, bind off next 2 sts, k 18, bind off next 2 sts, k9.</font></p>
<h3 align=left><font color="#000000">Right Back</font></h3>
<p align=left><font color="#000000">Next row: p9, sl rem sts onto st holder. Work even in St st for 2 rows. <strong>Dec row: </strong>k 1, k2 tog, k 
rem sts. <strong>Following row:</strong> purl. Rep last 2 rows 3 times more - 5 sts. Sl sts onto st holder.</font></p>
<h3 align=left><font color="#000000">Front</font></h3>
<p align=left><font color="#000000">P across the next 18 sts from first st holder. Work even in St st for 2 rows. <strong>Dec row (RS):</strong> k 1, 
k 2 tog, k across to within last 3 sts, k 2 tog, k1. <strong>Following row:</strong> purl. Rep last 2 rows 3 times 
more - 10 sts. Sl sts onto st holder.</font></p>
<h3 align=left><font color="#000000">Left Back</font></h3>
<p align=left><font color="#000000">P across rem 9 sts from first st holder. Work even in St st for 2 rows. Dec row: k across to 
within last 3 sts, k2 tog, k1. Following row: purl. Rep last 2 rows 3 times more - 5 sts. Sl sts 
onto st holder.</font></p>
<h3 align=left><font color="#000000">Sleeves</font></h3>
<p align=left><font color="#000000">With 2 strands of yarn held tog, cast on 12 sts. Working in St st, inc 1 st each side every 4th row 
4 times - 20 sts. Work even until sleeve measures 2 1/2&quot; from beg, end with a WS row. <strong>Raglan 
shaping:</strong> bind off 2 sts at beg of next 2 rows - 16 sts. <strong>Dec row (RS):</strong> k 1, k 2 tog, k across to 
within last 3 sts, k 2 tog, k 1. Following row: purl. Rep last 2 rows 5 times more - 4 sts. Sl rem 
sts onto a st holder.</font></p>
<h3 align=left><font color="#000000">Finishing </font></h3>
<p align=left><font color="#000000">Lightly steam-press pieces. Using matching sewing thread, sew the sleeve seams, then sew in 
sleeves. <strong>Neckband:</strong> with RS facing sl all sts from st holders onto left-hand needle -- 28 sts. 
<strong>Next row:</strong> p 5, p 2 tog twice, p 10, p 2 tog twice, p 5 - 24 sts. Following row: knit. Bind off as 
if to p. Sew back seam leaving top 1 1/2&quot; (for pullovers) and 2&quot; (for dress) unstitched. Using 
matching sewing thread, sew on snap to back neck opening.</font></p>
<h3 align=left><font color="#000000">Cropped Cable Pullover</font></h3>
<p align=left><font color="#000000">Use Jade to cast on 41 sts. <strong>Cable pattern - row 1 (right side):</strong> k 18, p1, k3, p1, k18. <strong>Row 2: 
</strong>p 18, k 1, p 3, k 1, p 18. <strong>Row 3:</strong> k 18, p 1, leaving sts on left-hand needle as you work, k 3rd 
st, k 2nd st, then k 1st st, remove sts from left-hand needle, p1, k18. Row 4: rep row 2. Rep 
these 4 rows for cable pat and work even for 1 1/4&quot;, end with a WS row. Keeping to cable pat 
as established, work raglan shaping, dec 1 st at center of front on last dec row so there are 10 sts 
rem. Use Jade for sleeves.</font></p>
<h3 align=left><font color="#000000">Dress</font></h3>
<p align=left><font color="#000000">Use Rose to cast on. Work even for 4 3/4 &quot;, end with a WS row. Work raglan shaping. Use 
Rose for sleeves. Before finishing, use 2 strands of Canary to embroider 6 petal lazy-daisy stitch 
flowers in a random pattern on front, back and sleeves. Using 2 strands of Jade, accent flowers 
and 3 straight stitch leaves.</font></p>
<h3 align=left><font color="#000000">Stripped Pullover</font></h3>
<p align=left><font color="#000000">Use Canary to cast on. Work 4 rows even. Stripe pattern: * work 2 rows Jade and 4 rows 
Canary, rep from * across 3 times, then work 2 more rows Jade. Work raglan shaping. Use 
Canary for sleeves.</font></p>
<blockquote>
<hr>
</blockquote>
<p align=center><a href="http://www.susanville.com"><img src="/graphics/stest.gif" align=bottom border=0></a></p>
</body>

