<head>
<meta http-equiv="Content-Type"
content="text/html; charset=iso-8859-1">
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 2.0">
<title>Copper Mountain Financial Group - Newsletter</title>
</head>

<body background="images/watchart.gif">

<p align="center"><img src="images/pookline.gif" width="722"
height="13"> </p>

<h1 align="center">WealthWatch</h1>

<h3 align="center">a quarterly report on money &amp; investing</h3>

<h5 align="center">June 30, 1996</h5>

<p align="center"><img src="images/pookline.gif" width="722"
height="13"> </p>

<h3 align="center">Understanding Diversification In A World
Economy</h3>

<p>Many investors are interested in further diversifying their
investments beyond U.S. stocks and bonds. To answer commonly
asked questions about international investing, Copper Mountain
recently interviewed Marcel Houtzager from the Wanger Asset
Management Group. Marcel is the manager of Acorn International
Fund which is one of the funds owned by Copper Mountain's
Commingled International Fund. Here are some of the highlights of
that interview: </p>

<p><strong>Copper Mountain:</strong> Why should an investor
consider international investing? </p>

<p><strong>Wanger Asset Management: </strong>We believe that
compared to 50 to 100 years ago, the U.S. can now be categorized
as a mature economy. That means it is growing more slowly than
many other countries which make up today's emerging markets. We
see more potential for high growth overseas. </p>

<p><strong>CM:</strong> What does a mature vs. emerging market
economy mean to international investing? </p>

<p><strong>WAM: </strong>The U S. currently represents one-third
of the entire world's economic market, and international markets
represent the remaining two-thirds. Taking into account that many
foreign economies are growing taster than the U.S., their share
of the pie should increase in the coming years. For an investor,
this means that a larger portion of growth investment
opportunities could actually be outside the U.S. Therefore, a
portfolio that is diversified to include domestic and
international markets could be well positioned to take advantage
of growth in both of these markets when it occurs. </p>

<p><strong>CM:</strong> What is the relationship between U.S. and
International markets? </p>

<p><strong>WAM:</strong> To a certain extent there is a time warp
between what happens in The markets of the U.S. and the rest of
the world. The performance of U.S. and foreign markets are not
synchronized: while some rise, others fall. And U.S. trends don't
show up overseas for a while. By understanding U.S. markets,
we're better prepared to capture opportunities when they appear
overseas. </p>

<p><strong>CM:</strong> But isn't international investing more
risky? </p>

<p><strong>WAM:</strong> The perception is that international
investing is risky. Actually. we believe that putting all your
investments in just U.S. companies is risky. America's purchasing
power has decreased because the value of the U.S. dollar has
fallen by half against the Japanese Yen. That's why Japanese cars
are more expensive than American cars. We do agree that getting
information about international investments can be more
difficult. That's why it's important to choose a money management
firm that spends time in the countries that they invest in,
getting to know the management and financial situation of those
companies. </p>

<p>There are several ways that an investor can diversify their
portfolio through international exposure. These might include: a
company 401(k) plan investment option, directly through a mutual
fund, or, via an IRA. A good idea is to begin learning more about
how the markets work. On a daily basis you can read your local
newspaper or Wall Street Journal, or watch &quot;The Nightly
Business Report&quot; on TV. Other good sources are the
&quot;Wall Street Week&quot; TV program and financial magazines
like <em>Barron's, The Economist </em>and <em>Money</em>. </p>

<p><strong>CM:</strong> Thank you Marcel. </p>

<p align="center"><img src="images/pookline.gif" width="722"
height="13"> </p>

<h3 align="center">Dollar-Cost Averaging. Or, the next best thing
to buying low and selling high.</h3>

<p>The sure-fire way to make money in your investments is to buy
low and sell high Unfortunately, that's easier said than done.
Because no one can predict with 100% certainty when a security is
headed up or down. </p>

<p>However, there is a way to take advantage of market
fluctuations. It's called dollar-cost averaging. </p>

<p>The key to this strategy is to make regular investments, which
is what you currently do in your retirement plan For example. by
contributing $100 a month, your contribution is used to purchase
securities. If the security happens to be at a low price, you'll
buy more shares than when it's at a high price. The benefit of
&quot;buying&quot; a little each month is that at the end of the
year, you will have made your investments at various highs or
lows in the market. Your average investment cost can be lower
than the average price of your entire investment. </p>

<p align="center"><img src="images/pookline.gif" width="722"
height="13"> </p>

<h3 align="center">Investment Tip</h3>

<p>The more money you contribute to your retirement fund the
faster your fund will grow. The trick is finding ways to make
larger monthly contributions. One way is as close as your garage:
your car. </p>

<p>Instead of buying a new car as soon as your old one is paid
off, consider driving it a few more years and investing that same
amount into your retirement plan. Or consider buying a less
expensive vehicle. </p>

<p><img src="images/pookline.gif" width="722" height="13"> </p>

