<h1 align="center">WealthWatch</h1>

<h3 align="center">a quarterly report on money &amp; investing</h3>

<h5 align="center">September 30, 1996</h5>

<p><img src="images/pookline.gif" width="722" height="13"> </p>

<h3 align="center">Conservative Growth Provides Success</h3>

<p><em>There are many successful methods to managing investments.
One of these is known as a growth style. The following article
was written by George Cohen of Cohen, Klingenstein &amp; Marks,
Copper Mountain's Large Cap Growth Style fund sub-advisor.</em> </p>

<p>Investments can be made in a variety of ways: stocks, bonds,
real estate and many more. Each type has distinctive
characteristics. Stocks and bonds are the two most commonly used
for retirement saving and they are very different from one
another. Bonds promise to pay interest each year, but do not
increase in value over time. Stocks do not promise to pay
anything each year (although most do pay dividends), but the
value of stocks increases over time as the companies behind them
grow. The year-to-year increase in stock prices cannot be
predicted, but historically they have done substantially better
than bonds. Over time the market rewards investors who are willing
to trade short-term uncertainty for superior long-term returns. </p>

<p>And not all stocks are the same &quot;Growth Stocks&quot; are
stocks that have greater potential for high returns than does the
average stock. Along with that goes more short-term uncertainty.
They can be expected to achieve higher returns amid bigger swings
in their prices. But, higher returns are very important for
long-term investing. The power comes from compound interest. A
dollar invested with a 9% return for twenty years grows to $5.60.
A dollar invested at 11% grows to $8.06. To say those returns are
each about 10% would miss something obvious. A little extra
return makes a big difference. And historically, growth stocks
have reliably delivered that little extra return. </p>

<p>And now is a particularly good time for growth stocks, because
the next couple of decades should be a period of above average
growth in America. These factors lead to that conclusion: </p>

<ul>
    <li>The &quot;baby boom&quot; generation that represents the
        biggest group in our population is at the age when they
        are most productive as workers. </li>
    <li>The Cold War is over, so resources are being redirected
        toward economic growth. </li>
    <li>Foreign economies are growing, offering opportunity for
        U.S. exports. </li>
    <li>U.S. businesses are managing themselves with more concern
        for efficiency. </li>
    <li>Government is increasingly concerned with encouraging
        economic growth. </li>
    <li>Technology keeps advancing faster and faster. </li>
</ul>

<p>If there ever was a time to bet on growth stocks, now is it. </p>

<p>Even so, we are not about to put all our money in any one
place. Most of us own a mix of asset types. We think that should
include growth stocks. As you might guess, there is more than one
way to invest in growth stocks. Our approach to growth is the
most conservative. We buy very large, stable, established
companies with growth character-istics. When the price is right,
we buy such companies as: Coca-Cola, Microsoft, Intel,
McDonald's, Bristol-Myers and Campbell Soup. We do not buy small
new firms with untested products. Instead, we buy diversified
companies that should benefit from overall growth in the economy. </p>

<p><img src="images/pookline.gif" width="722" height="13"> </p>

