<h1 align="center">WealthWatch</h1>

<h3 align="center">a quarterly report on money &amp; investing</h3>

<h5 align="center">October 17, 1996</h5>

<p><img src="images/pookline.gif" width="722" height="13"> </p>

<h3>Market Comments</h3>

<p>During the third quarter, both stocks and bonds rose nicely.
July was an ugly month, with stocks down almost 5%, but
persistent worries about accelerating inflation gave way to a
belief that the economy was slowing enough to control prices
without hindering corporate profits. Year to date, the S&amp;P
500 has advanced 13.5%, and the bond market has increased 0.61%.
During the month of September alone, the bond market increased a
whopping (for the bond market) 1.74%. </p>

<p>The bears who were arguing for a return of inflation were
disappointed by evidence that the economy is slowing. However,
that would be a natural consequence of the jump in interest rates
that started in February and peaked in July. </p>

<p>The governmental instrument for controlling growth in the
economy is the Federal Reserve. The Fed wants a slowdown, though
not necessarily a recession, to keep inflation in check. Under
the guidance of Chairman Alan Greenspan, the board's policy is
based on the premise that an economy that grows faster than about
2.25% a year raises the danger of accelerating inflation. They
will keep that target in mind and increase or decrease rates
accordingly. </p>

<p>Our fixed income sub~advisor, Pacific Investment Management
Company (PIMCO), has been arguing throughout the year that the
United States is in the midst of a period of disinflation, and
interest rates are in a secular trend downward because of
pressure on wages, high consumer debt, and weak foreign
economies. As an aside, PIMCO is a great bond manager that has
continually beat the bond index, even when their interest rate
calls were wrong, by using sophisticated trading strategies.
PIMCO is the type of sub-advisor that we hire at Copper Mountain
- the best of the best. </p>

<p>As the economy shows signs of slowing, concern about profit
margins and earnings will likely mount. This just goes to show
that there is no such thing as a worry-free rising market. </p>

<p>We at Copper Mountain share the same concerns as the rest of
you. Our personal retirement assets are invested right beside
yours. We wonder if the stock market is too high, why
international stocks have lagged their U.S. counterparts for the
past two years, and which direction interest rates are going.
Some of us even worry about who will win the elections in
November. But through it all we remain convinced that the most
successful long-term investors are those that allocate their
portfolios among different asset classes and styles, don't try to
time the market, and invest with proven managers with superior
track records over time. </p>

<p><img src="images/pookline.gif" width="722" height="13"> </p>

